<HEADLINE>
JEROME L. GREENE DIES AT 93; MAJOR NEW YORK PHILANTHROPIST
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jerome L. Greene, a lawyer, real estate investor and
benefactor of Columbia Law School, Montefiore Medical Center and
the Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts, died May 27 at his
residence in the Carlyle Hotel in Manhattan. He was 93 and also had
homes in Greenwich, Conn., and Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, whose family built a fortune through commercial and
residential real estate investments over more than six decades, was
a noted benefactor of Columbia Law School, from which he graduated
in 1928. He was a founding member of the law firm of Marshal,
Bratter, Greene, Allison &AMP; Tucker of Manhattan and a principal
owner of the Carlyle Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   A gift from Greene this year of more than $5 million enabled the
law school to complete renovations to its main building at 116th
Street and Amsterdam Avenue, as part of a $50 million construction
campaign. The building, was named Greene Hall in honor of the
donor. The renovations, scheduled for completion on Aug. 1, include
the creation of new faculty and administrative offices and a new
faculty library, lounge and conference rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Greene was chairman of the board of the Hirshhorn Museum at the
Smithsonian Institution in Washington and was a supporter of many
of New York's medical and cultural institutions. His gifts to
Montefiore Medical Center helped the construction of the Jerome L.
and Dawn Greene Medical Arts Pavilion and the Children's Hospital
of Montefiore Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-story Medical Arts Pavilion in the Norwood section of
the Bronx is the centerpiece of Montefiore's ambulatory care
network. ``This is a hospital with a social conscience, caring for
the poor and the underprivileged,'' Greene said at dedication
ceremonies on Oct. 3, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   His many philanthropic interests embraced the arts and included
the Vivian Beaumont Theater, Lincoln Center, WNET/Channel 13 and
the Juilliard School.
</P>
<P>
   ``His favorite composer was Mozart, so he underwrote the Mostly
Mozart Festival at Lincoln Center,'' said his wife, Dawn Greene.
``He loved those concerts.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by a daughter, Patricia
Humphrey of Concord, N.H.; a stepdaughter, Christina McInerney of
Manhattan, and two grandchildren. Another daughter of Greene's,
Cynthia-Sue Greene, predeceased him.
</P>
</TEXT>
