<HEADLINE>
EIGHTH-GRADERS IN NEW YORK TO TAKE TURN AT NEW TESTS
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With students, educators, parents and elected
officials still smarting from the abysmal results on New York
state's new fourth-grade English test, thousands children across
the state will begin a new round of similar testing this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday and Wednesday, about 240,000 eighth-graders will take
the new language arts test, which for the first time goes beyond
multiple-choice answers and requires written essays in response to
questions about complex passages of literature, poetry and
nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday and Friday, they will be tested in math, which for
the first time will require them to explain in writing how they
arrived at answers. Each day's test will last about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   And if the fourth-grade English test was not challenging enough,
about 210,000 fourth-graders will be tested in math over three
days, beginning Wednesday, for 45 minutes a day.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Mills, the state education commissioner who imposed the
new tests with the approval of the Board of Regents, and schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew urged test takers not to be disheartened by
results released last week. Two-thirds of the city's 75,000
fourth-graders failed to meet strict new reading and writing
standards. Statewide, about half the pupils passed the test, which
was administered in January.
</P>
<P>
   The scores prompted a loud public outcry from elected officials,
including New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who called for the
ouster of principals at poorly performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   But Mills emphasized that the higher standards were important.
``Youngsters who are going to be taking the tests need to know that
this is designed to help,'' he said. ``Everyone wants them to be
able to read and write well and know a lot of math. We need to know
how much they know. They should relax and know that the adults will
take care of the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   The adults in at least one of the city's 32 districts, however,
appeared more nervous than the students.
</P>
<P>
   When a classroom of eighth-graders at Roberto Clemente
Intermediate School in District 5 in Harlem announced that they
were not nervous, the principal, Aura Rivera, piped up with a laugh
to announce that she was. District 5 is one of the lowest
performing districts in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do well, I do well,'' Ms. Rivera said to the students,
who only moments before were hovering over sample English tests.
``We'll know we're doing our jobs and that you're ready for high
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxim Daniels, 14, a tall, athletic-looking boy dressed in a
white jersey and baggy jeans, explained that he was calm because he
was well prepared. He was one of about 100 eighth-graders at the
school who participated in two-hour after-school programs to
prepare for the test. The sessions, which began in November and
ended last week, met from 2:45 to 4:45 p.m. on Tuesdays, Wednesdays
and Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We read and talk about writing,'' Maxim said. ``We talk about
how we're supposed to write beginnings and conclusions, discuss the
purpose of writing and talk about the importance of understanding
what we're reading.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you know what's important?'' Ms. Rivera asked,
referring to passages like the ones that will be on the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first two sentences have some very important facts in
them,'' Maxim said, prompting Ms. Rivera to applaud. ``But you
don't tune out after that, because the other sentences have
supporting details.''
</P>
<P>
   The new test is full of concepts like ``supporting details,''
``the main idea'' and ``topic sentences.'' The old test simply
required students to read short passages and fill in missing words.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare students for the test, the school stepped up teacher
training in reading and math, Ms. Rivera said. The school focused,
in part, on diagramming stories and mathematical problems, which is
similar to sentence diagramming in that it picks something apart,
to help students' comprehension, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Results from the test will not affect a student's promotion to
the next grade this year because scores will not be released until
September, said Roseanne DeFabio, the state's assistant
commissioner for curriculum, instruction and assessment. Instead,
eighth-grade promotion will depend on grades, citywide test scores
and attendance, she said. The fourth-grade English scores will not
be used to fail students this year, either, but Crew has said that
the test will be one of several criteria next year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even before the release of the fourth-graders' test results,
educators had not expected high scores. Historically, students have
performed poorly on newly imposed standardized tests, especially
those with higher standards, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-grade test, created by CTB/McGraw-Hill, was developed
to set new, higher standards for reading and writing in an effort
to help prepare children for graduation requirements being phased
in during the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   A model being closely watched by educators across the country,
the test reflects standards and a curriculum developed by
committees of teachers in the last several years.
</P>
</TEXT>
