<HEADLINE>
HOMEOWNERS GROUPS UNDER THE GUN ON CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS FISCUS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ When a Phoenix man was shot in the back at a party, he
believed the shooter wasn't the only one to blame. He successfully
sued the condominium association where it happened, saying it knew
there was a need for added security.
</P>
<P>
   Another Phoenix association now is being sued after its added
security backfired.
</P>
<P>
   If a gang known for crime routinely hangs out in a common area
but a homeowners association cuts back on security to save money,
can it be sued if there is a crime? Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Valley of the Sun, as the Phoenix area is known, and
across the country, community associations are vogue. But when
crime happens on their turf, these groups are becoming targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Courts all across the country are starting to hold community
associations liable,'' says Beth Mulcahy, a Phoenix attorney who
represents more than 150 community associations _ which include
planned communities, condo communities and homeowners associations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``And when I say liable, I'm talking to the tune of $10
million, $5 million, $500,000 for inadequate security.''
</P>
<P>
   A Manhattan woman was grabbed in her condo complex, taken to the
rooftop and attacked. She sued the complex for $15 million, saying
security was lax.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas woman raped in her complex sued her association and
received $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts firm Liability Consultants Inc. examined nine
years of recent lawsuits against community associations and the
like. The average jury verdict for inadequate security: $3.35
million. The average out-of-court settlement: $546,000.
</P>
<P>
   GROUPS HAVE A DUTY
</P>
<P>
   ``Associations have a duty to keep their properties safe,'' she
said. ``Are you taking steps to increase security? Are you
proactive? If you knew there was a rape, did you notify the
membership?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No'' is a common answer to those questions for many
associations, she says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Some associations are getting the message. And insurance
policies. And legal advice.
</P>
<P>
   The courts ``definitely woke up a lot of communities,'' says
Mike Mielke, a member of the local Community Association Institute.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Boards of 10 or 15 years ago, they worked from emotion and
basically shot from the hip. Today, the boards have to be more
sophisticated, do more research . . . and they have to get legal
opinions. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Are there transients, are there drug problems? Even if you
hire a security guard, is that enough? A situation where an
association hires a guard then stops using him and something
happens, can that come back to haunt you?''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1997, the Arizona Supreme Court made what Mulcahy
calls a landmark decision regarding an association's responsibility
to make common areas reasonably safe.
</P>
<P>
   The case was ``Martinez V. Woodmar IV Condominiums Homeowners
Association.'' &QL; 
PARTY GUEST SHOT &QL; 
Carlos Martinez was a guest at a party. During the party, Martinez
and two others went to the parking lot to check on their cars and
found gang members around one of the cars. There was an altercation
and as Martinez ran away, he was shot in the back.
</P>
<P>
   The condominium association employed a security guard who
patrolled the area, and he usually dispersed the gang members. But
the Martinez shooting happened about an hour before the guard came
on duty.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez sued, saying the association knew gangs were using the
parking lot for drug deals and other crimes and had been warned
about the need for more security. The Arizona Supreme Court ruled
that an association must maintain common areas to make them
reasonably safe and to take reasonable steps to prevent danger on
the land it controls.
</P>
<P>
   There are no other reported cases so far in Arizona dealing with
the security liability issue, says attorney Curtis Ekmark, who
specializes in community associations.
</P>
<P>
   Ekmark is defending an association in a case that he says
illustrates the problems Arizona groups are having in dealing with
the ``Martinez'' ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kester v. Vista de Oeste'' is pending in Arizona's Maricopa
County Superior Court. &QL; 
RISKS OF ADDED SECURITY
</P>
<P>
   Vista de Oeste is a &UR; west Phoenix townhouse complex that hired
off-duty police officers for added security. Ekmark said one of the
association member's kids aimed a laser pointer at the officers;
unsure if it was a weapon, the officers pulled their guns and
detained the child at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The association now is being sued for emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   If there weren't off-duty police used, ``then people would
complain that there was not enough security,'' says Ekmark, a
partner in the law firm Ekmark and Ekmark. The association hired
the off-duty police, ``but then they get sued.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the problems are in low-income areas, he adds, ``and
those are the associations that don't have the money'' for added
security measures. ``It's not that they don't care. It's that they
don't have the money to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a question of where to draw the line.
</P>
<P>
   DIG A MOAT &QL; 
``Do you put a moat and machine-gun turret around the complex?''
Ekmark asked. ``A lot of associations are trying to come to grips
with `Martinez.' '' &QL; 
Community associations are non-profit corporations governed by
individual members elected by their peers. People automatically
become members when purchasing a home in the association.
</P>
<P>
   Mulcahy recommends that the associations take steps such as
adding electronic gates or surveillance cameras, or using security
patrols and screening employees for criminal records.
</P>
<P>
   She also recommends that board members not misrepresent the
level of security that exists, and that they notify residents if
problems occur.
</P>
<P>
   The court rulings have struck a nerve with community
associations, Mielke says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more talk today about thefts, drugs, muggings, rapes.
Now, I've seen committees formed to talk about it, about using
off-duty police, about notifying the neighborhood,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Says Phil Zeni, former president of the Montiel Homeowners
Association near 16th Street and Glendale Avenue, ``Anytime there
was anything minor, we got on the phone and called everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   They also trimmed back trees and bushes, started newsletters and
crossed their fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this litigious society, anybody who has more than $25 can
go file a lawsuit and decide they can try to take away the net
worth of anybody that's on their radar screen,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Associations have to walk carefully, he says, because any
decision ``can come back to haunt you.'' &QL; 
Chris Fiscus can be reached at (602) 444-7942 or at
chris.fiscus(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
