<HEADLINE>
A MODERATE MONTH OF MAY FOR THE NEW YORK REGION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Has it been your sense that this has been an
extraordinary month of May, an uncommon string of lovely days and
delightful nights capping a spring of phenomenal pleasantness?
</P>
<P>
   You're right.
</P>
<P>
   And wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It has been awfully nice. But according to Stephen Fybish, a
free-lance weather statistic fanatic who lives on the Upper West
Side, the most striking thing about this month has been its
normality.
</P>
<P>
   How moderate was it? Well, until a trio of sultry days arrived
in town for the Memorial Day weekend, the temperature had been
within five degrees of normal every day of this month, Fybish
reported. When the mercury in Central Park reached 85 on Saturday
(it hit 88 Sunday), it was the latest in the year that the
temperature had first topped 80 since 1928.
</P>
<P>
   You want to talk frighteningly pleasant? There were only seven
days with measurable rainfall this month, the fewest since 1970,
Fybish said. But it has not been dangerously dry. In fact, total
rainfall for the month _ 4.04 inches, most of which fell on just
two days _ is just about average.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Gadomski, a meteorologist at Pennsylvania State University,
agreed with Fybish's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you get a month that's average as a result of
extremes,'' Gadomski said. ``This May has tended to not stray
awfully far off the mark. It has been just about as benign a month
as you could ask for this time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   April, by comparison, was lousy. Despite 12 rainy days, there
were only 1.93 inches of rain last month, the third-lowest amount
since 1963. No fun for either the farmer or the sun worshiper.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's miniature heat wave, a sort of last-minute
browning to caramelize the month's sweetness, will continue for at
least another day or two, Gadomski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time Tuesday and Wednesday roll around, it will be
sufficiently moist that the specter of afternoon thunderstorms will
start to enter the forecast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fybish is hoping for a high of at least 85 Monday. If that
happens, he said, it will be the first time in the relatively short
history of Memorial Day weekends that the temperature topped 85
degrees on all the days. ``Whatever this month has had, it managed
to wind up on a positive note,'' he said. ``There's a lot of
emotional investment in that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
