<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TRAVEL-AGENCIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG CITY: THE TOURISTS ARE REPLACED BY REFUGEES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After two months of NATO bombing, the National
Tourism Organization of Serbia remains unbowed. It still maintains
a Web site offering cheery exhortations like, ``Come! In Serbia
something's always at the height of the season.'' The English is
not always perfect _ ``Roam through Serbia! You won't loose your
way'' _ but the enthusiasm is unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although more than 40 different nations live in Serbia, they
do have some things in common _ their homes are wide open to
friends,'' the tourist agency explains. ``Wherever you go in the
country painted in heart, large quantities of openheartedness and
smile are served, free of charge. Let's not forget something else.
In a Serb home, the best room, the largest slice of bread and the
kindest word have always been reserved for the guest or weary
traveler.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words inspired a disgusted sigh from Muzafere Beka on
Friday afternoon in the Bronx. ``Serbia is a factory of lies,'' she
said, sitting at her desk during another quiet day at the Kosova
Travel Agency. Kosova is the Albanian term for Kosovo, the native
soil of Mrs. Beka and many of her neighbors in the Albanian enclave
near Pelham Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs' homes are always open?'' she said. ``Yes, you stay
with them, you eat with them, you drink with them _ then they stab
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily at this time of year, Mrs. Beka would not have time
to contemplate tourist propaganda. She would be too busy booking
flights home for Albanian expatriates. ``This should be our high
season,' she said. ``In the summer, parents take their children
home to see relatives and learn about their heritage. But this year
_ nothing. No one goes to Kosova, of course. Everyone is running
out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Beka, who is 45, made her exit 13 years ago. ``To tell you
the truth, I just got sick and tired of the Serbs,'' she said. ``If
you are not their kind of people, you cannot remain. My husband and
I saw there was no future for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Abandoning her career as a civil engineer in Kosovo, Mrs. Beka
moved to the Bronx and worked for six years as a cleaning woman.
``Seven days a week I did work, in the day cleaning apartments, in
the evening cleaning garbage at offices,'' she said. ``I don't know
what welfare is. I never used this country. God bless America.
Nobody in America ever said, `You are Albanian, you cannot do that
job.'''
</P>
<P>
   The earnings helped send her two daughters to college and
provide start-up capital for the travel agency. The business grew
by catering to Albanians living in the Bronx and in the Glendale
section of Queens, where there was another office. It was managed
by her husband, Bashkim, who had been a doctor in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Then once again their careers fell victim to Serbian-Albanian
tensions. Business fell off so much in the last year that the
Queens office was closed several months ago, and Mrs. Beka is not
sure how much longer she can afford to keep open the Bronx office,
at 782 Lydig Avenue. But she doesn't like to discuss these
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am ashamed to be mentioning business when people are
dying,'' she said. ``First we worry about these Albanian people who
are refugees. Their life is hell.'' Mrs. Beka is expecting some
refugees this week: 10 relatives, who will be moving in with the
six people already living in their three-bedroom, one-bathroom
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God they got out,'' she said. ``We still don't know
anything about my brother's son. He and his wife were in
Montenegro. If the Serbs did anything to them. ...'' Mrs. Beka's
eyes misted for a moment. Then she lighted a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm smoking two, three packs a day,'' she said. ``I don't
sleep until 3 or 4 o'clock in the morning. There is so much to
think about: my family there, my family here, the political
situation there, the business here. I try not to worry. I tell my
kids when anything in life approaches you, you cannot stop and cry.
You have to fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
