u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FIRE-CAREERCHANGES     05-31 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FIRE-CAREERCHANGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING A DIFFERENT BATTLE, AGAINST FIRE INSTEAD OF CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It takes courage to stare down a suspect with a gun.
Does it take a different but equally impressive burst of bravery to
storm into a tenement awash in flames?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not why Brian Connolly, a highly decorated 11-year
police veteran who had risen to the rank of sergeant, says he
traded in his holster for a hose earlier this month and became a
firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something I always wanted, from the time I was a kid,''
said Connolly, who remembers the neighborhood firehouse, Engine Co.
308 on Lefferts Boulevard in Queens, as one of the hearths of his
childhood. ``Even when we were little, they were good to us. They
used to fix our bikes.''
</P>
<P>
   John Marsich, a firefighter with Ladder Co. 29 in the South
Bronx, spent 12 years as a patrolman before choosing a new job
three years ago, in part because he was disappointed with his old
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the police department, you can get jammed up for
anything,'' said Marsich, 35, who had patrolled two Bronx precincts
and left on good terms. ``You never got an `attaboy.' But you
always heard about it if you screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Connolly and Marsich are two of the 339 police officers, some of
them veterans with more than 10 years on the force, who have moved
over to the fire department in the last four years. Thirty-one
people, roughly 21 percent, of the 150 who graduated from the Fire
Academy with Connolly this month are former police officers,
including another sergeant. Connolly took a $15,000-a-year pay cut
to make the career change.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, police officers have migrated to the fire
department for an armload of different reasons, city officials
said. It happens in cycles, they said, and the cycle is on an
upswing. Three years ago, for example, the percentage of former
police officers in Fire Academy classes ran as low as 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For many police officers accustomed to the grind of a five-day
work week, the chief attraction of the firefighting life is the
opportunity to work 24-hour tours and have longer stretches of time
off.
</P>
<P>
   But several firefighters said they were also motivated by a
feeling that they had been unappreciated as police officers, often
suffering blame as a group for individual incidents, like the
shooting of Amadou Diallo, an unarmed man killed by police officers
in February.
</P>
<P>
   As firefighters, they said they felt admired again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have continued on happily in the police department for
20 years,'' said Robert Mahon of Ladder Co. 35 in Manhattan, who
left the police force two years ago. ``I wasn't running away from
it, but I felt like the public was very reactionary. Whenever a
police officer did something, all 30,000 cops were affected, and
you would have to listen to the public sentiments as if it was you
who did it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to measure how many officers are interested in
moving to the fire department, because the city does not track the
number who take the fire test. It records only the number who are
ultimately hired, so it is hard to say whether more officers are
now interested in firefighting jobs or just better at securing
them.
</P>
<P>
   But firefighters say interest has increased. Michael Carter, a
vice president with the Uniformed Firefighters Association,
estimated that almost every fire company in the city has three or
four police veterans. In one South Bronx firehouse shared by Engine
Co. 45 and Ladder Co. 58, there are 15 former police officers among
the 50 firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first question you are asked when you come through that
door as a probie,'' a probationary firefighter, ``is, `Are you an
ex-cop?''' said Thomas Dunn, who spent five years on the police
force and has been a firefighter for 10.
</P>
<P>
   Ranking police officers who make the switch can suffer cuts in
pay, as Connolly did. But patrolmen who make the move receive the
same salary, because of the pay parity between the two departments.
They also retain all their seniority and pension benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Several former police officers said they were drawn to the fire
department by a sense of teamwork that they had found missing in
the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Marsich said he noted the difference after a serious fire in the
Bronx several years ago where the firefighting effort had not gone
smoothly. A gas line exploded, and several firefighters, he said,
were blown down a flight of stairs and onto the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``A two-star chief came into quarters and everyone spoke openly
about what they would have done differently,'' he recalled. ``In
the police department, there was a saying: `Loose lips sink ships.'
People would never own up to a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, like most of the men who have fought both fires and crime,
said they required equal doses of daring. But Dunn, who has
received medals for valor in both jobs, noted that it was not
always the same type of courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear as a cop is your enemy,'' he said. ``You need to react.
On the fire department, fear can be your friend, because it can
help you have respect for the situation you are going into.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
