<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7040 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     05-31 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDY IS DAMAGED GOODS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's edition of The Sporting Muse, which never runs out of
gas:
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has run out of gas sometime in their driving career,
but that doesn't mean everyone knows how Robby Gordon felt Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Indy 500 remains racing nirvana for most drivers, so to lead
the race with mere laps remaining and then have the car go silent
for a lack of fuel is the epitome of exasperation. Especially when
you've hurdled as many barriers as Gordon has.
</P>
<P>
   The Cerritos-born Gordon, an off-road driving champ as a
teenager, finished third at the Long Beach Grand Prix in 1994 and
followed that with a fifth at Indy. In 1995, he won his first two
CART races and finished fifth again at Indy. He had every reason to
believe he'd have several more opportunities to improve on those
fifths.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the last Indy race featuring the Championship Auto
Racing Teams (CART) drivers. The snit between the driving teams and
Speedway President Tony George -- George essentially locked out the
major racing teams and started his own circuit featuring what
ostensibly are replacement drivers -- has soiled the 500 and forced
a lot of drivers, like Gordon, into painful corners.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon stayed true to CART in 1996 but suffered a subpar season.
In 1997, he jumped to the NASCAR circuit except for two open-wheel
races -- Indy, where his car and suit caught fire, and the
inaugural Fontana CART race, where he finished eighth. He returned
to CART at mid-season in 1998 and drove well.
</P>
<P>
   But the Indy pull was strong enough for Gordon and several old
racing friends to create their own team for 1999. As the only
owner-driver on the circuit, he eliminated the either-or policy
that vexes other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   An Indy win Sunday would have been an amazing achievement of
racing independence for someone who never runs away from
challenges. Perhaps that explains why he said that Sunday's result
was more crushing than 1997, when he suffered major burns on his
legs. ...
</P>
<P>
   For the millions who watch one auto race a year, the Indy 500 is
still fine entertainment. But considering the growth of auto racing
the last decade, Indy is soiled goods.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR has become a sports monster and the best open-wheel
drivers run CART. The Indy Racing League created by George is like
AAA baseball. There will always be driving errors and crashes in
the sport, but those at the Indy 500 are borne of inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   There were two major pit accidents at Indy Sunday. Eli Salazar,
as an example, has crashed in three of his four Indy 500 starts as
an IRL regular. There was more driving and less racing at Indy
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Foyt's return to the winner's circle as a team owner was a
beneficent moment for Indy. But how many people watching knew it
was somewhat hollow, that Foyt was one of the few names in racing
who cast his lot with George? ...
</P>
<P>
   The choice of cheering for the Pacers or the Knicks was an easy
one. How insufferable will New Yorkers be should their team go from
eighth in the eight-team Eastern Conference draw to the finals?
</P>
<P>
   But there's a second good reason to favor the Pacers. An
appearance in the finals would give former UCLA star Reggie Miller
some of the recognition that has evaded him over a 12-year career.
</P>
<P>
   The spindly and mouthy Miller has been one of the league's
premier shooters during an era where shooting has become a lost
art. He's the NBA's career leader in three-point shots taken and
made, he stands fifth among active players in points, and he's
playing in his fourth Eastern Conference final in the last six
years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Reggie has only been named to four all-star games, and has
been a third-team all league choice just three times. Coming into
this season, Miller had missed just 20 games due to injury over 11
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana lost all three of those previous Eastern Conference
finals in seven games, and each seventh game came on the road. This
is the first time Indy can count on game seven being at home
(although they already blew one home game with Sunday's loss).
</P>
<P>
   Miller's career has always been star-crossed. He was a prep star
in Riverside, but it took him awhile to sneak out from under the
shadow of his sister, Cheryl.
</P>
<P>
   His college days came during one of the funkier eras of Bruin
basketball. The Bruins lost seven of their last 11 games in 1984,
his freshman season. In 1985, the Bruins failed to beat USC at
least once for the first time since 1942. They won the NIT, but
that was a rather ignominious achievement.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Miller averaged 25.9 points a game, second all-time in
UCLA lore to Kareem Abdul-Jabbar. But the Bruins saw their 52-game
winning streak against Cal get snapped, and then they lost in the
first round of the NIT to UC Irvine. In 1987, Miller and the Bruins
won the Pac-10 but lost in the second round of the NCAA tournament
to Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The Miller of today looks, acts and plays just like the Miller
of UCLA, only with more confidence in his shot and more diligence
on defense. It would be nice to see Miller get a shot in the
finals. ...
</P>
<P>
   It might be time for a recount of the NBA's Top 50, named during
the league's 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Of the ten active players named in '96, six have not won a NBA
title. Only two of those six are still playing in '99, David
Robinson and Patrick Ewing. Three of the other four aren't likely
to get another shot (Charles Barkley, Karl Malone and John
Stockton). Shaquille O'Neal, alas, will have many.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 40 retired players named to that roster, only four failed
to win a title -- Dave Bing, George Gervin, Pete Maravich and Nate
Thurmond. Lenny Wilkens didn't win a title as a player but won one
as a coach. Elgin Baylor started the 1972 title season with the
Lakers but retired early in the season because of injuries. He got
a ring.
</P>
<P>
   The placement of Shaq and Robinson on the team looks specious
now, especially when you consider some of the fellows who won
multiple titles -- Joe Dumars, Dennis Rodman (five rings), Dennis
Johnson (titles with two different teams) and Horace Grant (four
finals appearances). ...
</P>
<P>
   Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy looks like he last slept in 1993.
I'd say the Phil Jackson rumors are affecting him, but he looked
like that when he got the Knicks job. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
