<SLUG> BC-CUNY-BADILLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI NAMES BADILLO, CRITIC OF CUNY, AS ITS CHAIRMAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gov. George Pataki has named Herman Badillo, a sharp
critic of the the City University of New York and a primary force
behind efforts to change it, as its next chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment gives Badillo, 69, a lawyer who has been CUNY's
vice chairman and a close ally of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the
opportunity to shape one of New York City's most important
educational institutions, one with 200,000 students, at a time of
enormous ferment. He will also be able to fill many top positions
that are now open at the university and its 17 undergraduate
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Like many public urban universities, CUNY draws many students
who are not viewed as prime college material: welfare mothers,
immigrants who speak little or no English, students from inner-city
neighborhoods who have little to show for their high school years.
</P>
<P>
   And at a time of budget cutting and a renewed focus on
standards, the education of these students has become a hotly
debated issue.
</P>
<P>
   Many CUNY traditionalists say that the university must not
abandon its mission to admit all students and try to help them. But
Badillo and other critics, including the mayor and governor, have
long accused CUNY of squandering its resources on weak students who
never graduate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question in my mind that CUNY needs reform,''
Pataki said in a telephone interview Sunday. ``Herman Badillo has a
knowledge of the system, he's a product of the system and he has a
vision for the system. That all made it plain that he's the man to
reform CUNY.''
</P>
<P>
   To achieve that reform, CUNY's critics say, the university must
set higher admissions standards to encourage applicants to work
harder in high school, push students to complete remedial work and
earn degrees more quickly, and establish tougher requirements for
graduation so that a CUNY degree will be more respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure that the value of the City University
diploma is accepted anywhere in New York City or the world,''
Badillo said. ``That is my goal.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics of Badillo's efforts to transform CUNY expressed
alarm at his appointment, which was first reported Sunday in The
New York Daily News, and said it would result in further disarray.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the fox guards the chickens, you don't expect to have
anything left except skin and bones,'' said Sandi E. Cooper a CUNY
history professor and former chairwoman of its faculty senate.
</P>
<P>
   Edward C. Sullivan, chairman of the state Assembly's Committee
on Higher Education, called the appointment an insult. ``The CUNY
board is in chaos, so why would the governor want to reward the
purveyor of chaos?'' he ased.
</P>
<P>
   And Robert Hollander, a CUNY graduate student and adjunct
professor, said he viewed Badillo as ``CUNY's worst enemy,''
someone who did not appreciate CUNY's mission to provide both
access and excellence to students.
</P>
<P>
   Badillo said his intention was not to harm the university, but
to improve it. ``I have no desire to curtail its traditional
function as a gateway for the poor, but to do it even better,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
