<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-AFTERMATH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENT RETURNS HOME TO THE BLOODY AFTERMATH OF A DEADLY
STANDOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELLIS E. CONKLIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHORELINE, Wash. _ His eyes red and stinging from lingering tear
gas fumes, Fred Westphal Sunday pointed to the blood-soaked sheets
crumpled on his son's bed.
</P>
<P>
   It was near that bed, he said, that 21-year-old Lonnie Davis
stood Friday afternoon, gasping for breath through a shattered
window as he made his last furious stand before a police sniper
killed him with a single bullet to the head.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Westphal returned for the first time to the four-bedroom
home he's rented for the past 11 years. He came to collect a few
personal belongings, clothes for the next few days, favorite items
for the children. He came to look for a family pet, a black
Scottish Terrier, which fled the house and cannot be found.
</P>
<P>
   But even late Sunday afternoon, two days after the shootout,
Westphal could not stay inside the home for more than a few minutes
without having to step outside for fresh air. Fumes from the tear
gas police fired into the house cling to the rugs and draperies,
and seem to have permeated the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place is uninhabitable,'' Westphal whispered as he sipped
from a can of 7-Up and gathered up some clothing for his wife and
three sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can live here any longer. We'll never live here
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The walls are riddled with bullets, some of them fist-sized
punctures where the tear gas cannisters came blasting in last
Friday before the nearly six-hour-long standoff came to a fatal
end.
</P>
<P>
   Blood is smeared on the white linoleum kitchen floor where glass
is scattered. Some of those shards have come to rest atop the
unwashed breakfast dishes. There is more blood in the hallway where
family photographs hang askew.
</P>
<P>
   Ransacked drawers and overturned tables are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The pale green walls of a child's bedroom are smeared with red.
</P>
<P>
   A cool afternoon breeze flows through the dozens of holes in the
sliding glass doors looking out on a wooden deck. The glass shower
stall is in a thousand pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' rampage began at about noon Friday at his family's home
in Brier, where Brier police say he fatally stabbed his mother,
Shelia Lindsey, 46, and 18-month old nephew Kahari Prince with a
small kitchen knife.
</P>
<P>
   He fled in his mother's car, smashed into a motorcyclist on
Interstate 5 and scaled a retaining wall, ending up in Westphal's
quiet, tree-lined neighborhood. There, he killed 63-year-old Erma
Spence with a garden hoe as she worked in her yard and seriously
injured 82-year-old Irene Hilton before barricading himself inside
Westphal's home. Hilton was in serious condition yesterday with a
broken neck.
</P>
<P>
   The nighmarish day began for Westphal as he turned his car
toward home about 3:15 p.m. Friday, tired from a day on the Boeing
777 production line in Everett. Police turned him away at Fifth
Avenue and Northeast 195th Street, just a few blocks from his house
in the 19000 block of Seventh Avenue Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal was not listening to the radio and had no idea what was
going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd go pick up my 10-year-old and we'd go out for
ice cream or something,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   But he would quickly discover that his 10-year-old was one of
400 North City Elementary School students who had been kept at the
school as the shootout unfolded just across the freeway from the
Westphal home.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal went to find a pay phone and called his wife at work to
tell her that police were everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something's going on in our neighborhood,' I told her. She was
watching the news. She just told me to turn on the TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed, he went to a nearby friend's house to find out where
his 14- and 16-year-old boys were. He was relieved to learn they
had gone to a friend's home in Richmond Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``So at least I knew all the children were accounted for.''
</P>
<P>
   At 4 p.m., Westphal watched the standoffunfold on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were all these helicopters circling around and showing
my house, and I said, `That's my house!' Then the thought hit me _
I have guns! So I called 911 and said, `There are guns in there.
Get your officers out of the way.'''
</P>
<P>
   Before it was over, Davis fired dozens of rounds from those
guns. Police found nearly two dozen bullet holes in two police
cars. A King County sheriff's deputy Diana Russell, suffered a
fractured skull after being hit with flying glass during the
standoff. She was in satisfactory condition Sunday at Harborview
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal stressed Sunday that he's a gun collector only.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a gun nut and I'm not into the militia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There were eight guns, all of them in Westphal's bedroom and out
in the open. There was also 150 rounds of ammunition, Westphal
said. Some of the guns included a .45-caliber semiautomatic
handgun, a 20-gauge shotgun, and one 12-gauge shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   After Westphal called 911, police ordered him to immediately
come to the Shoreline Command Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``In hindsight, it was a mistake (to leave the guns out in full
display),'' Westphal said. ``I should have completely disabled
those guns.''
</P>
<P>
   But Westphal quickly added that he never worried about the
potential dangers, even with three sons in the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids have all fired them and they know about the damage
they can do, and that they're not toys,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   At about 11:30 p.m. Friday, after the ordeal had been over for
hours, Westphal was permitted to come to the house to pick up his
dogs. He found his dachshund and the fox terrier hiding in the back
yard, but couldn't find his 8-year-old Scottish terrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea where he is. We need help in finding him.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said his boys are all traumatized and are staying with
friends. He and his wife plan to spend the next few days with
Westphal's father in West Seattle while they try to find another
place to rent.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said he's tried with no avail to find his landlord and
tell him what happened, and that he's moving out.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm not sure anyone can live here again,'' Westphal said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 0040EDT &QL; 
