<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAYANNE-POP-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAYANNE: A SLICK PACKAGE, A LIMITED VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To many of his new fans it seems that Ricky Martin,
the Puerto Rican pop sensation, came out of nowhere. He didn't. He
is simply the English-speaking point man for a Latin pop-star
system that has long been manufacturing hits and stealing hearts
across the Spanish-speaking world.
</P>
<P>
   Chayanne, one of Martin's rivals, brought his own stage
spectacle to the Theater at Madison Square Garden on Friday night.
Tall, dark and square-jawed with a boyish smile, Chayanne sang and
danced through a decade's worth of hits, with excerpts from his
video clips projected overhead.
</P>
<P>
   His songs, unsurprisingly, are vows of love: love that
overpowers him, desire that spikes his adrenaline, passion that
could make him sacrifice everything. He pleads for a kiss, for a
caress, for just a glance. Onstage, the women are more accessible
than they are in the songs; two blonde dancers twirled into his
arms and lingered for some bump and grind.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old Chayanne has spent the last 20 years as an
entertainer, first with Los Chicos, a Puerto Rican teen-age vocal
group, and then in a thriving solo career. He drew notice outside
that Latin world as the lead, opposite Vanessa L. Williams, in the
1998 film ``Dance With Me''; he also recorded a duet with her. But
he is not pitching himself to the U.S. mainstream yet. On Friday he
spoke English for just a few moments.
</P>
<P>
   Chayanne's generation of Latin pop singers is internationalist,
not letting traditionalism or local pride turn away potential hit
songs. He'll take a groove or a melody from anywhere: plena from
Puerto Rico, zouk from Martinique, axe from Brazil, merengue from
the Dominican Republic. And his band is equally capable of playing
a guajira or a power ballad. In ``Solamente Tu Amor'' Chayanne
could have been a Spanish-speaking George Michael; in ``Mira Ven
Ven'' the band fused blues-rock with mambo.
</P>
<P>
   As a singer, Chayanne is limited; his voice is sweet but
shallow, and he shows no inclination to improvise. But his job is
to put a pleasing face on a slick pop package, and on Friday the
shrieks that greeted every twitch of Chayanne's hips attested to
how well he was doing it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 0041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GISELLE-BALLET-REVIEW     05-31 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GISELLE-BALLET-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GISELLE': SPLENDID DANCING FROM CORPS AND PRINCIPALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not everyone was at the beach over the weekend. The
hot ticket at American Ballet Theater, which drew packed houses at
the Metropolitan Opera House, was ``Giselle'' in its first three
performances of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely has this beloved 19th-century ballet seen such a
concentration of splendid dancing from the corps and from a
succession of peasant heroines betrayed each time by an
aristocratic seducer. Viviana Durante, a guest from the Royal
Ballet in Britain, made her New York debut as Giselle on Saturday
night, and through the amazing power of her technique's
expressiveness, she triumphed along with her Albrecht, a fiercely
romantic Jose Manuel Carreno.
</P>
<P>
   The difference was in the details in each cast. At the Saturday
matinee Julio Bocca, stepping in as Albrecht for the injured Angel
Corella, brought his passion and bravura to complement Ashley
Tuttle's purity as Giselle. They met on the same high level,
although they approached the ballet from opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Kent and Vladimir Malakhov, by contrast, were in total
stylistic and dramatic harmony on Friday night, offering an
extraordinary depth that elevated this ``Giselle'' to one of the
best in years. Ms. Kent and Malakhov gave this epitome of a
romantic ballet a visual and emotional beauty rooted in classical
style. Verismo was banished from their acting, but expressiveness
through form was always present.
</P>
<P>
   There was the magic flow of a waking dream to their story of
love and betrayal, which made the drama unfold with unusual
inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   Tales of remorse and regeneration are the signature of the
romantic era, and ``Giselle'' comes alive only if these themes are
made believable to a modern audience. At its most superficial,
``Giselle,'' which had its premiere in Paris in 1841, can
degenerate into mere prettiness. Yet in its dichotomy between a
realistic first act among German villagers and the formal but even
more dramatic second act, set among wilis, the ghosts of jilted
maidens, the ballet's creators worked on a deeper subliminal level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giselle'' was the brainchild of the French romantic poet
Theophile Gautier, and in these two acts he embodied his theory
about ballet in general. Ballet was, he wrote, ``at once the most
material and ideal of spectacles.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kent and Malakhov, through carefully considered details that
not everyone copied, tilted toward the ideal side, but their
Giselle and Albrecht in Act I were still flesh and blood.
Abandoning the histrionic veneer of last year, Malakhov was all
classical restraint in the broader sense of a classical actor
approaching a romantic role.
</P>
<P>
   A high note was struck early on in the vivid stage business for
Clinton Luckett, as Wilfred, Albrecht's squire, who forcefully
protested his master's plan to disguise himself as a peasant to
seduce Giselle. Malakhov's count was, however, impetuous and used
to being obeyed. Unlike others, his Albrecht gave the audience a
knowing look when he tore off a daisy petal that told Giselle he
loved her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kent's entrance telegraphs a sunny disposition, but her
village girl was essentially shy with eyes downcast. She did not
overdo the moment when she had a faint heart, and there was an
elegance in her solos that matched Malakhov's noble line. Arms
linked, they danced as one.
</P>
<P>
   Giselle's solo in Act I has been simplified in this production,
presumably directly by Kevin McKenzie, the company's artistic
director. Only Ms. Durante ends the solo on the knee, as is
traditional, instead of standing up, and she packs more footwork
into her diagonal of turns. But Ms. Kent had no trouble with the
usual hops on toe, and her mad scene, when Giselle discovers
Albrecht's true identity, was effective in its simplicity, unlike
last year. The flute passages of Adolphe Adam's score were the
wilis' voices, which she heard so visibly in her haunted daze.
</P>
<P>
   Malakhov, ecstatic in the first act, refrained from his own mad
scene. All the more effective was his sudden rage and grief at
Giselle's death. Like Bocca, he was rejected by the villagers and
rushed out. Carreno, on Saturday night, threw himself at Giselle's
body.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the peasant pas de deux in Act I was vibrantly danced
by Yan Chen and Joaquin De Luz. Christine Dunham as Bathilde,
Albrecht's fiancee, distilled a range of emotions in a short time;
she was gracious, haughty and furious.
</P>
<P>
   An important foil to Malakhov was Ethan Brown, who magnificently
made Hilarion, Albrecht's village rival, especially embittered. His
acting and dancing were forceful; enraged in Act I, he was
desperate as the wilis' victim in Act II.
</P>
<P>
   Irina Dvorovenko as Myrta, the Wili Queen, had the high-flying
power and impressive authority to make the role all it should be.
Ms. Kent's wili in Act II was all the more different in its
ethereal grace. Yet this was an assertive ghost, no longer shy, who
pleaded for Albrecht's salvation.
</P>
<P>
   All the romantic images were found in Ms. Kent's solo, but it
was the two duets with Malakhov that gave this performance a
transformative purity. Always stretched in his line during his
partnering, Malakhov kept within a classical framework that carried
over to his solo. Toward the end his image of a spent Albrecht with
long curly hair, supported by Giselle, recalled pictures of
Nijinsky in the same pose.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Durante and Carreno worked in a very different emotional
key, and Ms. Durante's second act was more unusual than her first.
Temperamentally she is an allegro dancer and she darted out in her
first entrance with a swiftness that colored much of her
performance. This was a lively Giselle eager to express her love of
dance, which she did admirably in her big solo in Act I.
</P>
<P>
   The mad scene was strong, incorporating the traditional mime.
This Giselle had chills, imagined a baby she never had and pushed
hysterically through the crowd. Unlike the others, she seemed to
stab herself with Albrecht's sword, which would explain why
Hilarion makes her a cross in Act II. The church would not bury a
suicide in hallowed ground. Two years ago, the lush scenery by
Gianni Quaranta still had a stone cross with her name.
</P>
<P>
   Carreno's Albrecht was commanding but serene. His masculine
grace carried over to his solo in Act II, where he projected the
poetic sensibility of a repentant sinner. Ms. Durante was not a
wafting spirit: through her high extensions, sharp phrasing and
powerful leaps, she was a wili with a human heart who fought for
her man.
</P>
<P>
   Gillian Murphy's debut as Myrta showed technique, especially
leaps, used to expressive purpose, and Olga Yaroslavtzeva's
Bathilde had high drama. John Gardner excelled as a thinking man's
Hilarion, sly and mocking.
</P>
<P>
   An equally exciting performance came from Bocca's experienced
seducer with Ms. Tuttle's innocent but hearty Giselle. Their first
act was playful until Ms. Tuttle's startling mad scene, full of
rage.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of their dancing in Act II set off Sara Mau's fine
and severe Myrta. Rosalie O'Connor was a fun-loving Bathilde whose
world comes crashing down, a counterpart to Giselle. Charles Barker
conducted all three performances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
