</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TCHAIKOVSKY-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TCHAIKOVSKY': GUEST ARTIST PROVED HIMSELF AS EUROPEAN BALLET
PRINCE
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The message of George Balanchine's ``Tchaikovsky
Piano Concerto No. 2,'' presented by the New York City Ballet in an
all-Tchaikovsky program on Thursday night at the New York State
Theater, is that the essence of ballet classicism is a timeless,
simple formal grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   That message was reiterated intriguingly by the performance of
Robert Tewsley, a guest artist, in the male lead role. The
English-trained Tewsley is every inch a European ballet prince.
Royalty rests on his shoulders like a cloak, imbuing his every move
with its silken softness. But there was not a hint of classical
mannerism to his lyrical line or understated but unignorable
presence.
</P>
<P>
   The compelling simplicity of his turns and brise, and his easy,
accommodating partnering of Miranda Weese were a perfect foil for
the slightly subversive wit and musical phrasing of this remarkable
ballerina. Her mix of imperiousness and alert physicality said a
great deal about the immutable nature of classicism. Jennie Somogyi
brought extra authority and quiet pizazz to the second-ballerina
role. But somewhat ragged corps work detracted from the whole.
Cameron Grant was the piano soloist.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the line Balanchine's 1981 ``Mozartiana'' seems
to have changed from whispered prayer to sunny technical showpiece.
Darci Kistler and Philip Neal communicated that latter personality
well, though there were a few mispartnered moments toward the end.
New as the second male lead the always stylish Arch Higgins brought
an agreeable and appropriate astringency to the edgy Gigue.
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine's ``Diamonds'' completed the program. The evening's
conductors were Andrea Quinn and Hugo Fiorato.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
