<HEADER>
A7057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BURGOS-THEATER-REVIEW     05-31 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURGOS-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BURGOS': SWIFTLY PACED AND WELL ACTED
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Puerto Rico, N.Y.)  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(jw) 
 By D.J.R. BRUCKNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Anger belongs in art'' the young Puerto Rican poet Julia de
Burgos tells Pablo Neruda in Carmen Rivera's celebration of her
life and work, ``Julia de Burgos: Child of the Water.'' And in this
woman there was anger enough to fill countless poems. She was born
in Puerto Rico in 1918 and died on a sidewalk in East Harlem in
1953, leaving behind two shipwrecked marriages, the debris of
several disastrous affairs, a blank decade of incurable alcoholism
and three volumes of verse that testify to a fierce struggle to
achieve a magnificent purity and honesty of spirit, emotion and
expression.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rivera has a struggle of her own. In 17 scenes she evokes
the whole complicated life _ in Puerto Rico, Havana, Washington and
New York _ peppering the dialogue with lines from 20 de Burgos
poems and weaving into it many allusions to principal de Burgos
themes, mainly a longing for Puerto Rico's independence and the
identification of it and its people with the waters of one of its
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of the action she also introduces 11 other
characters, making one suspect that at least some of them are there
only to give voice to some of Ms. Rivera's ideas. Her passion for
de Burgos and her work is palpable, but it is doubtful that even a
viewer with extensive knowledge of the life and poetry will leave
this play without some sense of confusion.
</P>
<P>
   In the production by the Puerto Rican Traveling Theater, Manuel
Martin, the director, keeps the action swift, evenly paced and
deliberate, so that no matter how willful or even foolish de Burgos
sometimes seems, the specter of inescapable doom seems to shadow
her throughout. Another specter comes off more believably than
would seem possible. De Burgos famously complained she often seemed
to be two people in one body, and Ms. Rivera gives her two
embodiments: Sol Miranda as the de Burgos everyone else saw and
Lourdes Martin as the shadow de Burgos whom de Burgos battled with
throughout her life.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miranda is pure fire in this role: angry, hurt, petulant,
wildly intelligent, proud and fleeing every moment from fear and
doubt. And Ms. Martin's restraint, slightly perverse seductiveness
and sometimes cruel tongue finally convince one that she is indeed
the obverse image of the poet herself. These two actors richly
deserve the ovations they get.
</P>
<P>
   Performances are in English from Wednesday through Friday and in
Spanish on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `JULIA DE BURGOS'
</P>
<P>
   Child of the Water
</P>
<P>
   By Carmen Rivera; directed by Manuel Martin; sets by Salvatore
Tagliarino; costumes by Harry Nadal; lighting by Alan Baron; sound
engineer, John Sadler; stage manager, Sandra M. Bloom; movement
staging and assistant stage manager, Adolfo Vazquez; translator
(into Spanish), Raul Davila; poet translator, Susanne Cabanas.
Presented by the Puerto Rican Traveling Theater, Miriam
Colon-Valle, artistic director. At 304 W. 47th St., Clinton.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Tony Chiroldes (Pablo Neruda, Publisher, Super and Friend
in Cuba), Mateo Gomez (Juan Bosch and Tito), Lourdes Martin
(Woman), Sol Miranda (Julia), Ricardo Puente (Juan Grullon) and
Puli Toro (Mother, Boss and Stranger).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
