<SLUG> BC-CITATION-QUOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITATIONS GIVEN WITH HONOR, AND, AT TIMES, A LITTLE LEVITY
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Honoris causa means `conferred with honor' and is generally
said before a degree is conferred) 
 (rk) 
 (No byline)  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colleges and universities herald their honorary degree
recipients with a citation _ a brief resume, at times lighthearted,
at times poignant, of an accomplished life. These excerpts are from
citations provided by the institutions. Honoris causa ...
</P>
<P>
   WILKES UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   JANET RENO
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney General
</P>
<P>
   ``Janet Reno, you have combined the wisdom of the Everglades
with the simple majesty of the law in a self-governing nation to
provide a new kind of leadership: calm, balanced and resistant to
unwanted political pressure. Born to a father from Denmark who was
a police reporter with The Miami Herald and to a journalist mother
who was equally at home in a wickiup or at a congressional hearing,
you learned early to express yourself with candor and eloquence.
They would have been less surprised that their oldest daughter
became state attorney of Dade County or the attorney general of the
United States than that you became the first incumbent of either
position to inspire a rap song.''
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   GEENA DAVIS
</P>
<P>
   Actress
</P>
<P>
   ``First came the insect movies. In your first major role, your
lover metamorphosed into the fly; then, to rescue Winona Ryder from
the demon Beetlejuice, you rode on the back of a giant worm.''
</P>
<P>
   LONG ISLAND UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   JULES FEIFFER
</P>
<P>
   Cartoonist
</P>
<P>
   ``You have shown us how dumb we can be.''
</P>
<P>
   EMORY UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   CHARLES R. YATES
</P>
<P>
   Patron, golf enthusiast
</P>
<P>
   ``Drawing on lifelong friendships forged in fairways and greens,
you have helped Emory and the University of St. Andrew's establish
more enduring and satisfying links.''
</P>
<P>
   MANHATTAN COLLEGE
</P>
<P>
   JAMES PATTERSON
</P>
<P>
   Author, former advertising executive
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents both celebrate and lament your successful declaration
that `I'm a Toys ``R'' Us kid.'''
</P>
<P>
   SUSQUEHANNA UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   ALAN R. SHAW
</P>
<P>
   Senior vice president/managing director, Salomon Smith Barney
</P>
<P>
   ``We would love to know how things would have turned out if a
dean here at the end of your freshman year had not noticed that
your grades were not so great and suggested that you consider other
choices than returning for your sophomore year.''
</P>
<P>
   AMHERST COLLEGE
</P>
<P>
   AUGUST WILSON
</P>
<P>
   Playwright
</P>
<P>
   ``Young, gifted, black and poor, you grew up in post-World War
II Pittsburgh, one of six children in a working-class family. You
left high school at 15, when a foolish teacher challenged your
authorship of a precocious paper that, obviously, you had written.
Luckily for the American theater, that teacher's hurtful insult did
not dampen the fires of your enormous talent, nor did it extinguish
your hunger for knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   FRANKLIN PIERCE COLLEGE
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON DUNCAN
</P>
<P>
   Explorer
</P>
<P>
   ``Dayton Duncan has written that the promise of America is to be
free: free to live and free to pursue happiness, and that freedom
is only in the pursuit _ happiness itself isn't part of the promise
and isn't always caught. Like Tocqueville, he understands that the
only way American individuality and freedom can flourish is via the
empowerment that comes through participation of diverse
constituencies in communities.''
</P>
<P>
   SMITH COLLEGE
</P>
<P>
   CAROL GILLIGAN
</P>
<P>
   Clinical psychologist
</P>
<P>
   ``You have explored a range of gender-related issues, including
the ways in which boys and girls develop their moral faculties and
world views, and how adolescent girls stifle their authentic voices
in the face of social expectations of how women should think, feel
and behave. You have described the essence of the work you do as
`listening to women's voices and hearing how their inclusion
changes the resonances around us.' Thanks to your efforts, women's
voices are resounding as never before.''
</P>
<P>
   BARD COLLEGE
</P>
<P>
   CHUCK CLOSE
</P>
<P>
   Artist
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any artist of our time you have challenged the
conceits of the illusions of realism and forced us to question our
glib assumptions about what we see every day and what we fail to
observe. We honor you not only for being a great artist but for the
humanism in a world often marked by polemic, selfishness and lack
of generosity.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW SCHOOL UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   JUDY COLLINS
</P>
<P>
   Singer
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear within us an extraordinary gift, the distinctive
spirit-lifting audible texture and timbre of our desire for social
justice. Yours is an artistry with a clear moral compass, and
through the alchemy of your art that compass is embedded in our
memories _ and our aspirations _ as an inescapable measure of our
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSITY OF SAN FRANCISCO
</P>
<P>
   SISTER HELEN PREJEAN
</P>
<P>
   Author, ``Dead Man Walking''
</P>
<P>
   ``Helen Prejean, of the Sisters of St. Joseph of Medaille, knows
intimately this darkness devoid of stars. She has spent the last 15
years sharing with the American public her eyewitness accounts of
the death penalty. She knows the darkness of the families who have
lost loved ones to the senseless and brutal act of murder. She
offers them light and love. She knows the darkness and
dehumanization of death row inmates and their families, and she
offers them humanity. It is her fidelity to her faith and her
openness to the call of the Spirit that guide her through this
darkness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
