<HEADLINE>
`PHANTOM MENACE' LOOMS BIG SECOND WEEKEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``The Phantom Menace'' will become the first film
to top $200 million domestically in less than two weeks _ blowing
away the previous record for the shortest time to hit the milestone
by an astounding eight days.
</P>
<P>
   Studio sources say a tide of Memorial Day moviegoers will easily
blast ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' past the
milestone set by ``Independence Day'' in 1996. ``Phantom Menace''
showed impressive second-weekend legs with an estimated $49 million
at 2,970 theaters during Friday-Sunday, pushing its 12-day total
past $188 million, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people still in the mood to see `Phantom
Menace' who didn't want to go in the first few days,'' said movie
analyst Arthur Rockwell. ``There's also been a big shift in
sentiment in the positive direction after it opened with all the
negative buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' was so dominant that it took in more than
double the $22.8 million opening of ``Notting Hill'' even though
the Julia Roberts-Hugh Grant vehicle, showing at 2,745 theaters,
set a record for best opening ever by a romantic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth installment in George Lucas' saga, set 30 years
before the original ``Star Wars,'' took in $13.3 million on Friday,
$18 million on Saturday and a projected $17.7 million on Sunday as
the 20th Century Fox release saw its total decline less than 25
percent from its opening Friday-Sunday. ``There were a lot of
families and older audiences that came to see it this weekend,''
said Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source forecasting
service.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum said ``Phantom Menace'' will probably wind up with a
final domestic gross of $375 million, which would leave it fourth
on the all-time list after ``Titanic'' with $600.8 million, ``Star
Wars'' with $460.9 million and ``E.T. _ The Extraterrestrial'' with
$399.8 million. After 12 days, ``Menace'' is already the
29th-highest domestic grosser ever.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum predicted ``Phantom Menace'' will lead the box office
next weekend, when Disney opens adventure-thriller ``Instinct,''
and then surrender first place on the following weekend to New
Line's ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal's rollout of ``Notting Hill'' topped industry
expectations, and its four-day total could hit $28 million by the
end of today's shows. Bucksbaum said the final gross could hit an
impressive $105 million, adding, ``It's a classic example of
gearing your programming toward an audience because this is the
only date-crowd movie for the early summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell said the film benefited from Grant's presence as a
counterpoint to Roberts' star power, adding, ``Sophisticated
audiences know he's a good actor, so he's sort of the mysterious
plus in this movie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Notting Hill'' represented the third straight solid opening
for Universal, following ``Life'' and ``The Mummy'' in a clear
signal that the studio has turned around from last year's downbeat
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled,'' said Nikki Rocco, Universal's distribution
chief. ``We always believed there was room for another film besides
`Phantom Menace' and our surveys show `Notting Hill' is getting
well-above-average recommendations from the audiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal also continued to post strong results from ``The
Mummy'' with $10 million at 3,399 theaters, pushing the
action-adventure past $114 million after 24 days. ``The Mummy'' is
already the 129th highest domestic grosser, topping last year's
``You've Got Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing a distant fourth was Fox's fifth weekend of
``Entrapment'' with a respectable $5 million at 2,869 theaters,
followed by Sony's disappointing opening of virtual-reality
thriller ``The Thirteenth Floor'' with $3.1 million at 1,815 sites.
The latter's total barely edged Warner Bros.' ninth weekend of
``The Matrix'' with $2.6 million at 2,521 screens.
</P>
<P>
   Bucksbaum noted that ``Thirteenth Floor'' covered much of the
same territory as ``The Matrix,'' which has now topped $152 million
thanks to impressive special effects and the star power of Keanu
Reeves. ``The results show the importance of being first into
theaters with the same type of movie and having a major star for a
virtual-reality film,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were Fox Searchlight's third weekend of
``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' with $1.6 million at 1,093 theaters,
Fox's eighth weekend of ``Never Been Kissed'' with $1.4 million at
1,888 theaters, Universal's seventh weekend of ``Life'' with $1.2
million at 1,214 screens and DreamWorks' second weekend of ``The
Love Letter'' with $1.1 million at 781 locations. Paramount's sixth
weekend of ``Election,'' followed in 11th with $1 million at 827
sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
