<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S STAFF CAN'T STAND PROSPERITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ No giddiness was apparent in the Mariner clubhouse
before Sunday's game. But a milestone is a milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nary a single kazoo.
</P>
<P>
   The worst pitching staff in the major leagues had squeezed its
earned run average down to 5.98 _ the first time in nearly a month
the number had been below a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it was a small milestone, sort of like the Lewis and
Clark expedition getting to Nebraska. But no journey can begin
without these first steps.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' quest is to avoid being the worst staff in
baseball history, a distinction belonging to the 1930 Phillies at
6.30.
</P>
<P>
   Things were going so well, too.
</P>
<P>
   After reaching a team high of 6.81 at mid-month, the Mariners
until yesterday had won 10 of 12 games thanks mostly to a) pitching
that bordered on the respectable, and b) a weenie schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Then they gave up 15 runs to Tampa Bay, a Devil Ray club record,
sending a jolt of hope through the long-cold graves of the old
Philly staff. Sixty-nine years is a long time to hold a baseball
record. The late Phils would just as soon move on to a new gig in
that special place in hell reserved for guys who can't get anybody
out.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to know whether that hot spot is being prepared for the
Mariner staff, although yesterday's principal perpetrators, Ken
Cloude and Mac Suzuki, certainly would be wise to shop at the
Asbestos Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, one 15-7 loss does not a failure make. But neither
does a winning streak portend eventual success when the bad guys
have been uniformly mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are in the midst of a long run of opponent
ordinariness that is hard to come by. Barring a big winning streak
by a future foe, the Mariners are destined to avoid a team playing
better than .500 ball until a June 11 interleague game at the
Kingdome against the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Since the last good team they played was in Boston May 12, that
means the Mariners will have gone a month without meeting a single
team equipped with hairy knuckles and an unpleasant disposition.
</P>
<P>
   None of that is the Mariners' fault, of course. It is not the
players' responsibility that most baseball talent is grouped in a
few places, leaving the remaining clubs to forage for roots and
berries.
</P>
<P>
   But it does behoove the Mariners to come out of this 24-game run
with the claimers with at least 16 wins in order to have pretense
to the AL West throne.
</P>
<P>
   The current modest dash has left the Mariners four games in
arrears of Texas, which is hardly terrible for the end of May. But
yesterday's astonishing wildness in Cloude and Suzuki, who left
catcher Dan Wilson with enough bad hops to earn a permanent
bitter-beer face, forces the non-musical question:
</P>
<P>
   Moyer, Garcia and who?
</P>
<P>
   Erstwhile No. 1 pitcher Jeff Fassero leads the AL in hits, home
runs and earned runs served up, and is second in walks. After the
creditable performances of Jamie Moyer and rookie Freddy Garcia,
the Mariners had Cloude for the No. 4 spot and no one for No. 5,
thanks to a run of off-days.
</P>
<P>
   But soon enough they will play many games against many good
teams. It is asking a lot of the long grass and heavy air next door
at the Guilty Pleasure to keep the staff from its dubious dalliance
with the '30 Phils.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about that now,'' said pitching coach Stan
Williams before the game. ``We're trying to build confidence on a
daily basis. Success will build on itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the incremental approach is Williams' only possibility.
With a mind-bending eight pitchers having made their major league
debut under Williams this season _ and 18 pitchers employed
overall, a league high shared with second-year Tampa Bay _ there is
not exactly a thick book with which to gauge progress against
history.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude and Suzuki are among the most senior of the youngsters,
with a fair amount of major league time. But the kind of
noncompetitiveness shown yesterday _ ``Mac was terrible, there's no
other way to describe it,'' said manager Lou Piniella _ continues a
chronic problem that is destined to show later in the season: Too
many innings for the few good arms.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how strong Jose Paniagua, with 22 appearances
already, will be in September. No one knows whether John Halama is
a starter or reliever. No one knows whether Cloude or Suzuki can
stop out-thinking themselves on a major league mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked hard all spring on pitch command,'' said Williams.
``We had a good spring, then we start the season walking everybody
in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the year, our new people followed behind the leaders.
Our one and two guys got behind so badly, it spooked the rest of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the key moment was May 16, when Moyer's
eight-inning, 5-1 win over Kansas City ``showed the young guys it
was possible to get outs in the major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   That was also the start of the decent dozen games that made for
10 wins. Now Williams is praying that the reverse is not true, that
one horror show doesn't make for a week of kiddy screamers.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the staff ERA is back to 6.17, he's again hearing the
footsteps of long-dead Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
