<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVIL RAYS STING M'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The explosion started with extra-base hits, one after
another.
</P>
<P>
   It continued with walks _ a Tampa Bay Devil Ray going to first,
Mariners pitching coach Stan Williams heading to the mound, manager
Lou Piniella pacing in the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   It concluded when home plate umpire Rocky Roe rung up Jose
Canseco on a borderline third strike.
</P>
<P>
   Added up, it was 44 minutes of fourth-inning futility for the
Mariners, who were jeered by their own fans during Sunday's 15-7
defeat at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's eight-run fourth set a club record for runs in one
inning, and the Devil Rays set another team record for most runs in
a game.
</P>
<P>
   Though their four-game winning streak was snuffed, the M's still
managed to win two of three from Tampa Bay and remain one of
baseball's hottest teams. But they did not look the part from 6:12
to 6:56 p.m., when the Devil Rays sent 14 batters to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Three Mariners threw 64 pitches, most of which were nowhere near
the catcher's target. Instead, Dan Wilson was frequently forced to
go from a crouch to his knees, either to pray for a strike or to
stop a misguided delivery. Perhaps both.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the inning, the bases were loaded and Tampa Bay was
ready to fire. Six times, a Devil Ray appeared at the plate with
every base occupied. It seemed endless to everyone but the Devil
Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 44-minute half-inning? It didn't seem like that long at
all,'' center fielder Randy Winn said after his 4-for-5 evening.
``You don't want to be the guy to stop it. You feed off the guy in
front of you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just hoping we'd get the third out,'' said a perplexed
Piniella, who first had to wait forever for the second out.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Huskey hung out in right field and was just like a
Mariners fan, hoping that one of his teammates would throw a
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to happen or it won't stop,'' he said. ``When you're
standing on your feet busting your butt for that long, it's not a
very fun inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the abuse was self-inflicted by the Mariner pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Ken Cloude gave up runs in every inning he pitched.
</P>
<P>
   Mac Suzuki replaced Cloude. Just like his predecessor, Suzuki
served up a variety of juicy offerings when he wasn't giving
Wilson's hamstrings a workout with pitches in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki retired only one of the seven batters he faced, and the
fans heartily booed his ineffectiveness and cheered when Frankie
Rodriguez got up in the bullpen. Rodriguez finally muffled the
Devil Rays, but not before struggling with control problems like
everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the assault ended, Canseco did not have enough
energy to complain about Roe's questionable third-strike call.
Miguel Cairo was Tampa Bay's biggest instigator, starting the
inning with a triple off Huskey's glove and contributing a
run-scoring single a half-hour later.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude, who had a 2.04 earned run average in eight relief
appearances after being demoted to the bullpen, has not pitched
well since returning to the rotation. In his three starts this
month, Cloude has a 10.95 ERA after giving up seven runs in
three-plus innings Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed home runs to Fred McGriff and John Flaherty on
consecutive pitches, eliciting the first boos of the night. Cloude
also hung an 0-and-2 breaking ball to Canseco, who roped the
mistake into the blue tarp in left field to tie Ken Griffey Jr. for
the major league lead in homers with 19.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude can't figure out why he has been more successful as a
reliever than a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a hitter and you've got to throw strikes to get him
out whether you're starting, relieving or whatever,'' he said.
``You get an opportunity to go back in the rotation ... that's not
exactly going out and making a good statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Cloude's starting status was affected by his
performance, Piniella said: ``We'll assess that (Monday).''
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander John Halama is the leading candidate to replace
Cloude in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   His team trailing 13-2 after four innings, Piniella began
pulling his regulars, resting them for future battles like the next
three against Baltimore beginning Monday night at the Kingdome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
