<HEADER>
A7077 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-USC-PEPPERDINE-LA     05-31 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC ELIMINATES PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It looked like a regional final. It felt like a
regional final. Instead of Omaha and a trip to the College World
Series, though, USC gets Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be super.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans, who gave Pepperdine a second game, and a second
life, with a Bad News Bears fielding display, came back to beat the
Waves 12-7 on Sunday night at Dedeaux Field in the
double-elimination tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Second-seeded USC (36-24) won the first-round regional and plays
the Pacific-10 champion Cardinal next weekend in a second-round
``super regional'' to determine a spot in the CWS. Stanford, the
national No.6 seed that won its first-round regional, is the
favorite to host the best two-of-three series.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans don't care where they play next week; they're just
happy to stave off elimination after top-seeded Pepperdine (46-16)
won the day's first game 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   By the time USC reliever Jason Lane ended the seven hours of
play by striking out Dan Bir, the Trojans were ready to celebrate _
even though they don't receive a trophy, just a plane ride to Palo
Alto.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Losing the first game) was kind of like a wake-up call,''
said Lane, an all-tournament outfielder who pitched in both games.
``This could have been our last game. When you have that on the
line, it makes it feel like a big-time championship game. Which it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   USC catcher Eric Munson, selected as the most outstanding player
of the series after he hit two home runs Sunday, agreed with Lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all came down to one game,'' Munson said. ``It felt like a
big one, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waves made their first playoff appearance in four years, and
it showed in the second game. Pepperdine, the nation's No. 2 team
in fielding percentage, made four errors, including one by
shortstop Tony Sanchez in the second, when USC scored three runs,
and one by third baseman G.J. Raymundo in the third, when the
Trojans scored five.
</P>
<P>
   Raymundo had only eight errors entering the game, the Waves'
fifth of the weekend. He said fatigue played no role in his
defensive breakdown that allowed three runs to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a mental error, just physical,'' Raymundo said. ``We
were prepared to play, no matter how many games. We're used to
playing a lot of games in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans threw away the first game _ literally. Freshman
third baseman Beau Craig, who was an all-state catcher in high
school, had throwing errors on two consecutive ground balls in the
seventh that led to three Pepperdine runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hurried the throws,'' Craig said. ``Right after the game I
was thinking about it a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   USC right-hander Rik Currier (5-7) took the tough-luck loss in
the first game. Currier held Pepperdine to one run and six hits
through the first six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of Pepperdine's runs in the first game was earned.
</P>
<P>
   Gehrke, the Waves' All-American closer who leads the nation in
saves, matched his longest outing of the season in the first game.
He gave up one hit _ a bases-empty homer to Munson that made it 4-3
_ and struck out three in 21/3 innings to get the win.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves made the second game interesting in the seventh with
three runs to cut the lead to 10-7. At one point, they trailed 8-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to see a taste of why we won so many games,''
Pepperdine head coach Frank Sanchez said. ``(Our players) don't
have much quit in them. They fight tooth and nail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
