<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7078 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-INDIANAPOLIS500-B     05-31 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDIANAPOLIS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRACK INHERITS THE WIN 
</HEADLINE>
 500-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ In the end, Kenny Brack did not set his sights on
any one man or machine in his quest to win the biggest race of his
life. He simply laid out a strategy for driving a perfect race and
followed it to the letter because, as Brack discovered in the three
months he spent studying the race, it was going to take a perfect
day to win the 83d Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no way Brack could have planned what transpired
Sunday at Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   In a race that saw almost all the leaders fall by the wayside,
Brack inherited his first Indy 500 title when Robby Gordon ran out
of gas and fell out of the lead with one lap to go. As a result,
Brack, a 33-year-old native of Arvika, Sweden, and the Indy Racing
League's defending champion, needed to complete just one lap to win
the race, but mistakenly slowed down when Gordon's sputtering car
pulled into the pits just as the white flag was unfurled.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a matter of fact, I did,'' said Brack, admitting the one
flaw to his day. ``I started slowing down. I guess we had it won,
but we just hadn't won it yet. I was just concentrating on bringing
to the flag safely, I don't get too emotional before I see the
checkered flag.''
</P>
<P>
   When Brack finally did come around for the checkered flag, his
No. 14 PowerTeam Dallara-Aurora was greeted in Victory Circle by
legendary car owner A.J. Foyt, a four-time Indy 500 winner from
Houston who Sunday savored his first as a car owner. And while it
took Gordon's gas tank to run dry for Brack's cup to runneth over
with milk, the fabled Brickyard's traditional nectar of victory,
Foyt, too, enjoyed a great day after his two other drivers, Billy
Boat and Robbie Buhl, finished third and sixth, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say enough about Kenny Brack, Robbie Buhl, and Billy
Boat,'' Foyt gushed, sporting a Texas-sized grin. ``You qualify one
car in the front row (Boat), another in the third (Brack), and one
in the back (Buhl), and all finish in the Top 6. What else can you
ask for?''
</P>
<P>
   For Brack, it was a nice culmination of all that planning.
</P>
<P>
   It was, to be certain, a much better ending than his Indy 500
debut two years ago when he finished 33d after getting involved in
a crash on the warmup lap that wiped out the entire fifth row.
Brack returned to Indy last year as part of Foyt's stable and
started on the front row with his teammate Boat, the pole sitter,
but finished sixth when he ran out of fuel on Lap 88 and fell out
of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could win the Indy 500,'' said Brack. ``I set
goals for myself to win in whatever I drive. I physically prepared
myself for this race. The car was perfect, and we took care of it
all week. I ran this race exactly the way I wanted to. Obviously,
some things had to fall into place, and some guys fell out of the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the leaders seemed to become endangered species as
they were felled by one problem or another.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was Arie Luyendyk, the 45-year-old Flying Dutchman
whose farewell tour of the Brickyard came to a crashing halt on Lap
117 when he rapidly closed in on the slower car of Tyce Carlson,
got on the brakes hard to avoid a collison, and spun backward
across the track and up the banking before slamming into the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The furthest thing from my mind when I was going backwards
was, `I'm going to hit the wall here,' '' said Luyendyk. ``I was
thinking, `God, I can't believe that I did that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Another calamitous turn of events occurred three laps later when
Greg Ray, who had inherited the lead from Luyendyk, squandered it
in a pit-row collision with Mark Dismore that retired Ray's car to
the garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what happened,'' said Ray. ``I was told to go.
I was focusing on all the things I'm supposed to be focusing on
before heading back out again. The next thing I know, I went
sideways into the pit wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Cheever, the defending Indy 500 champion, then took the
point, but he, too, failed to hold the lead for longer than 20 laps
when smoke came pouring out of his wheezing Infiniti power plant on
Lap 140.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, there was Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   The CART driver, who crashed and finished 27th in Saturday's
Motorola 300 at Gateway International Speedway in Madison, Ill.,
was perhaps the most snakebitten of all the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   After Dismore crashed on Lap 169 while exiting Turn 2, Gordon,
who was behind the wheel of what was regarded as the fastest car in
the field, inherited the lead on Lap 171 when the leaders pitted
under caution with 30 laps to go. Problem was, Gordon and his
co-owner, John Menard, were gambling that they had enough in their
35-gallon fuel cell to cover the remaining 75 miles.
</P>
<P>
   They bet wrong and wound up big losers when Gordon's car
sputtered and fell dramatically off the pace as it came around Turn
4, ready to take the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end, we could have come in under yellow, splashed for
fuel and beat them all out, but we didn't,'' Gordon said. ``I
thought all the stars were aligned. There was a full moon last
night here at Indy, it was beautiful, but the stars weren't aligned
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   They were for Brack.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal when I entered this race was to drive a perfect
race,'' Brack said. ``I had my plan for driving, and the team had
their plan for the car, and it all came together.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfectly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
