</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES BUFFING UP IMAGE OF A CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ They've taken it on the chin here so many times, there
isn't a plastic surgeon in the world who could tuck and suture this
city's self-esteem. Buffalo is synonymous with chicken wings and
cheap jokes, the former best when lathered with blue cheese
dressing, the latter garnished with cruel stabs about the
downtown's post-World War II decay.
</P>
<P>
   But, guess what, this city's hockey team is no joke. The
Senators and Bruins found that out, up close and personal.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Maple Leafs, also on the verge of being dismissed from
the Stanley Cup playoffs, have had it pushed in their faces, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate that word, `desperate,' '' said Leafs coach Pat Quinn,
when asked following a humiliating 5-2 loss here Saturday night how
his club would respond for Game 5 of the series, Monday night in
Toronto. ``Desperate guys die.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that time now for the Leafs, whose fans were anticipating a
mid-June coronation and now await the coroner's siren song.
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs should have been desperate in Game 4, when they
already were in a 2-games-to-1 hole in the best-of-seven series.
Instead, they skated in a state of perpetual stupefication, like so
many pieces of petrified wood floating aimlessly across Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   A season in which the Leafs perhaps overachieved, during which
they flirted all season with the top spot in the Eastern
Conference, came crashing down in the second period of Game 4. The
Sabres struck for three goals in a span of 2:35, the Leafs
committing one giant boo-boo after another in their own end, and
were in command of a 5-0 lead well before the second intermission.
The Leafs at times looked as futile as, well, the Senators and
Bruins before them.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn tripped over his words in describing his club's
peformance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disintegrated isn't the word,'' he said, ``but it's pretty
close.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we hit the ice,'' added defenseman Bryan Berard, the
former Mount St. Charles star from Woonsocket, R.I., ``we left the
brains in the locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   It all has become such a repeat scenario in the last five weeks
that the redundancy is proof of miscalculation. It's time to begin
giving these Sabres appropriate credit.
</P>
<P>
   First off, discard the it's-a-one-man-team theory. Just as in
the Boston series, Buffalo netminder Dominik Hasek hasn't been a
critical factor in rubbing out the Leafs. He is, for the record,
hindered at the moment with a bothersome groin pull. However,
fronted by the Sabres' up-tempo forechecking game, which often
transforms into a '90s version of skate-and-shoot, Hasek has looked
more like a clinging bat than an acrobat in his cage. He's there.
He scares the Leafs. If they could put up any kind of assault and
get that red light to burn, maybe he would blink and fly away.
</P>
<P>
   There is just too much good stuff happening in front of Hasek _
much of it at the opposite end of the ice _ to say he's been
anything more than a distinguished attendee at this party.
</P>
<P>
   The brightest spot in Game 4 was the continuing renaissance of
Geoff Sanderson, the former Hartford 40-goal scorer whose career
has been stuck somewhere between slumber and comatose for the
better part of five seasons. He played on no fewer than three teams
last season (Carolina, Vancouver, and Buffalo), and in 75 games
totaled 11 goals and 18 assists. He was but a shadow of the speedy,
hard-shooting left wing who collected 46 goals and 89 points with
the Whale in 1992-93, the season in which he turned 21 years old.
</P>
<P>
   In 75 games this season, Sanderson again was a disappointment on
offense, knocking in only 12 goals and picking up a modest 30
points. Keep in mind, though, that Miroslav Satan led all Sabres
with only 66 points, albeit with an impressive 40 goals. For
six-plus months, October to April, the Sabre attack, if it could be
called that, was based on the conventional trap-and-counter
schematic that the majority of NHL clubs follow. Note: The only
team ever to win with that was the New Jersey Devils, who barely
have been a postseason factor since their '95 Cup.
</P>
<P>
   As the postseason has unfolded, the Sabres inch-by-inch have
stripped their trap-and-counter sheep's clothing. Sanderson is
skating and firing (two goals in Game 4). Satan, back in Game 3 of
this series after bruising an ankle in the Ottawa series, is
evolving as a creative (dare we say daring?) playmaker. And, hold
on, even the ham-handed Rob Ray chopped in a goal Saturday night,
ending a 110-game scoring drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously firing on all cylinders when Razor gets a
goal,'' kidded Lindy Ruff. Ray was so ecstatic, the Buffalo News
reported Sunday, that he called home to Sinclair, Ont., between
periods to share his joy with his family (one of those
only-in-hockey feel-good vignettes).
</P>
<P>
   The underlying truth in Ruff's good humor, though, is that the
Sabres have a lot more talent and touch in their lineup than most
of the hockey world believed all season. Chances are, neither
Dallas nor Colorado, the Sabres' probable next challenger, know it
yet. They're busy right now. But one of them had better be paying
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn can tell them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing a different way right now,'' said the Toronto
coach, sounding more bewildered than beleaguered after the Game 4
pounding, which included the outing of goalie Curtis Joseph after
40 minutes. ``At the end of the season, they played a fall-back
(i.e. modified trap) style of game. They were defense-first all the
time. When you play that, you don't get a lot of chances, and it's
harder to score when you get those chances. But they always were a
team that, per chance, was a pretty accurate team. In the games we
had against them, they didn't outchance us very often, but their
scoring ratio was much better. They showed they have scoring
ability.''
</P>
<P>
   All the Sabres have to do now is play .500 hockey, win five of a
possible 10 remaining games, and they'll have their first Stanley
Cup. A championship by itself wouldn't put an end to the maligning
of this metropolis, where, for the record, the sky was sapphire
blue and the temparature near 90 Sunday (take that, you frozen
tundra taunters).
</P>
<P>
   But you never know what could happen. Turnarounds can be rooted
in unlikely sources.
</P>
<P>
   Boston found its way by fashioning the back of Faneuil Hall into
an overpriced fast-food eatery (urban planning you only could learn
at Harvard, I bet).
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland made it big on the back of the Indians and a new
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills did a lot for this town, getting to four Super Bowls,
but in their own way, failing each time in the big one, ultimately
left only a cracked layer of shellack over Buffalo's faded image.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, the Sabres play on, a merry band of Czechs,
Russians, Slovaks, and assorted North Americans, at least
burnishing a battered city's psyche. While Canada's dollar sags,
its game spreads good cheer and high hope in a US city so desperate
_ sorry, Mr. Quinn _ for something really good to come marching
down Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, how about a parade?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
