<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX SWEEP INDIANS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-INDIANS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Perfect?
</P>
<P>
   No, Red Sox rookie Brian Rose's flirtation with a perfect game
ended with David Justice, the first Cleveland batter of the sixth
inning, when shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, ranging far beyond the
scope of what is considered a shortstop's terrain, couldn't put the
finishing touches to what would have been a highlight-reel play.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's off-balance throw from the right-field side of
second base after fielding Justice's bouncer pulled first baseman
Mike Stanley off the bag, which was akin to a figure skater's
wobbly landing after executing a triple salchow. It went in the
books as an error, but for degree of difficulty, it should have
been scored a 9 on a scale of 10.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as a perfectly splendid finish to what loomed as the
sternest test of the spring for the Sox, there could have been no
better sendoff for the team's return home than Sunday's 4-2 win
that gave the Sox a three-game sweep of the Indians. The victory
also gave the Red Sox a 12-4 record in a two-week test against the
iron of the American League and a 19-8 record for the month of May,
the team's best month in nearly three years, with a date against
the Detroit Tigers Monday at Fenway Park still to come.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who nearly threw his cherished glove in frustration
after his error opened the way to two Indians runs in the sixth,
has no need to turn in any IOUs to Rose. His three-run home run in
the third off Indians starter Doc Gooden spotted the kid a 3-0
lead, and he walked, stole second, and scored on Mike Stanley's
two-out single in the eighth, a run that reduced the anxiety level
for Tom Gordon's 10th save and second in two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in and said I was sorry, but what can you say, it was a
tough play,'' Garciaparra said of encountering Rose in the dugout
after the inning, in which Einar Diaz's one-out double ended Rose's
no-hit bid and an error by Stanley and a groundout brought home two
runs, spoiling the shutout, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think he was upset at all,'' Garciaparra said. ``I
was probably more upset for him. The guys were busting their butts
for him. We knew he was doing his job, and we wanted to do whatever
we could for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose would be hard-pressed to do his job any better than he has
in his first three starts, two of which came against the Yankees,
the defending World Series winners, and Sunday's against the
Indians, who merely led the league in hitting and were on a
record-setting pace for runs scored before the Sox swept into
Jacobs Field and took three straight. It was the first time this
season that the Indians have been swept, and the last time they
were swept at home by the Sox, in 1990, they were still occupying
Municipal Stadium, now a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as fine a game as I've ever seen a pitcher that young
(23) pitch _ not throw, but pitch _ in the big leagues,'' Red Sox
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said of Rose, who needed just 56
pitches to dispatch the first 15 Indians in order Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was working. That was just about as perfect as you
could throw 56 pitches,'' Kerrigan said. ``I think he might have
missed his spot four times in the first 56 pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Both of the Indians' runs allowed by Rose were unearned, which
means that in his first three starts since his summons from
Pawtucket, the righthander has allowed one earned run in 19
innings. Numbers like those keep you in the big leagues for a long
time. Those kind of numbers will make you Pedro Martinez money, if
you do it long enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 confidence thing for me,'' Rose said, ``is I'm
healthy. I'm working hard on my days off to stay healthy, because I
want to try and help this club out and get wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like everybody else, a piece of the puzzle on what
hopefully will be a championship team.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rose gave up a leadoff single to Manny Ramirez to open the
seventh, manager Jimy Williams let some of the other puzzle pieces
tumble out. Lefthander Mark Guthrie was the first of four Sox
relievers to finish off the Indians, with the finale Gordon's
strikeout of David Justice in the first rematch of Sox closer and
Sox killer since Justice ended the Sox' season last October with a
two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   ``It crossed my mind for a minute,'' Gordon said, ``but no more
than any other out. I still had trouble with the command of my
fastball, but the good thing is I have my curveball, and I can get
strikeouts again.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon had been reluctant to throw his nastiest curve, the one
that tends to travel about 59 feet and leaves hitters swinging at
air, for fear it would put a strain on his tender elbow. But with
his arm strength back, that concern is ebbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demon is back,'' Kerrigan said of Gordon's money pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Upon further reflection, Kerrigan decided that ``demon'' might
not set well with a guy who points to the heavens after every save.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's call it Lord Charles,'' he said. ``The old-fashioned
term.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, faced with 16 games against the Yankees, Indians
and Blue Jays in the last two weeks, responded with old-fashioned
grit, winning 12. They had to sweep the Indians just to maintain
their half-game lead over the Bombers, who now have won five
straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys play hard every day,'' said Guthrie, who struck out
Jim Thome after Ramirez stole second and retired the next two
hitters on ground balls before Jim Corsi and Rheal Cormier worked
the eighth. ``Only a handful of teams do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty intense group. I think that starts with guys
like Nomar and Pedro and Flash, the way they go about their
business every day. When you see your superstars doing that,
there's no reason everybody else can't do it, either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
