<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION ACHIEVED SOME GOALS VS. METROSTARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ John Harkes was conversing with Revolution
teammates on the field at Giants Stadium long before the start of
Saturday night's game when several fans started a welcome home
chant. Actually, it was more of a welcome home curse, echoing
through the emptiness amid the early arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the game, there were more than 40,000 spectators
in the stands, but Harkes made it a point to acknowledge his small
group of detractors behind the goal by cupping a hand around his
ear, rebuking them as they sat in momentary stunned silence. The
Revolution had just spoiled the festive atmosphere, holding the
MetroStars to a 3-3 tie in regulation time, then winning the
shootout.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution might have surprised their own fans, as well,
since the team had been in a record scoring slump. And, after the
Revolution fell behind to the MetroStars in the opening minutes,
they seemed to be falling into their losing form. But Ivan McKinley
nodded in a goal off the inside of the left post in the 21st minute
to snap a 360-minute scoreless streak, and Giovanni Savarese scored
twice. McKinley's score, off a precisely chipped pass from Harkes,
was the first Revolution goal in the run of play in 405 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, the Revolution appeared out of character as they
surrendered more than two goals for the first time this season.
They squandered 2-1 and 3-2 advantages as the game degenerated in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wide-open game and we did well to go in front,'' said
Harkes, who is from Kearney, N.J. ``But we need to be tighter. We
can't be all over the place and giving up three goals. That was
disappointing. But it's a plus that we walked away with a point.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Revolution displayed some of their most coherent
midfield play for part of the first half and early in the second
half. Harkes solved the team's lack of effectiveness on the right
wing and Jair and Kris Kelderman helped coordinate the midfield,
though the Revolution required much of the first half to mesh in
midfield.
</P>
<P>
   This was in contrast to last week, a 1-0 loss at Los Angeles,
and an encouraging sign for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played together more and the more we do that the
better,'' Harkes said. ``But we need to force the ball into the box
more. Our forwards are making runs and the ball is not coming in.
We need to work on that more. Once we get to the (penalty area), we
seem to hesitate and we don't do the right things.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the MetroStars, maintaining possession was the right
thing to do, especially in the second half. The MetroStars were
attacking desperately, and the Revolution central defenders were
left isolated too often with Eduardo Hurtado and Nansha Kalonji.
With Mark Chung controlling the pace in midfield, the MetroStars
were the more dangerous team in the final third of the game as the
Revolution went to a siege strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have eight points in 10 matches, two points
behind last year's pace. But in their 10th match last season, the
Revolution lost in a shootout to the MetroStars and slid into a
nine-game losing streak that destroyed their credibility and nearly
ended their playoff hopes. Now, they are facing home matches
against defending MLS Cup champion Chicago (Saturday) and Miami
(June 13).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution continue to regain health as Mike Burns
(hamstring) played his first full game since April 24. ``I'm not
100 percent, but it was good for me to play 90 minutes,'' Burns
said. ``As a team we didn't play well defensively. We were having
trouble scoring, but then we score in this game and we can't hold
the lead. It's entertainment for the fans, but we have to do
better.'' . . . El Salvador surprised Colombia, 2-1, in the second
game of the doubleheader as midfielder Elias Montes converted a
spectacular bicycle kick early in the second half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
