<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7084 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-FRENCHOPEN-BOS &LR;      05-31 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Andre Agassi never has been the king of France, but he
might be, having behaved like a revolutionary with the guillotine
concession at Stade Roland Garros Sunday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:30, racing desperately to his left, Agassi overtook a
fleeing yellow tennis ball and lofted it high into an azure evening
sky reminiscent of a French painting. Up, up it went, and Carlos
Moya began to run, too _ but it was no use. The ball descended
beyond him, falling like a fatal blade that severed King Carlos
from his kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Only minutes before, with 16,000 witnesses crammed into Court
Central screeching his name _ ``AG-AS-SI! AG-AS-SI!'' _ Agassi went
to the line to serve for a victory that had seemed out of reach
when he lagged a set and two service breaks to the rear, 4-6, 1-4.
But the husky Spaniard struck back fiercely to protect the crown,
almost taking Agassi's head off with a lusty forehand, and
shouldered him into a 0-40 corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd come too far not to step up my game one more time,''
Agassi said after rescuing four break points, closing a last-gap
threat with that brilliant lob and barging into the French Open
quarterfinals, 4-6, 7-5, 7-5, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to take it up a level when I was so far behind, and I
did,'' he said. He had leaped from a dungeon in the Bastille to
storming the joint and taking it apart. In doing so it seemed that
Agassi had flip-flopped a famous regal quote out of the 18th
century. King Louis XV said that after him a deluge would wash away
the royalty. But Sunday, after a deluge lashed Paris, flooding
streets and felling trees, Agassi took out the king himself.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, though favored, had failed in his final-round bids for
the throne against Andres Gomez in 1990 and Jim Courier in 1991.
Despite a spirited revival from a Grand Canyon plunge to No. 140
two years ago, and a return to the top 10 (now No. 14), he was
nevertheless stigmatized by flops in the majors. Not for three
years had he progressed as far as the quarters, that in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm well aware of that, and that I'm 29, and time's running
out. But I'm recommitted,'' Agassi said, his legs still shaking
from the excitement of deposing No. 4 Moya, the highest ranking of
the elite after the removals of Yevgeny Kafelnikov, Pete Sampras,
and Patrick Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still dreams I can accomplish,'' he said. ``This is
one dream.'' Merely four men have won all four majors _ Don Budge,
Fred Perry, Roy Emerson, Rod Laver _ and Agassi lacks only the
French to join them.
</P>
<P>
   Though the sun reappeared to create a gorgeous Sunday afternoon
for the 30,749 roaming the grounds, a curious Austrian deluge swept
away two female contenders _ No. 4 Jana Novotna and, yes, No. 5
Vibrant Venus Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, on a 10-match streak and wearing the badge of Italian
champion, became one of the tournament's larger upset victims,
letting No. 125 Barbara Schwartz escape three successive match
points. Schwartz, a 20-year-old from the Vienna suburb of Brunn am
Gebirge, struck a historic note as the lone female qualifier ever
to make the French quarters, 2-6, 7-6 (9-7), 6-3. ``Inspired by
Barbara,'' No. 34 Sylvia Plischke from Innsbruck then dropped
Wimbledon champ Novotna, 6-3, 7-6 (7-5).
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz also made journalistic history at home by breaking auto
racing's monopoly of the front sports page of the country's leading
paper, Neue Kronenzeitung, circulation 2.8 million. Considered a
jallopy in the tennis fast lane, she bumpered the Barcelona Formula
One story to the rear by flattening Williams's tires.
</P>
<P>
   Exulted Hermann Fuchs, the paper's tennis correspondent for 29
years, ``It never happened before for tennis to beat car racing.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5-6, 0-40, Schwartz brushed aside triple match point with her
own lefthanded daring and Williams's mistakes. ``I didn't know who
she was,'' confessed Williams, who added that none of her camp had
bothered to scout her. Williams's serve and footwork vanished.
Still she had a last chance, bungling a break point that would have
sent her ahead, 4-3, in the third.
</P>
<P>
   How many times did Agassi charge up ``Magic Mountain'' in Las
Vegas as he ``made up my mind to be in the best shape of my life''?
He smiles and says, ``We didn't count, but it was plenty. It's only
about 50 yards, but a pretty good incline that can make you burn.
Magic Mountain is what (trainer) Gil Reyes and I call it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no point in coming to Paris if you aren't
super-prepared physically,'' he said. Two years ago, his last
visit, Agassi was chided by the French for his ``poignees d'amour''
(love handles), and he was beaten in the second round by Chris
Woodruff.
</P>
<P>
   In the second round this time around, he came within two points
of losing to No. 81 Arnaud Clement, who eventually cramped in the
6-0 fifth set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did that to him, staying with him, moving him,'' Agassi
said.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed scrawny across the net from 6-3, 180-pound Moya and
was getting beaten up badly. At first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my work was done, two breaks ahead in the second
set,'' laments Moya. ``It was a bad mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Very bad, because Agassi was about to reach back to earlier
glories. ``We'd never played, and I was stunned by how heavy Carlos
hit. I knew I had to dictate. I had to get aggressive or I was
going home,'' Agassi said. He began to serve murderously and take
the ball earlier, practically half-volleying from the back court to
unbalance Moya. Quick-quick-quick. He started to play better than
he ever had in the hallowed 71-year-old dirt pit, driving Moya to
frustrated blunders.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with qualifier Marcelo Filippini, the conqueror of Greg
Rusedski, the next boulder in his way, Agassi is three wins from
summiting another magic mountain. That is a long way when you
consider that Marcelo Rios, Gustavo Kuerten, and Alex Corretja are
still in town.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, after hailstones pelted Paris, Andre Agassi did a
pretty fair imitation of Mother Nature as a shotmaking deluge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
