<HEADLINE>
KOSOVARS ADJUST TO SOUTHLAND LIVING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: This story contains information on making donations.) 
BY TROY ANDERSON AND PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With their Los Angeles culture-shock slowly
waning, 32 ethnic Albanian refugees from war-torn Kosovo have begun
their search for the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   The Vlashi family came from the blue-collar town of Hani-Elezit,
where a concrete factory was the major industry. Some were truck
drivers, security guards or supervisors. Others were skilled
craftsmen and professional musicians. The women were housewives.
</P>
<P>
   While the bloodshed and horrors of Kosovo remain fresh in their
minds, they've already taken steps to join America's working class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Thursday, they applied for their Social Security cards
and met with a vocational counselor,'' said Renee Vlashi of
suburban West Hills, whose husband sponsored his relatives as
immigrants. ``They have skills, and some of them will eventually
work. They're picking up English pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Martin, who is hosting part of the Vlashi family in his
home in Simi Valley in neighboring Ventura County, said two of the
young women are working hard on their English and have become
attached to a typing tutor computer program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like in a couple of months they'll be full-fledged
American citizens,'' Martin said. ``They're typing about 10 words
per minute now, but they're getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   The search is on for at least four low-rent houses. Some of the
Vlashis will eventually find work, but until then they'll make due
with government aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have it all budgeted out. It's minimal living, but it's
doable,'' Renee Vlashi said.
</P>
<P>
   With only seven months of minimal government help available for
newly arrived Kosovar refugees, charities say they don't have
enough donations to keep them fed and housed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears we're going to need quite a few thousand dollars to
accomplish this,'' said Barbara Creme, director of the Jewish
Community Relations Committee at Jewish Federation/Valley Alliance
in West Hills. ``It's going to take a lot of time and patience. Our
first need is to get them into housing.''
</P>
<P>
   The 28 refugees, all extended relatives of Hajrush and Renee
Vlashi, arrived last week. Six families have agreed to house
Vlashi's relatives for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   About seven or eight more members of the Vlashi family are
expected to fly from the war-torn Balkans to Los Angeles soon. In
all, the federation expects to help assimilate about 60 refugees
into the San Fernando Valley area in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to learn English, the children have to be placed in
schools, and they all have to be evaluated vocationally,'' said
Shoshana Hirsh, assistant director of operations at the federation.
``We need translators who speak Albanian. We could use a very
generous landlord in the West Hills area.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the federation's policy not to release the amount of
donations it receives. Refugee assistance groups provide a month of
financial help to the group, but then the government provides
assistance for seven months.
</P>
<P>
   For seven months after the first month, the government puts
people with families in the CalWorks program or pays people without
children on a sliding scale. The average is $279 a person. For
families, the aid can be extended up to two years.
</P>
<P>
   To donate money, send a check to the Jewish Federation/Valley
Alliance, 22622 Vanowen St., West Hills, CA 91307. For more
information, call (818) 464-3203. To donate furniture, clothing,
toys and other items, call Maya Segal at the Jewish Federation of
Greater Los Angeles at (323) 761-8333.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic Relief agency in Burbank, the agency's United States
headquarters, is also helping Kosovo refugees assimilate into the
Los Angeles area. The agency has offered to sponsor about 100
families altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, the agency raised $300,000 at a fund-raising
dinner, said Abdelsalam Serajudeen, adviser for the crisis at
Islamic Relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not only for Muslims,'' he said. ``We have two major
camps (in the Balkans). We have spent more than $1 million in this
crisis so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Those wishing to help families sponsored by Islamic Relief can
send checks to the organization at P.O. Box 6098, Burbank, CA
91510. For more information, call (818) 238-9520.
</P>
<P>
   So far, people have donated clothes, toys, furniture and money
to the Jewish Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response to these refugees coming here has been so
gratifying,'' said Bonnie Somers, spokeswoman for the federation.
``People of all religions have come through to ask us what they
could do and have volunteered both their time and money.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirsh said that the federation received a big donation of
clothes from the City of Angels Church of Religious Science, an
African-American church in Los Angeles. ``They brought out a huge
amount of clothes for our refugees,'' she said. ``At this point, we
don't need any more clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   A donation of toys brought smiles to Ibrahim Vlashi, a young
refugee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have seen the 7-year-old boy who got the whole box
of trains and cars,'' Hirsh said. ``He was so thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   The families taking care of the refugees committed to a few
weeks but have become quite attached to the Vlashis, Creme said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of when they leave, but when they will
relinquish them,'' Creme said.
</P>
</TEXT>
