A7088 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARR     05-31 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARGROVE WOULDN'T MIND SEEING NO MORE NOMAR 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-GARCIAPARRA-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Indians manager Mike Hargrove said Sunday that sure,
he could have had pitcher Doc Gooden walk Nomar Garciaparra with
first base open in the third inning, when the Red Sox had runners
on second and third with two out in a scoreless game.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't, Hargrove said, because he doesn't like the idea
of intentional walks so early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to intentionally walk a guy in the third
inning,'' said Hargrove. ``Troy O'Leary was up next and he's hurt
us in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I entertained the thought, but it's tough to intentionally
walk somebody in the third inning. Doc had handled him the first
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when the alternative is a three-run home run, like
the 439-foot bomb Garciaparra dropped on Gooden Sunday, Hargrove
might want to reconsider. Especially in light of the damage
Garciaparra has inflicted on the Indians since he broke into the
big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who hit four home runs and had eight RBIs in the
three-game sweep, is batting .358 (49 for 137) with 10 homers and
36 RBIs against the Indians. That includes last October's four-game
playoff set, in which Garciaparra hit .333 with three homers and 11
RBIs. In six games against the Indians this season, Garciaparra is
batting .360 with four homers and 11 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Twice, Gooden shook off catcher Einar Diaz, who was calling for
a curveball, and threw a fastball instead. ``I wanted to get it up
and in,'' Gooden said.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden's plan succeeded only halfway. The pitch was up, all
right, but over the plate and Garciaparra hit it just below the
huge Yard-Man tractor sign in left-center field, giving a new twist
to ``Going yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra said it wasn't for him to second-guess the Indians'
strategy. ``I'm not going to question any pitcher,'' he said.
``When I saw that they weren't going to do that (intentionally walk
him), I said, `All right, I've got to go out there and do my job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to connect on that one. If I had hit a fly ball,
people would have said he made a great pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The theory that opposing teams would not allow Garciaparra, as
the one big threat in the Sox lineup, to beat them has been
obliterated. With one day left in May, Garciapara has had one of
the finest months in his two-plus seasons to date. He's hitting
.349 with 10 home runs and 32 RBIs in 26 games, eclipsed only by
his July last season, when he hit .351 with 11 homers and 33 RBIs,
and there's still one day left this month.
</P>
<P>
   He's off to what is easily his best start in three seasons, his
.335 average 34 percentage points better than last season, and his
home run (10) and RBI totals (40 in 42 games) dwarf previous
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra may not fit the prototype of your classic cleanup
hitter, but he's leading the American League with a .691 slugging
percentage while hitting in the No. 4 spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomar isn't very big,'' said Indians reliever Paul Shuey,
beaten on Saturday by a three-run home run by Garciaparra. ``It's
not like you're facing Jose Canseco. But he almost hits the ball
the same way as Canseco.''
</P>
<P>
   And while all his other stats are on the rise, Garciaparra's
errors and strikeouts are going down. Sunday's error, which came on
a tough chance, was just his fourth of the season; he made 25 last
season.
</P>
<P>
   His strikeout Sunday was just his 15th in 167 at-bats. Project
that out over the 604 at-bats he had last season, and Garciaparra
would finish with just 54 strikeouts, eight fewer than last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
