<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINIDAD IS IN A BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN _ The real war began for Felix Trinidad Saturday night
less than an hour after the battle was over.
</P>
<P>
   He had just defeated Hugo Pineda in startling fashion, knocking
him into submission with a left hook to the stomach that becalmed
the challenger, leaving him on the floor of Roberto Clemente
Coliseum unable to get up.
</P>
<P>
   Pineda was counted out at 2:53 of the fourth round as Trinidad
successfully defended the International Boxing Federation
welterweight title for the 13th time since he first won it six
years ago, but after the battle, the war began. The war between his
promoter and his father. The war between his best interests and his
financial interests. The war to make him a star perhaps had entered
its final struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad may be the best welterweight in the world, but he is
not paid like it nor does he draw fans like it. Not even in Puerto
Rico, where he is a native son, can he sell out an arena the way
his American rival, Oscar De La Hoya, can, and so he cannot be paid
like De La Hoya regardless of what he believes he will do to him if
they ever meet wearing gloved fists.
</P>
<P>
   Don King, who has promoted Trinidad throughout his career,
understands this. Trinidad's father, Felix Sr., appears not to. And
so the two have fought for nearly three weeks over how much
Trinidad must be paid to fight De La Hoya Sept. 18. It is an old
story, but King put a new twist on it as they sat together inside
the ring an hour after Pineda had fallen not 10 feet from where
their chairs rested.
</P>
<P>
   With a heavy contingent of Puerto Rican press in front of him,
King went to work at that moment to build a box for his boxer, a
box from which the boxer could not easily extricate himself without
agreeing to meet his greatest challenge at a price King could live
with.
</P>
<P>
   It was a master stroke, a combination of praise and perjury. It
was a moment of translucent treachery. It was King at his best and
his worst, using his mind to use his boxer both for his own gain
and his own good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight you saw the march to destiny,'' King began. ``Felix
`Tito' Trinidad showed the world how great he is. Now the march
toward Oscar has begun. There is no way we will stand in the way of
destiny. We are family. We may fight inside the house, but when we
come out to the street, we are unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every head must bow! Every knee must bend! Every tongue must
confess that Tito Trinidad is the best welterweight in the world!''
</P>
<P>
   At that, even members of the local press cheered, but over in
the corner Don Felix, the father, glowered and said nothing. His
son beamed, promising to destroy De La Hoya as he had Pineda,
saying he would begin training Monday, beaming like a young man who
has just discovered his destiny.
</P>
<P>
   King smiled, too, but it was the malevolent grin of a master
manipulator who knew a meeting was coming in a few hours, a loud
meeting without the son or the press present. It would be a meeting
between Don King and Don Felix in which all that would matter would
be money, of which Don Felix seems to want nearly all and Don King
seems to want too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tito's punch has spoken for him,'' said Nicholas Medina,
Trinidad's lawyer. ``He has sent a message to Oscar. We are ready
to take the fight, but it is in Don King's court now. It is about
the financial agreement and a little misunderstanding. We said
tonight Tito would show what he is worth. He showed he's worth $15
million!''
</P>
<P>
   Sensing the Trinidads' unwillingness to bargain further, King
then began a new tactic Saturday night. He put his fighter in a hot
box between his homeland and his accountant and by the time he was
done, for Trinidad to refuse to fight began to sound like an act of
treason, a man refusing to defend his people.
</P>
<P>
   ``A family dispute is not the message Tito wants to send to our
people,'' King said, suddenly Puerto Rican for a night. ``It is not
a message he wants to send to the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seizing the time must be understood. This is Tito Time. It's
not about money. Certainly there's no more slavery. A man must get
paid for his labors. But this fight is about destiny. It's about
timing. We must all agree that Tito must fight Oscar. The message
has been sent. Tito is one of the greatest fighters in the world,
but the world will not recognize that until they fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon even the fighter was into it, standing up and pounding his
right fist into his chest and saying, ``I'm not worried about the
fight. I fight whoever I have to!
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, Oscar. I'm ready for you!''
</P>
<P>
   As Trinidad thundered his willingness to fight, King sat smiling
at his side. The representative of the people of Puerto Rico had
spoken. He'd also probably cost himself some money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
