u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-NCAACHAMPIONSHIP-     05-31 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-NCAA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A NET LOSS FOR HARVARD'S BLAKE 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ James Blake's season is over. The Harvard
sophomore sensation and top-seeded player in the NCAA men's tennis
championships lost in Sundya's singles final to second-seeded Jeff
Morrison of Florida in a 7-6 (7-2), 2-6, 6-4 thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Fairfield, Conn., resident, who has been the top-ranked
collegiate player since Dec. 8, will decide whether Sunday's match
was his last at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure right now'' said Blake, who is considering
forgoing his final two years of eligibility to turn professional.
Sunday, he lost his bid to become the first Ivy League player to
win the title since 1922 and the second African- American to do so
(Arthur Ashe won while at UCLA in 1965).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking about going back to Boston, hanging out a few
days and giving my rackets to my parents to take home and not see
those for a little while,'' added Blake.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those three or four days I'm not going to think about it.
I'm just going to relax and, as soon as my parents come and pick me
up, I'm sure the talks will start in the car. Then the next week is
going to be hectic talking to a lot of people. I will probably make
the decision within three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat also marked the third time Blake failed to reach the
main draw of the US Open. Two years ago he lost in the USTA
national boys' 18-and-under championships in the final round, a
match where, like Sunday, the winner gets an automatic wild card
into the Open. Last year, he lost in the last round of the US Open
qualifying tournament.
</P>
<P>
   USTA officials say Blake still can apply for a US Open main draw
wild card based on his results this season and what he does this
summer in satellite matches.
</P>
<P>
   Blake got off to a decent start but never looked as sharp
against Morrison, a sophomore whose second-set defeat was his first
in the tournament. Blake went ahead, 4-2, in the first set and was
up, 30-0, in the seventh game before Morrison rallied to take the
next four points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had chances, but in a match like this you only
get a few opportunities. A couple of times I didn't capitalize,''
said Blake, who forced a tiebreaker by taking the next game only to
see Morrison take the first three points of the extra frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of times (Morrison) came up with really big shots
that made all the difference in the match,'' said Blake. ``The
shots were just falling for him today.''
</P>
<P>
   They began falling for Blake in the second set. He held Morrison
without a point in three games and finished out the set with a
solid forehand cross-court winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second set, he stepped up his game a little bit, and I
started getting a bit tired,'' said Morrison. ``He was making me
run a bit and my legs started to go. I wasn't getting a lot of
first serves in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told myself going into the third set that I have one
more set for the national title and `If you can't find it now, I
don't know if you will ever be able to find it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison broke a 2-2 tie by taking the next three games,
including the second after Blake mistimed an overhand attempt at
the net. Blake captured the next two sets to break Morrison's
service, and it appeared they were headed for another tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   But Blake figured Morrison anticipated the same and backed off a
bit. ``At that point, I think I may have gotten a little relaxed
thinking I was just going to hold there, but he wasn't thinking
that at all,'' said Blake. ``That shouldn't have gone through my
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Morrison wasted no time closing out the match. He got
Blake to hit into the net for three consecutive points, then
captured the title on a passing shot from near the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done my share of winning, and I have to do my share of
losing to start winning some more,'' said Blake, one of six named
to the 1999 USA Tennis Collegiate Team, along with Morrison. ``I'm
upset about the fact I didn't win, but I'm going to just
congratulate him, move on, and enjoy the rest of the week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
