<SLUG> BC-HKO-MINOR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINGS DIVINE IN PROVIDENCE? 
</HEADLINE>
 LEAGUE NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They've been as close to perfect as a team can be,
compiling the American Hockey League's best regular-season record
before sweeping one series and losing only three playoff games thus
far. Three of their players were named first-team AHL All-Stars,
and their aura is such that someone who joined the team just before
the start of the playoffs scored three straight game-winning goals.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Providence Bruins wait to see whom they will play for
the Calder Cup, beginning next weekend, to fully appreciate how far
they've come, it's necessary to look back and see where they have
been.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Providence was as far from the postseason as a team
can be. The Bruins were long since home for the summer, finishing
with only 19 wins and the league's worst record. With attendance in
freefall after missing the playoffs for a second straight year,
management realized it had to take steps to rectify the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Step 1 was hiring a new coach. Peter Laviolette, a
player-assistant coach with Providence during the 1996-97 season,
was plucked out of the East Coast Hockey League after a year as
Wheeling's general manager-coach.
</P>
<P>
   Step 2, simply adding talent to the roster, was achieved by
signing several free agents, including Brandon Smith, Marquis
Mathieu, Terry Virtue, Peter Ferraro, and Dennis Vaske, all AHL
veterans. Mixed with rookies like Eric Nickulas and Andre Savage,
plus returnees such as Landon Wilson, Randy Robitaille, Cameron
Mann, Joel Prpic, Aaron Downey, and John Grahame, a competitive
club began to take shape.
</P>
<P>
   With Laviolette in command behind the bench, the Bruins set
dozens of team and AHL records over the regular season on the way
to a 56-20-4 finish, their 120 points by far the best in the league
_ and an astonishing 70 points better than last year's total. At
one juncture, the Baby B's didn't lose for well over a month, going
15-0-1.
</P>
<P>
   It's been more of the same during the playoffs. Providence
dropped just one game in its opening-round series against
Worcester, then swept aside Hartford in four straight. After going
up, 3-0, against Fredericton, the Bruins polished off the Canadiens
in six games as Ferraro scored the first of his two goals just 12
seconds in, leading the Baby B's to a 6-1 victory Saturday night at
the Providence Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 playoff victories added to its regular-season wins
enabled Providence to break an AHL record: the total of 67 is three
better than the old mark.
</P>
<P>
   With Wilson and AHL Most Valuable Player Robitaille joining
Smith as first-team All-Stars, Virtue named to the second team, and
the Baby B's boasting seven 20-goal scorers during the regular
season, it was an unlikely player who has given the team a
postseason shot in the arm. John Spoltore, sent for from Louisiana
(ECHL) after Robitaille was recalled to Boston during the parent
club's first-round series, scored the winning goal in each of the
first three games of Providence's second-round sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Spoltore led the Coast in regular-season scoring with 36 goals
and 77 assists, but at age 27 encountered a familiar curse _ being
considered too small and slow _ to play above the ECHL level.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's become a big part of what's going on with us,''
Laviolette told the Providence Journal-Bulletin. ``I guess I'm
going to keep putting him out there. When he's out there, things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoltore has six goals in all, while Nickulas is leading the AHL
in postseason scoring at 8-11_19, and Robitaille has 16 points,
including five goals.
</P>
<P>
   Grahame, who assumed the No. 1 goalie's job after Jim Carey was
released in March, has been rock-solid during the postseason after
posting a league-best 37 regular-season victories. Playing every
playoff minute thus far, Grahame is 11-3.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins do win the Calder Cup, it will mark the first time
the city of Providence has earned a championship since 1956.
Doesn't that make the parent club's 27-year drought seem a little
less severe?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the AHL's form-following playoffs, there seems to be at
least one preposterous story in each postseason. The International
Hockey League has this season's doozy in the Orlando Solar Bears,
who rallied from a 3-0 deficit to earn a spot in the finals against
the Houston Aeros. After tying their semifinal series at three
games apiece against Detroit, Orlando appeared dead in the water
before scoring twice in the last three minutes of Game 7 to tie the
score, then won in double overtime on a goal by Todd Krygier to
deny the Vipers a chance to win their second championship in three
years. Goalie David Littman (Boston College) and center Hubie
McDonough (St. Anselm) are two thirtysomething vets who have lent a
steadying hand to Orlando's postseason push. The Solar Bears will
have to mount another comeback if they are to win the Turner Cup;
regular-season champ Houston holds a 3-1 lead . . . Marty Turco was
named IHL Rookie of the Year after compiling a 24-17-10 record with
a 2.61 goals-against average and save percentage of 92 for
Michigan. The former University of Michigan goalie is property of
the Dallas Stars . . . The ECHL championship is down to a seventh
game with the series between Richmond and Mississippi tied, 3-3.
Helping send Richmond to the final was UMass's Sal Manganaro, whose
winning goal in the fourth game of the semifinals completed a sweep
. . . Former New Hampshire star Mark Mowers earned IHL top US-born
rookie honors with 14-22_36 numbers in 51 games with Milwaukee.
Mowers also saw significant action in the NHL with Nashville, with
whom he signed as a free agent before the season. Utah's Rob
Bonneau, a former UMass standout, was second . . . Dave Hymovitz
was a second-team selection at left wing to the IHL's postseason
all-star squad. The former Boston College standout ranked second in
the league with 46 goals for Indianapolis . . . For the second time
in three years, Houston's Greg Hawgood earned honors as the top
defenseman in the ``I.'' The former Bruin had 74 points and led all
IHL blueliners with 13 power-play goals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rarely do minor leagues stand pat from season to season, and the
AHL is no exception. Two expansion teams, Wilkes-Barre, Pa., and
Louisville, Ky., will be joining the league, and Fredericton will
become the Quebec Citadelles next year. Adirondack, a league member
for 20 years, will shut down operations for a year before moving to
Rossmore, Ohio, for the 2000-01 season, joining Hampton Roads, Va.
Amid all the changes, it's significant to note that the term
``large market,'' common in the major leagues, has begun to creep
into minor league vernacular and applies to about half of next
season's AHL teams, which will play in arenas that seat more than
10,000 . . . Musical affiliations: Lowell will have a new parent
club in Los Angeles next season, though the New York Islanders will
continue to use the Lock Monsters as a secondary team. With the
Kings switching to Lowell, Springfield will go with Phoenix as its
sole affiliate. Worcester recently signed a five-year deal to
continue with St. Louis, and Portland dropped Chicago as a
secondary feeder but will maintain its relationship with
Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
