<HEADLINE>
BEHRENS FINALLY NOTICED 
</HEADLINE>
 CAP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Behrens, whose accomplishments in the handicap ranks
hadn't exactly set the racing industry on fire, beat a hot horse
when he defeated Real Quiet, last year's Kentucky Derby and
Preakness winner, in Saturday's $600,000 Massachusetts Handicap at
Suffolk Downs. Now maybe Behrens will be noticed.
</P>
<P>
   The MassCap marked the third straight major victory for Behrens,
a son of Pleasant Colony, who came to Boston off tallies in the
Gulfstream Park Handicap Feb. 27 and the Oaklawn Handicap April 3.
Next for Behrens, who is trained by Jim Bond and ridden by Jorge
Chavez, could be the $1 million Hollywood Gold Cup June 27, which
would mean another meeting with Real Quiet. The winner of the
Pimlico Special May 8, Real Quiet finished third in the MassCap
after falling back from a three-horse battle that included European
invader Running Stag, who just missed going gate-to-wire. Behrens,
the second choice at 9-10 ($3.80 to win), covered the mile and
one-eighth in 1:49 to prevail by a half-length.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great race,'' said Bond Sunday. ``The English horse
really ran a terrific race. To be in the same league as Cigar and
Skip Away, it's an honor. I'm hoping to come back next year and try
it again. I'd like to be able to repeat in the MassCap, like those
two (Cigar won in 1995 and '96, Skip Away in 1997 and '98). I told
the owners (the Rudlein Stable and William Clifton) we'd be right
there, that we just might be favored over Real Quiet (who was the
choice at 4-5). I think that most people know when we point for a
race, six or seven weeks out, we are aiming to win it, and that
we'll run well.''
</P>
<P>
   Behrens was the leader of the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association's Champions series entering the MassCap, and he picked
up six more points with the triumph, for a total of 28. NTRA series
points can be worth up to $5,000 each, depending on how a horse
runs in the $1 million Pacific Classic at Del Mar Aug. 29, the
concluding event in the series. The Hollywood Gold Cup is worth 20
points, and that may be enough to lure Bond from his Saratoga
sanctuary, where he is stabled, even though Behrens doesn't like to
ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to talk to the owners, get back and see the horse, and
see what his next couple of workouts look like,'' said Bond. ``But
I'm thinking of the Hollywood Gold Cup or the Suburban (at Belmont
July 5, which also is in the series, but offers six points). As
I've been saying, our long-term goal is the Breeders' Cup.'' That's
at Gulfstream Park Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The MassCap contestants came out of the race in good shape.
Behrens was vanned back to Saratoga Saturday night and arrived
safely Sunday morning. ``He's out here on the grass,'' said
assistant trainer Maxine Owen. ``He's happy.'' Real Quiet and
Running Stag, who might come right back in the Stephen Foster at
Churchill Downs June 12 against Silver Charm and Victory Gallop,
vanned to Belmont Park Sunday morning . . . Suffolk, which closes
Saturday, will offer Fan Appreciation Day Wednesday. Admission and
preferred parking will be free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
