<SLUG> BC-RAC-INDIANAPOLIS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON RUNS OUT OF GAS AT END 
</HEADLINE>
 500-GORDON-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Robby Gordon knew he had the fastest car in
Sunday's 83d running of the Indianapolis 500. After all, it was the
car Greg Ray used as his backup and recorded the fastest official
lap (227.192 miles per hour) in the week of practice leading up to
last weekend's time trials.
</P>
<P>
   As he toured the 2.5-mile oval at Indianapolis Motor Speedway
with one blistering lap after another, driving relentlessly toward
his first Indy 500 victory, Gordon didn't know if he had enough
fuel in his car to carry him across the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon radioed his crew: Should he pit with the rest of the
leaders on Lap 170? Was it worth it to stay out and vault to the
lead? Would he have enough fuel in his 35-gallon tank to make it to
the end?
</P>
<P>
   ``Fuel is OK,'' came the reply from Gordon's co-owner, John
Menard. ``Don't worry about it. Just drive, drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon did, but his car sputtered and ran out of fuel with one
lap remaining, delivering Sunday's Indy 500 victory to Kenny Brack.
</P>
<P>
   It was the culmination of a whirlwind weekend for Gordon, who
pulled double duty by driving in Saturday's Motorola 300 CART
series race in Madison, Ill., where he finished 27th after crashing
on Lap 11. He sustained a bruised right calf, but appeared none
worse for the wear Sunday after finishing fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost got one,'' said Menard, who has invested millions in
his quest for an elusive Indy 500 title. ``We could have come in on
the yellow and been in a nice position, but we finished fourth with
all the wheels on it. It could have been worse. Our car showed that
we had enough fuel, but how many times does this race go the last
25 laps without a yellow?''
</P>
<P>
   Menard gambled it wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept praying for a yellow,'' Menard said, managing a weak
smile. ``But we put on a spectacle for the fans. That's what racing
is all about. I love it. If I live long enough, one of these days,
I'm gonna win this race. But you know hindsight is 20/20. We did
what we did. If there had been a yellow, we'd be drinking milk and
having a great time. But we're still having a great time. We had a
great time today.''
</P>
<P>
   It would've been better had a yellow flag come out.
</P>
<P>
   But one never did, leaving Gordon to try and wring out every
last bit of fuel from his tank. Gordon said his fuel gauge showed
there were 2.3 gallons left. ``That was enough for one lap,'' he
said. ``And I ran out in Turn 4. But I figured I could've used .3
gallons just getting the car back to the start/finish line to take
the white flag and the next two to maybe make it all the way around
and just coast home in Turn 4. It just wasn't our day.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was left to deal with the disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I want to sit here and cry,'' he said, his voice
cracking. ``But what can you do? It's not going to change the way
things are going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, rationalizing, Gordon said, ``I could go and kick the car,
but that's not going to do anything except make John mad at me. I
could go and punch one of the guys on the crew for not putting
enough fuel in the car, but what's that going to do? We have
another race to go, and we've got to suck it up, and get over it,
and do everything we can, like we did this year, to try and win the
500.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 0124EDT &QL; 
