r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-ROYALS-LAD     05-31 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ROYALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO STEPS UP FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mo Vaughn looks at the empty seats every night
and knows there is only one way to fill them.
</P>
<P>
   Drama helps, of course, but winning is more important and Vaughn
provided both Sunday night with a three-run homer that gave the
Anaheim Angels a 4-3 victory over the Kansas City Royals in front
of 31,429 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   For Vaughn, it was his 13th of the year, fourth in the past five
games and ninth in the last 18. But he knows he is only a novelty
act if the Angels don't win games like this against opponents
struggling to reach .500 like they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Boston the fans showed up whether we won or lost and you
would get spoiled,'' said Vaughn, who now has 38 RBI in his first
36 games with the club. ``Here you have to win to get fans to come
out and maybe that's the way it should be. You should never take
anything for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching Vaughn miss the first three weeks of the season
with a sprained left ankle, manager Terry Collins knows he'll never
look at his designated hitter that way. Not with Tim Salmon, Jim
Edmonds and Gary DiSarcina on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Not with the 24-26 team struggling to score runs and division
rivals Texas and Seattle starting to play well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a marvel just to watch him,'' Collins said. ``His
preparation and his determination are incredible. Every night he
shows us why we got him.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's fifth-inning shot made a winner out of Omar Olivares,
who pitched eight innings for his team-leading sixth victory. Troy
Percival came on in the ninth to record his 14th save. Percival,
who allowed a bases-clearing double in Saturday night's game, now
has three saves on this homestand that continues tonight against
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn credited Olivares and Darin Erstad, who emerged from a
slump with a leadoff home run in the first against Royals
left-hander Jose Rosado. Vaughn also cited the production of No.2
hitter Randy Velarde, who went 3 for 4 batting in front of him and
has five hits in the past two games, both victories.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake about who the hero was. Royals manager Tony
Muser didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo Vaughn is going to be in the Hall of Fame,'' he said. ``If
you set the table for him, this is what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosado, who entered the game 4-0 against the Angels lifetime
with a 2.38 ERA, agreed. He liked the pitch he threw, a fastball in
on the hands. Vaughn crowds the plate but got the head of his
36-ounce bat out quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want him to beat you, but I would throw that pitch
again, right in the same spot,'' Rosado said. ``It was right where
I wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could not be said on Erstad's homer.
</P>
<P>
   After going 2 for 18 to start this homestand, Erstad led off the
Angels first determined to make contact. He fouled off six pitches
before turning on a 2-2 fastball and driving it into the
right-field stands for his fifth home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was his best at-bat of the season,'' Collins said. ``He
battled at a time of the game when you can't see the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Velarde followed with a base hit, but Rosado settled down to
retire 12 of the next 14 batters.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals, who dropped below .500 after Saturday's 4-3 loss,
couldn't get anything going against Olivares. He was 0-4 lifetime
against Kansas City, but for most of the game kept the hitters off
balance.
</P>
<P>
   His only trouble spots came in the fifth and the eighth. Leading
1-0, Olivares walked three batters in the fifth and designated
hitter Mike Sweeney blooped a two-run single to right to give the
Royals a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by Vaughn's three-run homer in the bottom of the
fifth, Olivares retired nine consecutive batters before Jermaine
Dye hit his 11th homer with two out in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   He turned the game over to Percival. Unlike Saturday night, the
Royals didn't rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting that final out, that is the most rewarding thing for
me,'' Vaughn said. ``They brought me here to do a job, It's not
going to happen every night, but I don't look at it as pressure. I
see it as fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
