<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVARES REMAINS AGGRESSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels manager Terry Collins cringed
when Omar Olivares walked three batters in the fifth inning Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Collins had his bullpen busy, but he knew he had his most
consistent starter on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares allowed a two-run bloop single to Mike Sweeney, but
lasted eight innings and used Mo Vaughn's three-run homer to beat
the Kansas City Royals 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't always sharp, especially that inning, but usually he
was around the plate enough to keep him out there,'' Collins said.
``He gave us eight innings and got us to (Troy Percival). That is
all we can ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   The matchup between Olivares and the Royals' Jose Rosado was
curious. Olivares was 0-4 lifetime against Kansas City, Rosado was
4-0 vs. the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't just Vaughn's home run that made the difference.
Olivares spoke to pitching coach Dick Pole after the fifth and made
some adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick got him to stay aggressive and to stay with his sinker,''
Collins said. ``He got away from that a little but his performance
tonight gave us a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares, who hasn't lost since May 7, was coming off a 4-1
victory over Baltimore, where he lasted eight innings and allowed
just one run. He is the only Angels pitcher to throw a complete
game this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for one bad inning, I was pleased,'' Olivares said. ``I
went away from my sinker, but after Vaughn's home run I got focused
again. I wanted to finish the game, but I got us to Troy and that's
what matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Unsung hero: Randy Velarde is batting in front of Vaughn, which
means plenty of fastballs. Pitchers don't want to risk putting
Velarde on base and give Vaughn another chance for an RBI.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two games, both victories, that has translated into
five hits in eight at-bats. Sunday night it meant a two-out single
in the fifth that kept the inning alive and set up Vaughn's homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is making contact and taking advantage of the situation,''
Vaughn said. ``That is why this is such a team game. If he doesn't
do his job, I never get a chance to do mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Darin Erstad's leadoff homer in the first marked the
second time this season an Angels player has opened a game with a
home run. Orlando Palmeiro did it April 9 vs. Texas.... Steve
Decker, who was leading the Triple-A Pacific Coast League with 12
homers when his contract was purchased May 21, batted cleanup
Sunday and went 0 for 3. ``The reason I did that was because I
wanted a right-handed bat between Mo and Garret (Anderson),''
Collins said. ``He showed in the minors that he has some pop. He is
a quality hitter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 0138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
