<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7101 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-JONES-NIKE-SIDER-     05-31 2255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-JONES-NIKE-SIDER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Jones' affiliation with Nike reflects growing trend in recruiting
battles
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DANNY ROBBINS
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   As the University of Iowa assistant football coach responsible
for recruiting in the Houston area last year, Gene Jones brought a
wealth of experience and perspective to the job.
</P>
<P>
   A native Houstonian, Jones had coached track or football at the
college level for 20 years. In four years as Iowa's recruiting
coordinator and wide receivers and tight ends coach, he had been in
the hunt for numerous high school stars and had lured his share to
Iowa City.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing in his experience had prepared him for what he
encountered when he tried to sign Joel Harris, a defensive lineman
from Angleton who was one of the state's top recruits in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business, you're always competing against the Notre
Dames, the Colorados, the Texas A&AMP;Ms for the services of a young
man,'' he said. ``But, Lord knows, you don't think you have to deal
with a shoe company.''
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting Harris meant dealing with Elaine Jones, director of
the Nike-backed Houston Jaguars summer basketball program. And
dealing with her, according to Gene Jones, meant hearing how
important it was for Harris to play for a college team with the
Nike Swoosh on its shoes and jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Jones said Elaine Jones presented herself as being the
legal guardian of Harris and his older brother, James, a basketball
player at the University of Memphis, and stated repeatedly how
Joel's interests would be best served by attending a school
affiliated with Nike.
</P>
<P>
   Under Hayden Fry, Iowa's head football coach for 20 years before
his retirement at the end of last season, the Hawkeyes football
program was affiliated with Reebok.
</P>
<P>
   Harris ultimately signed with Colorado, a school that has been
heavily involved with Nike since entering into a sponsorship
agreement with the shoe giant valued at $6 million five years ago.
Red-shirted last season, Harris is projected to be a backup nose
tackle for the Buffaloes this year.
</P>
<P>
   Examining Elaine Jones' involvement in Harris' recruitment, the
Chronicle found she signed the player's Colorado letter of intent
as his legal guardian with no legal or written authority to do so.
</P>
<P>
   One of several Iowa assistants who lost their positions when Fry
departed, Gene Jones talked recently about Iowa's bid to sign
Harris as if it is something he will not soon forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had migraine headaches after that particular recruiting
episode,'' he said, ``because that Nike thing kept coming up in our
face. I'd never had that happen to me in all the years I'd been
recruiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' conduct is a window to the role a shoe company can play
in directing an elite high school athlete to a favored college.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly relevant in college basketball, where NCAA rules
have put a premium on summer recruiting and shoe companies and
their surrogates have gained extraordinary influence, the issue is
not a new one in college sports or in the world of Elaine Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana coach Bob Knight, in an interview with former Notre Dame
coach Digger Phelps broadcast by ESPN in January, called the
involvement of shoe companies in recruiting ``as bad a thing as has
happened in college basketball in the last 10 years'' and
illustrated his point with an apparent reference to Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our assistant coaches asked a woman from Texas about the
possibility of a kid on the team she's sponsoring perhaps being
interested in coming to Indiana,'' Knight told Phelps. ``Her first
question was, `Well, what shoe does Indiana wear?' Our coaches
said, `Well, we wear Converse shoes.' Her answer was, `Well, I'm
really partial to coaches who wear Nike shoes.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Nike is pumping money into this program, in what they call
their `grass-roots' program, and the return for them is that the
sponsor is going to direct anybody on that team who might have the
wherewithal to play college basketball to a school that wears Nike
shoes, going all the way up to the chance that if this kid becomes
a professional prospect he is so heavily involved with Nike that
Nike gets the (endorsement) contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike spokesman Dean Stoyer said the company frowns on its
representatives pushing athletes to colleges with Nike ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to see kids have the opportunity to play sports
and get an education,'' he said. ``What kind of shoes a school
wears should not have an impact on that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight did not respond to interview requests for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' involvement with Joel Harris was rooted in her ties to
his older brother, James.
</P>
<P>
   The two brothers were born in the Virgin Islands and raised in
Angleton by their mother, Violet Harris, a certified nurse's aide.
</P>
<P>
   James Harris, 6 feet 9 inches and 240 pounds, played basketball
at Angleton High School and became part of Jones' program in the
summer of 1995. Following that summer, he moved to Westbury
Christian School in Houston for his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   At Westbury Christian, Harris joined a team that included Jones'
nephew, Trey Austin, and helped the Wildcats win the Texas
Association of Private and Parochial Schools (TAPPS) Class 2A state
title.
</P>
<P>
   Westbury Christian coach Greg Glenn said Jones approached him
about taking Harris, citing the fact the player needed an
``environment'' similar to that of her nephew. According to Glenn,
Jones said she had been ``granted authority from the mother'' to
enroll James at the school.
</P>
<P>
   As a TAPPS school, Westbury Christian is not subject to the
residency and eligibility requirements imposed on the athletic
programs at Texas' public high schools by the University
Interscholastic League.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his year at Westbury Christian, Harris signed with
the University of Texas-El Paso, a school with a basketball program
affiliated with Nike, but never enrolled, choosing instead to
attend the University of Memphis, also a Nike school. He sat out a
year at Memphis and became eligible in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   A copy of Harris' UTEP letter of intent, obtained by the
Chronicle from the school under the Texas Open Records Act, shows
Jones signed the document in the place designated for the player's
parent or legal guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Joel (pronounced Jo-El) Harris, a 6-3, 275-pound defensive
lineman, lost his eligibility to play high school football at
Angleton as a senior in 1997 because of a mixup over his age but
was regarded as one of the state's premier college prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Although he remained enrolled at Angleton for the 1997-98 school
year, he spent much of his time at Jones' home in Sugar Land,
according to Mark Wright, Angleton's football coach.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said he directed all inquiries about Harris from college
football coaches to Jones at Harris' request.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called the mother (Violet Harris) a couple of times but
never talked to her,'' Wright said. ``I always tried to get in
touch with her. Then at one point Joel told me, `Coach, my other
mother is the one who's handling everything. If you need anything,
call her.' That's what he always called her (Jones) _ his `other
mother.'''
</P>
<P>
   For Gene Jones, the former Iowa assistant coach, the situation
quickly turned frustrating due to Elaine Jones' constant references
to the fact the Hawkeyes were affiliated with Reebok and not Nike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept trying to ask, in a polite way, `What's the difference
whether he's wearing Nike or Reebok shoes? What influence does Nike
have on his coming to any institution and being able to play
football, get an education, get a degree?''' he said. ``She would
say things like, `Well, I know if he went to a Nike school, if the
coaches weren't treating him right, all I'd have to do is call Nike
and they would check into it, make sure he's being treated right.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Ma'am, I don't care whether it's Reebok or Nike, he's
going to be treated right by most institutions, and, if he's not,
you can come in and check yourself. I don't see how a shoe company
is going to do that.' She'd say, `Well, I'm loyal to them (Nike),
and they've been loyal to me. I'd feel good about them taking care
of it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We went round and round. She'd keep saying, `He really likes
you guys and stuff, but I don't know. The sticking point is you
guys are Reebok.'''
</P>
<P>
   Annoying as the situation might have been, it didn't cause Iowa
to stop recruiting Harris, Gene Jones said, because the player
seemed genuinely interested in attending the university. According
to the former Hawkeyes assistant, Harris had a good visit to Iowa
and indicated he would visit Colorado only because of his ``mom.''
</P>
<P>
   When Harris informed Iowa of his decision to attend Colorado,
Gene Jones said, he cited the relationships he had formed with
several members of the CU coaching staff and the fact his ``mom''
wanted him to attend a Nike school.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Colorado and Nike entered into a six-year sponsorship
agreement. Under terms of the deal, described in depth under the
heading ``CU and Nike'' in the school's 1998 football media guide,
Nike provides the CU athletic department with equipment and
financial support, including $2.7 million in cash over the course
of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hundley, who recruited Harris as an assistant coach at
Colorado and has since moved to the University of Washington, said
he knew the Iowa coaches believed Jones was trying to direct Harris
to a Nike school but never felt that way himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a pretty good heart, I think,'' he said. ``Beyond
that, I don't know. It's hard to read personalities in that amount
of time. I just always thought she was somebody who cared (about
young people). She wasn't going the extra mile for Joel because of
his future. He was an older kid who hadn't played the year
before.''
</P>
<P>
   When Harris signed with Colorado during a ceremony at the
Angleton Independent School District office, Jones was a
participant, but Violet Harris, the player's mother, was not
present.
</P>
<P>
   During the ceremony, Jones was photographed signing Harris'
letter of intent.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing her sons' relationship with Jones recently, Violet
Harris said she signed a document giving Jones ``parental guidance
or custody or something'' relating to James, her eldest son, but
had done nothing in that regard for Joel.
</P>
<P>
   She said she suggested that something be put in writing giving
Jones the authority to act on James' behalf after an incident in
which James, then attending Westbury Christian, needed medical
attention in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she was aware that Jones had signed James' UTEP letter
of intent, Violet Harris said she did not know her eldest son had
even signed with the school ``until you just told me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she never signed anything giving Jones parental
authority for Joel, she said she had no problem with Jones handling
his recruitment and signing his Colorado letter of intent as his
legal guardian.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knows more about sports than I do,'' she said. ``I want my
children in her hands.''
</P>
<P>
   A national letter of intent is essentially a contract stopping
the recruiting process and binding a recruit and a school for one
academic year. Letters of intent are administered by the Collegiate
Commissioners Association and not the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   According to Carl Hicks, a Southeastern Conference assistant
commissioner and the Collegiate Commissioners Association's
administrator for the National Letter of Intent program, the
individual signing a letter of intent as a legal guardian must at
the very least have something in writing from one of the
student-athlete's natural parents.
</P>
<P>
   If the individual signing a letter of intent as a
student-athlete's parent or legal guardian does not have the
standing to do so and the student-athlete has yet to enroll, the
letter can be declared null and void, Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   Violet Harris, in her portrayal of Jones, also spoke of a woman
with virtually no limits to her generosity.
</P>
<P>
   According to Violet Harris, Jones helped James Harris purchase
two vehicles _ including a van on his 21st birthday _ paid his
tuition at Westbury Christian and helped with his tuition at the
University of Memphis when he was enrolled at the school without a
scholarship in his first year.
</P>
<P>
   She said Jones also has been paying James' apartment rent in
Memphis during the 1998-99 school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``God sent an angel to me,'' she said. ``I don't care what
anybody says about her.''
</P>
<P>
   The assistance described by Violet Harris might conflict with
NCAA regulations regarding the amateurism of student-athletes and
could impact her son's eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   According to Steve Mallonee, an NCAA director of membership
services, student-athletes at NCAA schools are barred from
receiving cash, vehicles and other items of value based on their
athletic ability.
</P>
<P>
   He said the rules allow student-athletes to receive such
benefits from individuals upon whom they are naturally or legally
dependent or individuals with whom they have relationships that
predate the recruiting process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (NCAA) membership believes if you get something from
someone who is truly an established family friend, someone you knew
before you became a good athlete or a (college) prospect, there's
no reason to question it,'' he said. ``But when individuals are
attaching themselves to kids later in the process, after they are
of prospect age and the relationship is developing out of
athletics, then the benefits involved have to be scrutinized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
