<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-LONG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BEACH ST. RUNS OUT OF PITCHING
</HEADLINE>
 BEACH-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ You don't mess with Texas, the folks in
these parts like to say, and on Sunday Long Beach State's Dirtbags
got a thorough lesson in good ol' boy hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   Needing to win one game to take that next big step on the road
to Omaha and the College World Series, the Dirtbags lost twice to
Texas A&AMP;M, in resounding fashion, too, and now they go home, their
season ended.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies (50-15) rebounded mightily from their loss Saturday
to the 49ers to win Sunday afternoon, 9-5, and force a deciding
game Sunday night in the double-elimination NCAA Regional
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies wasted little time taking command, spinning the
Dirtbags for an eight-run third inning on their way to a 17-7
victory and a berth in next weekend's Super Regional against
Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   The Dirtbags ended their season 35-25 and with little doubt
where to place their emphasis for next season: pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies took apart the 49ers' two starters, Kasey Olenberger
and Russel Rohlicek, pounding out 11 hits in the first game, 19 in
the second.
</P>
<P>
   The loss matched the 49ers' most-lopsided setback all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran into a buzz saw,'' understated Dave Snow, the 49ers'
coach. ``I tip my hat to the Texas Aggies. I know what it's like to
experience the joy of winning two games on Sunday, because we did
that last year.''
</P>
<P>
   That was at Stanford, where the Dirtbags stormed out of the
loser's bracket to eliminate North Carolina State, then Alabama,
and move on to the CWS. There was no such storm this time around,
except by the Aggies' batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really exposed our shortage of pitching,'' acknowledged
Snow. ``It was like we were playing the extra game, not Texas
A&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Aggies, didn't use more than two pitchers in any of
the five games they played, and two were complete games. The
Dirtbags, in four games, never used fewer than three. And not one
starter lasted past the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the championship game Sunday night, the Dirtbags actually
broke out on top, leading, 3-0, after 2{ innings, with a run in the
first inning and two more in the top of the third. But they
couldn't muster a knockout blow either inning, leaving the bases
loaded in the first, then two more in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``That took the air out of us little,'' Snow said, sizing up the
turnaround first inning, when right fielder Daylan Holt robbed Abel
Orozco, crashing against the wall for the third out. ``That was a
big momentum swing right there.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a bigger one in the third inning. That's when it all
came crashing down on the Dirtbags.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen Aggies paraded to the plate in the wild third, and eight
of them scored, four on Steven Truitt's grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first of three homers off of reliever Jason Berni,
who took over for Rohlicek in the third inning. It was the fourth
homer of the Regional by tournament MVP Truitt, all of them against
the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies jumped on Berni again in the fifth. Holt followed an
error and a walk with his 32nd home run, giving him four RBI for
the game, 11 for the tournament --- and an incredible 98 for the
season, a Texas A&AMP;M record. John Scheschuk followed with his ninth
homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies poured it on, with two more runs in the seventh
inning and two more in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The Dirtbags might have avoided Saturday night's embarrassment
had their defense stayed together better in the first game Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wobbly start by Olenberger --- he gave up four runs
on four hits, six walks and three hit batters in just five innings
--- the 49ers actually had a one-run lead an inning after he left.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Dobbs' 10th homer of the season and third of the
tournament, a two-blow in the bottom of the sixth, lifted the
Dirtbags on top, 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   But Dobbs' throwing error and a passed ball on catcher Mike Hota
led to two unearned runs in the seventh off of reliever Dan Thomas
(0-3), who absorbed the loss; Dobbs' second error of the game
helped produce two more runs in the eighth, and the Aggies added
one more in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Texas A&AMP;M's Khalid Ballouli, a freshman right-hander,
slammed the door on the Dirtbags after Dobbs' homer, retiring the
next 10 batters in order and allowing only more hit for his first
complete game all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the game, then let it get away toward the end,''
Snow said. ``We didn't play good defense behind Thomas.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor pitch well, either.
</P>
<P>
   DIRTBAGS NOTES: Dobbs and center fielder Terrmel Sledge were
selected to the all-tournament team. ... Catcher Bryan Kennedy
sustained a bruise to his right foot on Saturday and was held out
of the first game. ... The 19 hits allowed by the Dirtbags in the
second game were the second-most allowed in a game all season (they
gave up 20 in an 11-10 loss at Sacramento State on May 9. ... The
only time the 49ers lost by as many as 10 runs was April 4 at
Nevada, 18-8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
