<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7103 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-JONES-HNS &LR;      05-31 3852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-JONES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Elaine Jones' pipeline to Nike has made her a force in Houston high
school basketball recruiting, but her maneuvers might have cost
Williowridge a shot at the state title.
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DANNY ROBBINS
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   A few days before the start of the school year last August, two
young men _ one 6-8, the other 6-7 _ were enrolled at Willowridge
High School by the same 50-year-old woman.
</P>
<P>
   The young men, Ivan McFarlin and David Anderson, had come from
different backgrounds _ McFarlin having grown up in Houston,
Anderson in Puerto Rico _ and were connected only by the fact they
had played basketball during the summer on a team organized by the
woman who was enrolling them, Elaine Jones.
</P>
<P>
   They were able to enroll at Willowridge because Jones had been
granted power of attorney for that purpose and had represented that
the two young men would be living with her at a residence in the
Chasewood section of Missouri City.
</P>
<P>
   While some might have considered such an arrangement unusual,
perhaps even suspicious, Willowridge personnel barely gave it a
second thought. McFarlin and Anderson were placed in the 11th grade
and slated for spots on the school's basketball team, regarded as
one of the strongest in the state. No alarms went off.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months later, in the wake of an embarrassing eligibility
snafu and a ruined season, some in the Fort Bend Independent School
District are still trying to understand why.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Getting involved with Jones meant Willowridge was dealing with
the director of the Houston Jaguars, a Nike-sponsored summer
basketball team for elite high school players.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting much of what she represented as fact on official
documents meant Willowridge was setting itself up for a fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we jumped off a cliff with this thing,'' said Keith
Kilgore, the Fort Bend ISD athletic director. ``I don't think we've
dealt internally with anything like this before.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilgore and others have been trying to sort out the details of
Jones' relationship with Willowridge since the February decision
that rendered McFarlin ineligible and caused the Eagles, then the
Chronicle's top-ranked Class 5A team, to forfeit 28 victories.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling occurred after Fort Bend ISD administrators became
aware Jones had represented herself as McFarlin's legal guardian
without having obtained such standing in court.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-8 forward, McFarlin returned to the Fort Bend ISD last fall
after spending his first two high school seasons at Girls and Boys
Prep Academy, a Houston charter school, where he had emerged as one
of the top players in the state. McFarlin's mother and stepfather,
Delphine and Jerry Jordan, live near Willowridge, but their
neighborhood is in the Dulles attendance zone.
</P>
<P>
   Because Jones was not McFarlin's legal guardian, the player was
in violation of the University Interscholastic League rule stating
that a student enrolled by an individual other than his or her
parents is not immediately eligible for UIL competition unless the
individual has been the student's court-appointed legal guardian
for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the implications for McFarlin and the Willowridge
basketball team, which failed to gain a berth in the playoffs, the
imbroglio has raised lingering questions about the judgment of
those at Willowridge who knew of Jones' link to McFarlin and
Anderson and never saw it as a potential problem.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly troubling for some Fort Bend ISD officials was the
fact they were never informed of McFarlin's relationship with Jones
even after they had asked Willowridge administrators during the
fall semester to check information indicating Anderson was living
at a home Jones owns in the Sweetwater section of Sugar Land, which
is part of the Clements attendance zone.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in Puerto Rico, the 6-7 Anderson came to
Willowridge after spending the 1997-98 school year in Stratford,
Conn., where he lived with his stepbrother.
</P>
<P>
   After the issue of Anderson's residency was raised, the player
was withheld from varsity competition at Willowridge. He withdrew
from school at the semester break and later enrolled at Hargrave
Military Academy in Chatham, Va.
</P>
<P>
   According to Arthur R. Culver, a former Fort Bend ISD area
superintendent who had oversight of Willowridge last fall, the
Anderson matter should have prompted Willowridge personnel to
disclose McFarlin's relationship with Jones to school district
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what really upset me about the whole thing,'' he said
recently. ``They never told me Elaine enrolled both of them,
because, to me, if somebody comes in with two 6-8 players and
neither one is her true son, that should be (cause for) immediate
suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
   Culver, now superintendent of schools in Longview, said there
was another occasion last fall when he asked Willowridge principal
Charles R. Polk and the school's boys basketball coach, Ronnie
Courtney, specifically how McFarlin had been enrolled. He said they
responded by saying McFarlin lived with his parents in the
Willowridge attendance zone.
</P>
<P>
   When the facts relating to McFarlin's enrollment came to light
months later, Culver said, he was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be frank with you, sir, I just felt like I was flat-out
lied to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Polk, Willowridge's principal since January 1996, said he might
have spoken to Culver about McFarlin last fall but did not give the
district administrator reason to believe McFarlin was living in the
Willowridge attendance zone with his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not lie and I did not cover up,'' he said. ``That's
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Courtney did not respond to interview requests for this story. &QL; 
 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Willowridge's alliance with Jones was a product of basketball's
so-called ``shoe war,'' the heated competition between shoe
companies _ primarily Nike and Adidas _ to gain marketing points in
the sport.
</P>
<P>
   The competition starts at the youth level, particularly the
summer tournaments and camps for rising high school stars.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA rules make it necessary for college coaches to evaluate
prospects mainly during a three-week window in July. As a result,
the month is a whirlwind of tournaments and camps designed as
showcases for high school talent.
</P>
<P>
   Motivated by the hunt for the next Michael Jordan, Nike and
Adidas sponsor virtually every summer team, camp and tournament and
compete aggressively to lock up the top players.
</P>
<P>
   Because the summer recruiting period heightens the influence of
those who coach and organize summer teams _ individuals who do not
answer to the rules of the NCAA or state high school athletic
associations and whose motives might be questionable _ many high
school and college coaches would like to see it modified or
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The summer leagues, the AAU and all that stuff _ that's what's
got everything all screwed up,'' said Paul Graham, who recently
became head coach at Washington State after six years as an
assistant at Oklahoma State, ``because now you're dealing with
people who are trying to get something out of the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Clark Francis, who covers college basketball
recruiting extensively through his ``Hoop Scoop'' Web site and
column, some summer basketball operatives are looking for a
windfall while others are truly interested in helping young players
better themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big business,'' he said. ``A great player can wind
up in the NBA, get big bucks from Nike. There are a lot of things
that can potentially happen out of it (gaining a position of
influence with a player). Now if this were everyday America
business, would this be wrong? No. But everybody gets huffy because
you're dealing with kids who are 15, 16, 17, 18 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these people, their motives are for the right reasons.
They're doing great things for the kids. In other cases, the kids
are getting exploited.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis said summer operatives often direct players to certain
high schools, the idea being to help a school and eventually get
players from that school in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put a kid in High School A instead of High School B,
you're more likely to get all the players in that (High School A's)
program to play for your AAU team,'' he said. ``I give you a
player, you're going to give me players back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Jones' team, the Houston Jaguars, is one of about 40 of its kind
sponsored by Nike as part of the its ``grass-roots'' program,
described in company literature as an effort to increase
opportunities for players and help ease funding burdens for teams
and other organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, the Jaguars won the Nike Peach Jam Invitational, a
tournament in Augusta, Ga., and one of the most prestigious events
on the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' roster at the Georgia event included McFarlin and
Anderson as well as Antonio Fal, the former Waltrip guard who has
signed with the University of Houston; Quinton Ross, a 6-6 swingman
from Dallas Kimball who has signed with SMU; and Taliek Brown, a
point guard from New York City who will be a senior next season and
is expected to be one of the most sought-after players in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Jones declined to be interviewed at length by the Chronicle or
answer questions relating to her efforts to enroll McFarlin and
Anderson at Willowridge.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of brief phone conversations, she described how she
organized her summer basketball program eight years ago mainly
because of her nephew, Trey Austin, who was then moving through the
youth basketball ranks and has since gone on to play at Westbury
Christian School and the University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Calling herself a ``church-going, God-fearing person,'' Jones
said she believes her organization is as much about those values as
it is basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a gift that comes from God to minister his word to my
players,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other than her connection to Austin, there is little in Jones'
background to suggest a basketball CEO.
</P>
<P>
   In documents filed in November 1996 as part of a Chapter 13
bankruptcy proceeding she initiated three years earlier, she
described herself as divorced and unemployed. She listed her
monthly income as $3,500 from an annuity in the name of Melody
Roberts, her stepsister.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, 26, was severely burned in a house fire in Diboll in
1984 and filed suit in federal court in Beaumont against Carrier
Corp., the manufacturer of the furnace in the home at the time of
the blaze. The parties settled the suit in November 1985. Records
relating to the settlement were sealed by the court.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Jones became Roberts' legal guardian, according to
Harris County Probate Court records.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' bankruptcy papers show she previously owned and operated
a business that sold computer supplies in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' creditors included nine companies seeking payment for
outstanding debts relating to her computer-supply firm. Another
creditor was the Internal Revenue Service, which contended she had
failed to file income tax returns for the years 1987, 1988, 1989,
1990, 1991 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Stoyer, a Nike spokesman, said his company has had a
six-year relationship with Jones and supplies her team with free
shoes and equipment. Citing company policy, he declined to disclose
other aspects of the sponsorship arrangement, including the amount
Nike provides Jones for travel and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   He said Nike is aware of Jones' involvement in the McFarlin
eligibility case and believes she made an ``honest mistake'' based
on the assumption the power of attorney she obtained to enroll the
player at Willowridge would also allow him to be eligible under UIL
rules.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Although McFarlin had attended a charter school for two years,
he came to Willowridge with a growing basketball reputation.
Entering last season, he was ranked No. 8 on the list of the
state's top 50 juniors compiled by Texas Hoops newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Kunstadt, editor of Texas Hoops, remembers watching
McFarlin play at Girls and Boys Prep as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the only player they had,'' he said. ``They (the team)
got killed, but he had 30, 40 points.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was a different story, a player whose skills were just
developing and one who had yet to become known to recruiting
analysts or college coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in Puerto Rico, he spent the 1997-98 school year
in Stratford, Conn., where he lived with his stepbrother, a New
York City police officer, and was a reserve on a senior-dominated
Stratford High School team that lost only four games.
</P>
<P>
   Stratford coach Paul Dudzinski said he envisioned Anderson as a
starter in 1998-99 as well as a potential college prospect and was
shocked to learn in the middle of last summer that the player would
be leaving.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dudzinski, Anderson said he would be attending a
high school in Texas but seemed unsure which school it would be.
</P>
<P>
   Dudzinski said he initially thought the school would be Waltrip
because Anderson and Fal grew up in the same area of Puerto Rico
and knew each other there. Fal came to Houston from Puerto Rico in
1997 and played that summer for Jones' team before enrolling at
Waltrip.
</P>
<P>
   Dudzinski said Anderson also indicated Jones would become his
legal guardian.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were amazed at the whole thing,'' he said. ``I mean, where
are the parents?''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Fort Bend ISD registration forms for McFarlin and Anderson show
the players were enrolled at Willowridge by Jones last August and
that their parents had granted her power of attorney to do so.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fort Bend ISD policy, a student can be enrolled at
a school by an individual other than his or her parents if the
individual resides in the school's attendance zone and has obtained
power of attorney from the student's parents.
</P>
<P>
   The registration forms for McFarlin and Anderson, obtained by
the Chronicle from Fort Bend ISD under the Texas Open Records Act,
listed the same home address for both players, a residence in the
Chasewood section of Missouri City.
</P>
<P>
   The residence, located within the Willowridge attendance zone,
is one of two homes owned by Jones in Fort Bend County, according
to county records. Jones' other home is in Sweetwater, part of the
Clements attendance zone. County records show the taxable value of
the Chasewood home is $76,120 and that of the Sweetwater home is
$481,660.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 28, 1998, six months before McFarlin and Anderson were
enrolled at Willowridge using the Chasewood address, Jones filed a
notice in her bankruptcy case stating her home address had changed
to that of the Sweetwater residence.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also notified the Texas Secretary of State's office of the
change of address in a January 1998 document relating to her
organization's status as a nonprofit corporation.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bill Malinowski, Fort Bend ISD director of
administrative services, an individual using power of attorney to
enroll a student at a school in the district must reside at the
home address listed as that of the student on the student's
registration form. Signing a registration form with one address
while residing at another would be falsifying a government
document, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to enrolling McFarlin and Anderson, Jones signed UIL
Previous Athletic Participation forms for the players as their
parent or legal guardian.
</P>
<P>
   The UIL uses such forms to ensure that high school athletes
transferring to new schools are moving for reasons unrelated to
athletics.
</P>
<P>
   A check of district- and probate-court records in Fort Bend and
Harris counties by the Chronicle found no evidence of Jones having
taken the steps necessary to assume legal guardianship of either
player.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Jones placed McFarlin and Anderson at
Willowridge, the school received a sponsorship package from Nike
that included free shoes, apparel and other gear worth thousands of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Outlined in a Sept. 4 letter from Lynn Merritt, Nike's director
of high school programs, to Courtney, the Willowridge coach, the
sponsorship package included 30 pairs of shoes, 30 pairs of socks,
four pairs of coaches' shoes, 25 T-shirts, six coaches' polo
shirts, 20 travel bags, 24 hats and 15 warm-up suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again this year it is our goal to provide our elite
programs with the very best that Nike has to offer in the way of
performance footwear and apparel,'' Merritt wrote in the letter,
provided to the Chronicle by Fort Bend ISD in response to a request
for public information regarding Willowridge's relationship with
Nike.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fort Bend ISD policy requires schools to report all
donations to the district's Board of Trustees, there is no record
of Willowridge having reported the Nike merchandise to the board. &QL; 
 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Polk, the Willowridge principal, said he approved Jones' plans
to enroll McFarlin and Anderson after speaking to her as well as
McFarlin's mother, Delphine Jordan. He said he gave his approval
because he found that Jones had legitimate reasons, which he
declined to identify.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he said, he had no knowledge of Jones' relationship
with Nike or her involvement with summer basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it would have been prudent to question why the same
woman had obtained power of attorney for two students, one 6-8 and
the other 6-7, Polk responded:
</P>
<P>
   ``Your knowledge of Mrs. Jones is completely different from my
knowledge of Mrs. Jones. I did not know Mrs. Jones to be this
representative or that representative. I assumed her intent was the
best interests of these young men, and I proceeded accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Polk also said he was not aware McFarlin was a basketball
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm out of touch,'' he said. ``I did not know Ivan
McFarlin, did not know anything of his basketball skills before he
enrolled at Willowridge. It wasn't the focus of the
conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   Polk said he did not challenge Jones' assertion she was the
legal guardian for McFarlin and Anderson because at the time he
believed the power of attorney required for enrollment by Fort Bend
ISD was sufficient for UIL eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas public-school teacher and administrator since 1968, Polk
became Willowridge principal in January 1996 after 15 years as a
principal and assistant principal in Baytown. His son, Eric Polk,
was a star running back at Baytown Sterling and attends Sam Houston
State University on a football scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney was hired as Willowridge basketball coach in 1997 after
eight years as coach at Davis High School in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kilgore, the Fort Bend ISD athletic director, the
first he learned of Jones' involvement at Willowridge was a call he
received in October indicating Anderson was living at Jones' home
in Sweetwater. Kilgore declined to identify the caller.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving the call, Kilgore said, he asked Culver, then
the area superintendent with oversight for Willowridge, to check
out the caller's information.
</P>
<P>
   Kilgore said the matter caused Anderson to withdraw from school
at the semester break but did not prompt Polk or others at
Willowridge to inform the district that McFarlin also was connected
to Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, he said, the district had no reason to make
further inquiries regarding Jones' involvement at Willowridge and
did not do so until receiving a request for public information
regarding McFarlin and other basketball players at Fort Bend ISD
schools in January. The request was made by Matt Jackson, a UH
student researching a story for the school newspaper, the Daily
Cougar.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was told he (Anderson) was no longer participating, I
didn't delve into it anymore,'' Kilgore said. ``I wish I had.''
</P>
<P>
   Culver, who became superintendent in Longview in March, said he
first noticed McFarlin and Anderson when he visited the Willowridge
campus early in the fall semester and wandered into the gym during
an athletic period.
</P>
<P>
   When he asked Polk and Courtney about the two new players, he
said, he was told McFarlin lived with his parents in the
Willowridge attendance zone and Anderson lived with Jones in a home
she owned in the Willowridge zone.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, he said, he asked again about Anderson as a
result of Kilgore's request for information regarding the player's
residency.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Polk and Courtney) said, `Well, she (Jones) owns a home
in the Willowridge area,''' he said. ``I said, `Well, that's not
legal. It's not where she owns a home. He (Anderson) has to go to
school where she resides.'''
</P>
<P>
   Culver said he did not raise the subject of McFarlin at that
point because, based on his previous conversation with Polk and
Courtney regarding the player, he had no reason to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason they didn't tell me (the truth about
McFarlin) is because they knew how I would respond,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Polk acknowledged that McFarlin's connection to Jones was not
part of the discussion when the district sought information
regarding Anderson's residency but said there was no intent by
anyone at Willowridge to deceive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those (McFarlin and Anderson) were two different cases,'' he
said. ``Ivan McFarlin was in fact residing there (at the Chasewood
residence). Keith Kilgore had been alerted by somebody _ at
Clements, I think _ that Anderson was living near the Sweetwater
Country Club, but there was no reason to relate that to Ivan
McFarlin.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Culver's contention he was misled, Polk said he might
have discussed McFarlin with the administrator one afternoon last
fall in the Willowridge gym but did not say anything to make him
believe the player was living in the school's attendance zone with
his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the controversy is the fact McFarlin's enrollment at
Willowridge for most of the spring semester has been based on a
power of attorney granted to Ben Caldwell, a Missouri City resident
whose son, Chris Caldwell, was Willowridge's leading scorer as a
senior in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   The document, provided to the Chronicle by Fort Bend ISD, was
signed by Delphine Jordan on Jan. 26 _ six days after Fort Bend ISD
officials received the public-records request that caused scrutiny
of McFarlin's link to Jones and eight days before the player was
declared ineligible as a result of the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   McFarlin will be able to play for the Eagles as a senior next
season if he completes the school year at Willowridge and
legitimately lives at the Caldwell residence. He will not be
subject to the UIL rule requiring a court-appointed legal guardian
for eligibility because he will have been enrolled at Willowridge a
full year.
</P>
<P>
   Of McFarlin's present arrangement, Culver said: ``To me, it's
obvious you're playing games. Who does this guy really live with?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, where Willowridge High School basketball is concerned,
the question is one that apparently can't be asked enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm biased,'' Kilgore said recently, weariness in his voice.
``I want to think a lot of the things that have happened were due
to ignorance. At the same time, if people are knowingly breaking
rules, there should be consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle staff writer Sarah Hornaday contributed to this
report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
