<P>
   Here are the top stories from The New York Times News Service
report for PMs Monday, May 31.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, (888) 346-9867, opens at 7 a.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ART ADV: Graphics and photos have been sent, as indicated below,
to NYT graphic and photo subscribers. Clients needing
retransmissions or information, or non-subscribers seeking to
arrange individual purchases, should call (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL _ GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS-POLITICS (Washington) _ Older Americans, once among the
most loyal of Democratic voters in congressional elections, are
drifting toward the Republicans for a number of reasons. By Robin
Toner.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   GANSKE-PROFILE (Washington) _ Every session of the House of
Representatives has its own emblematic types. Maybe Rep. Greg
Ganske, R-Iowa, is a fitting symbol of the current House _ the
edgy, ever-shifting House where Republicans are trying to govern
with 222 votes out of 435, the slimmest majority in 45 years,
meaning that every vote counts. When a Greg Ganske gets frustrated
and decides to buck his leadership, as he did last week, it
matters. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (Seattle) _ Just as Congress is on the verge of
approving measures like background checks for gun buyers and safety
lock devices, gun-control measures that had been languishing in
many states are now advancing, from an Oregon plan to require
criminal background checks for people buying firearms at gun shows
to a bill that would make New Jersey the first state to require
that all handguns sold there have ``smart-gun'' features, allowing
a gun to be used only by its registered owner. By Sam Howe
Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOL-YOUTH (Undated) _ A look at a little-noticed fight over
whether to expand the federal drug-fighting agency's mandate to
alcohol abuse by young people. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   HONORARY-DEGREES (New York) _ A look at honorary degrees. To a
university, the honorary degree is a way to recognize achievements
of people respected within the institution as well to add glitter
to the ceremony. It is also a useful way to enhance a relationship
with someone who can benefit the university. By Karen W. Arenson.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-WEALTH (New York) _ In a city where the well-worn paths
to success have led through the trading floor or the ranks of large
media corporations, the emergence of sudden Internet-bred wealth
holds out the promise of much quicker rewards. It is exposing New
Yorkers to the Silicon Valley culture of entrepreneurial risk. And
it is prompting resentment, envy, and a scramble to be a part of
it. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   DIVORCE-MEDICINE (Washington) _ As modern medicine extends the
lives of people with chronic diseases (from diabetes to cystic
fibrosis), the rate of divorce among them is increasing, leaving a
growing number without income, health insurance, or support at
home, health analysts say. By Peter Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   BABY-SELLERS (New York) _ A look at the two women who ran the
Long Island baby-selling operation.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and four of his top officials have now been
indicted for war crimes in Kosovo. But by all accounts here, the
person with the most influence over him is his dreamy and
complicated wife, Mirjana Markovic, whose life-long sense of
persecution will only be intensified by this new threat to her
husband and her family. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ Developments concerning a
possible Serb strategy to place civilians and refugees near sites,
like bridges or military installations, that could be vulnerable to
NATO attack. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With map and photos.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ Four NATO warplanes bombed a major
bridge in southern Serbia Sunday, as the alliance seized on clear
skies to intensify daytime bombing raids across Yugoslavia, allied
officials said. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi, India) _ Update on Indian-Pakistani
fighting over Kashmir. Two days after Pakistan offered to hold
peace talks with India about the current crisis along the
cease-fire line in Kashmir, the Indians said on Sunday that they
are still unsure whether they want to participate in any such
negotiations. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-POLITICS SOWETO, South Africa _ A political cartoon in
South Africa shows the front-running presidential candidate, Thabo
Mbeki, dressed as Snow White looming with an unconcerned smile over
seven miserable dwarfs who represent the opposition parties. They
are a colorful lot. ``Grumpy'' depicts the often-cantankerous Zulu
Chief Mangosuthu Gatsha Buthelezi; ``Crazy'' is Gen. Constand
Viljoen, still pining for an Afrikaner homeland; ``Bully'' is Louis
Luyt, a fertilizer magnate turned rugby czar who has been fighting
with the government; ``Choppy'' is the Rev. Stanley Mogoba, a
Methodist bishop who has advocated chopping off the hands of
criminals. But all seven together may not collect one-third of the
vote in South Africa's second post-apartheid national elections on
Wednesday. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SETTLEMENTS (Jerusalem) _ Alarmed by 11th-hour moves by
the departing Israeli government to expand Jewish settlements,
Palestinian officials warned Israel's prime minister-elect, Ehud
Barak, Sunday that they would not resume peace negotiations without
a halt to settlement activity. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS DAY
</P>
