A7106 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIVATE-PLANE-CRASHES     05-31 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-PLANE-CRASHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANE CRASHES KILL 2 PEOPLE AND INJURE 7 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two people were killed and seven injured Sunday in two separate
small-plane crashes in New York and New Jersey. On Saturday, a
small passenger plane went down in New Jersey, killing two people.
</P>
<P>
   The first crash Sunday occurred in Montgomery, N.Y., about 50
miles north of New York City, at 3:45 p.m. The plane went down in a
field next to West Searsville Road in rural Orange County, said
Trooper Michael Wzintek of the New York State Police. The pilot and
the passenger were killed, Wzintek said. He did not identify them,
but said they were from New Jersey. Wzintek said he did not know
the type of plane that crashed or its destination.
</P>
<P>
   The second crash Sunday occurred in Piscataway, N.J., at 5:43
p.m., said Sgt. George Maurer of the Piscataway Police Department.
A single-engine Cessna 206 passenger plane crashed into a tree,
then fell into a house at Day and Vera Avenues, Maurer said. The
plane caught fire, and the pilot and four passengers were pulled
from the flames by neighbors and rescue workers.
</P>
<P>
   Two people on the plane were seriously burned and were flown by
helicopter to the Robert Wood Johnson University Hospital in New
Brunswick and then to Saint Barnabas Hospital in the Bronx. They
were in critical condition, said a spokeswoman for Robert Wood
Johnson. The three other people on the plane were in stable
condition at Robert Wood Johnson. Two people on the ground suffered
minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Maurer said that the plane had been based at Morristown Airport
and appeared to be headed there.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday afternoon, a plane went down in Hillsborough, N.J.,
killing two people. A 1969 single-engine piper that had taken off
from Central Jersey Airport crashed at the edge of the Roycebrook
Golf Course, about 3,500 feet from the runway's end, the
Hillsborough Township Police Department said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, John Jackson, 51, of Staten Island, was killed
immediately, as was the sole passenger, John E. Coleman Jr., 53, of
Laurelton, Queens, the police said. The plane was rented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
