<HEADER>
A7145 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     05-31 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER DAY, ANOTHER TOXIN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  YOU CAN LEARN so much from reading your newspaper (he says,
hopefully).
<P>
   In a recent story in this very paper, I learned a new word and a
new phrase that I'm sure everyone will find useful.
</P>
<P>
   The thousands of portable classrooms in California are made with
woodlike products, plastics and synthetics. The story says that
these materials outgas.
</P>
<P>
   Outgas, verb. These building materials and objects radiate or
give off airborne carcinogenic chemicals like benzene and
formaldehyde. By the end of the school day, some kids are
practically embalmed. You might say these children ingas.
</P>
<P>
   Or, if their bodies are able in some ways to partially detox
once they leave school, then every school day they regas.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, fortunately, is easy. Children in portable
classrooms should not inhale. But kids will be kids, as will
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Ingas is a handy word that should be expanded beyond this narrow
meaning, not that it's not wonderful in this narrow use, where it
helps bad news go down easier.
</P>
<P>
   You'd feel terrible sending your children to school in
classrooms where the furniture and linoleum were ``poisoning''
them. Or where the classroom was ``passing gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Outgassing could easily be expanded to use in politics. We've
all been struggling to describe the skill perfected by President
Clinton, where he seems to be saying something, but it turns out he
didn't really mean what we thought he said.
</P>
<P>
   And now we learn that Republican front-runner George W. Bush has
the same gift. Some observers call this Bushspeak, but that's not
fair because Junior  &LR; Bush didn't invent it, though he's good. Bush,
asked to define his position on the war in Bosnia, said, ``I
support winning.'' He didn't say by whom.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals' scrappy team of the '30s was known as
the Gashouse Gang, and an excellent name for one of those TV shows
where the experts argue politics would be The Outgas Gang.
</P>
<P>
   We can all get involved. For starters, it's time we retired the
crude term ``BSer.'' If someone is giving you information or
opinion you know to be wrong or exaggerated, and you know that they
know it's wrong or exaggerated, you can simply call outgas.
</P>
<P>
   Or the term can be used in milder contexts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What were you and your friends talking about in the corner,
honey?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we were just outgassing.''
</P>
<P>
   The news story on classrooms said that the outgassed organic
toxins in some cases are 15 times the level considered ``the
comfort zone.'' Yes, science has a comfort zone for human snorting
of formaldehyde.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you children comfortable with the number of micrograms of
formaldehyde per cubic meter of air in here, or should we all put
on our gas masks? Children? Children?''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the paper recently, the story of a woman who went to a
fertility clinic, had several of her fertilized eggs implanted and
gave birth to fraternal twins. One was the biological combo of her
and her husband, the other was the combo of a couple whose egg got
mixed with the first couple's batch. Oops!
</P>
<P>
   The author of the newspaper story, uncredited, called this
situation ``the embryo imbroglio.''
</P>
<P>
   Poetry. There is much fine literature hidden in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Take a recent wire-service story about 49ers backup quarterback
Jim Druckenmiller. He is accused of raping a woman who was drunk.
We pick up the story with the defense attorney named Caldwell-Bono
speaking to the judge, referring to the alleged victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to her statement at the hospital, she does not
remember anything after getting into the car,'' Caldwell-Bono told
Judge Ray Grubbs. ``She remembers waking up, and he was on top of
her. She did not tell him to stop. She let him finish. She did not
say help, and when they finished, she started to cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Matters notes, ``That paragraph is the best bad Hemingway
I've seen in The Chronicle in years.''
</P>
<P>
   Really, your newspaper is just bad news in a funny package.
People send me police-log items from small-town newspapers, and
they can be darn cute. But consider this from the Half Moon Bay
Review, submitted by Anne Weinberger:
</P>
<P>
   ``An incident of `gopher taunting' that resulted in the death of
one of the furry tunnel diggers at HMB High School has been
referred to the District Attorney's office for review.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students in PE class were teasing a gopher that kept
popping out of a hole in the field. A teacher warned them to be
nice to the animal, but one student kicked the gopher five feet
into the air, and another student kicked it, and the gopher wound
up dead.
</P>
<P>
   Hate crime? You be the judge. But there's a possibility these
kids were just overgassed.
</P>
<P>
   In coal mines, canaries in cages are more sensitive to dangerous
and odorless gases than are humans, so their death is a warning
signal (especially to other canaries).
</P>
<P>
   If a gopher is taunted and kicked to death on a school
playground, it could be a warning signal that toxic chemicals in
the classroom may be outgassing the comfort zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 0335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 03:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7147 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNIVERSE-MATTER-SFCHR     05-31 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSE-MATTER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   STANFORD STUDY TO CONSIDER THE MATTER OF THE UNIVERSEBy DAVID 
 PERLMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ An international team of scientists has
launched a pioneering experiment at Stanford aimed at explaining
how all the matter in the universe came to exist _ from the stars
and galaxies in the heavens to the microbes and humans on Earth.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inside a huge underground machine, the team has begun firing
beams of subnuclear particles at each other, creating tiny
fireballs of new particles that could reveal the answers the
scientists are seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Their goal is ambitious, indeed: to understand in unprecedented
detail why the universe contains so much more real matter than the
stuff called antimatter _ and whether science's current views of
nature's fundamental forces and particles need changing.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen years after it was conceived, the Stanford
Linear Accelerator Center's $287 million Asymmetric B Factory is
finally in operation. About 650 scientists and engineers from 10
nations designed and built the massive facility, and scores of them
are operating it day and night on this holiday weekend in a final
tune-up before turning it up to full power.
</P>
<P>
   The project is a joint venture between SLAC and the Lawrence
Berkeley and Livermore National Laboratories, with contributions
from the California Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the beginning of a great adventure,'' said Nobel laureate
Burton Richter, the retiring director of SLAC, who has watched the
facility being built and teased into operation for the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're exploring tiny regions of space where titanic events
take place. And with the help of the Department of Energy and the
steady support of funds from Congress, we've begun operations
exactly on schedule and even under budget.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``titanic events'' that the new machine creates are the
result of thousands of collisions between bunches of high-energy
electrons and their identical but oppositely charged particles
called positrons _ pairs of invisible matter and antimatter
objects.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the explosive collisions should soon be creating
millions of rare, fast-vanishing particles called B mesons. These
are prime examples of matter and antimatter that can be analyzed
precisely to understand how they are at once the same and yet so
vastly different.
</P>
<P>
   Those fleeting pairs of B mesons decay with almost inconceivable
swiftness _ within a trillionth of a second _ and as they fly
through less than a ten-thousandth of an inch of space within the
vacuum of the B Factory, the machine's 1,200-ton detector can
separate the antimatter B mesons from the more prosaic Bs to yield
arcane information on their different decay modes.
</P>
<P>
   The B Factory's twin beams of opposing electrons and positrons
were conceived in 1986 by Pier Oddone, a Peru-born physicist at the
University of California's Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory. Oddone
reasoned that if the electrons could be shot out of the machine at
three times more energy than the positrons, the B mesons resulting
from the explosion should fly into the detector at different
velocities so scientists could analyze them separately. It was an
inspiration that made the entire project possible.
</P>
<P>
   As Oddone calculated, the anti-Bs would decay much faster than
the normal Bs, and as he saw the first computer-generated images of
the collisions inside the machine's detector this weekend, he was
elated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pictures look terrific,'' he said. ``They're like baby
pictures, and within a few days they should show us the first
evidence that we're really producing Bs.''
</P>
<P>
   Physicists designate the antiparticles of a B meson as the
letter B with a bar on top, so the huge particle detector in the B
Factory is nicknamed BaBar, a moniker  &LR; inspired by the French
stories of Babar, the quixotic and impulsive young elephant.
</P>
<P>
   BaBar's effort has a long history that began when the  &LR; French
physicist Paul Dirac predicted the existence of antimatter in 1929,
and the world's physicists later accepted the model of the Big Bang
to explain the birth of the universe. But since, they have puzzled
over one of the great mysteries of cosmic evolution:
</P>
<P>
   Within trillionths of a second after the Big Bang, they have
reasoned, the primordial explosion _ many billions of degrees hot _
must have created a universe that contained equal quantities of
matter and antimatter. But the physicists have also observed that
whenever particles of matter and antimatter encounter each other,
they annihilate themselves instantly in flashes of pure energy.
</P>
<P>
   So somehow, as the universe began creating stars and galaxies
and clusters of galaxies _ and ultimately planets and people _ most
of the antimatter must have vanished in what is now known as the
cosmic microwave background radiation. And matter, the stuff of
everything, has dominated antimatter everywhere ever since.
</P>
<P>
   At the instant of the Big Bang, physicists theorize, nearly all
the matter and antimatter particles annihilated themselves;
although within a fraction of a second, one out of every billion
original particles remained as pure matter _ enough to build
today's universe.
</P>
<P>
   As Richter put it: ``If matter hadn't come to dominate over
antimatter, our universe today would be nothing but a huge expanse
of pure radiation, with nothing else in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The B Factory's explosions of electrons and positrons, then, are
designed to produce huge quantities of the B mesons and anti-Bs so
that physicists can determine precisely how fast they decay and
what their decay products are _ the varied fundamental quarks and
the cascades of other particles that also vanish fleetingly.
</P>
<P>
   In the two basic beams of the B Factory, the electrons race
around their separate ring at energies of 9 billion volts, while
the positrons, their antimatter counterparts, speed in a separate
ring at an ``asymmetric'' energy of 3.1 billion volts. And this
asymmetry is what causes the pairs of B mesons to fly forward
separately toward the huge target where their exotic properties and
decay times can be measured.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial detector, where David Hitlin of Caltech presides, is
actually a massive and complex onion-shaped array of six separate
detectors that include a layer of pure silicon; a drift chamber
holding 27,000 wires strung through gas; a series of 192 quartz
bars; another layer of 8,500 cesium iodide crystals imported from
Russia, England, France and China; a large superconducting
solenoid, and a final ring of 19 iron plates.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese physicists have finished building their own B factory
at Tsukuba near Tokyo _ an equally huge and costly machine called
KEK. Sunday Jonathan Dorfan, the B Factory leader who takes over as
the director of SLAC in August, flew to Japan with Richter for a
conference with their Japanese colleagues. The two teams of
physicists have been sharing data all along, but competition is
keen to deliver the first results.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a neck-and-neck race,'' Dorfan said. ``We'd love to be
the first to report that we've produced Bs, but then we have to do
physics with them. And it's not the kind of physics you do in a few
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it could be a year or more before either team of
physicists reports the first findings from their B factories _ and
at least 10 years more of research before they can answer all the
questions that they have asked about the ``Standard Model'' of the
universe as they now perceive it.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists who provide the first valid answers, however, are
almost certain to win a Nobel Prize in physics, for the answers
that emerge from the B factories are so profound that they could
alter much of science as it stands today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
