<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 08:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7237 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEMINIST-THEOLOGY-LIF     05-31 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEMINIST-THEOLOGY-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMINIST THEOLOGY EXPANDING WOMEN'S ROLES IN CHRISTIANITY
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color photo a woman reaching out to Michelangelo's famous
painting of God) 
 By CARY McMULLEN 
 c.1999 New York Times Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few people leave a church because the pastor is a woman, says
the Rev. Hollis Boardman, based on her nearly 20 years' experience.
</P>
<P>
   But they can certainly cause problems.
</P>
<P>
   Boardman recalls that earlier in her career as a United
Methodist minister, she received a visit one day from a couple in
her church.
</P>
<P>
   ''They said, 'We've decided we need a family man as our pastor,
and we want you replaced,''' said Boardman, who was appointed last
year as pastor of First United Methodist Church of Fort Meade, a
small, rural town in Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The discontented couple went to the committee in charge of
pastoral appointments and were turned down, Boardman said, but they
responded by waging a smear campaign that, for a year or more, made
life difficult for her.
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment Boardman encountered is hardly unique. Of the 10
largest Christian denominations in the country, only four
officially allow women to be ordained as ministers, according to
the Yearbook of American &AMP; Canadian Churches. In the Catholic
Church, the Vatican strengthened its position that women may not be
ordained as priests by declaring the teaching ''infallible'' in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Baptist Convention, the largest Protestant group,
has taken a similar position since passing a resolution in 1984
that ''the Scriptures teach that women are not in public worship to
assume a role of authority over men.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than 25 years since Mary Daly's ''Beyond God
the Father'' fired the opening shot in a war against what she and
others claimed is ''patriarchy'' in the Bible, and in church
doctrine and practice. Since men are the writers and interpreters
of scripture and doctrine, the argument goes, there is a bias in
the church against women having positions of authority, and, in
some cases, these documents are used to justify belittling or
oppressing women.
</P>
<P>
   Daly's book opened the floodgates to a type of theology that
specializes in rooting out this bias and offering an alternative.
Under feminist theology, women are not only equal as children of
God, but could also be preachers and bishops and makers of rules.
</P>
<P>
   Some Protestant denominations were ahead of feminism in placing
women in positions of authority. The United Methodist Church and a
branch of what is now the Presbyterian Church (USA) were the first
to ordain women as ministers, starting in 1956, preceding Betty
Friedan's ''The Feminine Mystique'' by several years.
</P>
<P>
   But since the early 1970s, feminist theology has moved far and
fast, questioning every major point of scripture and doctrine, even
the nature of God, and providing the intellectual ammunition for
one side of the continued debate over the role of women in the
church.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has been about bringing women's experiences to bear on the
whole religious tradition, its symbols and practices, affirming
some and challenging others,'' said Elizabeth A. Johnson, professor
of theology at Fordham University in the Bronx, N.Y., and one of
the pioneers of feminist theology.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Johnson points to the way traditional theology has
identified pride as the cardinal sin. ''That's fine if you're a
male authority figure. Grace then comes as humility. But what if
you've been called all your life to be subservient? Then sin might
be being overdependent, not assuming responsibility for yourself
enough. Grace then comes as a call to affirm oneself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For the traditional church-going woman, ''feminist theology''
carries connotations of radicalism; of rejecting all male leaders,
from the pope to the president of the youth fellowship; of
rewriting the Bible and worshiping a goddess. Yet Cynthia Rigby,
assistant professor of theology at Austin (Texas) Theological
Seminary, said in a recent article in the independent magazine
''Presbyterian Outlook,'' that while some feminist theologians hold
those views, many other church women and men accept insights from
feminist theology without realizing it.
</P>
<P>
   For instance: that Jesus treated women with dignity uncommon for
his day, or that God is neither male nor female, and the Bible
occasionally attributes motherly or feminine qualities to Him.
</P>
<P>
   In the Old Testament, Isaiah writes in chapter 66, verse 13,
that the Lord says: ''As a mother comforts her child, so will I
comfort you.'' The parable of the woman searching for the coin in
Luke 15:8-10, represents God searching for a lost person to bring
him into His kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Feminist theology has liberated some biblical passages from
interpretations that are misogynist, says Sara Fletcher Harding,
assistant professor of religion at Florida Southern College in
Lakeland, Fla. An especially abused passage, she says, is the one
in Genesis in which Eve and Adam eat the forbidden fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ''Augustine called Eve a temptress. Others said women were to
blame for bringing sin into the world, and because of Eve, Christ
was crucified. Well, in Genesis, the text doesn't say she seduced
Adam, she hands him a piece of fruit, and he eats it. We're just
setting the record straight,'' Harding said.
</P>
<P>
   Some feminist theologians, like Daly, say the church is so
hopelessly corrupted with patriarchy, the only solution is to
create a separate, all-woman church that is free to develop its own
ideas and forms of worship, including for some, the worship of a
female deity.
</P>
<P>
   Janice Shaw Crouse, a Methodist laywoman and director of the
Ecumenical Coalition on Women and Society, a project of the
conservative Institute on Religion and Democracy in Washington,
D.C., attended a Reimagining conference in April 1998 and calls
what went on there ''apostasy and heresy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They believe feminism cannot be defended within the context of
scripture. By reinterpreting scripture, they redefine what the
Christian faith is all about,'' Crouse said. Crouse also accuses
the women's departments in mainline churches of being a conduit for
the more heretical ideas of feminist theology.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition Crouse heads, formed in 1994, represents a
backlash against feminist theology, mostly from evangelical and
''orthodox'' church leaders. The group has become more organized
and vocal, as evangelicals have gained confidence and political
clout.
</P>
<P>
   But just as feminist theology represents a variety of responses
to perceived male oppression, neither are its critics of one mind.
Crouse's coalition does not have a position on the ordination of
women, because, she says, the issue is too divisive. Crouse herself
favors allowing women to be ordained. Her mother, at age 64,
entered seminary and was later ordained and appointed as pastor to
the congregation her late husband had served.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Cary McMullen writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
