<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPATIENS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING ONE'S IMPATIENS: VERSATILE FLOWER A SHADY SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color photo of bed of pink and orange impatiens) 
 By SUSAN MCCLURE 
 c.1999 Susan McClure 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Impatiens, a flowering garden plant which arrived on the garden
scene in the 1980s, has quickly replaced petunias as a favorite
bedding annual. What has proved most enticing about impatiens
plants is their love of shade.
</P>
<P>
   In dark or dappled areas under trees or on the north side of a
wall, in mature suburbs and in the shadows of skyscrapers,
impatiens thrive. All summer and into fall, they are covered with
flat-faced, bright flowers in shades of red, pink, purple, white,
and orange. The pastels look especially luminous in dark settings.
</P>
<P>
   Impatiens have even more of which to boast. Each small seedling
quickly grows into a graceful mound, making an attractive focus for
pots, clusters, and entire beds. The flowers, which need no
deadheading, fall off when done blooming.
</P>
<P>
   Bedding impatiens, and a number of other species and garden
plants, are named for their seed pods. When ripe, the pods snap
open flinging seeds across the ground. This character is
particularly pronounced in wild touch-me-nots, impatiens that grow
locally in moist, shady woodlands and can be harvested to use the
juicy sap to relieve the itching produced by poison ivy.
</P>
<P>
   While bedding impatiens are the best known, there are a number
of other impatiens flowers _ old-fashioned busy lizzies,
sun-tolerant New Guinea impatiens and exotic species from Africa
and elsewhere. Here is a preview of the many kinds of impatiens
that you might try in your garden. &QL; 
 &UR; Bedding Impatiens &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Developed from flowers native to Tanzania and Mozambique, these
are the impatiens that are sold everywhere in spring. Different
varieties come in mind-boggling numbers and grow from 8 to 24
inches high, usually reaching equally wide.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most compact is the popular Accent series with
luscious flowers in colors such as apricot, burgundy, carmine,
coral, cranberry, deep pink, lavender blue, lilac, orange, pink,
pink blush, red, rose, salmon, scarlet, violet, and white. Other
varieties in this series have a central white star or contrasting
white petal edge.
</P>
<P>
   Other compact impatiens include the Dazzler series, which has
the only coral-colored flowers available, and the Deco series with
striking dark green foliage. The Super Elfin series has
particularly large flowers and comes in a new color, ''Sunrise'',
with a salmon orange center and purple edges. The Swirl Series has
bicolor flowers _ light coral, rose, or salmon with dark edges.
</P>
<P>
   Growing slightly larger, 10 to 12 inches high, are Show Stopper
impatiens with big, 2-inch-wide flowers ideal for for hanging
baskets. This series includes Cherry Flair, a creamy white with
streaks of rose and Soft Blue, a pastel lavender blue.
</P>
<P>
   The Tempo series also includes large bloomers in many colors
including Watermelon, which is salmon pink with a cherry red eye.
</P>
<P>
   Of increasing popularity are double flowered or rosebud
impatiens, which look like the graceful buds of roses before the
flowers open. Some rosebud impatiens combine these attractive
flowers with white-edged foliage, making beautiful specimen plants
for a pot.
</P>
<P>
   You may find rosebud impatiens in the Carousel series,
Confection Series, and under the name Victorian Rose. &QL; 
 &UR; New Guinea Impatiens &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This even more recent newcomer to American gardens hails from
Southeast Asia and tolerates sun or light shade. Its flowers, which
reach 2 or 3 inches wide, surpass bedding impatiens in size.
</P>
<P>
   The plants also stretch up taller, easily reaching 2 feet high.
The elongated leaves may be found in ordinary green, and also in
bronze, white variegated, and even pink-splashed colors, making for
electric color combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Look for the Spectra series, which comes in colors such as
lilac-rose, pink velvet, and shades of red, salmon, and rose. Give
a sniff to the new Socialite series, which are unique for their
fragrance. Tango, with fluorescent orange flowers, is one of the
few to grow from seeds instead of cuttings.
 &UR; Busy Lizzies &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This flower, which hails from China and India, has an old-
fashioned look well-suited for cottage gardens, blending with
perennials, or mixing in other informal beds.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers stretch along the upper portions of the stem,
dangling out from under the lance-shaped leaves more demurely than
bedding or New Guinea impatiens. Lightly perfumed, they come in
pink, red, white, lavender, and yellow, with single or double
petals.
 &UR; Caring for Impatiens &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Impatiens, particularly sensitive to frost, should not go out
into the garden until after mid- to late May. Give bedding
impatiens light to full shade, and rich, moist garden soil. Busy
Lizzies and New Guinea impatiens will grow well in sun, as long as
the soil is kept moist.
</P>
<P>
   Fertilize once a month, or more often if growing impatiens under
a shallow rooted tree or in less-than-fertile soil. Water weekly
when there is less than an inch of rain.
</P>
<P>
   When growing impatiens in pots or hanging baskets, add a
water-holding gel to the potting soil before planting. Fertilize
weekly with a water-soluble product and water daily, if needed,
during hot weather.
 &UR; (Susan McClure writes frequently on garden topics.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
