<SLUG> BC-SAFFRON-BURROWS-IN-LOSS-OF-INNOCENCE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFFRON BURROWS: THE DARK SIDE OF INNOCENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Saffron Burrows with Stefano Dionisi,
Rodney Charles and Julian Sands in a scene from ``The Loss of
Sexual Innocence.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Any minute now Saffron Burrows may find herself a movie star,
but if she ends up famous it won't be her fault.
 &HT;    ``It's undeniable that receiving a compliment from someone you
admire _ a friend, journalist, politician _ is a wonderful
feeling,'' the British actress says. ``But there's a very large
difference between that and the mad, mad, mad world of celebrity.
 &HT;    ``I've gotten a small taste of it, but I've seen it really
happen to people I know, and it can be scary and disorienting,''
she says. ``It's nothing I want for myself.''
 &HT;    The 26-year-old Burrows first generated buzz as the chic,
popular one of the three Irish friends in the surprise hit ``Circle
of Friends'' (1995). More recently she's juggled projects both
mainstream and offbeat, starring in the misbegotten big-screen
version of ``Wing Commander'' (1999) and in three upcoming films _
two of them the independent features ``The Loss of Sexual
Innocence'' and ``Miss Julie,'' the third a big-budget thriller,
``Deep Blue Sea.''
 &HT;    First up is ``Sexual Innocence,'' now in limited release.
Written and directed by Mike Figgis, the man behind ``Leaving Las
Vegas'' (1995), the movie explores various chapters in the life of
a filmmaker (Julian Sands), intercutting them with scenes depicting
the relationship between Adam and Eve. Burrows plays two
characters, twins raised in different countries.
 &HT;    Something of a cinematic curio, ``Sexual Innocence'' forgoes
standard storytelling structure, with images floating by like
thoughts. There are interracial relationships, violence and scenes
of child abuse, not to mention enough exposed flesh to make Hugh
Hefner blush.
 &HT;    ``I was immediately intrigued by the way Mike wrote it,'' says
Burrows, a tall, beautiful redhead, during an interview in the
Manhattan offices of the film's publicist. ``He broke all kinds of
screenwriting rules and popular myths, which made it liberating to
read.
 &HT;    ``I love films, but am rather disappointed by what's out there
at the moment,'' she says. ``So much of it is inane and often
doesn't require any intelligence at all to take in.
 &HT;    ``You just sit there and let it wash over you. You can't do that
with this film.''
 &HT;    Burrows has seen the film with audiences in America, Germany,
France and Ireland, and she finds that it affects different people
in different ways.
 &HT;    ``It's amazing,'' she says. ``Everyone seems to have very
radical, polarized responses. I've seen people left with images in
their mind that they've embraced, with ideas they love or don't
agree with, that led to some kind of debate.
 &HT;    ``The film certainly inspires conversation, on the sexual and
physical level, on the level of race,'' she concludes. ``How often
does a film challenge you?''
 &HT;    It was a challenging film to make as well, especially for
Burrows, who for the first time was taking direction from Figgis,
her offscreen beau of two-plus years.
 &HT;    ``Whatever is going on privately, my sense is that you have to
behave with professionalism and with the same sense of respect and
cooperation you would on any film,'' Burrows says, clearly
uncomfortable with the subject. ``You have to maintain that with
everyone and not tip the balance.
 &HT;    ``Mike was probably tougher on me than he might have been on
someone else,'' she adds. ``When you know people well, you're more
tough on them. And I was more tough on myself.''
 &HT;    During a separate conversation, Figgis sheds additional light on
the realities of mixing business and pleasure on the set.
 &HT;    ``You're much crueler,'' he says. ``In a working relationship
you've got to be seen as being much tougher on that person than you
would be on another actor.
 &HT;    ``You can't favor that actor, and you've got to push that actor
even more,'' he says. ``Saffron understood that. On the other hand,
you've got something that is quite personal, which is quite
fragile, too, and you don't want to squash that.''
 &HT;    Figgis stares at the ground.
 &HT;    ``It's f--king difficult,'' he says. ``You can't relax in that
relationship. The good news is that Saffron is really talented and
has a vibrancy that the camera captures, and it pays off. She'll
blow everybody away in `Miss Julie.'''
 &HT;    ``Miss Julie,'' also directed by Figgis, is an adaptation of
August Strindberg's classic stage drama. Shot in a mere three
weeks, ``Miss Julie'' stars Burrows as the title character, an
aristocrat in love with a commoner.
 &HT;    ``It stays very true to the play, but it's incredibly filmic,''
Burrows says. ``It's very literate, which scared investors and
distributors. Now, though, people are watching bits and pieces of
it and they're realizing that it's really a movie.
 &HT;    ``Hopefully people will get a chance to see it soon.''
 &HT;    One film that definitely won't have trouble finding a
distributor is the anything-but-highbrow ``Deep Blue Sea,'' opening
July 30. The Renny Harlin thriller offers genetically enhanced
sharks biting back at their creator (Burrows) and a group of
scientists (including Samuel L. Jackson, Stellan Skarsgard, Thomas
Jane and L.L. Cool J) after a tropical storm traps everyone on a
research rig adrift on the Pacific Ocean.
 &HT;    It's an unabashedly commercial undertaking, and Burrows makes no
apologies for that.
 &HT;    ``Big movies open doors, or they can if people go,'' she says.
``I wanted to do `Deep Blue Sea' because I was drawn to the cast.
`Deep Blue Sea' is a big studio movie with a big budget, but it had
more going for it, in my opinion, than most studio movies.''
 &HT;    Burrows has taken a different road to her event-movie debut than
the average model-turned-actress. Born in England, she modeled from
1988 until 1994, and _ unlike many former models _ she doesn't
knock the job, grateful for the money she earned and for the
freedom to travel and pursue her dream of acting.
 &HT;    ``For me, acting meant a chance to do something _ a film, a play
_ that could affect the way someone feels about an issue, be it
political or emotional, that could push you to go out and change
things,'' she says. ``That may sound very naive, but I was about 10
years old when I discovered the films of Ken Loach, and they had
such a profound impact on me.
 &HT;    ``I remember walking out of the cinema feeling very alive after
seeing his films,'' she says. ``I also remember being inspired by
Vanessa Redgrave after seeing her in a play. I thought, `What an
amazing marriage of activism and performing _ maybe I could do
that.'''
 &HT;    Redgrave recently turned 62, and in 1997 celebrated the 40th
anniversary of her stage debut. Still a relative newcomer, Burrows
finds it hard to imagine so long and prolific a career as
Redgrave's.
 &HT;    ``Wow,'' she says, nodding her head in thought. ``Forty years.
To be honest, I don't know.
 &HT;    ``I'd love to have a couple of kids,'' she says after a moment.
``I'd like to do so many things. I'd like to think that I'll still
be acting _ but even in a year, so much can happen in one's life.
 &HT;    ``I love what I'm doing now and I hope I'll always love it,''
she says. ``I just don't want to peak at the age of 26!''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
