<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7253 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-STUDENT-BEHAVIOR-RE     05-31 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-STUDENT-BEHAVIOR-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETHINKING AMERICA'S SCHOOLS OF HARD KNOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy was perplexed. Having grown up in a
California suburb in the 1950s, the Supreme Court justice objected
to the way his colleagues were calling what schoolboys do to
schoolgirls ``sexual harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   As he put it in his dissent in a key ruling last week, ``The
real world of school discipline is a rough-and-tumble place where
students practice newly learned vulgarities, erupt with anger,
tease and embarrass each other, share offensive notes, flirt, push
and shove in the halls, grab and offend.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Georgia boy whose behavior the court considered a
violation of federal law was not a tease. For months he had
taunted, propositioned and put his hands all over the girl seated
next to him. This was not 1950s flirting.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the case reflects how much has changed in the lives of
the young in recent decades. As the nation's school year draws to
an anxious close, with teachers and principals exhausted from worry
about safety and undetected rage, educators and psychologists say
they are re-examining adolescent behavior _ the moods, the cliques,
the barely repressed violence _ and finding that American society
has failed to come to terms with those changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that this is their world, `Lord of the Flies,'
sadistic and hierarchical, that it has always been that way and
they just have to work it out, doesn't fly anymore,'' said Dr. Gil
Noam, a professor of psychiatry and education at Harvard
University. ``Especially in the wake of what happened in Colorado,
we have to reassess that.''
</P>
<P>
   A few specialists accept the implication of Kennedy's dissent
from the Supreme Court's ruling last week that schools may be held
liable for a student's persistent sexual harassment of another.
Those experts say little has changed in the last half century,
except perhaps the way society views how men act toward women, and
it makes no sense to apply the law to teen-age hormones and
immaturity.
</P>
<P>
   Most, however, say a lot has changed, and the problem is that
adults do not grasp the significance of those changes. Youthful
behavior has deteriorated markedly, many say, guns are easily
available and there are far fewer adults around to influence
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, violent television and video images, instead of
older friends or relatives, have become role models. Moreover,
research on aggression suggests that even what some might consider
old-fashioned name-calling can do serious harm.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a 14-year-old New York girl hanged herself in a
high school restroom. Friends said she had suffered continual
verbal abuse by classmates. Psychologists note that such suicides
have been on the rise among the young in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started in this field, people really believed the old
saying about sticks and stones breaking bones but words never
harming,'' said Marla R. Brassard, a professor of psychology at
Teachers College at Columbia University whose research focuses on
aggression in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``But today there is a growing body of research that shows that
the core element of abuse is psychological,'' she said. ``Physical
aggression has no anti-social impact unless it is part of
psychological abuse. Getting picked on at school can be the most
damaging.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harold Koplewicz, director of the Child Study Center at New
York University, said researchers point to five challenges
adolescents must navigate by the time they reach about age 22: they
must adjust to bodily changes; separate psychologically from their
parents or guardians; develop a social network of friends to whom
they can talk; develop educational and vocational goals, and
establish their sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Those are a lot of developmental tasks to face in the space of a
decade or less, he noted, and it is no surprise that adolescents
are moodier than younger children, or that high school can be a
very daunting place.
</P>
<P>
   He and others believe that those challenges have essentially
remained unchanged over the generations. Michael Gurian, a family
therapist from Spokane, Wash., and author of ``A Fine Young Man''
(Putnam, 1998), even believes male adolescent behavior is fairly
constant through all the primates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adolescence is a time for children to become adults, and part
of what they have to do is test each other,'' he said. ``Adults are
their teachers, but other youths are their testers. What we do in
junior high school and high school is normal primate behavior. We
have to do this stuff to each other. The question is, where do we
draw the line? For this generation, the lack of adult supervision
is a very big issue. Over the last 30 years we have gradually been
cutting out adult supervision.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a widely held view of researchers. They point out that
the reduced supervision stems not only from both parents or single
parents working out of the home; it is also because relatives and
neighbors are away as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never in the history of the civilized world been a
cohort of kids that is so little affected by adult guidance and so
attuned to a peer world,'' said William Damon, a professor of
education and director of the Stanford University Center on
Adolescence. ``We have removed grown-up wisdom and allowed them to
drift into a self-constructed, highly relativistic world of
friendship and peers.''
</P>
<P>
   Damon said that he was stunned when he went to Littleton, Colo.,
after the high school shootings there last month, to find parents
saying they felt they had no business learning what their children
were doing on the Internet. The two students who carried out the
Littleton carnage had vented their hatred on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Damon said the fact that modern adults have a less
black-and-white view of morality and human behavior, that they have
perhaps a more nuanced perspective, seems to be blocking their
ability to give clear-cut guidance and make strict rules for their
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understanding can paralyze you,'' he said. ``Understanding the
roots of a boy's misbehavior should not stop you from dealing with
it strictly.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurian, the Spokane therapist, says ``Lord of the Flies,'' the
chilling 1954 William Golding novel about boys marooned on an
island without adults, is a useful model of unsupervised male
adolescent behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pick on those they consider weak partly to establish a
pecking order and partly to protect the group against weakness,''
he said. ``It is natural for boys to do this and it is natural for
adults to supervise and stop this behavior. We are allowing too
much of the first piece and not enough of the second.''
</P>
<P>
   Something else is going on as well. The view of what is
appropriate male behavior is shifting.
</P>
<P>
   Jay P. Heubert, a professor of education at Columbia's Teachers
College, said he and his wife were watching an old James Bond movie
recently and noted that Bond, played by Sean Connery, grabbed a
nurse and tried to kiss her. When she resisted, he warned her that
he would tell her boss that she was not performing her job well.
</P>
<P>
   While by today's lights, there could hardly be a clearer example
of sexual harassment, there was no mention of it in the film.
Instead, Bond and the nurse are seen shortly thereafter in steamy
embrace and she becomes his companion for the rest of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our norms of what constitutes offensive behavior are
changing,'' Heubert said. ``This only adds to the difficulty of the
young understanding what is appropriate behavior and of their need
for adults to talk to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
