A7255 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-COLO-SHOOTING-REVIE     05-31 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-COLO-SHOOTING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVING GUN CONTROL: IT'S ABOUT THE ELECTIONS, STUPID 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It did not happen after the bullets flew and the
bodies fell at a high school in West Paducah, Ky., in December
1997, nor did it happen on the heels of the gunfire and bloodshed
at schools in Jonesboro, Ark., or Springfield, Ore., last year.
</P>
<P>
   But after Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., became a
deadly shooting gallery on April 20, the earth finally moved, at
least politically speaking, in subtle but undeniable ways.
</P>
<P>
   States dusted off languishing gun-control laws. The Senate
approved its own measures, incremental but significant. And last
week Republican leaders in the House, where gun control has
traditionally been a harder sell than in the Senate, signaled that
they would probably follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting to chalk up this change to the statistical fact
that the body count at Columbine, where 15 people died, was triple
the toll at any of the other schools.
</P>
<P>
   But the legislative action was the result of a confluence of
factors, from the enormously high stakes of next year's
presidential and congressional elections to the location of the
violence, and from the vulnerability of the National Rifle
Association to the growing discomfort of some Republicans with the
most conservative faction of their party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, undoubtedly, a fortuitous moment for pro-gun control
forces,'' said Robert J. Spitzer, a political science professor at
the State University of New York, who wrote ``The Politics of Gun
Control'' (Chatham House, 1995).
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, other political analysts and several politicians
stressed that the gun-control legislation being passed now had been
years in the making.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue came to a head after Littleton for a number of
particular, special reasons, politicians and gun-control experts
said. One was the looming elections of 2000, when the White House
will be up for grabs and control of the House of Representatives,
where the Republican majority is slim, could go to either party.
</P>
<P>
   Those stakes have left both Republicans and Democrats nervous
about falling on the wrong side of any volatile issue or conceding
any potentially popular cause to their rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, a California Democrat who helped plot her
party's gun-control strategy on the Senate floor, said Republicans
in the Senate might have beat back Democrats' efforts and tried to
stifle the whole debate at a less fraught moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they knew the outrage over this would have been
deafening had they not allowed this _ and that there would have
been political consequences,'' Boxer said, referring to the debate
on the Senate floor, where Democrats outmaneuvered Republicans and
lured a number of moderates over to their viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Edwards, a former Republican congressman from Oklahoma
who now teaches at Harvard University's Kennedy School of
government, said another political factor came into play as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impeachment drive _ and the failure of it _ somewhat
weakened the really hard-line conservatives in the Republican Party
and strengthened the moderates,'' said Edwards, noting that a fair
number of Republicans broke ranks in the Senate and that House
Speaker Dennis Hastert has called for some gun-control measures.
``The hard-core conservatives overreached one time too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Littleton, more than the locations of other school shootings,
was precisely the kind of archetypal suburban setting that both
parties have cast as pivotal political battlegrounds. So
Republicans and Democrats alike were particularly eager to show
such constituents that they cared.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, the Kentucky Republican who heads the
Senate Republican Campaign Committee, noted that the gun-control
measures that passed the Senate benefited from an additional, less
politically loaded factor.
</P>
<P>
   As the aftershocks of Littleton rumbled across America, it just
so happened that there was a Senate bill that addressed the
prevention and punishment of juvenile crime. It had been
percolating in a committee for years and was overdue in coming to
the floor of the chamber. The bill became an appropriate vehicle
for gun control, so when Senate Democrats pressed for a gun-control
debate, it was hard for Republicans to resist them.
</P>
<P>
   There was, of course, yet another player in these events: the
National Rifle Association. Although it had been a potent foe of
new restrictions on firearms, the call for such regulations after
Littleton hit the group at a moment of relative frailty. Membership
was down from the early 1990s; ties between the rifle association
and the militia movement had battered its image.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA was also wounded by an astonishing quirk of scheduling.
As Osha Gray Davidson, author of ``Under Fire: the NRA and the
Battle for Gun Control'' (Henry Holt, 1993), said, ``The fact that
the NRA's annual meeting was planned for the week after the
shooting in virtually the same place guaranteed that they would get
extra media scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the final ingredient in the recipe for legislative
action was the banality of the motives of the teen-age boys who
opened fire in Littleton, at least as those reasons were initially
reported in the news media. These children were outsiders hurt by
their exclusion from cliques, and guns gave them their revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``When students who come from what appear to be affluent, normal
families suddenly go berserk,'' said Bob Walker, president of the
advocacy group Handgun Control Inc., ``people begin to recognize
that it could happen anywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 0925EDT &QL; 
