<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 09:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7256 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-DEFENSE-LAWYERS-REV     05-31 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-DEFENSE-LAWYERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE JOB REQUIRES A WALK ON THE ETHICAL SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By LAURA MANSNERUS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A good trial lawyer spins a story from threads of
fact and possibility, and Marvyn Kornberg made his best effort. In
defense of the police officer charged with brutalizing the Haitian
immigrant Abner Louima, Kornberg promised the jury evidence that
the injuries to Louima's rectum and bladder could have happened
during consensual sex.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in his opening statement Kornberg said three experts
would testify that the injuries were not consistent with an
assault. He added that a sample of Louima's feces collected from
the station house ``contains the DNA of another male.''
</P>
<P>
   The finer lines of this story will never be known; last week the
officer, Justin Volpe, aborted his defense, pleaded guilty to
violating Louima's civil rights, and gave his own account of
ramming a stick into Louima's rectum in a fit of rage. After his
opening argument, Kornberg never mentioned the possibility of a
homosexual encounter, even during four hours of cross-examination
of Louima.
</P>
<P>
   After his client pleaded guilty, Kornberg said he owed Louima no
apology, because he had never directly said that Louima was injured
by consensual sex.
</P>
<P>
   But Kornberg's initial strategy kept provoking. The Rev. Al
Sharpton protested that it had amounted to ``a second rape.'' And
plenty of others asked: How can lawyers suggest these things? The
answer, Kornberg said in an interview, is that ``it's an
obligation: The defense counsel must do everything in his power to
defend the client.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers say that obligation includes suggesting almost
any scenario that can sow enough doubt to spring the client, as
long as the lawyer does not produce testimony he knows is false.
</P>
<P>
   ``Short of that, there's a whole lot that can be done to
challenge the prosecution's case, and that often includes
distorting the prosecution's case,'' said Abbe Smith, the associate
director of the criminal justice clinic at the Georgetown Law
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence in support of the theory might be quite scant,''
said Ms. Smith, a former public defender. ``But I would embrace it
and argue it passionately, whether I believed it or not. Would I
feel good about it in the morning? It's not fun.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy, of course, to know what is false. As to where to
draw the line, ``People in the profession are split on this,'' said
David Rudovsky, a professor at the University of Pennsylvania. ``It
crosses the line if you don't have the scientific or medical
evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg did plan to present a forensic pathologist and two
colorectal surgeons as expert witnesses, according to a letter
filed with the court. And legal experts pointed out that his
contention _ that Louima's injuries were, as he said in his
opening, ``not, I repeat, not consistent with a nonconsensual
insertion of an object into his rectum'' _ avoided any direct
assertion.
</P>
<P>
   But Rudovsky said Kornberg raised a damning tactical problem for
himself. ``I think it's a crazy theory anyway,'' he said of
Kornberg's gay-sex scenario. ``It was going to be rejected. But
aside from that, one of the first rules of trial advocacy is,
`Don't promise too much.' What I can't imagine is a lawyer making
that claim and not having some proof, because in the end you get
the most devastating statement from the prosecutor: `Where's this
pathologist?'''
</P>
<P>
   Smearing the victim with sexual innuendo, a favored approach in
rape cases, is always a high-risk tactic. ``This isn't a claim that
the umbrella couldn't have opened a certain way,'' Rudovsky said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a risk taken by Alton Maddox in defending Steven Bowman,
one of the men accused of slashing Marla Hanson, the model, on a
Manhattan street 13 years ago. The lawyer said Ms. Hanson, who did
not know her attackers, had ``racial hangups,'' and he badgered her
on cross-examination with questions and innuendo about her sex
life. ``My job,'' Maddox said later, ``is to walk Bowman out of
this courthouse.'' (In the end, he did not.)
</P>
<P>
   The same outrage was directed at Jack T. Litman, the attorney
for Robert Chambers, who killed 18-year-old Jennifer Levin during a
sexual encounter in Central Park. Pursuing Chambers' claim that he
struck Miss Levin when she hurt him during ``rough sex,'' Litman
sought to introduce the girl's diary, which he called ``a
chronicle'' of her ``kinky and aggressive'' sex life.
</P>
<P>
   If rapists are hard to defend, Ms. Smith said, police officers
can be even harder. ``Defense lawyers are easy targets, and
Kornberg is an especially easy target because folks who consider
themselves civil libertarians are less comfortable when it's a
police officer engaged in the level of horrible conduct,'' she
said. ``These are the cases that cause my parents' friends to ask
how I could defend those people.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond public outrage, the doubly humiliated victim or witness
has no recourse for statements made in a courtroom. However
fantastic and damaging, they are privileged. But lawyers can be
made to pay for what they say on the courthouse steps.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Pagones, a former prosecutor, sued the advisers of Tawana
Brawley after they accused him of abducting and raping the
teenager. He charged that the advisers _ including Sharpton and
Maddox _ had made repeated and baseless accusations outside court.
Last year, after a trial in state Supreme Court in Poughkeepsie,
they were found liable and ordered to pay Pagones $345,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
