<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7272 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBAC     05-31 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 6)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This selection of paperbacks is from the New &AMP; Noteworthy
columns that have appeared since the 1998 Holiday Books issue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ABOUT A BOY &LR;  By Nick Hornby. Riverhead, $12.95. A comic novel
about a bachelor and his unlikely pal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEACH: THE HISTORY OF PARADISE ON EARTH &LR;  By Lena Lencek and
Gideon Bosker. Penguin, $13.95. Beach culture from the Romans to
the Californians.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHARMING BILLY &LR;  By Alice McDermott. Delta, $12.95. Eloquent,
disturbing fiction set among Irish-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLOUDSPLITTER &LR;  By Russell Banks. Harper Perennial, $15. A rich,
soulful novel about the abolitionist John Brown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE COLLECTED POEMS OF AMY CLAMPITT &LR;  Knopf, $19.95. A
posthumous overview of an extraordinary life's work.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFEDERATES IN THE ATTIC: DISPATCHES FROM THE UNFINISHED CIVIL
WAR &LR;  By Tony Horwitz. Vintage Departures, $14. In the field with
hard-core battle re-enactors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DAMASCUS GATE &LR;  By Robert Stone. Scribner, $14. Complex, heady
fiction set in Jerusalem's Old City.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DESPERATE CHARACTERS &LR;  By Paula Fox. Norton, $12. An intense
1970 novel about a bitter New York marriage.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ECHOES OF A NATIVE LAND: TWO CENTURIES OF A RUSSIAN VILLAGE &LR;  By
Serge Schmemann. Vintage, $15. A journalist's elegant history of
his ancestral home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EVERYBODY WAS SO YOUNG: GERALD AND SARA MURPHY. A LOST
GENERATION LOVE STORY &LR;  By Amanda Vaill. Broadway, $15. A rich
American couple in 1920s Paris and the Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FREEDOMLAND &LR;  By Richard Price. Island/Dell, $7.99. Realistic
fiction about racial turmoil in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL: THE FATES OF HUMAN SOCIETIES &LR;  By Jared
Diamond. Norton, $14.95. Why Europe and Asia dominated other
civilizations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HENRY MITCHELL ON GARDENING &LR;  Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $13.
Sparkling essays by a celebrated newspaper columnist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW THE MIND WORKS &LR;  By Steven Pinker. Norton, $17. Lively,
witty popular science by an MIT psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HUXLEY: FROM DEVIL'S DISCIPLE TO EVOLUTION'S HIGH PRIEST &LR;  By
Adrian Desmond. Helix/Perseus, $22.50. The life of a highly
contentious 19th-century scientist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AN INSTANCE OF THE FINGERPOST &LR;  By Iain Pears. Berkley, $7.99.
An ambitious thriller set in Restoration England.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEMOIRS OF A GEISHA &LR;  By Arthur Golden. Vintage Contemporaries,
$14. A bold first novel about the making of a kept mistress.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NIGHT TRAIN &LR;  By Martin Amis. Vintage International, $11. A
tough-minded police procedural with a lot on its mind.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PARADISE &LR;  By Toni Morrison. Plume, $13.95. Dense, troubling
fiction set in a small black utopia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PILLAR OF FIRE: AMERICA IN THE KING YEARS, 1963-1965 &LR;  By Taylor
Branch. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $17. Volume 2 of a planned
trilogy about the life and times of Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRESTON FALLS &LR;  By David Gates. Vintage Contemporaries, $13. A
scary novel of male vanity and middle-age angst.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RED-TAILS IN LOVE: A WILDLIFE DRAMA IN CENTRAL PARK &LR;  By Marie
Winn. Vintage Departures, $13. The struggle of a young male hawk to
get ahead.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TENDER AT THE BONE: GROWING UP AT THE TABLE &LR;  By Ruth Reichl.
Broadway, $13. A restaurant critic recalls a life of eating and
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TERRA INCOGNITA: TRAVELS IN ANTARCTICA &LR;  By Sara Wheeler. Modern
Library, $12.95. A British journalist's love affair with a
continent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VICTOR HUGO &LR;  By Graham Robb. Norton, $19.95. An engaging
biography of the prodigious French writer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A WALK IN THE WOODS: REDISCOVERING AMERICA ON THE APPALACHIAN
TRAIL &LR;  By Bill Bryson. Broadway, $13. Breezy travel writing with
Chaucerian panache.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WICKED WOMEN: STORIES &LR;  By Fay Weldon. Atlantic Monthly, $12.
Satirical swipes at insecure men and New Age blather.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WOLF SOLENT &LR;  By John Cowper Powys. Vintage International, $15.
A 1929 British novel about a sensitive young man.
</P>
