 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2545 - May 31, 1999  NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2545 -- May 31, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. THE NEXT CLINTON What are the politics of being a first lady,
a potential senator - and a Clintonian above all? Does Hillary
Clinton really want to be a senator from New York? Could she
survive a street fight with a nasty opponent? Could she stand the
pawing of New York City's feral reporters? In the chance to win
office for herself, Clinton glimpses freedom, or so her friends and
advisers say - freedom to participate in politics fully, with her
own constituents, on her own terms, for her own purposes. By James
Bennet. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (8,500 words)
+ edited article available. 2. A BRUTAL CURE A young man's
tuberculosis had resisted every drug treatment. His last hope was a
crude technique abandoned in the 1950s : the wholesale removal of
his diseased lung. By Lisa Belkin. From The New York Times
Magazine. Full-length (4,900 words) + edited article available.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
MY NEW SOUTH AFRICAN IDENTITY As the Mandela era draws to a close,
South Africa's most renowned novelist sees her nation, for all its
problems, embracing an expanded notion of 'us.' By Nadine Gordimer.
From The New York Times Magazine. 3,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
DEPRESSED? TRY HEROIN : A CASE FOR LEGALIZING DRUGS
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE ELDERLY Paul Parin, 83, is a prominent psychoanalyst and
ethnographer. The son of a Jewish landholder in Slovenia, he left
that country in 1938 and completed his medical studies in
Switzerland. In 1944-45 he served as a doctor for the Yugoslav
Partisans. Back in Zurich, he and his wife Goldy practiced
psychoanalysis for 40 years. Now a widower, Parin has often taken
provocative stances. Recently he sparked controversy by calling for
the legalization of hard drugs for older people. Otherwise, he
says, they would suffer needlessly. The risk of addiction, Parin
insists, is irrelevant if someone has only a short time to live.
From Der Spiegel. 1,000 words. (English translation available.) 
____________________________________________________________________
____________ 5. WHO'S OUT THERE? The search for intelligent life in
outer space is going so well, scientists need a little help from
you and your home computer. Astrophysicist Dan Werthimer is looking
for aliens, or more precisely, he is listening for them via a
modified screen saver for a personal computer. His brainchild -
called SETIhome - is a data saving software program that masks as a
screen saver and will allow amateur computer jockeys to receive and
collate chunks of data from outer space from the privacy of their
own homes. By Jeff Greenwald. From Discover magazine. 1,000 words +
photos. 6. WHAT'S DOING IN VENICE Events, sightseeing, hotels and
restaurants in Venice. By Alessandra Stanley. From The New York
Times Way To Go! 2,000 words + photos. 7. MICHAEL OVITZ,
SUPERAGENT, IS BACK Michael Ovitz, the superagent who once ruled
Hollywood by fear, is back. In the '80s he cornered the market on
movie talent, but that kind of power wasn't enough for him. Now
he's scrambling to get that talent again - and reminding Hollywood
how much trouble he can make. By Lynn Hirschberg. From The New York
Times Magazine. Full-length (8,300 words) + edited article
available.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
FROM NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE (N/A Brazil, Australia, New Zealand)
</P>
<P>
   A. THE GREAT ECLIPSE : LIGHTS OUT You have about two minutes to
take in the full drama of one of the oldest sights the world has to
offer: the great eclipse. Forewarned is forearmed. By Marcus Chown.
1,000 words. B. MAKING TRACKS
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's to be Chardonnay in France, beer in Bavaria or tea
in Torquay, you'd better start plann
</P>
