<HEADER>
A7319 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      05-31 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(jt) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, June 1, 1999:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (Category `i')
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Arlington, Va.) _ President Clinton speaks at
Arlington National Cemetery. By John N. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Belgrade) _ Yugoslavia charges that at least 11
people are dead after NATO bombs hit a sanitarium and retirement
home. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes, Albania) _ Heavy fighting is reported
along the Yugoslav-Albanian border. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ Military developments in Kosovo.
By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIANANMEN (Beijing) _ Ten years after army troops and
tanks were used to smash pro-democracy demonstrations in Tiananmen
Square, more than one hundred relatives of the dead have petitioned
the government to open a criminal investigation of the officials
responsible. By Eric Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Beijing) _ China's information minister calls a
special press conference to deride and denounce the Cox report on
Chinese spying, while showing a U.S. internet site that has much
U.S. nuclear information. By Eric Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Another reformer, Viktor Khristenko,
is appointed first deputy prime minister in charge of economy,
replacing the official who lasted in the job for three days last
week. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN ( New Delhi) _ India's prime minister accepts
Pakistani offer of high-level talks on Kashmir. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECT (Johannesburg) _ Reporter's Notebook on the South
African election Wednesday. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Category `a')
</P>
<P>
   ILL-MUSEUM (Chicago) _ Finding themselves face-to-face _ or
rather face-to-knee _ with a colossal, roseate statue of
Tutankhamen, museumgoers returned this weekend to the Oriental
Institute for the first time since 1996, when its galleries were
closed to the public for remodeling. By David W. Dunlop.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-JEWS (Undated) _ More than a century ago, leaders of
Reform Judaism declared such practices as wearing skullcaps and
prayer shawls and using Hebrew in services to be the dated relics
of the past, and emphasized instead a focus on social ethics and a
highly cerebral approach to the faith. But in a symbolically
resonant gesture, and with an eye on the approach of a new century,
Reform's rabbinic arm, the Central Conference of American Rabbis,
last week adopted a document that encourages the movement's members
to explore traditional rituals. By Gustav Niebuhr and Nadine
Brozan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (category `f')
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-LAWS (Undated) _ A patchwork of state libel laws that was
aimed at protecting makers of agricultural products from food
scares is putting a chill on what kinds of projects broadcasters
and publishers are willing to back. By Iver Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   RAIL-TRAFFIC (Undated) _ Beginning Tuesday, Norfolk Southern and
CSX, which already dominate commercial rail traffic in much of the
East, take over chunks of the huge Conrail system. The switchover
will herald the most sweeping change in a generation in the
Northeast's commercial railroads _ especially in the New York area.
By Agis Salpukas .
</P>
<P>
   LAWYERS-ASSESS (Undated) _ In recent weeks, two prominent
securities lawyers have found themselves standing before judges
with lawyers of their own. While the two cases are very different
in magnitude, both illuminate the power that defense lawyers wield
in securities-law prosecutions _ and the limits of the Securities
and Exchange Commission's patience with defense lawyers who may
have used that power improperly. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   YEN-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The so-called yen carry trade _
which contributed to the currency plunges that set off the global
financial crisis in 1997 _ is back. With the recent widening of the
spread between Japanese and American interest rates, this
speculative trade is an opportunity for investors again. Still,
there are not a lot of takers, maybe because of the losses that
some speculators suffered when this trade backfired. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-ECON (Tokyo) _ Just when it looked like South Korea was
about to overhaul its rickety financial system, the country's
unexpectedly rapid recovery has cast doubt on the government's
resolve to dispose of some of the worst banks. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY  &LR; (`k' category)
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   MOVING LATER:
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture, fashion, sports, and
ScienceTimes will move by 3:00 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER _ A list of stories being considered by
New York Times editors for Page 1 will move at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ Stories scheduled for Page 1 will be
listed by 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
