<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7330 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOYE31-GDRURY-AZR &LR;      05-31 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOYE31-GDRURY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUSERVE BACK WITH A NEW LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Guess what? CompuServe is still alive!
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe you didn't think it was dead. But chances are, you
haven't given it much thought over the past few years, which is why
it's had so much trouble.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing a recent television commercial for the one-time top
dog in online services, I thought it was time to give CompuServe
another try. The last time we parted company, I believe the
software had just crashed my computer.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't exactly a beginner when I first signed on with
CompuServe (www.compuserve.com).
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1987, I covered the police and fire beat for ``The
Phoenix Gazette.'' My office in the ``cop shop,'' otherwise known
as the Phoenix Police Department headquarters, had a weird little
computer that connected to the newspaper building via a 300-baud
modem.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the computer wasn't so little. It was about the size
of a large microwave oven. And it was green! I used that machine to
transmit my stories to the ``Gazette's'' computer system a few
blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   When things slowed down between deadlines, I'd explore the
workings of my electronic friend. I discovered that I could use it
to connect to computer bulletin boards run by computer enthusiasts
around town, a local law enforcement agency and even a Valley
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   That's all it took. I was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, I had a desktop PC at home, and I used that baby to
connect to computer bulletin boards and what was then a new service
_ America Online (www.aol.com).
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, I was asked to take over the job as computer
writer for ``The Gazette.'' I discovered that the position came
with a CompuServe account. I was excited to give the service a try.
After all, CompuServe was the granddaddy of online services.
</P>
<P>
   After a few months of using CompuServe almost daily, I found
myself logging on fewer and fewer times each week. Meanwhile, I was
spending more and more time on America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The reason was simple: I found America Online easier to use.
Despite having been online for a few years, I found CompuServe
complicated. It made me feel as though I'd walked into a private
club, wasn't dressed right and didn't see anybody I knew.
</P>
<P>
   With America Online, I could log in and chat with someone or
check out messages in a special interest forum without trouble. On
CompuServe, exploring forums required signing up and looking for
messages in special places.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the constant worry that I'd accidentally ventured
into a special-use area that would add charges to my monthly
CompuServe bill.
</P>
<P>
   So it was no surprise to me when, several years later, America
Online passed CompuServe in popularity. Today, America Online now
between 17 million and 18 million members, about 1.1 million of
whom are always online at the same time. AOL says that's about
double the prime-time television audience that views CNN.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I became the computer writer for ``The Arizona
Republic,'' I'd pretty much quit doing stories about CompuServe.
Although I do remember doing an article back in 1996 about
CompuServe's ill-fated comeback attempt via a new service it
called, simply, Wow!
</P>
<P>
   But a lot has changed since then. Today, of course, CompuServe
is owned by AOL. And, despite recent layoffs, CompuServe is on the
comeback trail, having just released its latest software version _
CompuServe 2000 for Windows 95 and 98.
</P>
<P>
   I downloaded and installed the software the other day. Then it
took me about 10 minutes to open a new account, sign on and begin
exploring.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? Although the new CompuServe is all Web-based and is
geared toward adults, it looks and feels like AOL. Not much
surprise there, I suppose.
</P>
<P>
   What I like about the new CompuServe is that it's been
streamlined. Pages are clean and crisp. Navigation is simple,
thanks to a menu bar at the top. And because it's geared toward
adults, CompuServe lacks the annoying kiddie stuff you'll find on
AOL.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the famous CompuServe forums? They're still there!
Veterans may complain that the forums aren't what they used to be.
But there's still plenty of quality information, whether you're
interested in the latest headlines, how to plant a garden, Web-site
design, personal finance, travel or just about anything in between.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, I found the service a bit slow at times. And there remain
a few maddening glitches. A special page devoted to the new Austin
Powers movie, for example, just would not load for me. And I tried
several times during a six-hour period. Additionally, sometimes the
back button at the top of the screen would work, sometimes it
wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing for the revamped CompuServe is on par with what AOL
charges. Pricing plans include a $9.95-a-month plan that comes with
20 hours (extra hours cost $2.95 each), a $19.95-a-month plan with
unlimited use and an unlimited-use annual fee of $199.
</P>
<P>
   Why try CompuServe? For one thing, with just 2 million members
it should be easier to dial into than AOL. Also, it looks and feels
like a big Web site, so it's easy to find your way around. And
those forums are packed with tons of information.
</P>
<P>
   I can't imagine CompuServe will ever again be the granddaddy of
online services. But it just might be the comfortable online spot
you've been looking for. &QL; 
Web sites of the week &QL; 
- It's hot outside. The kids are bored. What to do? You might fire
up the computer and check out Favorite Kid Links. Find the site at
www.goodnet.com/eel (Note the tilde before eel.) The site is the
creation of Lee, who lives in Scottsdale, Ariz. You'll find links
to sites for Barney, Blues Clues, Rugrats and more. There is even a
couple pages of links for Mom and Dad.
</P>
<P>
   - If you surf the Web a lot, you might be tired of having to
fill out all those registration forms by hand or having to remember
all those passwords to access special sites. Here's an idea:
Jotter(at)Your Service. It's a free utility developed by Jotter
Technologies Inc. in Mesa, formerly known as Mindquake Interactive.
Find out how it works at www.jotter.com.
</P>
<P>
   - Looking to buy a computer, digital camera or some other
electronic gadget? Check 20-20Consumer first. The Web site, at
www.20-20consumer.com, claims to be an independent consumer
comparison-shopping service that updates its price listings daily.
It's not a store, but service that surveys what retailers are
asking for specific items. It's worth a look!
</P>
<P>
   - Are you one of those people who likes to send electronic
greeting cards? Now you can send an e-mail greeting with original
music that mentions the recipient's name in the lyrics! Valley
residents Tim and Kathy Penrod are the people behind
MusicalGreetings.com, at www.musicalgreetings.com. Don't like
sending e-mail? You can also get the greeting on an audio CD or
cassette tape so it can be mailed to the recipient. Prices start at
just $7.95. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)home.net by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
