<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Tuesday, June
1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES  &LR; (Category `a')
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTRO (Chicago) _ The first results of a new survey of the
heavens has found a large number of so-called brown dwarfs, which
are bigger than planets but smaller than stars. By John Noble
Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FLEAS (Undated) _ Fleas' habits would surely place them
among the more repulsive of living things. Upon landing on their
victim, they proceed to harass, extract blood, induce allergic
reactions, introduce infectious organisms and deposit their eggs on
their unwelcoming host. As if that is not enough of a turnoff, the
tiny worm-like larvae emerging from the eggs feed principally on
the feces of their parents, who nourish the next generation with
partially digested blood. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STATUS (Undated) _ Scientists have known for decades that
poverty translates into higher rates of illness and mortality. But
an explosion of research is demonstrating that social class _ as
measured not just by income but also by education and other markers
of relative status _ is one of the most powerful predictors of
health, more powerful than genetics, exposure to carcinogens, even
smoking. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TRIANA (Undated) _ Al Gore's midnight inspiration for a
satellite that could provide continuous Earth views grew into a
scientifically worthy mission before it ran into politcal
opposition. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WOLF (Undated) _ Timber wolves from Canada are unlikely to
recolonize the northeastern United States on their own, leaving the
politically more contentious course of deliberate reintroduction as
the best strategy for restoring the wild wolf's howl to the region,
a new study sponsored by New York's Wildlife Conservation Society
has found. w/ sidebar. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WOLF-ROCKIES (Undated) _ Experimental restoration of the
gray wolf to Montana, Idaho and Wyoming has been so successful
since 1995, Federal officials say, that the first steps toward a
single, integrated wolf population in the Northern Rockies have now
been taken. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MATING-ESSAY (Undated) _ Because mating lies at the center
of so much of life, it is a particularly important area of study
for evolutionary psychologists. Sociologically, mating affects the
distribution of wealth. Psychologically, it influences nearly
everything from depression to social success. Mate preferences _
how we pick partners, attract them, conflict with them, keep them,
lose them, and then start all over again _ determine who is
selected and shunned, altering our species' evolution. By David M.
Buss.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FAMINE (Undated) _ Hordes of creatures living in the hidden
depths of the deep sea are in danger of starving to death,
scientists report. This remote part of the planet is believed to
harbor millions of undiscovered species, an unknown number of which
may be in crisis. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-WATCH (Undated) _ Items on research with implication in
molecular-scale devices, what can be learned from ancient emu eggs
and an 18th moon for Uranus.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CENTENARIAN (Undated) _ Until recently, very few people
lived to be more than 100 years old, but more and more are living
to extreme old age in very good health. A study of 169 centenarians
in Massachusetts reveals: Only three have had cancer; a
disproportionate number are women who never married; there is no
pattern of diet and exercise; the only common personality trait is
the ability to manage stress; about 80 percent are women, but the
relatively few men in the group are far healthier than the women,
and among the women who are mothers, the ones who had children
after age 40 are disproportionately represented. By Philip J.
Hilts.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEROIDS (Undated) _ Girls with an interest in the lean
muscular look are turning increasingly to steroids, say prominent
researchers in field. Meanwhile, use among boys also is increasing.
By Holcomb B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STREND (Undated) _ For those who have fond memories of the
president's Physical Fitness Test, there is now a grown up version
of it called Strend, a challenging six-event contest that is
attracting more and more competitors. By Liz Neporent.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Not all summer camps are created
equally. And safety should be a major consideration for parents.
Tips for choosing safer summer camps. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SUNSCREEN (Undated) _ New guidelines and definitions for
sunscreens are introduced. By Alisha Berger.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ If a body temperature of 107 degrees
Fahrenheit is nearly always fatal, what low body temperature is
generally fatal? By C. Claiborne Ray.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART (Undated) _ Adding a ``super aspirin'' to a standard
clot-dissolving drug was a more effective and safer treatment for
heart attacks in an international study being published. By
Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HORMONE (Undated) _ By new study suggests that low-dose
hormone replacement therapy combined with calcium and vitamin D
supplements may increase bone mineral density in women over 65 by
at least as much as the higher hormone doses now recommended but
without unpleasant side effects. By Nancy Beth Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE &LR;  (Category `e')
</P>
<P>
   HARE-INTERVIEW (Undated) _ Interview with playwright David Hare.
By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   CRITICS-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ Critic's Notebook: When composers
ask musicians to do the impossible. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   MONET-EXHIBIT (Paris) _ Arts Abroad: Paris has another great
Monet exhibit. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   WALLACE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Brief Interviews With Hideous
Men,'' by David Foster Wallace. By Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS  &LR; (Category `s')
</P>
<P>
   BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports column on the
Cleveland-Yankees series, generally conceded to be the two best
teams in the American League. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEES-INDIANS (New York) _ Cleveland at Yankees, 1:05 p.m.
By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-REDS (New York) _ Cincinnati at Mets, 1:15 p.m. By
Jason Diamos.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN (Indianapolis) _ Sports column on the Knicks
and Pacers, who practice on Memorial Day as they get ready for Game
2 on Tuesday night. Column likely to focus on Rik Smits, who had a
bad game on Sunday but could give the resilient Patrick Ewing a
tough time on Tuesday. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS-PACERS (Indianapolis) _ Knicks and Pacers prepare for
Game 2. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-WISE-COLUMN (Indianapolis) _ On Basketball column on Knicks
and Pacers, comparing coaches Larry Bird, who leads the most even
of existences as a revered coach in Indianapolis, and Jeff Van
Gundy, whose every day is another soap opera installment. By Mike
Wise.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SPURS-TRAILBLAZERS (San Antonio) _ Portland at San Antonio,
5:30 p.m., the Spurs lead this series, 1-0. By Chris Broussard.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-SABRES-MAPLELEAFS (Toronto) _ Buffalo at Toronto, 7:30 p.m.
By Joe Lapointe.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-FRENCH-OPEN (Paris) _ The French Open continues. Two
Brazilian men are in the quarterfinals, one of them a surprise. By
Robin Finn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLE &LR;  (`l' category)
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS-FASHION (New York) _ Fashion notes and news. By
Anne-Marie Schiro.
</P>
<P>
   DUTCH-DESIGNERS (New York) _ Why are all these fanatically cool
people pouring into Visionaire, the fashion publisher and art
gallery in SoHo, to check out the latest haute couture creations by
a couple of Dutch designers named Viktor Horsting and Rolf Snoeren?
By Cathy Horyn.
</P>
<P>
   BY-DESIGN-FASHION (New York) _ Denim has made such a strong
comeback that it is being used for many things other than jeans.
There are dresses, shorts, shoes and bags in different shades of
blue. By Anne-Marie Schiro.
</P>
