<HEADER>
A7352 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK-COX     05-31 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MONEY TALK: Advice for novice investors
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of this year's college graduates are eager to start saving
and investing for their future.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect, however, that this generation is no better prepared
for the job than mine was.
</P>
<P>
   Few of today's beginners have gotten any formal education in
managing their investments. A surprising percentage say they rely
on parents or even on their young contemporaries for financial
advice. Our offspring will need plenty of professional help, just
like we did.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, a lot of publishers have offered to sell us
books that promise to give that help.
</P>
<P>
   Notable among these is ``If You're Clueless About the Stock
Market and Want to Know More,'' a yellow-covered competitor for
Eric Tyson's ``Investing for Dummies.''
</P>
<P>
   Seth Godin, author of the ``clueless'' book, has made investing
easy to understand, for the uninitiated and even for complicated
topics.
</P>
<P>
   His explanation of corporate financial reports, for example, is
the clearest I've seen. Godin explains not only how to understand
balance sheets and the like, but also why any investor should do
it.
</P>
<P>
   He makes an admirable case for taking risks of investing in
stock but doing it carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there is plenty of reason to be optimistic about the
long-term financial benefits of investing in stocks,'' he writes,
``there is also a need for individual investors to temper optimism
with a solid dose of caution and good sense. Stocks can be very
lucrative investments, but they can easily be as slippery as
fish.''
</P>
<P>
   This is by no means the only book aimed at novices, but it is
one of the best. Among the strong points: A step-by-step guide to
picking a stockbroker; discussions of common strategies, such as
dividend reinvestment plans and the dogs of the Dow; and lengthy
lists of further resources.
</P>
<P>
   Godin also suggests some crucial pre-investment homework for
beginners:
</P>
<P>
   _ Take care of debt first. Any money you invest in stocks should
be considered risk money, money that is not necessary to keep you,
your family and your dogs and cats alive. Pay the mortgage, pay the
car payment and by all means get rid of those credit card debts.
You most likely will be paying far more in interest on those things
than you will probably make in the market.
</P>
<P>
   _ Think about diversification. Try to build a portfolio of
investments in different types of stocks, or even buy shares in a
bond fund or two. While taking great risks can, and sometimes does,
result in fantastic profits, not losing all your money has more
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never, ever, bet the ranch. No matter how much money your
broker or your friends say you'll make on a stock, don't risk
everything on a single stock.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do your homework. Make sure you really like the company's
financials before you throw your money into the ring. Don't buy
anything that you don't understand and about which you can't find
any information.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't forget the costs. You will pay a commission on every buy
and every sell, so factor that in right from the start. Don't
forget about income taxes on your profits.
</P>
<P>
   Godin does not pretend that every aspect of investing is
straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   But when he comes to an ambiguous topic, such as understanding
the significance of a company's price-to-earnings ratio, he
explains how to put the numbers into a meaningful context.
</P>
<P>
   Given all those ambiguities and uncertainties, a lot of young
investors will choose to abandon stock picking and put their money
into mutual funds instead. A lot of older investors have done the
same thing.
</P>
<P>
   After all, a mutual fund turns all the uncertainties over to
professionals to wrangle with. If that's your choice, there are
plenty of other books to look into. John Bogle Sr., founder of the
Vanguard Group of mutual funds, has written several. Guess what: So
has Seth Godin.
</P>
<P>
   RESOURCES _ BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   Here are more good books on investing and personal finance,
starting with the simplest and going to the most comprehensive:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Rookie's Guide to Money Management: How to Keep Score of
Your Finances.'' Carolina Edwards and Ray Martin. $12. Truly a
beginner's book. Includes explanations of why things need to be
done and a useful encyclopedia of financial terms.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Green Magazine Guide to Personal Finance: A No B.S. Book
for Your Twenties and Thirties.'' By Ken Kurson. $12.95. Covers a
lot of territory and is strong on explaining the basics.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Making the Most of Your Money,'' Jane Bryant Quinn, $30.
Also ``Marshall Loeb's Lifetime Financial Strategies,'' Marshall
Loeb, $17. Big, all-purpose books on organizing your financial
life.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Wall Street Journal Lifetime Guide to Money,'' edited by
C. Frederic Wiegold, $15.95. Probably the most detailed of the
bunch but still comprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   RESOURCES _ WEB SITES
</P>
<P>
   Some useful Web sites for new investors:
</P>
<P>
   _ www.ndb.com/ _ Click on ``NDB University'' to start an
extensive set of lessons on investing and personal finance.
Prepared by the sponsoring brokerage and Money magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.investoreducation.org _ The Alliance for Investor
Education has some good ideas as well as links to other useful
sites.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.kiplinger.com or www.dtonline.com/pfa/pfa.htm _ Large
collections of personal finance information.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.smartmoney.com _ Includes plenty of market news and views,
extensive commentaries on personal finance topics.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
