<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7355 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REUNITED-COX     05-31 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REUNITED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Papa-san! Papa-san!' Nearly a half-century ago, an American
soldier took in a homeless Korean boy and became `like a daddy' to
him; recently, through a stroke of luck, they were united again.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Brad Schrade
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life inside the army tent was cold and remote for John Walters.
The pair of wood-burning stoves were no match for the freezing
winds that blew down from China at night. His wife and baby girl
back in Atlanta seemed a million miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Outside there were men dying in icy darkness and mothers
starving in snow-covered street gutters and refugee children trying
to survive that horrible time a half-century ago, when American
soldiers sailed across an ocean to fight a war on the peninsula
called Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst year of my life,'' said Walters, who never
heard his wife's voice the whole time he was away at war. ``It's an
everyday drain on your emotions. It's like a damn debilitating
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kim was 12 in the fall and winter of 1952. Communist
troops had swept through his Korean farming village, and his family
had joined the stream of refugees fleeing south.
</P>
<P>
   He had friends among the 2 million Koreans who died in the war.
Amid the chaos, he lost his family. He was living on the streets
and didn't know whether his family was alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was winter,'' Kim said recently from his home in St. Paul,
Minn. ``You know the cold here in Minnesota. It was colder than
that in Korea. Freezing, hunger, 20 below _ oh, horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Walters, then 26, arrived south of Seoul, at Osan, South Korea,
in November 1952 with Company C, the 841st Engineer Aviation
Battalion. He had gotten lucky, sort of. His orders were to help
build an 11,000-foot airstrip there, behind the front. It gave him
a better chance to keep his name off the casualty list, which would
eventually include 54,000 dead U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-hour workdays, filled with the growl of bulldozers and
the grinding thump of rocks being crushed, exhausted Walters. Every
so often, enemy Korean planes _ known as ``Bed-Check Charlies'' _
would drop bombs on the airfield at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I'd think when I woke up every morning was how
many days until I rotate (home),'' Walters said. ``I kept a count
in my head.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy, Kim, ``just appeared'' at the officers' tent one day,
with flapping ears that made him look a little like Mickey Mouse,
Walters recalled recently at his home in Cumming.
</P>
<P>
   Kim had an infectious smile and a cheery disposition. The only
outward sign of the hardship he had endured was his ragged clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Walters and the five other officers who shared the tent took him
in to be their tent boy. He sang along to their country and western
records in between keeping the two wood stoves burning, cleaning
and washing clothes. In exchange for these chores, the boy got a
place to sleep and a steady diet of Army food _ relative luxuries
for a Korean refugee.
</P>
<P>
   Walters would show Kim home movies at night. His wife, Shirley,
sent them over a couple of times a month. And Walters would sit
with Kim and watch his little girl, Becky, grow up, one 8mm reel at
a time.
</P>
<P>
   The boy would ride with Walters around the air base in his Army
Jeep, which had ``Shirley'' and ``Becky'' painted on the
windshield's frame.
</P>
<P>
   Kim made Walters laugh. ``You'd come in (to the tent) and the
kid's singing damn country music and he can barely speak English,''
Walters remembered. ``He was just the cutest little guy you ever
saw. The longer he was there, we just bonded. He was like a son to
me, and he helped me get through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim's wooden cot was placed next to Walters', and the boy
started calling him ``papa-san.'' Walters called Kim ``boy-san.''
</P>
<P>
   ``War time is very horrible,'' said Kim, now 58. ``I was alone.
That's why I depended on him, Mr. Walters. He raised me like a
daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Walters' year at war ended. In October 1953, he sailed back
home aboard the Gen. M.C. Meig. Eventually the letters stopped
traveling back and forth across the Pacific, and the two men lost
touch.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Kim found his parents and siblings. He eventually
married and raised two sons, and now he has three grandchildren.
Two decades ago, he moved his family to Minnesota to be near his
sister and her husband. He owns a delicatessen at the base of a
tall building in downtown St. Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Kim asked military men whether they knew a man
from the South whose first name was ``Lieutenant.'' Kim thought
Walters lived in Louisiana. ``I gave up a couple of years ago,'' he
said. ``I thought he passed away or he was too old.''
</P>
<P>
   Walters retired in 1989, after 38 years at Lockheed producing
hydraulic equipment. Now 72, he lives with Shirley in a one-story
house on a spacious, manicured lot in Forsyth County.
</P>
<P>
   A large photograph hangs in their kitchen. It shows them smiling
at their 50th wedding anniversary party last year, surrounded by
their four children, eight grandchildren and other loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   Walters never forgot Kim. Whenever he would meet pilots from the
South Korean air force at Lockheed, he'd tell them about Kim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd ask them to look for him and let me know if they found
him. Nobody ever did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Walters eat regularly at the Golden Buddha restaurant in
Cumming. In December, a waitress there was headed to South Korea to
visit her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Walters took another shot in the dark. He gave her $100 and a
photograph of Kim as a college student, and she placed an ad in a
Korean newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Days later, the Walters' telephone rang. It had been 45 years
since he left Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's Becky?'' the voice asked. It was Kim. A relative had
seen the ad and told him about it. A reunion was set up in Atlanta
for the following weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On the flight to Atlanta, Kim told his story to the flight
attendants and passengers around him. After the plane landed at
Hartsfield International Airport, women were getting off in tears.
</P>
<P>
   When he saw Walters, Kim fell to his knees, grabbed Walter's
ankles and cried, ``Papa-san! Papa-san!''
</P>
<P>
   Memories of the war still bother Kim. He has had trouble
sleeping after watching television footage of Kosovo, because it
``reminds me of Korea. Very sad.''
</P>
<P>
   But since his December reunion with Walters, with phone
conversations every week and a reunion in Minnesota last weekend,
Kim has started to tell his own family about the war experience
that for years was ``too sad'' to share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I've met him, I've told my story to my son, wife,
church people,'' Kim said. ``I found him. I can't hide my back
life. I told the truth. I told my whole story.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
