<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEUTRAL FEW, ULSTER JEWS IN UNIQUE SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ It's a joke every Belfast Jew knows, and tells,
because it's so telling about Jews' status here.
</P>
<P>
   You're approached on the street and asked what religion you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm Jewish,'' you reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah yes,'' the inquisitor says, ``but are you a Catholic Jew or
a Protestant Jew?''
</P>
<P>
   In a land where nearly everyone has been compelled to choose
sides, it's only natural that Belfast Jews would, too. But the tiny
Jewish community has stayed neutral. Determinedly so, at least as
far as the congregation as a whole is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   With precisely the result intended: Jews have earned the respect
of both sides in the sectarian battles, or at least they've escaped
their enmity, an impressive achievement for a people who in so many
nations have been a lightning rod for vilification and violence.
</P>
<P>
   It's partly their even-handedness. Small numbers also make it
easier to stay on the sidelines. And the Jewish community has a
warm relationship with the Catholic cardinal at the same time that
leading Protestants, especially evangelical ones, feel an affinity
with the Old Testament's chosen people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably been less anti-Semitism in Northern Ireland
than in most other places,'' says Ronnie Appleton, president of the
congregation and former Chief Crown Prosecutor, a posting that saw
him go after terrorists from both camps.
</P>
<P>
   And Jews have used their neutrality to bridge gaps, especially
at the start of the Troubles in the early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The premises of the synagogue were practically the only safe
meeting point in the whole of North Belfast for opposing
factions,'' recalls Cyril Rosenberg, a long-time Jewish leader.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Jews haven't been touched by the Troubles.
</P>
<P>
   One was killed, another wounded, and several were attacked
during 30 years of violence. But those incidents stemmed from being
in the wrong place at the wrong time, or in businesses where their
money made them easy targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true to say that the Jews have largely remained outside
the conflict,'' says Marie Smyth, who runs a research group that
studies the human and other costs of the strife.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jewish roots in Northern Ireland run deep and strong, even if
the notion of an Irish Jew seems an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   The first arrived from Germany in the 1840s, while descendants
of most of today's Northern Ireland Jews came 50 years later from
Russia, fleeing deadly pogroms. They were poor, couldn't speak
English, but founded a mainly Orthodox community that over time
sponsored everything from a social club and dance hall to tennis
courts, football fields, burial grounds, and a synagogue that held
hundreds. They also influenced the wider community, providing it
with doctors and dentists, lawyers, merchants, and now, a lord
mayor of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   At its height in the early 1970s, the Jewish community here
numbered 1,500, with most living in north Belfast. Today barely 250
remain, so few that the community has sold social halls,
partitioned its synagogue, and struggles to get the 10 men needed
for a religious service.
</P>
<P>
   The decline was due largely to young Jews leaving for England,
Israel, or the United States in search of spouses, or broader
educational and professional opportunities. The Troubles also were
a factor, limiting the chance for Jews, as for everyone, to safely
congregate and raising doubts about the future.
</P>
<P>
   What about the Jewish community's future?
</P>
<P>
   Most here are pessimistic, barring an infusion of Jewish
immigrants fleeing oppression or seeking economic opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``But how many will that be?'' asks Rosenberg, a retired
jeweler. ``And they have got to be young, married people who will
produce families. We don't need any more old people or even
middle-aged ones.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
