<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-LLBEAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE PORK IS KING, THEY DON'T KNOW BEANS ABOUT MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's capital, which already has the White
House, the Chinese pandas, and the House Republican managers, is
about to get its own trout stream. Inside. At a shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   L.L. Bean, the venerable Freeport, Maine, purveyor of hunting
boots and chamois shirts, is coming to a mall just a few miles
outside the Washington city line. The 75,000 square foot store
planned for Tysons Corner, Va., will be the beginning of a chain of
Bean stores across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, you say: More evidence of the homogenization of America.
Except for one thing: Even with regional differences seeping out of
American culture, it would be impossible to make Washington
anything like Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Here the preeminent outdoor sport is hiking over to the
Government Printing Office to pick up early copies of the
President's Budget Message to Congress. Here the most treacherous,
winding trail leads from the third floor of the Senate side of the
Capitol to the third floor of the House side of the Capitol. Here
big-game hunting is done by fund-raisers employed by the Democratic
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Maine Hiking Shoe that Leon Leonwood Bean advertised for
$2.85 (postpaid) in Hunter-Trapper-Trader magazine in 1929 is all
but unknown here; this is the land of a different sort of footwear.
During a late-night tax markup session in the mid 1980s, anxious
lobbyists paced in front of the closed doors of the Senate Finance
Committee hearing room. Senator Bob Dole, at the time the Finance
chairman, was told that the lobbyists were Gucci-to-Gucci in the
hallways (although he allowed as to how they would be barefoot in
the morning).
</P>
<P>
   In my 20 years in exile from New England I have seen with my own
eyes Washingtonians walking on mountain trails in beach
flip-flopssweatshirts;; Washingtonians flopping down demanding ski
trails in the freeze of mid February wearing Florida State
sweatshirts; Washingtonians passing a beautiful spring picnic
afternoon talking about community development block grants;
Washingtonians sitting at the shore with their briefcases;
Washingtonians paying $10 a pound in a grocery store for the most
pitiful, listless lobsters you have ever seen; Washingtonians who
have no moxie and never have tasted Moxie; Washingtonians who think
that a clam roll consists of scrawny little clam necks stuffed in
an untoasted bun.
</P>
<P>
   So before L.L. Bean plants its store in Tysons Corner, it ought
to know the following things about Washington:
</P>
<P>
   1. Thrift is not embraced in Washington, as it is in Maine. L.L.
Bean himself once crusaded for the flinty values that the nation
now celebrates only in nostaligia. ``We wish to call your attention
to the fact that throwing away a pair of used Maine Hunting Shoes
is about the same as throwing away a $5 bill,'' he once wrote,
asking customers to send their old shoes back to Freeport to be
rebuilt. Washington, on the other hand, is the city where the
deficit blossomed, and where the budget surplus that followed was
marked by a remarkable burst of feeding at the troughs by the
porkmeisters of Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   2. The greatest of all New England values, the reluctance to pop
off about something you know nothing about, is not honored here. At
any hour Capitol Hill is full of experts on subjects they have
hardly ever encountered. Representative Perkins Bass, a Republican
who represented the western congressional district in New Hampshire
between 1955 and 1963, was known as Small-Mouth Bass. (His son, who
has represented the same district since 1995, is no talkaholic
either.) Advice to human resources coordinator for the Tysons
Corner Store: Taciturn Maine salespeople will not do. Find a
filibusterer. The locals love a talker.
</P>
<P>
   3. There are no seasons here, at least not like the ones there
are in Maine. But there is election season, and for that the
preferred attire is the blue Oxford-cloth shirt and the red tie. No
one who has ever worn anything remotely like the short-sleeve
hibiscus floral shirt on page 32 of the current cataloghas ever
been sighted in the Speaker's Lobby. Sad but true.
</P>
<P>
   4. It does not snow here, at least not like it does in Maine.
Last March the local authorities closed the public schools in the
District of Columbia after the area was hit by the icy blast of
winter and huge amounts of snowfalls, with drifts approaching
three-quarters of an inch in my backyard. In Maine they say that
``the snow of winter did lie very long upon the ground.'' Here the
``snow'' of ``winter'' lasts for but a few hours. No need here for
snowshoes, except maybe on the wall of a bar, where they might be
mistaken for old tennis rackets.
</P>
<P>
   5. People do not stir here in summer, at least not like they do
in Maine. In his famous elegy to a lifetime of lake summers in
Maine, E.B. White wrote: ``Summertime, oh, summertime, pattern of
life indelible, the fade-proof lake, the woods unshatterable, the
pasture with the sweetfern and the juniper forever and ever, summer
without end.'' Even if a writer of White's read lived here (and
none would), he would never write a sentence like that.
</P>
<P>
   A Washington summer is a lot like a sauna without a shower.
James Russell Wiggins, who was managing editor and editor of The
Washington Post, abandoned the game of tennis and just about
anything else outdoors when he came here. ``When I moved to
Washington I quit doing things outdoors,'' said Wiggins. ``It was
too damn hot.'' Wiggins, who at 95 now edits The Ellsworth American
(circulation 12,000) in Ellsworth, Maine, has a theory that might
explain Bean's marketing strategy: ``Maybe,'' he told me, ``they're
appealing to the people in Washington who are planning to move up
here, to Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   6. Geography and geology have conspired to make the Washington
area recreation-free, and not at all like Maine. It is possible to
get to decent mountains from Washington. It takes four hours. It is
possible to get to a decent beach from Washington. It takes three
hours. This is one explanation for why Washingtonians are so
severe.
</P>
<P>
   For years an L.L. Bean catalog cover has hung in my home. It was
produced in fall 1933, and it is mostly blue, like the times. In
the background is a dog, and in the foreground is a hunter with a
long rifle standing in knee-high boots in the snow. This man has
never been to a food court. This man has never consumed homemade
pasta with spinach, mortadella ham and three cheeses baked in a
cream sauce, nor has he ever dipped his freshly caught fish in a
Parmesean egg batter, flash-fried it, topped it with hollandaise,
and plopped it on a plate with bliss potatoes. (These are actual
menu items from the best-known pub in Tysons Corner, a rifle shot
from the very spot where L.L. Bean will be located.)
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday night I was paddling a canoe on Great Pond in
Rome, Maine. The breeze was brisk, the sky clear. There was an
osprey nest in the tree on the big island. The ducks paddled
quietly. The blue flag of Maine flapped from a pole on the shore.
The water was cool, a hint of March mixing with the reality of May.
It was a real Maine moment, ``under the silent spruces,'' as Edna
St. Vincent Millay wrote in her Maine poetry, ``where the wide,
quiet evening darkens without haste.''
</P>
<P>
   For that Maine moment I felt far from my worries, from my
obligations _ and from the mall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David M. Shribman is chief of the Globe's Washington bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
