<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENT-INDICT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDICTMENT OF MILOSEVIC TO TEST NATO'S WILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH NEUFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Slobodan Milosevic, indicted at last. More than a decade after
the Serbian strongman incited a campaign of poisonous nationalism
that fanned deadly conflicts across the Balkans, he and four of his
top aides were charged last week by the International Criminal
Tribunal in The Hague with war crimes, including murder.
</P>
<P>
   But indicting Milosevic for atrocities in the Yugoslavian
province of Kosovo and actually bringing him to the dock are two
different things. The next few months will be a critical test of
whether NATO's political leaders are as serious about bringing war
criminals to justice as they have claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Should the North Atlantic Treaty Organization fail to do all it
can to help the tribunal bring Milosevic to trial _ including
providing key intelligence, or acting on the arrest warrants that
accompanied the indictment _ it will cement the tribunal's
reputation as powerless, and underscore how feckless are the
political leaders in Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the war crimes tribunal, created by the United
Nations Security Council in 1993, is independent from NATO, which
can have no influence over whom the tribunal indicts. But in
practice, the tribunal relies on governments to enforce its
actions. In the Balkans, where countries refuse to cooperate, that
means the job falls to NATO. It, after all, has a military presence
on the ground _ and there's no one else to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Yet NATO's reactions to the indictment were mixed. Despite the
condemnation of Milosevic that has poured out of the US and
European capitals in recent weeks, many diplomats have made it
clear they fear the indictment will imperil, if not sink, ongoing
efforts to devise a peaceful halt to the Kosovo conflict. Before
the indictment had even been announced, French Interior Minister
Jean-Pierre Chevenement had slammed it as ``counterproductive.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the tricky issues raised by the fact that the
Yugoslav president is the first sitting head of state ever to be
indicted for war crimes. Can you negotiate with an indicted war
criminal? Only British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook immediately
brushed aside concerns. Even though Milosevic has been indicted,
Cook said, it would be ``irresponsible'' of NATO not to press him
for a peace settlement in Kosovo as long as he remains in power.
Cook also vowed that such negotiations would not include a promise
of amnesty for Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   There is precedent: Diplomats met with former Bosnian Serb
leader Radovan Karadzic after his indictment for genocide. But this
nonetheless remains a troubling issue for many in NATO, who are
uneasy negotiating with a man who is now officially branded an
international criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Arbour, the tribunal's top prosecutor, says as much, but
the idea troubles her for a slightly different reason. The
tribunal's evidence raises questions about Milosevic's ``suitablity
to be the guarantors of any deal, let alone a peace agreement,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The key question now is how far NATO is willing to go to ensure
that Milosevic is actually brought to trial. Several problems
emerge, among them NATO's continuing concern about turning over key
intelligence to prosecutors, and its failure so far to arrest war
criminals in the Balkans. Both are critical to what happens next.
</P>
<P>
   The latter issue is the most troubling. NATO's own track record
reveals its utter lack of commitment: Of the 84 persons publicly
indicted for crimes in Bosnia, only 25 are in custody, and many of
those surrendered voluntarily. Karadzic and General Ratko Mladic
remain at large, despite their indictments for genocide. Many feel
their arrests would have prevented the tragedies of Kosovo from
occurring in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had arrested Karadzic, then Milosevic would have known
what his future would be,'' said Blerim Shala, editor of the Kosovo
weekly Zeri. ``He'd know the West wasn't just making a statement on
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   But will NATO arrest Milosevic, and failing that, at least
arrest Karadzic, who could link Milosevic to war crimes in Bosnia?
(The indictment charges him only for war crimes in Kosovo, much to
the distress of many Bosnians.)
</P>
<P>
   Given NATO's track record, no one believes Milosevic's arrest
will be swift. ``I don't think anybody expects NATO troops to go
searching for Milosevic in Belgrade,'' said Reed Brody, advocacy
director of Human Rights Watch, ``but these crimes have no statute
of limitations, and 15 years from now, Milosevic will still be
under indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   Should NATO troops ever enter Kosovo, or Serbia, it's also
important to avert the kind of farce that occurred in Bosnia, where
NATO troops avoided Karadzic so as not to have to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   NATO should make clear that it takes seriously not only the
arrest of Milosevic, but also of his indicted henchmen: Milan
Milutinovic, president of the Republic of Serbia; Nikola Sainovic,
deputy prime minister of the federal Republic of Serbia; Dragoljub
Ojdanic, chief of the General Staff of the Armed Forces; and Vlajko
Stojiljkovic, minister of interior affairs.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot afford to repeat the indifference it exhibited to the
last important indictment unveiled against an alleged war criminal:
Zeljko Raznjatovic, otherwise known as Arkan. NATO was silent even
as the brazen Arkan appeared on CNN and network television.
</P>
<P>
   It's also vital that NATO continue to supply the tribunal with
key intelligence. Notably, the indictment against Milosevic _ for
crimes against humanity and violations of the laws and customs of
war _ charges him with personal criminal responsibility. This is
good news; it means NATO leaders, who have made a show of turning
over evidence, must have given the tribunal something to directly
link Milosevic and his underlings with the crimes. Those familiar
with Milosevic's habits say he rarely leaves an incriminating paper
trail, doesn't use the telephone, and issues no written directives.
</P>
<P>
   Every shred of evidence will be needed to make the case, should
it ever come to trial. Legal experts and those familiar with
Milosevic say it will not be easy. In addition to individual
criminal responsibility, Milosevic is also charged in the
indictment with responsibility for crimes committed by those he
oversees, under a strategy known as ``command responsibility,'' a
legal theory not raised since Nuremberg.
</P>
<P>
   The theory _ under which leaders can be charged not only with
ordering their subordinates to do something, but also with failing
to halt a crime or punish those who commit them _ has been used in
several cases at The Hague. But prosecutors have had mixed success
in proving it to the tribunal judges' satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   In one key case last year, the first to put Bosnian Muslims on
trial for war crimes committed against camp prisoners, judges
acquitted the overall military commander. They said that while he
may have had responsibility for the camp, prosecutors did not prove
he was responsible for his subordinates' actions.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say that means future prosecutors will have to
prove a commander's complicity, not just argue he is automatically
responsible for crimes committed by his subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   That means NATO governments will have to be willing to turn over
everything _ from telephone intercepts to other forms of
intelligence _ to ensure Milosevic and the others indicted are
directly linked to their subordinates' crimes. That's what it will
take to counter efforts by this master manipulator.
</P>
<P>
   To escape prosecution, Milosevic is likely to ``come up with
some concocted memo that orders all the refugees to be treated
humanely,'' predicted Terree Bowers, an assistant US attorney in
Los Angeles, who worked as a prosecutor in The Hague. ``Karadzic
attempted to do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's indictment alone sends the message that no one is
above the law, but it does not yet send the message that those who
commit atrocities will be punished. As the former head of the
tribunal, Richard Goldstone, put it: ``It's second prize, but it's
better than nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The question for NATO _ and all of us _ is whether second prize
is what we want.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Elizabeth Neuffer, a visiting fellow at the Council on Foreign
Relations, is on leave from the Globe, where she last was European
bureau chief.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7363 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-31 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NO ILLUSIONS' WITH COX REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Two Republican congressmen. Two similar jobs _
running a deadly serious investigation. Two similar mandates _ from
some guy named Gingrich who used to work around here. And two very
different outcomes: For Henry Hyde of the Judiciary, there was
political disaster masquerading on its best days as farce in the
impeachment proceeding against President Clinton; for Chris Cox of
California and his special committee investigating China's
acquisition of American nuclear secrets, there was bipartisan
success and deserved applause from most corners of the political
and policy world.
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident. Anything big around here gets done in a
bipartisan manner or it simply doesn't get done in this period of
bitter politics. Bipartisanship, however, is not a mood, it's the
result of hard work and give and take.
</P>
<P>
   In impeachment, what was available was official, stern
condemnation of the president's behavior in return for dropping an
effort to remove him. In the case of the Cox Commission, the
decision to come together was limited to two major points: a focus
on the glaring deficiencies in the counter-intelligence systems
that are supposed to protect national security information hasn't
been getting protection for more than 20 years; and a worst-case
description of China's nuclear potential as a result of its having
obtained nuclear weapons data _ especially about warheads.
</P>
<P>
   The result was genuine progress, at the legitimate price of
intentionally steering away from matters that would have produced
division. Grown-ups will take that deal nearly every time.
</P>
<P>
   It's important, however, not to ignore the areas where the Cox
report avoided conclusions. A good example is the odd and murky
tale of how, beginning four years ago, the US first became aware
that China was in possession of gobs of material it could only have
obtained by hook, if not by crook.
</P>
<P>
   In cursory form, the committee report confirms that in 1995 a
Chinese person approached US officials (there are indications it
was on Taiwan but that has yet to be confirmed) bearing classified
documents, offering more, and looking for spy work.Included in the
person's deliveries was a military document running at least a few
hundred pages on China's nuclear weapons program. And inside that
document was data that the Chinese intelligence agencies had
gathered about American warheads, especially the most advanced, the
W-88. The 11-year-old document is central to what is known about
what China knows; without it, the Cox Committee report would have
been a Sominex pill.
</P>
<P>
   There's a catch, however. While this person was making his
deliveries, the report says the US intelligence community came to
the firm conclusion that he was what the spooks call a ``directed
walk-in'' _ or a double-agent, or a Chinese agent working for
Beijing all along.
</P>
<P>
   This raises the most basic of questions about the whole affair,
none of which are dealt with, much less answered in the report.
Just consider the most plausible explanations:
</P>
<P>
   1. A simple screw-up, with the agent in possession of something
his superiors had either not reviewed carefully or didn't
understand would be explosive. It's convenient but hard to accept,
though screwing up is something most intelligence agencies are
adept at.
</P>
<P>
   2. The document was actually written much later but back-dated
to 1988 to protect its source. Interesting, but it doesn't explain
why the super-sensitive information was given to the US.
</P>
<P>
   3. Because the material was being shared with Taiwan, it could
have been a warning to the land China covets, advertising the
mainland's power and potential to further intimidate.
</P>
<P>
   4. It could have been a direct signal to the US, not so much to
intimidate as to make China's military potential more of a chip in
the multitude of ongoing talks that characterize our complicated
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Again, nobody knows for sure, but it is obvious from this one
nugget how much more important the future is than an endless
shouting match here over how much each of the last four presidents
knew or didn't know, did or didn't do.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that China has yet to modernize a primitive
intercontinental nuclear force that currently consists of about two
dozen single-warhead missiles stuck in silos. It is also clear that
China has yet to decide whether to embark on what for a still-poor
country could be a ruinously expensive and diverting fool's errand.
</P>
<P>
   That is why jumping to conclusions on a partisan basis could be
dangerous. That is also why none of the reactions to the Cox report
was more perplexing than that of Texas Gov. George Bush, who
denounced our current relationship of ``strategic partnership
without illusions'' with China that goes back to Richard Nixon's
famous visit more than 27 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to breaking with his father, Bush's use of the word
``competitor'' to describe China was dangerous, offering the
prospect of tension and instability on the basis of no hard
evidence. As a bipartisan success, the report is raising our guard
here and strengthening the attitude of ``no illusions.'' Beyond
that, however, lies silly scapegoating and irresponsibility about a
country much too dynamic and large for Cold War stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
