<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7366 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-31 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MAYOR'S DISSENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF JACOBY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
The place: A city hall press room 
The time: Now 
The city: Not this one, alas 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ital) Mr. Mayor, now that Los Angeles, San Francisco, and
Boston have decided to sue gun manufacturers, are you going to do
likewise? (unital) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No. As I said last fall when New Orleans and Chicago first set
this bandwagon rolling, these lawsuits are misguided. The reason we
have judges and juries is to effect justice, and there is nothing
just about punishing gun makers for lawful sales of a legal
product. The chief of special litigation in San Francisco describes
his city's lawsuit as being grounded in a law ``that reaches all
sort of conduct that might not be technically illegal.'' Well, this
city is not going to play that game. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ital) But shouldn't gun manufacturers be held liable when their
products are used to commit crimes? (unital)  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Look, if we head down that road, there'll be no turning back.
We'' have to hold Ford and Toyota liable because some of their
products are driven recklessly and cause fatal car crashes. We'll
have to sue IBM and Compaq because some computer users maliciously
crack government or corporate databases? (ital) Any (unital)
product can be used unlawfully. Our wrath should be directed at the
criminal, not the manufacturer whose useful product was wrongly
misused. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ital) `Useful product'?! How can you talk about guns that way,
especially after Littleton? (unital) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Please, spare me the histrionics. Guns are an extraordinarily
useful product, which is why tens of millions of Americans _
including many thousands of residents of this city _ own them. What
happened in Littleton was a horror. (ital) Every (unital) murder is
a horror. But using a gun to commit a crime is aberrant. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ital) Hello? Mr. Mayor, there are 450,000 gun-related crimes a
year in this country. You call that `aberrant?' (unital) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I do when there are 240 million civilian-owned guns. On average,
how many crimes would you say a criminal gets out of one gun? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ital) How would I know? I'm a journalist. (unital) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Make an estimate. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ital) Mmm _ three. (unital) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fine. Sounds reasonable. Three crimes per gun means that 150,000
guns _ out of 240 million _ are used criminally each year. That's
six-100ths of 1 percent. I'm not a statistician, but in my book,
0.06 percent is an aberration. If it's only two crimes per gun, the
percentage is still just 0.09. In any given year, 99.9 percent of
guns in America are (ital) not (unital) used for crimes. So how can
the Chicago lawsuit _ and some of the others, like Boston's _ argue
in good faith that gun companies are marketing and distributing
weapons so that they'll end up in criminals' hands? The crooks'
share of the market is too microscopic to bother with. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ital) Well, what about the product-liability theory _ gun
makers are selling weapons that are patently unsafe. They don't
incorporate safety features like trigger locks, and the result is
more gun deaths. (unital) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the result has been fewer gun deaths. Haven't you
heard? Murder and violent crime are down almost everywhere,
especially in big cities. Accidental gun fatalities have been
dropping for decades, even as the population and the number of guns
has gone up. John Lott at the University of Chicago Law School has
pulled together all kinds of data proving that the states with the
largest increases in gun ownership have posted the largest declines
in violent crime. Patently unsafe? I'd say guns are safer than
ever. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ital) Yeah, right. Tell that to the parents in Littleton.
(unital) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Again with the (ital) reductio ad Littleton? (unital) Listen,
this is not a difficult concept: The fact that guns were used to
perpetrate an atrocity does not negate the fact that guns are far
more likely to be a blessing than a curse. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ital) Come again? (unital) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let me read you something written by Lott, the University of
Chicago fellow: ``There are 15 national surveys that have been
conducted by academics as well as polling organizations like the
Los Angeles Times and Gallup, and their average estimate indicates
that people use guns defensively well over 2 million times each
year. My own survey put the defensive uses at about 2.1 million in
1997.'' Okay? Crimes involving guns _ 450,000. Crimes prevented by
guns _ 2 million. Blessing outweighs curse, 5 to 1. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (unital) With or without you, Mr. Mayor _ these lawsuits are
going forward. And if the tobacco litigation is any guide, there's
apt to be a big pot of money at the end. Can our city really afford
to deal itself out of the game? (unital) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ah. At last we get to the real issue: Money. Tom Cochran _ you
know, the executive director of the US Conference of Mayors _ put
his finger on it last December. ``The lawyers are seeing green on
this issue.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ital) Don't you have a fiduciary obligation to the people to
get as much of that green for the city as you can? (unital) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No. I have a moral obligation to them to conduct myself at all
times responsibly and with integrity. As long as I am mayor, this
city is not going to use the courts to extort money out of
industries that have not broken the law. People who wish to impose
restrictions on the design, manufacture, or sale of guns should
address their concerns to the City Council and the Legislature. The
honest way to change public policy is through debate and
legislation _ not litigation. Other mayors may be willing to
subvert the democratic process. I won't be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jeff Jacoby is a columnist for The Boston Globe.).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
