<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. VOTE ON KING HOLIDAY REVEALS A CHANGED STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ New Hampshire last week finally became the 50th state
to make the birthday of the late Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. a
state holiday. Now the question is whether the social change that
led to that decision will influence the 2000 presidential
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt that, over the years, the great influx of residents
from Massachusetts into southern New Hampshire has influenced the
outcome of statewide elections _ such as that of Democrat Jeanne
Shaheen to the governor's office in 1998. And, for the first time
in 100 years, Democrats have taken control of the New Hampshire
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   While some political strategists believe New Hampshire remains
more conservative than other states, the steady change in its
social landscape may well favor Democrats in the primary and
presidential votes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic primary, Vice President Al Gore stands to gain
more than Bill Bradley, the former US senator from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The views of both candidates reflect the thinking of the people
behind the successful campaign to have a King holiday in the state.
What bodes well for Gore is that President Clinton, Gore's biggest
backer, has also fared well there. He can presumably pass some of
that strength on to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire's changing political and social landscape may, in
the end, work against the expected GOP nominee, George W. Bush _
even though polls now show Bush thrashing Gore. A more realistic
measurement of Bush's popularity in the Granite State will come
after he faces media scrutiny as he campaigns there.
</P>
<P>
   How well Bush does in fielding reporters' questions about any
problems in his past may determine how well he does with New
Hampshire's evolving electorate.
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley, winning New Hampshire is crucial to his survival as
a presidential hopeful next year, even if he were to win Iowa.
Gore, on the other hand, can afford to lose both primaries and
still be able to win the nomination. But he also risks losing
important momentum to Bradley if Bradley comes out on top in the
Granite State.
</P>
<P>
   Some political pundits might suggest that New Hampshire has not
changed all that much in recent years, and they point to the fact
that, in 1996, the GOP's right-wing candidate, Patrick Buchanan,
won the state's Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   But what helped Buchanan was not his philosophy, but his message
about the status of the nation's workers, and their risk of losing
their jobs as companies moved out of the country. That hit home
with New Hampshire voters _ many of the same voters who supported
the Legislature's decision last week to make the national holiday
honoring King also a state holiday. The House passed the measure by
a comfortable 212 to 148.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Shaheen's expected signing of both a House and Senate
version of the legislation shows that both chambers want to claim
some credit for its passage. That's far different from only a few
years ago, when neither wanted to go near the bill.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt both Gore and Bradley, as well as the GOP candidates
Bush and Elizabeth Dole, will embrace the King holiday bill. But
Gore, while he may benefit from New Hampshire's changing political
climate, may have other obstacles to overcome. He may have a
problem that is as far away from New Hampshire as China _ with the
Republicans still pursuing the Democrats' fund-raising involving
Chinese interests.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP is also pursuing the recent disclosure of China's
stealing enough secrets during the Reagan, Bush, and Clinton
administrations to acquire a nuclear arsenal that rivals the United
States'.
</P>
<P>
   Since Gore is part of the Clinton administration, these issues
could hurt him as much, if not more, than the changing New
Hampshire political and social landscape could help. Gore's job, if
he is to deflect these controversies, is to find a way to have
voters accept him as one of their own during the primary.
</P>
<P>
   But even after New Hampshire's historic vote to embrace the King
holiday, making Gore blend into the state's political landscape may
be an even higher mountain to climb.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
