<HEADER>
A7372 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-AUSTRIA-BOS &LR;      05-31 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-AUSTRIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIA EASES PLIGHT OF THE EXILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA _ It is Friday night in Espresso Bihac, a cafe in a
cellar in a poor quarter of the Austrian capital, and 30
middle-aged guys, just finished with a hearty meal of boiled and
baked calves' heads, are belting out Bosnian folk tunes to the
accompaniment of accordion, guitar, and homemade white lightning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wind, wind, you should blow from the Neretva, so the fog will
be dispersed from over Mostar,'' they sing, in poignant allusion to
a beautiful river and city in a homeland lost. A portrait of
Bosnian President Alia Izetbegovic hangs on the wall. Photos of the
Bihac soccer squad, one of eight teams in the Bosnian League of
Austria, line the sides of the room.
</P>
<P>
   Much can be learned in this room, and in dozens of other small,
ethnically oriented cafes around the city, about realities of the
Balkan wars seldom appreciated by Americans: That Austria is
setting a new standard in humane treatment of refugees; that few of
the million-plus Bosnians still in exile will ever return to their
pre-war homes; that NATO nations had best study the Bosnian
experience if they expect to do better with the million new
refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The need to cope is pressing.
</P>
<P>
   Only about a third of the 95,000 Bosnian refugees who received
asylum in Austria have gone back since the Bosnian war ended in
late 1995. An estimated 60,000 have been integrated into Austrian
society. But the same cannot be said of other European countries.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, which received 200,000 Bosnians, has been pushing them
out steadily; only a quiet transfer of these Bosnians to the United
States has kept the Germans from forcing them back to the Balkans,
US sources say. Such a step would have put an ugly blot on the
humanitarian role in which the West is casting itself in the former
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   And the Kosovars are coming.
</P>
<P>
   In Espresso Bihac, named for the town from which most of the
patrons hail, the men's shirts bulge with muscle. Some came
straight from their jobs, still wearing the dark blue coveralls and
white T-shirts of construction workers. One breaks into a chant _
``NATO! NATO! NATO is a god!'' _ then segues into uproarious,
affectionate impersonations of Bosnia's neighbors in Albania and
Montenegro. No one speaks of the Serbs, the neighbors who drove
them from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Sead Kovacevic, the owner, who emigrated to Austria decades
before Yugoslavia disintegrated, sits at a back table, beaming. ``I
opened this club when the war broke out to keep people together,''
he says, well pleased with his success. But his children, and those
of many newcomers, are citizens of Austria. Many speak better
German than Serbo-Croatian. And does Kovacevic still think of going
back? ``Not really.''
</P>
<P>
   More-recent arrivals are hesitant to go that far. It smacks of
disloyalty. But they are being pushed in that direction. The reason
_ and the lesson of their experience for Western countries striving
to defeat ethnic cleansing in the Balkans _ is that the refugees
are making decisions based on their children's needs more than on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   Azra Merdzan, who fled Sarajevo with her daughter and son when
Serb forces began shelling the city in April 1992, was one of many
Bosnians who, trying to stay close to home in the hope the war
would be brief, initially took refuge in Croatia. That August, she
took ship for Austria because ``the kids had to go to school, and
there was no school for them in Croatia.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman from a well-to-do family with credentials as a social
worker and teacher, Merdzan labored days as a housekeeper, studied
German at night, and eventually was able to work as a professional
again. The roses she brought to dinner last week, she said happily,
were from an Albanian man she helped with his work permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bosnia is something like a love you cannot forget, but which
you have lost,'' said Merdzan, who is 46. ``I am satisfied with my
life. I had it so hard, and now I have a home in this country where
I keep alive the good memory and talk to my kids of the Bosnia I
used to know. But that Bosnia, and the life I had before the war,
can never be again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hussein Hasic, 38, had just invested in new machinery for his
woodworking company in Brcko when the fighting started, and wanted
to hang in for a while. His mother, he says, told him no, ``you
have to leave, you have to save the children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to go back, but my kids are 16 and 10 now, and
they are fully integrated,'' he said over Turkish coffees in
another cafe. ``The only memory my older daughter has is the dog
she had there. To the younger, Bosnia is only a word. For me, and
for my brother'' _ who recently relocated, under strong pressure,
from Germany to the United States _ ``this is all about our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Rohan, secretary general of the Austrian Foreign Ministry
and a longtime Balkans specialist, said ``there is not a prayer''
people like these will go back, nor do the Austrians want that.
``We are quite happy about the experience. . . . Their young people
have become Austrians.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the efforts of Jorg Haidar's Freedom Party to mount an
anti-immigrant platform, Austrians generally have treated the
Bosnians with great generosity.
</P>
<P>
   Hasic, his wife, and their daughters were taken in by an
Austrian family with whom they lived for their first three years in
the country. The family helped them get work permits, good medical
care, and the best schools for the children. They bought them
clothes, lent them money.
</P>
<P>
   ``A brother wouldn't do as much,'' Hasic said. ``I felt like I
was in my own house. I still have a key. We spend holidays
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Many refugees had a harder time, but such experiences are not
rare. Austria's reputation in the West was blackened by the
country's embrace of Nazi Germany, but it had a long history as a
tolerant, multiethnic society both before World War II, when the
policies of the Austro-Hungarian empire helped make Sarajevo a
multicultural wonderland, and after, when Hungarians, Poles,
Czechs, and Jews fleeing Soviet oppression all found support here.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary response to the Balkan crises is not limited
to helping refugees inside Austria. Neighbor in Need, a partnership
of the national broadcasting company, the Red Cross, and Caritas,
raised $100 million over three years for assistance to people
displaced by the Bosnian wars, with much of the money coming in
from schoolchildren, social clubs, and church groups. The initial
response to the Kosovo crisis has been even greater, with $40
million raised since Easter.
</P>
<P>
   It is a Globe Santa-like effort, with newspapers regularly
featuring photos of politicians, schoolchildren, and corporate
executives donating checks and sending off trucks loaded with food
and medicine. Per capita, the Austrians are giving far more than
Americans or Germans.
</P>
<P>
   However, says Bruno Kapfer, a legal counselor with Caritas of
Austria, the willingness to accept refugees from Kosovo is
substantially less than existed for the Bosnians, and integration
into Austrian society is not an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kosovar Albanians are protected until the end of December,
but if the situation in Kosovo changes they lose their right to
stay in Austria,'' Kapfer said. ``It is official.''
</P>
<P>
   The government says it will give refuge to up to 10,000 Kosovar
Albanians, but the initial quota of 5,000 has not been filled, even
though Austria would be the easier country to which they could be
relocated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the Germans and we feel that if there is solidarity in
the European Community, it should extend to burden-sharing,'' Rohan
said, ``but many countries did not take any'' of the Bosnia war
exiles. As a result, he said, Austria feels ``you can only start
burden-sharing if you limit your own intake, to force the others to
do their share.''
</P>
<P>
   As for allowing, even assisting, refugees to integrate into
Austrian society, he said this has not been ruled out. ``In Bosnia,
we knew from the beginning it would take many years'' before there
was a possibility of return. ``In Kosovo, we still cling to the
hope that it can be resolved soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 1512EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7374 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKPLACE-COMPUTER-BO     05-31 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COMPUTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREAT THE BOSS'S PC LIKE YOUR OWN _ AND GET CAUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The personal computer is an indispensable tool in the workplace.
But don't be fooled: It may be personal, but it's not private.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Thiemann thought it was. We now find out his resignation
in November as dean of Harvard Divinity School was prompted by
university techies' discovery of pornography on the Harvard-issued
PC in his Harvard-owned home.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight employees of the St. Louis-based Edward Jones &AMP; Co.
brokerage thought their PCs were private _ before they were
disciplined last month for sending e-mail that contained either
pornography or dirty jokes. Another 19 employees at Edward Jones _
ranked the 11th best company in America to work for earlier this
year by Fortune magazine _ were dismissed on April 29.
</P>
<P>
   The company, with 17,000 employees worldwide, has been inundated
with requests from other businesses for information on its
electronic usage policies and what types of programs were used to
uncover the offending employees.
</P>
<P>
   While politicians focus on protecting privacy rights on the
Internet _ ensuring, for example, that no one steals your credit
card number when you shop at amazon.com _ the real advance in
cyber-surveillance is in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are spying eyes everywhere, but by far the person most
likely to be spying on you is your boss,'' says Lewis Maltby,
director of the American Civil Liberties Union's workplace rights
office.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven percent of businesses surveyed by the American
Management Association said they review employee e-mail, up from 20
percent in the 1998 survey. What employees may find especially
discomfiting is this: The majority of e-mail ``screens'' are done
without any provocation by the worker, such as a complaint to
management. They are totally random.
</P>
<P>
   And bosses are perfectly free to check up on employees' on-line
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general rule with respect to the the computer that sits in
front of you at work is there are no rules,'' says L. Camille
Hebert, author of ``Employee Privacy Law'' and associate dean of
the Ohio State University College of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Maltby is blunter: ``Employers can do whatever they want. The
only statute that is even remotely applicable is the wiretapping
laws, and that only applies to the spoken word. So your boss might
have some trouble listening to your telephone calls at work, but an
employer can freely read your e-mail, when the same message would
been a violation if it was a telephone conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   And surveillance doesn't stop with e-mail. There are many
computer programs that will monitor which Internet sites are being
visited, and how long an employee stays there.
</P>
<P>
   For example, SurfWatch Software can either block access to sites
or simply monitor what sites are being used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are looking at this type of solution more and more
for three reasons,'' says Theresa Marcroft, director of marketing
for the California company.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is productivity. If I am spending half my day buying books
or planning a vacation, the boss is not getting the productivity he
would like, he would expect, or he is paying for. Second, there is
liability, with huge color monitors that show pictures of nudes,
white supremacists, or antiabortionists. That can create a hostile
workplace environment. And thirdly, companies look at this to
optimize their networks. If rich videos are being downloaded, the
network is not as fast for people trying to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about the worker who comes to work after having been to
the doctor's and been told she has breast cancer? Or the employee
who is coming to grips with being a survivor of incest? In both
cases, it is probable that they would do some research on the
Internet, and just as probable that they would not want anyone _
especially supervisors _ to know about it.
</P>
<P>
   Policies on computer, Internet, and e-mail usage vary widely
from company to company. Some prohibit any personal use, others are
quite liberal. In most cases, the company's written policies
indicate whether employees can be monitored. But the American
Management Association survey found than in about 15 percent of the
cases, employees were not informed that their computer, Internet,
or e-mail use could be monitored.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this day and age, I would say that an employee is foolish
or naive who allows information to be stored in his or her computer
that he or she does not want the employer to be aware of,'' says
Craig M. Cornish, a Colorado lawyer and cochairman of the privacy
committee of the American Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that 21.4 percent of companies review stored
computer files of employees, and as with e-mail, more than half of
those reviews were conducted randomly, rather than on preselected
employees.
</P>
<P>
   What an employer finds on one's PC can lead to considerable
public embarrassment. In the case of Thiemann, discovery of the
pornographic images on his Harvard-owned computer resulted in not
only the loss of his deanship, but also great personal and
professional discomfort for the Lutheran minister who is married
and the father of two girls.
</P>
<P>
   His case is unusual for several reasons: his high profile in the
community, his outspokenness on matters of morality, and the fact
that the computer in question was in a Harvard-owned house. Would
Thiemann's punishment have been any less severe if the offending
material were discovered on a bookshelf in his home instead of on
his disk drive?
</P>
<P>
   While not speaking specifically about the case, Thiemann's
lawyer, Charles Ogletree, believes there is a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about a common-sense approach to what a
reasonable expectation of privacy might be, it would be much
different if it was in a library, but common sense and technology
seem to clash. That is not to say the outcome in the present case
is justified or reasonable,'' said Ogletree, a professor at Harvard
Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Another complication in the Thiemann case is that he requested
more disk space for his computer and asked the computer department
to transfer some files to the new disk drive.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Harvard says it did nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The factual premise that Dean Thiemann's resignation was the
product of an intrustion on his privacy initiated by university
staff members is incorrect,'' said Harvard spokesman Joseph Wrinn.
``In both policy and practice Harvard is deeply respectful of the
privacy interests of its faculty and staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrinn would not comment further.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the technician performing the work saw
graphic images on the screen when they began working, or if files
were opened, something that would not ordinarily be necessary when
transferring them. If it was the former, that could have raised
harassment issues for the technician or technicians who did the
work. If it was the latter (regardless of one's views of
pornography), it raises the question of whether Thiemann's
expectation of privacy was violated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one thing to say `transfer these files' and quite
another to say `feel free to look at anything I've done for the
last 12 years,' '' says Ohio State's Hebert.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the issue, Harvard University's
computer-use policy prohibits obscene material.
</P>
<P>
   While court cases involving employee privacy in cyberspace have
been view and far between, Hebert does not hold out much hope for
relief there.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess,'' she says, ``is the way courts will ultimately go
is they will find employees have relatively little right to privacy
in employer-owned machines.''
</P>
<P>
   And don't look to Washington for relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress is sitting on their hands,'' says Maltby. ``Everyone
agrees that privacy laws are badly outdated and need to be updated,
even the business community agrees with that, but the current
Congress could not be less interested.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you accept the reality that a workplace PC does, in fact,
belong to the employer, it's hard to deny the logic that follows:
If a company owns the machine, it has a right to examine its own
property, including what information is being stored there and what
Web sites are being visited. Still, many employees have a hard time
believing that, day to day, what they do on their PCs is anyone's
business but their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is popular now for an employer to monitor and censor the
content of information that people can put in a computer because of
sexual harassment in the workplace,'' says Cornish. ``It is just a
New York minute from there to say, `We want to censor you with
respect to violent content.' Then, eventually, it becomes
political. It is classic `Big Brother.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
