<HEADER>
A7377 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MELANOMA-BOS &LR;      05-31 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MELANOMA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELANOMA: THE DARK SIDE OF THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the late 1960s, Robert Flynn, now 63, tried to talk his seven
brothers into using sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn and his 10 siblings spent much of their childhood
swimming, sunning, and playing on Revere Beach, just outside
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, they didn't listen to Robert. About eight years
ago, his brother Larry, now 60, found out he had melanoma, the most
fatal form of skin cancer. He contacted his other siblings and
found out that Frank, too, got the diagnosis. And Harry. And Gus.
Fortunately, all were caught in time and the brothers have lived to
tell the tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``My doctor thought we should have done ourselves a favor and
grown up in Alaska,'' said Robert Flynn, who has fair skin and blue
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn's doctor believes he didn't get the disease because of his
religious use of sunscreen. But 30 years ago, there was less of an
awareness by the general public that there was such a strong
connection between sunlight exposure and melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were young, mother just gave us 11 kids tomato
sandwiches and sent us to the beach. No protection,'' Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Half of all cancers diagnosed in the US this year will be skin
cancer, making it the most common cancer diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   The incidence of melanoma, the least common but most deadly form
of skin cancer, has doubled among Caucasians in the past 20 years,
probably due to a combination of factors including depletion of the
earth's ozone layer _ which filters out the sun's most damaging
ultraviolet wavelengths _ and greater time spent outdoors on
beaches, golf courses, hiking trails, and the like.
</P>
<P>
   While adults may suit up for the sun with a hat, sunglasses, and
long pants, children and teenagers usually have better things to do
than conjure up ways to avoid the sun.
</P>
<P>
   But studies indicate that intense, early exposure to sunlight
may trigger many cases of skin cancer. Indeed, just a few severe
sunburns during childhood may be all it takes to set the stage for
melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   Although whites get melanoma at far greater rates than blacks,
Asians, and Hispanics _ mainly because their skin has less
protective pigment _ no racial group is immune from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Last month a federal ``cancer report card'' noted that the
number of new cancer cases declined significantly for most cancers
between 1990 and 1996 _ except for non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and
melanoma. The incidence of melanoma rose almost three percent a
year during the six-year period.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 44,200 new cases of melanoma are expected to be
diagnosed in the US this year, a six percent increase over last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, melanoma is one of the most preventable _ and if detected
early _ curable of the deadly cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Because about 80 percent of a person's lifetime exposure to the
sun was accumulated before he or she turned 18, it's important to
put sunscreen on young children and drive home the point to
teenagers, said Kenneth Arndt, chief of dermatology at Beth Israel
Deaconess Hospital in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Adults who had even one severe sunburn during childhood increase
their risk of developing melanoma by 40 percent, said Margaret
Tucker, chief of the genetic epidemiology branch at the National
Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gary Peck, director of the Melanoma Center at the Washington
Hospital Center in Washington, D.C., said he had a patient with
melanoma who could only recall one blistering sunburn during her
childhood. It was on the top of her foot, near the toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the exact spot where she got her melanoma,'' said Peck,
who added that he recently diagnosed a 12-, 13-, and 15-year-old
with melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   So it's critical for people to check their skin for
unusual-looking moles or moles that have changed in shape or color
and to get an annual skin check by a primary care doctor or
dermatologist, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   New York dermatologist Dr. Patricia Wexler said that she sees
more cases of melanoma than she did 10 years ago and in
progressively younger patients. In the early 1980s, for example,
most of the melanoma cases she saw were in adults in their 50s to
70s. In the last four years, she has seen patients in their 20s to
40s.
</P>
<P>
   When a new patient comes in to see Wexler about facial wrinkles
or acne, she requires each one to go through a full-body skin
check.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to completely undress, including underwear. Even
though they frequently say `I've had a checkup or I have a doctor,'
'' said Wexler. ``If I take care of their skin, I have to know if
they have any skin cancers. That's the first order of priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Although melanoma is the most feared form of skin cancer, it is
the least common. Basal and squamous cell carcinomas are the most
frequent type _ they account for about 95 percent of all skin
cancers _ and they are easy to remove. Basal cell carcinoma is
rarely fatal, but if the squamous cell type is left untreated, it
can spread and be deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Flynn had two cases of basal-cell carcinoma, which occurs
most frequently on the face, ears, and arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``My doctor said that the only reason I got basal instead (of
melanoma) was because I started using sunscreen as soon as it came
out on the market,'' said Flynn, who added that he ``positively
loves the sun'' and still goes to the beach every day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(SIDEBAR) &QL; 
SKIN CHECKS NOT USUALLY PART OF PHYSICAL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Gross wished her husband's primary care doctor had been
a little more forceful about having him go to a dermatologist.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1996, the physician noticed a spot on her husband
Louis' left shoulder and simply told him, `you should get it looked
at,' Patricia recalls. Louis never did. Five months later, Patricia
noticed the mole and suggested that her husband see a
dermatologist.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising as it may seem, checking the skin for melanoma is not
a standard part of the routine physical exam, said Dr. Julie R.
Lange, assistant professor of surgery at Johns Hopkins Medical
Institutions. She and her collegues conducted a study, published in
February in the Journal of the American Medical Association, that
indicated that physicians were four times more likely than patients
to detect early melanomas. The melanomas doctors caught were also
substantially thinner than patient-detected tumors, meaning they
were found at an earlier stage.
</P>
<P>
   Lange recommends that everyone take the initative and ask their
primary care physician to look at their skin during regular
physical exams.
</P>
<P>
   However, fair-skinned, blue-eyed people of northern European
ancestry and those who have a lot of freckles and moles are most at
risk for melanoma and should talk to their doctor about whether
it's necessary for them to see a dermatologist for a yearly exam,
doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to keep in mind, however, that anyone, of any
race, can get melanoma, Lange said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't assume just because you are not Caucasian,'' Lange
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reggae musician Bob Marley died of melanoma at age 36.
</P>
<P>
   And those with a family history of melanoma are also at risk,
even if they do not spend a lot of time in the sun; researchers are
not completely sure why this is but they suspect some people have a
genetic predisposition to the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Once Larry Flynn found out he had a melanoma tumor, his doctor
asked him to call his 10 siblings. Three brothers have had melanoma
and only one sister has escaped skin cancer so far. Flynn's tumor,
which was a large mole, bigger than a pencil eraser, was removed in
1984 and he has had no recurrences.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn, 60, now makes regular visits to his dermatologist once or
twice a year. He never put a dab of sunscreen on before his wife
discovered the odd-looking mole on his chest. Now he slathers it on
every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even go to the store without something on,'' Flynn
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
