<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO ROYALTY, SOPHIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Do little girls still dream of marrying a prince? Or do
they know better now? In the PD (Post Diana) era, we must be
grateful that there are so few princes in circulation. Who would
wish the princess life on any girl?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, The Sun, a British tabloid owned by Rupert Murdoch,
published an 11-year-old photo of Sophie Rhys-Jones's bare breast
with the headline ``Sophie Topless.'' ``Sophie who?,'' you may ask,
because the June 19 royal wedding has failed to excite much
interest here.
</P>
<P>
   Even in England, the union of Prince Edward and the lovely
Sophie hasn't captured the public imagination the way other royal
marriages have. That was true until last week, at least, before the
unveiling of the soon-to-be-royal-by-marriage nipple.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to think that the widespread lack of interest
in their marriage is a legacy of the Diana debacle, that the press
and the public have learned the price celebrities pay for our
relentless curiosity about their private lives. But that doesn't
appear to be the case. We haven't learned a thing.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the problem: Baldish prince, remotely in line to the
throne, weds 35-year-old PR woman. Dullsville. Their union lacks
the glamour of the Charles and Diana wedding, the rumbustiousness
of the Andrew and Fergie nuptials. Until last week, the wedding
threatened to be exactly what the couple wishes, a private affair,
as private as royal affairs get, at least.
</P>
<P>
   But now the world has the bride's bare breast to contemplate,
and suddenly it all seems a little more interesting. A former
co-worker of Sophie's sold the snapshot, the fruit of holiday high
jinks to The Sun for a sum said to be in the neighborhood of
$400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Sophie. Marrying into that family, knowing that inevitably
she'll have to to endure _ variously _ scrutiny, vilification,
adoration, scorn from the media and the public. There is something
about commoners who dare consort with royals that brings out the
savage in some observers, kind of a who-does-she-think-she-is
response.
</P>
<P>
   In the April issue of W, the editors invited various fashion and
beauty luminaries to describe in detail what they would do to
``improve'' Camilla Parker Bowles. ``She needs a total makeover _
she's looking dowdy and frumpy,'' said one fashionista. A plastic
surgeon prescribed ``a complete rejuvenation.'' A designer advised
her to wear black leather by day, red by night. ``She could be a
Scarlet Woman,'' he sniffed. ``After all, she is anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a scurrilous article, and I lapped up every word, even as
I contemplated how awful it must be to have to endure such
uninvited critical attention. We've seen what it did to the
emotionally fragile Diana. But despite her physical resemblance to
the late princess, Sophie appears to be made of stronger stuff.
She's not an emotionally vulnerable, self-obsessed neurotic but a
successful career woman. She's what bridal magazines call a
``mature'' bride, and thus, perhaps, a disappointment to those who
long for another royal virgin sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Given the way it played out, the incident might have been a PR
stunt engineered to make Sophie seem more sympathetic and
appealingly human than she has to date. She is in the business,
after all. But the bride-to-be was reportedly ``distraught'' over
the photo. It must have been difficult for her to find that her
bare breast was winking at the world from the Sun's pages, but
perhaps she should try to put the situation in historical
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the word ``topless,'' applied to royal
marriage, had a more sinister meaning. Off with her top? Better
than off with her head.
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a Globe staff columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
