<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7386 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-GIRLS-BOS &LR;      05-31 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GIRLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIGHT GIRL, BIG CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE GIRLS' GUIDE TO HUNTING AND FISHING 
By Melissa Bank. 
Viking. 274 pp. $23.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody wants a kid sister like Jane Rosenal, at least in
theory: She's brainy and mouthy and hilariously funny, and she can
make cracks at the dinner table that will salvage a deadly family
reunion. She's loyal beyond measure, even when her brother, Henry,
is being a jerk, or when no one in the nuclear unit can talk about
her father's impending death. In the larger world, this fidelity
can get her into trouble _ keeping her tied to a lazy, Cruella
DeVil of a boss, say, or holding up the sinking vessel of her
alcoholic lover. But throughout most of the foibles of
young-white-girl Manhattan, Jane tends to rally with a survival
instinct that would make her father proud. If she can't always
navigate the straightest path to a decent job or boyfriend, she at
least possesses enough wry one-liners to get her from one jam to
the next.
</P>
<P>
   As the protagonist of Melissa Bank's debut story collection,
Jane also has a lot riding these days on just how captivating she
turns out to be. Surfing the latest wave of self-induced publishing
frenzy, ``The Girls' Guide to Hunting and Fishing'' is supposed to
be one of America's answers to Bridget Jones, the fictional British
gooflet who won her public's heart by losing her pantyhose and
obsessively measuring the circumference of her thighs. The book
industry on this side of the Atlantic has responded by searching
for every first-time, 30ish single woman writer between here and
Pasadena _ with the hope that a well-timed publishing trend may
constitute a Zeitgeist, or at least a barrelful of profits.
</P>
<P>
   So: Poor Jane, who is now in danger of being overexposed by
publicists and underestimated by disappointed critics. Separate
from all the hype, she actually belongs to the current school of
funny-sad fictional heroines whose narrative lives are accomplished
by laconic prose: Rebecca Stowe's ``Not the End of the World,'' or
Julie Hecht's ``Do the Windows Open?'' Bank's strength is dialogue,
and the consequent emergence of Jane as an authentic character is
largely handled with streamlined grace. After only two of the seven
linked stories (which follow Jane from age 14 to her mid-30s), you
realize she's taken on depth and color: You know who this
girl-woman is, or will become, solely through her inimitable voice.
</P>
<P>
   That's harder than it looks, since it's a matter of delivering
essence instead of window dressing. But this kind of fictional
structure also raises the bar on Jane's life: Because her story is
delivered mostly in the first person, we have no wider view of the
world or even much alternate opinion about Jane herself. What we're
offered instead is the obviously limited internal scaffolding of a
young, coming-of-age bio _ a girl nurtured in the sheltering
suburbs of Philadelphia, fed and watered annually on the Jersey
shore, then thrust into the lion's den of midtown Manhattan, where
murderers and mean boyfriends and bad temp jobs await.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these stories were published individually in
periodicals, and their cumulative effect is that of a photo collage
of Jane at different life stages: Poised at adolescence, looking to
Henry for the instruction book on how to live; struggling through
her mid-20s by leaning on an older man; facing the shifting sands
of loneliness and illness without the physician father who so loved
her. These moments are all captured with comic understatement,
self-pity and self-importance being traits Jane wouldn't recognize
if they mugged her. But it soon becomes clear that the experiences
of ``a blurry young woman,'' as her older lover calls her, stripped
of any overarching metaphor, are simply poignant, amusing, and
ordinary. They're not so much cliches as they are universally
predictable: Oh, there's the mentor father-figure, you think;
wonder how long before she outgrows the relationship and dumps him?
Oh look, there's Mr. Right! Hope she doesn't blow it!
</P>
<P>
   Though much of Jane's resonance as a character unfolds through
her comic reflection, Bank is clever to a fault: The over-the-top
one-liners, and there are more than a few, stick out like drugstore
jewelry on a little girl. But the real danger of this kind of
armor-humor is that, once it stops, the serious prose underneath
begs to be covered back up. Take the breakup with Archie, Jane's
elder by 28 years, who's drinking himself to death and, even stone
sober, wouldn't be right for her:
</P>
<P>
   ``As gently as I could, I told him what I'd figured out about
us. He nodded, and I went on, saying what I thought was wrong and
why. When I told him that we couldn't talk openly to each other, I
realized that I was now. It made me wonder if we really did have to
break up.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps unfairly, I have quoted what may be the worst passage in
the book. But the crimes committed in this sequence of emotion _
youthful sentimentality, delusion posing as insight _ are
indicative of the greater problem with ``The Girls' Guide to
Hunting and Fishing,'' one fairly common to first works of fiction.
The book feels autobiographical, which is to say that it suffers
from the limitations of a writer's insular emotional experience.
Whether these subplots actually mirror Bank's life is beside the
point; real life almost always prowls inside of fiction, but it
can't breathe without some kind of technical and aesthetic
transformation. Otherwise, what you have is memoir with the names
changed, and you can feel it in a dozen different ways. The story
is funny, but the wisdom is over-the-counter, and there's not
enough air in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Bank is a talented writer whose gifts promise wider
territory ahead; she has probably learned a great deal from the
writing of these stories. The title story, the last in the
collection, is a delightful sendup of the troglodyte prom-queen
dating guide ``The Rules,'' and it's charming enough to make you
forget all her creator's missteps in order to wish Jane well. By
now _ having endured the cruelties of youth in the cruelest of
cities _ she has a standard poodle named Jezebel and a cartoonist
boyfriend, and her favorite novel is ``Anna Karenina.'' Maybe her
days of bad choices are over.
</P>
<P>
   (Caldwell is chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
