<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7388 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TRUFFAUT-BOS &LR;      05-31 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TRUFFAUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECALLING A FILM PIONEER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TRUFFAUT 
A Biography 
By Antoine de Baecque and Serge Toubiana. Translated, from the
French, by Catherine Temerson. Knopf. 462 pp. Illustrated. $30. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This solid chapter-and-verse study of Francois Truffaut gives a
sense not only of completeness but also of closure. Antoine de
Baecque and Serge Toubiana are the editors of Cahiers du Cinema,
the periodical Truffaut used as a professional launching pad
between 1953 and 1958, when the preferred delivery system for film
comment was impassioned polemics rather than soundbites, or thumbs.
Truffaut _ bright, nervous, intense, and shrewdly opportunistic _
came sizzling into the limelight with a broadside against French
blue-chip films and an enthusiasm for American genre movies.
</P>
<P>
   He began writing screenplays almost as soon as he began writing
criticism. His days and nights as a critic ended in 1958, when he
got his father-in-law, film distributor Ignace Morgenstern, to back
his first film, ``The 400 Blows.'' It became a landmark that
launched not only Truffaut, but also his young contemporaries known
as the New Wave. Drawn from a troubled childhood shared with a pal,
Robert Lachenay, it also established Truffaut as among the most
personal of filmmakers. Like his idol, Jean Renoir, Truffaut kept
his films intimate and domestic in scale, lyrical and modest in
gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Truffaut even named his film company Les Films du Carosse, for
Renoir's ``The Golden Coach.'' The open-ended closing shot of ``The
400 Blows,'' with its freeze-frame of a delinquent boy staring
blankly at the ocean, caught the Zeitgeist of the culture of
alienated youth to come in the '60s and '70s. Many of Truffaut's
films were chapters in an ongoing psychic autobiography. With ``The
400 Blows,'' Truffaut created a cinematic alter ego, Antoine
Doinel, played by Jean-Pierre Leaud. In four subsequent films _
``Antoine and Colette,'' ``Stolen Kisses,'' ``Bed and Board,'' and
``Love on the Run'' _ Truffaut took Doinel from juvenile
delinquency to a career as a minor author, repeatedly snatching him
from the jaws of bourgeois respectability by endowing him with
unreliability. (Just as Truffaut was taken under the wing of critic
Andre Bazin, so he and his wife took in Leaud to live with them.)
</P>
<P>
   Truffaut documented his own life with a meticulousness that
verged on obsession, and the authors had access to his letters,
diaries, journals, papers, and notes for the autobiography he never
lived to write. They reinforce the image from ``The 400 Blows'' of
Truffaut as an unwanted (and out-of-wedlock) child who spent a
lifetime in a state of anxiety over his ability to attract and keep
the love of a woman. The message he got from his own mother was
that she'd just as soon not have him around. He had a number of
intimate women friends, but was close to few men. Predictably,
there was much sexual infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   The book makes a good case for the view that Truffaut's most
inconsequential film, ``The Man Who Loved Women,'' might have come
closest to the truth about him. About that skirt-chaser, Truffaut
himself wrote, ``It seems that Joey never got through to his
mother.'' Its lothario was anything but the cocky figure played by
Burt Reynolds in the disastrous Hollywood remake. Rather, he was
always in a sweat about women, desperate and nervous. Another
Truffaut flop, ``The Green Room,'' about a man fixated on the dead
in his life, was something Truffaut envisioned for years. But it
didn't actually happen, the authors point out, until Truffaut
himself went into mourning for the death of his relationship with
Catherine Deneuve, who dumped him when she learned he had been
unfaithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truffaut: A Biography'' doesn't so much unearth new aspects of
Truffaut's life as corroborate with a satisfying fullness of detail
what we knew. It quotes New Wave colleague Claude Chabrol as saying
unhesitatingly that Truffaut's great theme in his love and work was
the search for harmonious relationships. Certainly Truffaut's films
about actors _ ``Day for Night'' and ``The Last Metro'' _ represent
idyllic re-creations of the extended communal families the lonely
adolescent found first in the cine-clubs of postwar Paris, then,
once admitted to it, in the world of film itself.
</P>
<P>
   In a culturally divisive era, he was one of the few who bridged
French and American styles and concerns. A certain elan is common
to both cultures _ and to most of Truffaut's films. The gentleness
and affection that permeate so many of them inspired a
quintessential piece of casting by Steven Spielberg. When Spielberg
made ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind,'' a statement of
trusting, childlike belief in a benevolent higher intelligence, he
cast Truffaut as the wonder-struck scientist who embodied its
message. Long after his New Wave colleagues went off in their
different directions, Truffaut retained his ability to convey
sophisticated, subtle emotional worlds with childlike enthusiasm
and freshness of vision.
</P>
<P>
   But he also retained enough critical, and self-critical,
intelligence to realize the trap that mindset could be. What was
charming at 30 was less so at 40. Truffaut, who died at 52 of a
brain tumor, said he began feeling old in his 40s. His later films
seemed to reflect a decline in vitality and spontaneity. He never
got the chance to show us _ and himself _ whether youthful
impetuousity would be replaced by mature reflectiveness and
expansiveness. Whether, in short, he'd have become his own Renoir.
It's impossible to watch Truffaut play the scientist who tames the
primitive boy in his own film ``The Wild Child,'' and not wonder if
he wasn't fashioning an allegory of his own self-taming. He never
lived to grapple fully with the problem of making the transition
from youth to age. But his films, at their best, don't have to.
This bountiful portrait of them, and the man they sprung from, will
help keep both alive.
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Carr writes about movies for the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
