<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS LIQUID NITROGEN GOOD FOR THE LAWN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The groundskeeper (for the Red Sox spring training camp) in
Fort Myers said one reason the grass looks so good is that he
regularly fertilized it with liquid nitrogen. Would this do
anything more than freeze the grass?
</P>
<P>
   M.S. MIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This might be a good time for you to get out of the lab and
into the garden.
</P>
<P>
   The liquid nitrogen used for scientific, medical, and industrial
purposes to deep freeze things very quickly, is indeed cold enough
to freeze grass _ 320 degrees below zero, Fahrenheit!
</P>
<P>
   That's the stuff (nitrogen gas under pressure) with the mist on
top in that beaker at the science fair that you dip a rubber ball
in for a few seconds, take it out, drop it and watch it shatter
like a lightbulb.
</P>
<P>
   The groundskeeper was probably just using nitrogen fertilizer
mixed with water.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How does fertilizer effect the environment?
</P>
<P>
   J.B., Fitchburg, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. By definition, fertilizer helps plants grow and function
efficiently. But too much of a good thing can be a bad thing. Too
much fertilizer, and too much growth, can mean environmental
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   You may have seen the N-P-K formula on fertilizers. The N is for
nitrogen, which promotes growth by helping cells grow longer. The P
is for phosphorous, an important part of the process by which all
living things convert nutrients into usable energy. The K in the
fertilizer formula is for potassium (K stands for Kalium,
potassium's German name).
</P>
<P>
   Potassium balances the electrolytes in tissue so the right
amount of water stays in the plants cells. Think of each plant cell
like a water balloon. Too much water and it can burst. Too little
and it shrivels up. (Think of a wilting flower that hasn't been
watered.)
</P>
<P>
   The right amount of water in each cell helps it function
efficiently and maintain the right shape and strength to support
the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the environmental problem with N. If we use too much, the
plants can't absorb it all. When the extra nitrogen (from
fertilizer on our lawns or gardens, or from leaking septic systems)
washes into surface aquatic ecosystems, it fertilizes the plants
living there.
</P>
<P>
   That's called eutrophication, the process of enriching the
aquatic ecosystem more than it's used to. Plant growth increases.
Ever see a little pond choked with algae and plants so thick you
can't even swim in the water? That's eutrophication.
</P>
<P>
   But that's more than just bad news to swimmers or boaters, or
wildlife like birds or aquatic mammals. When those plants die,
microbes digest their tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Microbes need oxygen to help them break down their food just
like we do. They get their oxygen from the water.
</P>
<P>
   Too many dying plants feeding too many microbes using up too
much oxygen in the water, means too little oxygen left for the fish
and other organisms that need oxygen for their processes.
Eutrophication can cause massive fish kills.
</P>
<P>
   Fertilizer can have a more direct environmental effect.
Chemically, the N and the P and the K are almost always salts,
which means a positively-charged cation and a negatively charged
anion bonded together.
</P>
<P>
   Salt molecules pull water out of cells like a magnet. Too much
fertilizer on a plant that isn't well-watered causes that burning
you hear about. It's plant cells dying because the fertilizer salts
are pulling out their water.
</P>
<P>
   Organic fertilizers, like manure and compost, have less of an
environmental impact. They'll still burn plants, but the nitrogen
in them occurs in a form that plants can't use until microbes
convert it to a different form.
</P>
<P>
   That takes time. Excess nitrogen from organic fertilizers that
washes into aquatic ecosystems doesn't cause eutrophication as
quickly or dramatically as manufactured fertilizers that provide
nitrogen in forms that plants can use right away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
