</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7392 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-WEATHER-BOS &LR;      05-31 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WEATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WAYS OF MOTHER NATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIR APPARENT &QC; 
How Meteorologists Learned to Map, Predict, and Dramatize Weather &QL; 
By Mark Monmonier &QL; 
University of Chicago Press, 309 pp., illustrated, $27.50 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the threatening day of Jan. 2, something like a million
households were tuned in to the Weather Channel as a major
snowstorm was blanketing the Midwest and _ as virtually all storm
systems do _ heading east.
</P>
<P>
   Radar images looped across the cable channel's weather maps,
snowfall amounts were tracked and predicted, and controlling high-
and low-pressure cells were charted. On a stay-indoors Saturday, it
was endlessly fascinating as well as instructive.
</P>
<P>
   What those Weather Channel viewers receive, writes cartographer
Mark Monmonier, is ``graphic confirmation'' of the ``scientific
sophistication'' that goes into the making of a daily weather
forecast. He could just as easily say that they _ along with those
newspaper readers who turn first to the day's weather map _ are
getting scientific confirmation of the instinct to look out the
window at the state of nature.
</P>
<P>
   In previous books, Monmonier, a professor of geography at
Syracuse University, has explored such matters as the way maps are
used to track environmental dangers and how they can be used (and
very often misused) to influence political decisions about
environmental issues. Now, in ``Air Apparent,'' he turns his
attention to maps that can track the present and future immediate
environment, not to mention let us know whether to bring along an
umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   Monmonier is solid enough in his discussion of geographic and
meteorological information to satisfy the experienced weather
watcher. But even if this information were not presented in such a
lively and engaging manner, it would still hook any reader who
checks the weather map every morning or who sits happily entranced
through a full cycle of forecasts on the Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   In tracing the development of weather mapping, Monmonier turns
the controversy on the impact of weather fronts _ which, along with
symbols for cloud cover and precipitation, are the most prominent
features of today's newspaper weather maps _ into a fascinating bit
of scientific history.
</P>
<P>
   Well into the 1930s, Monmonier writes, US Weather Bureau
officials were ``smugly confident their successful forecasts were
not likely to get much better'' and ``stubbornly resisted the
promising theoretical and practical advances of a small group of
Norwegian meteorologists.''
</P>
<P>
   These scientists' research confirmed the importance of warm and
cold fronts as predictors of approaching changes in the weather. Of
course, ``people could feel their passage'' long before that
research was done. But ``meteorologists gave little thought to
mapping their locations.'' It took pressure from US airline
companies and the military, plus a research project at MIT (headed
by a student of the Norwegians), to get the Weather Bureau to
include fronts as standard features on its maps.
</P>
<P>
   Weather-map addicts will be interested in Monmonier's discussion
of the strengths and weaknesses of today's bright graphics and
innovative presentations. He credits USA Today's ``revolutionary
full-color weather package,'' dominated by a ``large, visually
distinctive map,'' for prompting many newspapers to ``buy color
presses and overhaul their weather packages,'' and impelling the
Associated Press to provide regional weather maps to its
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air Apparent'' is lavishly illustrated. The historical maps
have been redrawn by Monmonier, and in the case of the Portland
storm he aims to recapture ``the map's frantic clutter'' while
focusing on its ``most frightening feature: the huge area of low
pressure centered on southeastern Michigan.'' A 16-page section of
color plates traces the development of weather mapping from the
early 19th century to the present _ including a photograph of his
favorite local Syracuse television weathercaster interpreting a
futuristic ``3-D SkyTrack'' animation.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the threat of a blizzard or a hurricane, most of us
will be checking a weather map at some point today. And now there
is ``Air Apparent'' to explain how it got the way it is _ and what
it all means.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
