<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
!!! ``Notting Hill'' Think of this satisfying romantic comedy as a
Hollywoodization of ``Four Weddings and a Funeral.'' It's served up
by that film's producer, writer, and star, Hugh Grant, who
resuscitates his career by playing yet another struggling Brit who
falls for an American. What lifts it all into orbit is Julia
Roberts, drawing on her own experience to play an American screen
goddess with an irresistible mix of poise and vulnerability.
(PG-13) 
 
!! 1/2 ``Southie'' Nobody's going to accuse this home-grown Boston
gangster movie of being slick or formula-free. What keeps it
watchable is the urgency imparted by a totally committed cast
headed by Donnie Wahlberg, James Cummings, and John Shea, playing
characters who can't separate the supportive love from the
pervasive danger on their home turf, delivered with a gritty
realism that's a big help. (R) 
 
! 1/2 ``The Thirteenth Floor'' Snazzy visuals, but little else in
this alternative-worlds sci-fi murder mystery. The best thing in it
is a slightly sepia-toned simulated Los Angeles, circa 1937. Armin
Mueller-Stahl and Vincent D'Onofrio have their moments. Craig
Bierko and Gretchen Mol don't. (R)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! 1/2 ``Xiu Xiu: The Sent-Down Girl'' Chinese-born actress Joan
Chen makes an impressive directorial debut with this film about a
teenage girl betrayed by China's Cultural Revolution. Sent into
virtual exile in a remote grassland, she scarcely notices the
Tibetan herdsman who loves her. This understated but devastating
story is a deeply felt piece of guerrilla filmmaking, shot without
permission by Chen, whose crew worked the border between China and
Tibet and sent the film back for processing to San Francisco. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
