<HEADER>
A7396 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV06-NY     05-31 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COMEBACK WORD'S WILD RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 6)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The word  &UR; adventurer &LR;  has been through a half-millennium of
exciting times.
</P>
<P>
   Disrepute was its cradle. The Latin  &UR; advenir &LR;  meant ``come to,''
as in ``come to pass; arrive, happen,'' and a vestige lingers in
gambling lingo as ``betting on the come'' in the hope that what
will come next will enable the gambling  &UR; adventurer &LR;  to win.
 &UR; Adventure &LR;  meant ``coming by chance; the luck of the draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Applied to a person,  &UR; adventurer &LR;  meant ``gamester,'' what we
would now call ``gambler.'' Accordingly, an English ordinance in
1474 decreed that the royal household would bar the ``swearer,
brawler, backbyter'' and `` &UR; adventorer &LR; .'' Five centuries ago the
 &UR; adventorer &LR;  was a fit companion for the secretive  &UR; backbyter &LR; , the
calumniator who whispered his slanders, stabbing reputations in the
back.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling and war combined, as soldiers of fortune bet their
lives on their livelihood; a 1555 usage derided ``our
 &UR; adventurers &LR; , that serue withoute wages,'' supported only by their
plunder. Just seven years before that, Edward Hall in his Chronicle
provided the etymology: ``He gave them a Pennon of St. George and
bade them,  &UR; Adventure &LR;  (of whiche they were called
 &UR; Adventurers &LR; ).''
</P>
<P>
   Most soldiers of fortune were self-glorified brigands; to be
called an  &UR; adventurer &LR;  was to be insulted.
</P>
<P>
   Then the pejorative word had a run of good luck. John Milton, in
his 1667 ``Paradise Lost,'' wrote of ``the Heav'n-banished host''
of fallen angels awaiting the return of their satanic leader ``now
expecting/ Each hour their great  &UR; adventurer &LR;  from the search/ Of
foreign worlds.'' (Though devilish, Lucifer was ``great.'')
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a commercial company was founded in Antwerp and
chartered in England called the Merchant  &UR; Adventurers &LR; , in the
sense of ``enterprise,'' and led in the exploration and
colonization of North America. The hazard to be undertaken was no
longer a time-wasting game, but a dangerous journey, an exploration
for riches or a moral crusade. Jonathan Swift wrote in his ``Tale
of a Tub'' (1704) ``to encourage all aspiring  &UR; adventurers &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   But then it was applied to Prince Charles Edward Stuart in the
pretender's desperate insurrection of 1745; his sobriquet was ``the
Young  &UR; Adventurer &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Then  &UR; adventuring &LR;  became an -ism and lost even more respect. An
English review in 1843 lumped together ``Concubinage, Socialism and
 &UR; Adventurism &LR; ,'' scorning all three as evidence of social decline.
The OED defined it as ``the principles and practice of an
 &UR; adventurer &LR;  or  &UR; adventuress &LR; ; defiance of the ordinary canons of
social decorum.'' An  &UR; adventuress &LR; , especially, was not just a
pinko kept woman but was stigmatized as ``loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse,  &UR; adventurism &LR;  was taken up by politics to define the most
dangerous form of policy. Russian communists in the 1920s called it
 &UR; avantyruizm &LR;  and Lenin considered it so deviationist as to border
on revisionism.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Harold Nicolson, in his 1932 ``Public Faces,''
deplored the way the public ``had ousted the Churchill government
on a charge of  &UR; adventurism &LR; .'' In 1957, The Observer wrote, ``Of
the three official accusations against Marshal Zhukov, that of
` &UR; adventurism &LR; ' appears to be based on no evidence whatsoever.''
Under the communists, it was not merely the practice of a rash,
reckless, precipitate or impetuous policy; it was a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Today, an  &UR; adventurer &LR;  is no longer a person to be feared. The
word has reasserted the romantic, courageous quality that the poet
Keats, in ``Endymion,'' gave it: `` &UR; Adventuresome &LR; ,/ I send My
herald thought into a wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, to be  &UR; adventuresome &LR;  is to be ``bold, daring,'' taking
risks without a connotation of impetuosity or imprudence. Foolhardy
_ having the hardiness of a fool _ is no longer automatically
attached to today's  &UR; adventurers &LR; . The battered old word that
gambled on the come to make its comeback has at last arrived.
</P>
<P>
   HELLMOUTH
</P>
<P>
   ``New York, which gave us a generation of female political
superstars,'' wrote Gail Collins in The New York Times Magazine,
``has turned into the  &UR; hellmouth &LR;  of women in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   What's a  &UR; hellmouth &LR; ? In the back of my head was Tennyson's
``Charge of the Light Brigade'': ``Into the jaws of death,/ Into
the mouth of hell/ Rode the six hundred.'' The image of the
entrance to hell as the mouth of a horrifying sea monster is
familiar to infernologists; the Book of Job's crocodilelike
Leviathan has lips ``ringed round with fearsome fangs'' and ``from
his mouth flames leap like sparks of fire escaping.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudyard Kipling, in his 1891 ``Tomlinson,'' had the Devil taunt
his hero, ``Now ye wait at  &UR; Hell-Mouth &LR;  Gate,'' taking the word
Spenser used three centuries earlier in his ``Faerie Queene.'' On
the medieval stage in Metz, France, the mystery play employed
special effects of a mechanical monster with what was called its
 &UR; hellmouth &LR;  agape, sparks shooting out. Was this the derivation of
my colleague's unfamiliar usage?
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; Hellmouth &LR; , right now, comes most directly from `Buffy the
Vampire Slayer,''' Ms. Collins said, referring to the series
telecast Tuesday nights on the WB (Warner Bros.) network. ``It's
the place where all things evil sort of arrive on the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a bit of an etymological letdown, but it's good to see
writers for today's TV series drawing on medieval theatrical
traditions. In the community of Sunnydale, the fictional
``watcher'' of Buffy _ a high school student with a knack for
slaying the evil beings lurking at the local  &UR; hellmouth &LR;  _
explains, ``The Spanish who first settled the area called it Boca
Del Infierno _ roughly translated, ` &UR; Hellmouth &LR; ' _ a sort of portal
from this reality to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to its rebirth in the series, the archaic word (it had
all but abandoned hope) has returned to vogue in related contexts
of horror. In the Kokomo, Ind., Tribune, Todd Burlage warned:
``They appear as  &UR; hell mouths &LR;  in the road and can sneak up on a
driver about as subtly as a hurricane. They are potholes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
