<HEADER>
A7400 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-MAMET-BOS &LR;      05-31 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-MAMET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THING ABOUT `BOSTON MARRIAGE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The American Repertory Theatre is billing the new
David Mamet play, ``Boston Marriage,'' as a groundbreaking work for
the playwright because it is ``set at the turn of the century'' and
``features an all-female cast.'' But Mamet himself isn't talking.
And he doesn't want anyone to read the script before the play opens
at ART on Friday because it's changing daily during rehearsals. So
precisely what territory is being conquered here? What ground is
beingbroken? What is the thing about the thing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of Oscar Wilde and Samuel Beckett and mush them
together,'' Rebecca Pidgeon says.
</P>
<P>
   ``And throw in a little, a little, a little, a little what?''
adds Felicity Huffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well . . . a little Mamet,'' is the reply.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, that explains it.
</P>
<P>
   Wilde. Beckett. Mamet. The master of Victorian manners, the
granddaddy of postwar absurdity, and the maestro of contemporary
machismo. Those are three writers you'd never expect to inhabit the
same paragraph, much less the same room or the same stage. But as
Pidgeon and Huffman, joined by colleague Mary McCann, discuss the
play in an ART rehearsal studio, the sensibilities of all three
writers seem to influence the conversation _ that is to say, the
dialogue is polished and polite, with a hint of futility and a bit
of an edge.
</P>
<P>
   You see, the performers don't want to reveal too much about the
plot, which they say is full of Mamet's signature twists and turns.
``Oh, it gets very complicated, and we don't want to get into
actual plot details, do we?'' says Pidgeon. All three women are
longtime collaborators of the playwright (Pidgeon is his wife), and
they say they've never seen him _ or anyone else, for that matter _
write anything quite like this.
</P>
<P>
   This much we do know: Popularized by Henry James's 1886 novel,
``The Bostonians,'' the term ``Boston marriage'' is an antiquated
euphemism for two women sharing their lives in relationships that
were passionate and romantic, yet sexually ambivalent, at least to
the outside world. In Mamet's play, the partners (played by Pidgeon
and Huffman) are women of a certain class who live on the fringes
of genteel society; they don't have the income to keep crumpets on
the table and a roof over the parlor, so one of them finds a man
with an endowment who will become their ``protector.'' Meanwhile,
the other has fallen in love with someone else, raising questions
about the meaning of marriage and the sanctity of bonds.
</P>
<P>
   These women are forever dropping obscure literary and scientific
facts, but they're really quite ``clueless'' about the dirty,
down-to-earth details of life. The maid, played by McCann, serves
as a sort of Greek chorus, interrupting the high-minded chatter
with simple yet profound truths. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mamet's women &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so educated, but in a way, they're so vacant,'' says
Pidgeon. ``Dave said to me on the way home from work the other day,
`God, these women are just so dumb, aren't they?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Some would argue that the women in Mamet's other plays aren't
exactly brain-surgeon material, either _ if they appear at all. In
the theater, Mamet is best known for creating a testosterone-pumped
world where bruisers and losers compete viciously in man-eat-man
battles, whether they be the two-bit thugs of ``American Buffalo,''
the oily salesmen of ``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' or the smarmy
Hollywood types of ``Speed-the-Plow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have had strong'' _ a pause _ ``and diverse reactions
to the females of his other plays,'' says McCann. The character of
Carol in ``Oleanna'' received the strongest reaction of all; in the
play, a college student destroys a professor's career by charging
him with harassment, among other things. That play divided
audiences, mostly (but not exclusively) along gender lines. Anyone
predisposed to object to so-called ``political correctness'' saw
the student as a manipulative witch; others saw Mamet as the
manipulator, stacking the deck to make the woman seem like a
witless pawn in a grand scheme to emasculate the powers that be.
</P>
<P>
   Pidgeon played the role at ART and on Broadway; McCann replaced
her in the New York production. Often, audience members interrupted
the performance, yelling things like ``Kill her'' and ``Bitch.''
``It was like a Rorschach test,'' says McCann. ``Everyone's
reaction was very much from their own experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The women in ``Boston Marriage,'' of course, are wildly
different from the character in ``Oleanna.'' They're from a
different time, a different social class, different backgrounds and
education _ and, McCann says, ``they get to wear better clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   And speak a different language. The play is a drawing room
comedy in the style of Wilde; while Mamet is known for capturing
the precise rhythms of contemporary speech _ the fractured syntax,
the unfinished thoughts, the evasions and the profanity _ there's
none of that in ``Boston Marriage.'' ``The dialogue is very
Victorian/Edwardian,'' Pidgeon says. ``There is much more _ what's
the word? _ oh, oh, sort of floral. And it's a very feminine
piece.''
</P>
<P>
   There is only ``a wee bit of profanity'' in the piece, Huffman
says, noting that you can't enter a drawing room comedy spewing a
particular verb about a woman named Ruthie the way one character
did in ``American Buffalo.'' ``There are words that are
anachronistic for the time period,'' Huffman adds. ``It's nice
because it keeps shocking you, waking you up and making you look at
the play anew. Who is that guy who keeps shocking you out of it?
You won't believe I forgot his name. That guy who wrote political
plays?''
</P>
<P>
   Brecht?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Brecht. It's not like Brecht; it's not political. But
the effect is the same,'' she says. ``Just when you're lulled into
thinking, `Oh, what nice drawing room ladies,' he'll throw in a
word that you heard Thursday on the street. Not profanity, but
something jarring.''
</P>
<P>
   These drawing room ladies are waiting around for something big
to happen, like Beckett's tramps taking tea in the parlor.
``They're like Gwendolyn and Cecily in a Beckett play,'' says
Pidgeon, referring to Oscar Wilde's ``The Importance of Being
Earnest.'' ``There are elements of absurdity in it. They think
they're in such control, and that they're going to change their
lives, but no. They're out of their element. And then in walks the
maid who blurts out some profound truth and then off she toddles.
We tell her repeatedly to go away, to go away, to go away, but she
never goes away. She's always there to carry some message from the
gods, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Floral language, messages from the gods. ``American Buffalo''
it's not. But, as they say, things change. Mamet is defying his own
stereotypical image as a man's man these days. His latest screen
outing, an adaptation of Terence Rattigan's ``The Winslow Boy,'' is
a gentle exploration of an Edwardian family that risks everything
to clear the name of a teen-age boy accused of a minor crime. A
young suffragette, played by Pidgeon, is the quiet center of the
film, a serene soul with both a genteel demeanor and a steely
dedication to justice.
</P>
<P>
   While Mamet's stage plays have often seemed to be painted in
bold strokes of black and white, ``Winslow Boy'' is sensuously
muted in a soft wash of pastels. Granted, Mamet simply adapted the
play, but he directed the film with a sort of studied reverence for
such values as loyalty and propriety.
</P>
<P>
   Are ``Winslow Boy'' and ``Boston Marriage'' signs of an artistic
shift? Perhaps. It's certainly different: Mamet meets Beckett meets
Wilde. We haven't seen that one before. As for the ``all-female
cast,'' Pidgeon downplays the idea that one ought to call that a
groundbreaking change. ``I don't see it as soft or feminine,'' she
says. ``I see a real play about marriage that is profound and
poignant and beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a love story,'' adds Huffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not soft because of all the stuff they go through to
get to the other side,'' says McCann.
</P>
<P>
   And what is the thing about the marriage thing? What does it say
about marriage _ the Boston kind or the institutional kind? ``I
don't know, to tell you the truth'' says Huffman. ``I'm not trying
to be cagey . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Pidgeon finishes the thought. ``I do, but that would be giving
it away, wouldn't it?'' No surprise there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 1528EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7404 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-JAPAN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     05-31 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-JAPAN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NAGOYA, Japan: ... are unlimited.)  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neither the first batch of MFA shows nor the Nagoya museum's
architecture is worth much of a detour. MFA officials are quick to
insist that Nagoya is a museum about collections, not about a
building. Rather than signing on a Gehry, a Meier, or an I. M. Pei,
Nagoya looked to a big Japanese firm, Nikken Sekkei Ltd., with
Yoshinobu Sato the lead architect on the project. There's been
hairsplitting about whether the museum is part of the hotel complex
or adjacent to it, as if being part of it is somehow less
dignified, even though Japan has a tradition of credible museums in
department stores and corporate headquarters. The Nagoya building
is, in fact, seamless; the museum lobby is a continuation of the
hotel's. Before the recession, there was talk that the hotel would
be developed by Ritz-Carlton. Instead, the Grand Court Nagoya fell
to ANA, a Japanese-based worldwide chain, not exactly in the Ritz
league. (The headboards in the bedrooms are vinyl.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Decent but not dazzling &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The museum lobby feels corporate and chilly. There's no art in
the vast space; there are lots of zigzagging escalators and a glass
elevator that rises between two Ionic columns that replicate those
on the MFA's facade. The exterior of the 31-story skyscraper, the
city's third-tallest structure, is a severe grid of granite, glass,
and metal, the top floors in accordion angles, folded like a
Japanese screen. A resolutely stark contrast to the gaudy chaos of
the rest of downtown Nagoya, the complex is a decent if not a
dazzling building. It boasts something the MFA doesn't have, at
least not yet: underground parking.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the Nagoya museum's three floors is entirely
devoted to the ticket booth and gift shop, the latter a
disappointment. Why the Italian pottery? Why are virtually all the
books about French painting, with nary a one related to the ancient
art exhibition? Why not represent Boston by having work by living
Boston artists, including some from the MFA's affiliate school, for
sale? The shop, operated by Meitetsu Department Stores, is
disappointingly generic _ and in a country that has raised the
department store to a high art. (Japan's finest emporia easily
outclass Harrods or Neiman Marcus.)
</P>
<P>
   As for the inaugural exhibitions, Nagoya got a drab version of
what it asked for and an excellent version of what it didn't.
``Monet, Renoir, and the Impressionist Landscape'' is a lineup of
62 paintings that don't resonate together. They're a hodgepodge,
with some fine works and some duds, big names mixed with
nonentities, and what is possibly the worst Renoir ever, the vapid
_ even by Renoir standards _ ``Children on the Seashore, Guernsey''
(from circa 1883). Given the Japanese public's familiarity with
Impressionist painting, a focused show might have been more
effective than this one-of-everything approach, which, adding
insult to injury, came with wall texts geared toward kindergarten
level.
</P>
<P>
   The Impressionist show is up for five months. ``Art of the
Ancient Mediterranean World'' is up for five years, and its
installation is far more elaborate and inventive. The Japanese
design team is the star here, along with the objects themselves.
The show opens with a stunner _ a glorious gilded mummy mask in
splendid isolation, set against deep turquoise walls. Doorjambs
from the Egyptian tomb of Mehu are set into a doorway, to suggest
their original site. A colossal head of Ramses perches on a tall
pedestal, to give a sense of its height back when it still had a
body. Doll-size models of a brewery and a boat are charming. Dim
lighting makes the mummy coffins extra magical. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Greek enlightenment &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lights go up as you enter the Greek galleries: It's
enlightenment literal and figurative, the installation opening with
an elegant abstraction of a columned portico with a tiny, riveting
Cycladic female figurine hovering in the center. In a farther room
is a series of pedestals, each topped with a Greek marble figure
fragment. Your relationship with these sculptures is all the more
intimate because they're not under glass bonnets. Instead, the
architectonic sprawl of a series of ground-level platforms prevents
your getting too close. Still farther on is a circular,
pantheon-like room whose niches are filled with Roman statuary; in
its center is the marble figure of a woman clad in gloriously
liquid drapery that ripples down on the diagonal.
</P>
<P>
   The MFA's classical collections, long overdue for new galleries
back home, have never looked better than they do now in Japan.
Nagoya also sets a standard for its parent in a spiffy resource
room, a handsome, glass-walled space with Italian chairs and a
serpentine table full of computers where you can consult both
museums' Web sites. The current selection of books for browsing are
all on Boston. Alas, for the most part they're basic tourist
guides, a chamber of commerce selection.
</P>
<P>
   As for future shows bound for Nagoya, the bright spot is an
exhibition on Okakura Kakuzo, the influential Japanese-born curator
of Boston's Department of Chinese and Japanese Art early in this
century. Along with masterpieces Okakura acquired for the MFA,
there will be photographs and archival material about him. It is,
in other words, a show that will require curatorial skills.
``Karsh,'' another show on Nagoya's calendar, is less promising.
The 1996 MFA exhibition of Yousuf Karsh's stilted celebrity
portraits was a low point in the museum's recent programming. The
Nagoya show sounds like a replay. Between Okakura and Karsh comes
``Voice of Mother Earth,'' a selection of Native American art
focusing on Pueblo pottery. Japanese ceramics are, of course,
celebrated worldwide: Japanese reaction to another pottery
tradition will be interesting to track.
</P>
<P>
   Nagoya programming beyond next year hasn't been announced. Let's
hope, though, that the MFA administration encourages its curators
to use their imaginations, to come up with shows that duplicate
neither content nor context. In Japanese museums, artworks are
usually strictly divided according to medium and period, like
paired with like. Shows like the MFA's late, lamented
``Connections'' series, which paired contemporary and historic work
with results both startling and illuminating, might interest the
Japanese as an alternative approach. For the moment, the most
intriguing aspect of the Nagoya/Boston Museum of Fine Arts project
is that, with the luxury of 20 years to experiment with
exhibitions, it could actually succeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
