<HEADER>
A7405 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-TITANIC-BOS &LR;      05-31 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-TITANIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UNSINKABLE TITANIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ On a recent warm Sunday afternoon, an appreciative
audience at the Civic Opera House applauds a musical with no stars,
a trimmed-down set, and a story that everyone knows so well it
borders on a cultural cliche.
</P>
<P>
   So what are all these people doing on their feet for ``Titanic:
The Musical''?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're applauding the whole show,'' says Kevin Gray,
who plays Mr. Andrews, builder of the doomed British luxury liner,
just a few minutes after the final curtain. ``What makes this show
go is a team effort. Everyone pulling together. If the people who
built the ship were this selfless, it might still be floating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic: The Musical'' almost suffered the same fate as its
namesake. The $10 million Broadway show (it cost $2.5 million more
than the actual ship), was nearly sunk by the same sort of hubris
that accompanied the liner to the briny deep. But after an initial
pounding by the media and lackluster ticket sales, the musical was
re-rigged and _ powered by the strong winds of five Tony Awards,
the sensationally popular film, and the nearly daily promotion of
the Broadway run by Rosie O'Donnell _ it's now successfully
floating across America.
</P>
<P>
   Before she even left her berth in Southampton, RMS (Royal Mail
Service) Titanic symbolized the grace, wonder, and arrogance of the
modern age. Engineered to withstand all but the most unlikely
blows, the luxury liner represented the biggest, fastest, grandest,
prettiest, classiest, and, yes, safest ship afloat. While she
crossed the North Atlantic on her maiden voyage, the manufacturers
and owners floated on pure hubris. The record shows that an iceberg
sliced the side of the ship just before midnight on April 14, 1912,
off the coast of Nova Scotia, causing it to sink with 1,517 of the
2,228 passengers and crew going down with it. When the unthinkable
happened to the unsinkable, arrogance was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the sea disaster that took down a Guggenheim and an Astor,
along with all the third-class passengers who were locked below,
seems to sail on forever. From James Cameron's Oscar-winning
cinematic spectacle to the touring company of ``Titanic: The
Musical,'' the queen of the White Star Line has taken on mythic
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   When the musical, with music and lyrics by Maury Yeston and book
by Peter Stone, opened on Broadway on April 23, 1997, the icy
critics were prepared to put it in dry dock before it even left its
moorings at the Lunt-Fontanne Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Tipped off by rescheduled previews _ one had to be canceled just
a few weeks before opening, because the stage ship wouldn't sink _
the critics seemed prepared to hate it. The New York Times's Ben
Brantley opined, `` `Titanic' . . . doesn't sink. Unfortunately,
that is also probably the most exciting thing that can be said
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the original liner, which had such an auspicious
beginning and tragic end, the opposite has occurred with ``The
Musical.'' The producers have had the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   They cut back many of the special effects that burdened the
Broadway show. Gone are the smoking coal bins and the elaborate
lifeboat scenes, replaced by suggestive scrims. Leaner, cheaper,
faster. Apparently, the producers also learned a lesson about
hubris.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the actors in the touring company, Melissa Bell, who
plays Kate McGowan, an unwed Irish woman on her way to America, has
had the most interesting perspective. She's been with the show, in
one capacity or another, since that fateful Broadway opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, it was like the ship, we were just going too fast. I
started as part of the swing group,'' says Bell, referring to the
stand-by group of actors that reinforce the cast. ``I had to be
ready to play nine diferent parts. I started as a dancer. But now
there's no dancing. I was in the chorus. But now there is no
chorus.''
</P>
<P>
   Being backstage, Bell has seen the evolution of ``Titanic: The
Musical'' from disaster to hit. ``The reviews were scathing. How
did we go from the worst show in the world to winning five Tonys?
Sometimes there's more hubris on the other side of the
footlights.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell says changes occurred on a nightly basis. ``We lost all the
big technical effects along the way. And with each special effect
we lost, the focus got more and more on the characters and the
music and the story rather than the special effects. The movie had
all the special effects you need. Whole sections would be moved or
eliminated. But it all worked out for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should see my scrapbook,'' she says with her mouth smiling
but her eyes raised to the sky in memory of the disastrous opening.
``I've got all the clips.''
</P>
<P>
   Including the negative reviews?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she says. ``But it wasn't so much the reviews as the
gossip columns. They loved to write things about the Titanic
sinking and those things. They just liked playing with the words
and, I think, they wanted to see it fail. But it didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell smiles. The matinee audience was appreciative today, and
she appreciates that. ``It makes me happy to be part of this
cast,'' she says. ``They tried to sink us but they couldn't because
there are so many great songs and the story's so great. So we won.
We weathered the storm and succeeded.''
</P>
<P>
   The original ship's owners, says Gray, ``threw all their
statistics into the faces of the gods and look where it got them.
It's a story worth telling. It's a new angle on the old angle. It's
hard for us to imagine what it was like when an unsinkable ship
went down with Astor and Guggenheim. It would be as if a plane went
down with Michael Jordan and Wayne Gretzky. While people think it
was women and children first, more men from first class survived
than from second and third class combined.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray, sounding more like the attorney he plays, pleads his case.
``There were 16 compartments. Any two could be breached. In an
emergency, the first four could be breached. So the ship could have
stayed afloat if they hit the iceberg head-on . . . but it was the
near miss that killed them. Legally, they had enough lifeboats. The
law was 20 lifeboats per ship but that was based on the usual
12,000-ton ship. Titanic weighed 46,000 tons. It's funny but her
sister ship, Olympic, had a long and fruitful life. These people
really thought it couldn't sink.''
</P>
<P>
   Since they've already played other cities _ including Seattle
and Denver _ does Gray sense any difference in the way different
areas react to the play?
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain cities have a greater appreciation of class
stratification with old money, old families,'' he says. ``People
who understand that seem to have a fuller understanding of the
show's underpinnings. I think Boston is one of those cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray knows the city, having spent time with the Boston
Shakespeare Company back in the early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had rotating rep then. It was more fun than an actor should
be allowed to have,'' said Gray, looking matinee-idol handsome in
his backstage dressing room. He took a deep breath and returned to
the subject of the famous vessel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ship was the result of irrational exuberance,'' he says.
``These people really thought it couldn't sink. They could have had
more lifeboats but they used the space to upgrade the first-class
cabins. But the other element to consider is its grandness and
scale _ nearly operatic. The Captain was the highest-paid captain
of his time and came out of retirement to sail Titanic. The state
rooms went for $4,500. How could anything as majestic as this
sink?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a story about class and privilege,'' agrees Taina Elg,
who portrays Ida Strauss, wife of merchant Robert Strauss, who
founded Macy's in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I auditioned for this role three times before I got it,'' she
says, without a hint of animosity. ``They thought I was too old.
And it was a bit risky. They thought I might get hurt.'' She
smiles, implying that she's as tough as they come.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very well-schooled company,'' she adds. ``An
exceptional company. Some of the critics haven't been kind, but
we're doing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Elg even enjoys touring. She's looking forward to Boston for a
pair of reasons. She can visit with her friend, Harvard professor
and theologian Harvey Cox, and revisit the Colonial Theatre, where
she played in the touring companies of ``Gigi'' and ``Irma La
Douce.'' ``Also,'' she adds, ``my son, Raoul Bjorkenhein, is a
graduate of the Berklee School of Music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally understood what the original crew never
understood,'' summarizes Gray. ``It takes teamwork and cooperation,
not ego, to have a successful sailing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
