<HEADLINE>
RETIRED COUPLE SHOULD DIVERSIFY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  I am 69 and my wife is 67. We are both retired and living
comfortably on my pension and Social Security benefits, which
amount to $45,000 a year. Our home is free end clear and we have no
outstanding financial obligations. Our portfolio consists of
$750,000 _ $600,000 in mutual funds and $150,000 in cash. All of
the funds are with Fidelity: Blue Chip Growth, 13 percent; Capital
Appreciation, 10 percent; Contrafund, 2 percent; Contrafund II, 10
percent; Equity-Income, 7 percent; Equity-Income II, 4 percent;
Fidelity Fund, 24 percent; Growth and Income, 6 percent; Large Cap
Stock, 7 percent; Puritan, 13 percent; and Value, 4 percent. Do we
have too much of our total invested in mutual funds? Do we have
excess duplication of funds? R.F., LYNN, MASS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I see no big problem having 80 percent of your nest egg in
mutual funds, especially since at this point you don't require an
income stream. But I do think this is a pretty poorly balanced
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   With the Capital Appreciation and Value funds, you have 14
percent of the fund portfolio in mid-cap stocks, and the
fixed-income side of the Puritan holding gives you about a 5
percent position in cash and bonds. The remaining 81 percent of the
fund portfolio is entirely invested in large-cap stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   You could make things easier by consolidating some of the
holdings, but unless these savings are in tax-deferred accounts,
there likely would be unpleasant tax consequences of selling some
of your positions just for the sake of simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   There's a pretty good argument to be made for selling some of
your large-cap holdings for the sake of diversification. For one
thing, you're probably in a tax bracket that's high enough so that
you would profit by owning a fund such as Fidelity Spartan
Massachusetts Municipal Income, the yield of which is free of both
state and federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to analyze your tax situation to determine if
tax-free holdings would work for you. My guess is that the current
portfolio has been providing you with fairly little income in the
way of yield, but with some very substantial taxable income from
distributions. Moving to tax-free and fixed-income investments
should help.
</P>
<P>
   If you can make additional moves without tax penalties, you
should add some international stock exposure, such as through
Fidelity Overseas, and it would also be nice to have some exposure
to small-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   However, Fidelity Low-Priced Stock fund is now closed, its
Small-Cap Selector fund has built a poor record, and its Small Cap
Stock fund, although promising, is still too young to have built a
record. I think I'd wait a bit before making a decision on a
small-cap fund.
</P>
<P>
   But more important, I'd like to see a lot more fixed-income
holdings, such as Mortgage Securities or Spartan Government Income
or Investment-Grade Bond. If you put at least 30 percent of the
fund portfolio on the fixed-income side, it would provide you with
more buffer against a possible downturn in the market.
</P>
<P>
   While you can probably afford to take a long-term viewpoint, and
I agree that domestic large-cap stocks are a great long-term
investment, I also believe that a broadly diversified portfolio
will provide you with greater safety, and probably with substantial
growth as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
