<HEADLINE>
WHY `BUFFY THE VAMPIRE SLAYER' WAS THE BEST THING ON TV THIS
SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you think this is yet another lecture on how badly you've
been squandering your Tuesday nights watching the wrong show, then
skip this piece and move directly to Travel or some other innocuous
section.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not here to make you feel guilty about the way you've been
ignoring the season's best drama. Go right ahead and watch ``JAG''
or PBS or whatever else that is keeping ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' off your prime-time menu.
</P>
<P>
   In the just-concluded season of ambivalent law firms and Prozac
mob families, of sports nights and everybody's love for Raymond,
``Buffy'' stood alone, and not because the buffed one ultimately
would win in a drag-out street brawl with all comers. Emotion for
emotion, kick for kick, the drama on which the WB network continues
to coast was a sheer pleasure trip.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it time due reverence is paid?
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: No other series this season pulled off a similar
degree of cinematic difficulty with as much consistency, panache
and unpredictability. Not the outlandishness of ``Ally McBeal,''
not the violent domesticity of ``The Sopranos,'' not the
pitch-perfect yakkers populating ``Sports Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Horror, humor, action, romance and adolescent angst _ ``Buffy''
stuffed it all in a zippered sandwich bag. In fact, this year, the
series, created and meticulously produced by 35-year-old Joss
Whedon and starring Sarah Michelle Gellar as the teen-age demon
dethroner, not only improved upon its tricky blend of meshing one
element into the next but managed to get deeper.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for ``Buffy'' has always been how to combine
horror and seemingly normal high school life without making one
seem silly or fake. Each week, it delves into the murky mythology
of the American teen and actually emerges as a hipper mirror of the
teen psyche than those whiny neurotics of ``Dawson's Creek,'' who,
by the way, wouldn't last one day in Sunnydale.
</P>
<P>
   Both shows may wallow in self-aware, brand-name,
psychotherapy-rich banter that can be as annoying as it is
exhilarating. But ``Buffy'' doesn't expect its pop-cultural
references to be taken seriously. (No wonder a character can
appraise a student's outfit and snap, ``I see you've been enjoying
the softer side of Sears.'')
</P>
<P>
   Now I can go all TV symbolism on you here and say that Buffy is
television's outstanding emblem of anti-''Ally'' feminism:
confident, powerful, focused, a character who suggests that fantasy
television can tell stories about women that reality-based shows
like ``Dawson's'' can't.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, Whedon, who honed his tangy dialogue and idiosyncratic
characters writing movies (''Alien: Resurrection,'' ``Speed,''
``Toy Story,'' the 1991 ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' movie),
continues to pull a ``Titanic'' on us.
</P>
<P>
   Like the big boat used as a prop, Buffy's vampire slaying and
saving of the world is merely the background scenery of a journey
that's less about stamping out evil than it is about coping in an
image-crazed culture.
</P>
<P>
   That connection in mind, it's understandable why the WB yanked
last week's explosive season finale in which high school graduates
face annihilation from their commencement speaker, who has
transformed himself into a 60-foot demon. (Though it also seemed a
bit calculated; why, for instance, didn't they pull the first part
of the two-part finale, as well?)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, what Whedon has done is craft a pretty traditional story
of a girl in search of herself, her place among her peers, and the
guy she loves, and merely surrounded it with horrific consequences.
For instance, when Buffy finally loses her virginity to her vampire
boyfriend Angel (David Boreanaz) it would have been no big deal
were it not for a Gypsy curse that doomed him to lose his human
soul should he ever achieve true happiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dates are things normal girls have,'' Buffy complains during
one episode. ``You know what I think about? Ambush tactics and
beheading.''
</P>
<P>
   Whedon is old-fashioned when it comes to heart and story, and he
has made the series about disenfranchisement. Buffy is a social
outsider (OK, a stretch considering Gellar's homecoming-queen
beauty), and we can relate to the pain in her sense of otherness,
whether she's merely the school outcast, the slayer stuck in a job
she never wanted, or the girl yearning for the guy she can't have.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Buffy is like a harried contemporary working woman who needs to
get through the day without distractions, so that she can have some
energy left to devote to other things. Like homework, dating,
hanging out with friends. (This is a girl who spent her prom night
fighting furry demons and dancing with a guy 200 years her senior.)
</P>
<P>
   Gellar, who has acted since the age of 4 and won a daytime Emmy
as the bad-seed daughter to Susan Lucci's Erica Kane on ``All My
Children,'' plays the slayer with emotional resonance and cheerful
delight. The fight scenes, at least two per show, are shot like
mini-martial-arts movies, with flying fists and vicious leg kicks
and, at times, absurdly exaggerated leaps and flips.
</P>
<P>
   My theory behind ``Buffy's'' continued it's-good-but-not-great
reputation involves the reluctance of critics to see it as anything
more than a comic-book-style series that's simply shrewdly crafted.
It's intellectually safer to champion series like, say, ``The
Practice,'' what with its high-brow morality plays and real-world
plot twists.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the question of whether ``Buffy'' is too gender-
and generation-specific (older adults don't get it when Buffy
accuses her more cautious mentor Giles, played by Anthony Stewart
Head, of ``Scullying'' her hunches). Then there's its home on the
smaller, less-seen network.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, ``Buffy'' ends this season with a weekly audience of
5.3 million, a ranking of 124 out of the 168 programs that aired at
least one episode since September. (In comparison, ``ER'' attracted
a weekly average of 25 million.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the series _ which also stars Nicholas Brendon as the
meek but well-intentioned Xander, Alyson Hannigan as novice witch
Willow, Charisma Carpenter as the spoiled pain-in-the-rear
Cordelia, and Seth Green as the werewolf Oz _ has turned out to be
the WB's strongest show among women 18 to 34.
</P>
<P>
   Whedon, who was raised by ``an extremely hard-working woman,''
takes great delight in giving Buffy strength and such an
independent, underdog spirit, particularly since young women ``are
not overly represented in the cinema.''
</P>
<P>
   Since far too much coverage of hyped shows consists of first
raves and then critical backlash, perhaps we should take solace in
the fact that ``Buffy'' in season No. 3 has not gained the media
stature of an ``Ally McBeal'' or even ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd question whether too much attention would undermine that
underdog spirit of a series working harder to stay true to its
mission. The way I see it, there's something to be said about a
program having an inkling, but not knowing full well, that it's the
best thing on prime-time TV.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him: kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
