r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAILORS-THANKS-TEX     05-31 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAILORS-THANKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH SAILORS GRATEFUL FOR AID IN `THE YANGTZE INCIDENT'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HORACE CRAIG 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is for the officers and men of the U.S. hospital ship
Repose who served on the China station 50 years ago. It is a story
about surviving British sailors consumed with a desire to thank
someone _ anyone _ remotely responsible for saving their lives.
</P>
<P>
   It began with what has come to be known as ``the Yangtze
Incident,'' in which four British warships innocently got caught up
in the Chinese civil war. Forty-six British sailors were killed,
and 68 others were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The wounded credit a U.S. Navy presence for keeping them alive.
</P>
<P>
   The nightmare began when the frigate HMS Amethyst steamed up the
Yangtze River in April 1949 to relieve the British station ship at
Nanking, the Nationalist capital. Communist artillery on the north
bank of the river opened fire at close range, crippling the neutral
Amethyst and causing heavy human casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Going to the aid of the Amethyst were the destroyer HMS Consort,
the frigate HMS Black Swan and the cruiser HMS London. All came
under the same withering gunfire with added damage and casualties
before they were forced to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   The disabled Amethyst was trapped upriver for 100 days. The
other three ships returned to Shanghai, along with the Amethyst's
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The casualties were beyond the ability of shipboard medical
attention, and qualified civilian medical help wasn't available in
Communist-threatened Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. hospital ship Repose happened to be anchored at the
mouth of the Yangtze. Its medical facilities were offered to the
British. My ship, the USS LCI 989, a converted landing craft,
transported the wounded about 20 miles downriver to the Repose.
</P>
<P>
   While playing around on the Internet early this year, I noticed
a call for any items about the Yangtze Incident that might be used
in a special 50-year exhibit at the City Museum in Plymouth,
England. I had photographs of several of the wounded being hoisted
in wire baskets from the deck of my ship up the side of the Repose.
As a radioman, I also had copied much of the distress radio
traffic. I offered these.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks came immediately from John Dunstan, secretary of the
sponsoring Four Ships Association, who invited me to come to
Plymouth for the 50th anniversary memorial.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Loquita, and I (because I was the only former U.S.
sailor present) were unexpectedly called before the Lord Mayor of
Plymouth and 560 crewmen and relatives from the four ships. I was
presented with a framed, commemorative plate in appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, a queue of those who had been wounded formed at my
table to thank me ``for saving my life,'' or ``for giving me such
good care.''
</P>
<P>
   One wheelchair-bound ``boy sailor'' was hit in the chest with
shrapnel and had been paralyzed for 50 years; yet he had
established a successful business and said he has ``had a good
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Another man lost both legs. A former HMS London sailor seated at
my table had been hit by nine pieces of shrapnel. Another survivor
still carries shrapnel in his hip.
</P>
<P>
   Many wanted to know if I remembered a certain doctor or a
particular nurse aboard the Repose.
</P>
<P>
   A moving memorial service was conducted the next day in the
packed St. Nicholas Church at the historic Plymouth Dockyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shall not grow old as we who are left grow old.
</P>
<P>
   Age shall not weary them nor the years condemn.
</P>
<P>
   At the going down of the sun and in the morning
</P>
<P>
   We will remember them ...''
</P>
<P>
   My only part in the incident was on the periphery, a very minor
role. My ship was so small that it didn't rate a proper name, only
a number: 989. I was uncomfortable being the recipient of such
well-intentioned gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   But I accepted the thanks anyhow in the name of those who truly
deserve it, particularly those who served aboard the Repose.
</P>
<P>
   I will keep and cherish the memento presented to me, but I pass
on to those who warrant it the profound gratitude of some British
sailors who owe their lives to a humanitarian offering of care by
the U.S. Navy a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   (Horace Craig is a retired editorial writer and columnist for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. He is a Navy veteran of World War II
and after the war served with the Navy on the China station. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
