<HEADER>
A7413 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-JAPAN-BOS &LR;      05-31 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-JAPAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MUSEUM SHOWS OFF BOSTON'S COLLECTIONS, NAGOYA'S AMBITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAGOYA, Japan _ If Kyoto is the Boston of Japan, Nagoya is the
Detroit. Kyoto and Boston _ officially sister cities _ share a
historical charm that makes them a magnet for tourists. Nagoya,
bombed into oblivion during World War II, is now a city of mile
after mile of banal buildings, hundreds of bleak high-rises only
occasionally relieved by a low-lying traditional temple.
</P>
<P>
   In this drab context, the $200 million hotel-and-office complex
that houses the new Nagoya/Boston Museum of Fine Arts stands as a
beacon of architectural integrity. Not that it's a great building.
Far from it. But compared with the shoddy haphazardness of nearly
everything else in Japan's fourth-largest city, the shiny white
skyscraper at least looks planned.
</P>
<P>
   The museum itself is the outcome of eight years of planning by
Nagoya's city fathers and the administration of the MFA. Arduous
negotiations, begun when Japan was enjoying an economic boom and
concluded after recession had hit, resulted in a deal with Nagoya
giving $50 million to the Boston museum, and the MFA reciprocating
with 20 years of loan shows drawn from its copious collections.
It's a great arrangement for the Boston museum, which, in addition
to the money and the chance to see long-hidden works cleaned and
conserved for the journey to Japan, has reaped reams of publicity
for being the first Western museum with an Asian outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Is it as good a deal for Nagoya? No, I'd argue. The project is
trumpeted as the ``first encyclopedic museum in Japan,'' which is a
stretch. An encyclopedic museum exhibits art of all, or at least
most, major civilizations at the same time and under the same roof,
so visitors can compare and contrast cultures and centuries. It's
one-stop shopping. Because Nagoya's is a very small museum _ at
just over 10,000 square feet of exhibition space, it's about the
same size as the MFA's Gund Gallery, where major temporary shows
appear _ it will house just two shows at a time. One will be up for
five months; the other, for five years. Over the 20 years of the
contract, the offerings will add up to something approaching
``encyclopedic'' _ but so does the programming of other Japanese
museums, if you look at it over two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Nagoya have free choice among the MFA's collections.
The skeletal, nonspecialist staff of the new museum merely select
from among a list of shows suggested by the MFA. Originally, the
Japanese hadn't asked for encyclopedic programming at all, just for
their favorites: the traditional art of their own country and the
painting of 19th-century France. The MFA responded to the first
request with an aptly named ``Japanese Corner,'' a small space
where Boston will mount concise shows drawn from its immense stores
of Asian art. As for the second, one of the first exhibitions to
fill Nagoya's two larger spaces is a dutiful survey of French
painting, Barbizon to Henri Le Sidaner, one of several
lesser-knowns in the show likely to inspire a ``who?'' response in
both America and Japan. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mediterranean antiquities &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The other inaugural exhibition, ``Art of the Ancient
Mediterranean World,'' was the idea of former MFA director Alan
Shestack, who thought the Japanese could benefit from an overview
of the ancient art of Egypt, Greece, and Rome. At the time of his
suggestion, this particular art was little seen in Japan. But with
the 1997 opening of the spectacular Miho Museum outside Kyoto, that
changed. The Miho boasts such dazzling examples of antiquity that
MFA curators felt pressured to send some star objects of their own
just to compete.
</P>
<P>
   The Nagoya/Boston Museum of Fine Arts is part of a recent
expansionist trend in the museum world. When a museum's collections
or programs fill its own quarters to overflowing, it opens a branch
or two. New York's Whitney and Guggenheim museums and London's Tate
Gallery have all had such outlets for years. All, though, were
domestic. Then, in 1997, the Guggenheim upped the ante and went
international with its spectacularly successful Spanish branch, the
Guggenheim Bilbao.
</P>
<P>
   Bilbao's purpose was somewhat the same as Nagoya's. Both cities
are industrial, glamorless places, accustomed to playing second
fiddle to other metropolises in their countries: Barcelona and
Madrid in Bilbao's case, Tokyo and Kyoto in Nagoya's. Culture,
along with new airports and international conferences, was supposed
to spiff up their images. In the case of Bilbao, the strategy has
succeeded. In an era when a museum's architecture is often as much
of a draw as its collections, Frank Gehry's joyous titanium
pirouette at Bilbao became the most photographed and instantly
recognizable new building on earth. Most gratifyingly, it showed
off the Guggenheim collections rather than overwhelming them, as
people had feared. Bilbao drew 1.3 million visitors its first year,
about a third of them foreign. Along with Richard Meier's Getty
Museum, sitting atop a hill overlooking Los Angeles like an
American Acropolis, Bilbao became a point of pilgrimage. Anyone
serious about the international art scene had to pay a visit.
</P>
<P>
   No one could seriously say the same about the Nagoya museum,
which even its backers insist is intended mostly for the home
crowd. Nagoya officials' optimistic estimate of first-year
attendance is 600,000, with 80 percent of the total local. On the
assumption that the initial curiosity will wear off, the next
year's attendance projection plummets to 330,000. The fact that
half the Nagoya shows will be up for five years may discourage
return visits, as will the odd _ by American standards _ policy
that allows museum members only three free visits per short-term
show. (Visits to the long ones are unlimited.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
