</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOPLIN-ANNIVERSARY-1000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 100 YEARS, SCOTT JOPLIN'S RAGTIME MUSIC REMAINS A CULTURAL
TREASURE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanied by BC-JOPLIN-CD) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One hundred years ago, while Gustav Mahler pushed the symphonic
tradition to monumental heights and Claude Debussy invented musical
impressionism, an equally remarkable event took place in a dark,
upstairs ``gentlemen's club'' for African-American men in Sedalia,
Mo.
</P>
<P>
   There, a young African-American musician who made his living
playing the piano in barrooms, brothels and dance halls fused the
European tradition and the march forms of John Philip Sousa with
the thriving _ albeit degrading _ black minstrel tradition, the
leading popular idiom of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The result was ragtime music _ perhaps the best-known example of
which is the ``Maple Leaf Rag'' _ which went on to become one of
the landmarks of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   And the young musician? Scott Joplin. Between 1897 and 1899 _ no
one knows quite when _ he wrote the ``Maple Leaf Rag.'' In 1899,
the piece was published, becoming one of the most popular and
well-known works written in America. This week, through Sunday,
Sedalia celebrates the centennial of that publication with a week's
worth of concerts at the 16th annual Scott Joplin Festival.
</P>
<P>
   As Edward A. Berlin points out in his Joplin biography, ``King
of Ragtime: Scott Joplin and His Era,'' the origins of ``Maple Leaf
Rag'' are obscure. The club at which Joplin played the piano was
the Maple Leaf Club; whether he named the piece for the club or the
club was named for the piece is not certain.
</P>
<P>
   Why ``Maple Leaf''? Berlin concludes, simply, that the
inspiration was the plenitude of maple trees in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Joplin was born near Texarkana in 1868 _ no one has proved
conclusively whether on the Arkansas or the Texas side. He managed,
in an era of total oppression of African-Americans (slavery had
ended only three years before his birth), to get decent piano
lessons as a child, and also learned to play violin from his
musical father. Joplin's greatest musical influence in Texarkana
was the German-born teacher Julius Weiss, who recognized Joplin's
extraordinary talent and showed him the glories of European art
music.
</P>
<P>
   Though a career in classical music was unthinkable for an
African-American in those days, Joplin as a teen-ager became a
professional musician in the touring dance bands from which the
ideas of ragtime began to emerge. He made Sedalia his home base in
the 1890s, and continued studies in harmony at George R. Smith
College.
</P>
<P>
   And that's how one of the greatest convergences in American
music came about. From one direction came the lively, sassy music
of the barroom, brothel and minstrel show; from another, the
sturdy, reliable structures of Sousa's marches, which were
ubiquitous at that time; and from another, the clarity and
intellect of the Mozart and Mendelssohn that Joplin learned in his
piano lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of composers of the day wrote rags, but Scott Joplin's were
the best, exploiting the sonorities of the piano simply but
beautifully, setting the always surprising syncopated melodies
against a solid, always predictable ``oom-pah'' bass. And there's
something extra, there, too, in Joplin's music: an indefinable,
expressive quality, speaking of a great soul communicating through
music.
</P>
<P>
   A publisher in Sedalia, John Stark, took a liking to the ``Maple
Leaf Rag,'' and agreed to publish it in the fall of 1899. Within
the year, it became a national hit. For years afterward, it
remained a standard item on piano music stands in parlors across
the land, and, in arrangement, for pit orchestras at shows and for
hotel and dance-hall orchestras. For a piece of popular music, it
had remarkable staying power, holding the public imagination until
the 1920s. Joplin followed up with 37 other rags, including the
famous ``Entertainer,'' ``Easy Winners'' and ``Wall Street'' rags;
you could argue all day about which is the best, just as you could
argue about which of Chopin's etudes is the best. They're all
great.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite international recognition as ``the king of ragtime,''
Joplin's life declined into tragedy. His attempts to establish
himself as a producer of opera in St. Louis and New York failed; he
died in 1917, in advanced stages of syphilis. While satisfying the
public taste for ragtime, he wrote two operas, a piano concerto and
a ragtime ballet, and was working on a symphony at the time of his
death. All are lost except for the second opera, ``Treemonisha.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in Joplin and ragtime rekindled in the 1960s, but
musicologist Vera Lawrance had to hound seven publishers before
finding one who would take on republication of the music in 1971.
Musicologist-pianist Joshua Rifkin recorded a selection of the rags
_ now classified as ``classical music'' by the record companies _
for Nonesuch in 1970, producing a surprise hit. Marvin Hamlisch
wove several of the rags into the score for the hit movie ``The
Sting'' in 1973, and ``Treemonisha'' was produced in Houston and on
Broadway. A special posthumous Pulitzer Prize was awarded to Joplin
in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   But, if there was a Joplin ``craze'' for several years, it has
now given way to Joplin as a permanent symbol of American culture,
as entrenched in our national self-image as are Elvis Presley,
Grant Wood and ``The Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like Emily Dickinson in poetry,'' says composer-pianist
William Bolcom, one of the leaders of the Joplin revival. ``His
range is small, but many of the rags are perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Composer-conductor Gunther Schuller, who led the New England
Conservatory Ragtime Ensemble during the height of the Joplin
revival, says, ``I gave 1,700 performances of his music, and I
never got tired of it. I could go into a concert after a horrible
day, play four bars of Joplin, and be flying. This is great music,
and it will live forever.''  &QL; 
INFO BOX:
</P>
<P>
   The Scott Joplin Ragtime Festival opened in Sedalia, Mo., Monday
and continues through Sunday. Performers include the Ophelia
Ragtime Orchestra and pianists Max Morath, John Arpin, Scott Kirby,
Tony Carania and Bob Milne. For ticket information, call (660)
826-2271.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
