<HEADLINE>
SCOTT JOPLIN ON CD
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-JOPLIN-ANNIVERSARY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scott Joplin's music is well-represented on compact disc;
recordings range from solo harpsichord to brass quintet to a
combination of tuba, flute and piano. Some suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   PIANO: For generous selections of the complete rags in their
original versions for piano solo, there's a complete version by
pianist William Albright on the Music Makers label. Pianist Joshua
Rifkin's recordings of a large part of the rags are still available
on Nonesuch compact disc.
</P>
<P>
   ORCHESTRA: Gunther Schuller's authentic orchestrated versions
with the New England Conservatory Ragtime Ensemble are available
under the title ``The Red Back Book,'' named after the original
publication of these versions.
</P>
<P>
   PIANO AND ORCHESTRA: Try EMI/Angel's ``Digital Ragtime,''
featuring pianist Rifkin and the Southland Stingers instrumental
ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   PIANO AND VIOLIN: Composer William Bolcom has said that
sometimes the rags seem to have been written to be played by piano
and violin; violinist Itzhak Perlman and pianist Andre Previn do
just that on ``The Easy Winners and Other Ragtime Music of Scott
Joplin'' on EMI.
</P>
<P>
   OPERA: The flawed but immensely rewarding opera ``Treemonisha''
is available on Deutsche Grammophon, with Schuller conducting the
Houston Grand Opera.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wayne Lee Gay
</P>
</TEXT>
