<HEADLINE>
OF ATTACK RABBITS AND WHY SUSAN BECAME SIGOURNEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was Jimmy Carter really attacked by a rabbit when he was
president? _ A.D., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: April 20 was the 20th anniversary of President Carter's
encounter with a ``killer rabbit.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Carter was fishing in Plains, Ga., when a rabbit swam
toward his canoe making hissing noises and baring its teeth,
according to press reports.
</P>
<P>
   The president responded by either hitting the animal with his
paddle or by splashing water at it until it swam away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Secret Service having been caught flatfooted _ I'll grant
you an amphibious rabbit assault is a tough thing to defend against
_ the president did what he could to protect himself,'' Cecil Adams
wrote in 1995 in his column, Straight Dope.
</P>
<P>
   The incident did not become public until August 1979, when Press
Secretary Jody Powell let the rabbit out of the hat by telling AP
reporter Brooks Jackson about it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the meaning of Sigourney Weaver's first name? _ J.T.,
San Mateo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A: Susan Weaver was 14 when she decided to take the first name
Sigourney, inspired by the name of a minor character in ``The Great
Gatsby.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49-year-old actress comes from a family with an interest in
unusual names. Her parents, former NBC President Pat Weaver and
actress Elizabeth Inglis, named thier son Trajan and almost named
Susan Flavia.
</P>
<P>
   Fans can write to Sigourney Weaver in care of International
Creative Management, 8942 Wilshire Blvd., Beverly Hills, CA 90211.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the Elia Kazan movie ``A Face in the Crowd'' available on
videotape? I've looked for it on television, but it never seems to
air. _ F.S., Spencer, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Crowd,'' a 1957 film that stars Patricia Neal and Andy
Griffith, is available from several video retailers.
</P>
<P>
   One place to find it is the Internet movie retailer Reel.com,
which is selling new copies for $16.99 at www.reel.com. Or, call
its Berkeley, Calif., retail store at (888) 707-7335.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 1535EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
