<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S MUSEUM SCENE IS VIBRANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Japanese park art museums in department stores and
corporate headquarters, in Western-style buildings by Le Corbusier
or Japanese proponents of the Bauhaus, and in Asian ones with tile
roofs that curl up at the corners. Their tradition of
open-to-the-public art museums is roughly as old as ours, getting
seriously under way in the late 19th century. And, like ours, it
was greatly influenced by the dour, didactic model of London's
Victoria and Albert. You see that in Japan's national museums,
where, as in the V &AMP; A of yore, objects are categorized and lined
up in cases, without regard to dramatic display.
</P>
<P>
   The current talk in Japan's art world is all about the bubble
economy that burst, the recession that has resulted in art
galleries closing, in sales slipping (especially in the fragile
contemporary market), and in the likelihood that the national
museums, supported since the start by the government, will soon be
cut loose. During my recent visit to Japan, news came that the San
Francisco Museum of Modern Art had bought 10 contemporary paintings
by artists including Lichtenstein and Johns from the Fukuoka City
Bank _ for $60 million. A few years ago, the traffic was going in
the other direction.
</P>
<P>
   To put matters into perspective, though, if I hadn't already
known about Japan's recession, I never would have guessed. Japan is
hardly Third World, and compared with the museum and gallery scenes
I've observed recently in truly troubled countries _ Russia, Egypt,
and South Africa in particular _ Japan's seems positively
prosperous. Major museums in Cairo and St. Petersburg seem to be on
the brink of collapse. Roofs leak. Ceilings sag. The national
museums I saw in Tokyo and Kyoto looked in need of paint, and the
lighting is lousy, but you don't feel that the artworks are
actually endangered by their surroundings, as you do in Russia. The
Russians are, by the way, earning money in Japan at the moment,
through a show of paintings from the Hermitage at the Museum of
Western Art in Tokyo. It's one of several current shows in Japan on
loan from Western museums, including one from London's National
Gallery. The Japanese seem eager for a steady diet of Western art.
</P>
<P>
   Recession or no, they're still building museums, even museums of
vision and ambition. Foremost among them is the Miho, a $1.1
billion project outside Kyoto (see accompanying story). The Miho is
an art museum pure and simple. More common in Japan's private
sector is the museum that is part of a larger entity, often an
office building or department store. Westerners trained to think of
art museums as secular cathedrals tend to see this as
</P>
<P>
   sacrilege, but these corporate museums often have impressive
collections and mount their own temporary shows, complete with fat
catalogs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
An international entry &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new entry, and a new wrinkle, in Japan's corporate museum
world is the Mori Art Center. Scheduled to open in 2003 on the 52d
and 53d floors of a new tower in Tokyo's Roppongi district, the
center is the brainchild of Minoru Mori, Japan's largest real
estate developer. Programming in the space _ a European-style,
non-collecting kunsthalle _ will be international. Mori curator
Yukiko Harada is forging links with foreign museums, including
those at Harvard. On her US forays she's visited Cambridge to talk
with Harvard University Art Museums director James Cuno about shows
he might send to the new space. The Mori center will focus on all
of contemporary culture, not only ``fine'' art, but advertising,
animation, and fashion from all over the world. The team of
designers and architects working on the building complex is also
multinational, including Britain's Terence Conran and America's
Richard Gluckman.
</P>
<P>
   A man whose mission is nothing short of imposing some sort of
order on Tokyo's chaos, Mori is an admirer of the utopian planned
cities of Le Corbusier. A Mori proposal to replace single-family
sprawl with 40-story high-rises surrounded by green space echoes Le
Corbusier's 1925 ``Plan Voisin,'' which would have replaced central
Paris with dozens of identical office and residential blocks. To
Americans bred on individualism, this sounds horrible _ but much
more so in the case of Paris than Tokyo, an urban-planning
nightmare where almost any change would be for the better.
</P>
<P>
   Le Corbusier was also a painter, strongly influenced by Cubism
and Leger, and Mori is a major collector of his paintings,
sculpture, and works on paper. At the moment, they adorn a private
club in a Mori-owned building, where the privileged few can enjoy
them. Harada hopes that they'll one day be on loan to the Mori
Center, for everyone to see.
</P>
<P>
   Le Corbusier's only building in Japan, the National Museum of
Western Art, doesn't make me regret there aren't more. For someone
who was a painter, he designed a structure notably unsympathetic to
the display of art. The thick concrete pillars and low ceilings
painted black weigh down the paintings, a cache whose core was
bought between the two world wars by shipbuilding magnate Kojiro
Matsukata. Centered, predictably, on the big names of 19th-century
French painting, the Matsukata collection was held hostage by the
French government during World War II, then ultimately released to
its Japanese prison, designed by a French architect.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's fascination with Western art fascinates Westerners. The
country's passion for Impressionism is legend. Truth to tell, the
Japanese have sometimes bought by name rather than quality,
snapping up third-rate Renoirs just for the sake of the signature.
In Tokyo's Bridgestone Museum, built by the tire tycoons within
their corporate headquarters, is a room filled with the Japanese
version of Impressionism, which shares the same not-quite quality
of America's Monet wannabes.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's relationship with 20th-century Western art is more
complex. The country's first museum to focus on recent art is a
private one. Tokyo's 20-year-old Hara Museum of Contemporary Art is
housed in a converted 1938 Bauhaus-style building by Japanese
architect Jin Watanabe. Its sleek curves and walls of glass brick
make a suitable setting for the international art on view: You'd
never guess you're in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   At the Museum of Contemporary Art, Tokyo, you see Japanese
artists coming to grips with Abstract Expressionism and Pop, and
coming into their own with their own movements. The museum is the
result of the city recognizing a need _ and then filling it rather
questionably. The building, which opened in 1995, is the kind of
concrete bunker that suits huge installation pieces but is
incompatible with painting on anything but a heroic scale. It's so
far off the beaten track _ a $40 cab ride from the city center _
that it's little visited. The major show I saw there was
photography by Araki Nobuyoshi, whose gritty documentation of seamy
street life and quasi-pornographic pictures of trussed-up women
with their kimonos half off have earned him comparison to American
photographer Nan Goldin _ even though Araki was practicing the
style first.
</P>
<P>
   The West still expects Japanese artists to be exotic, and
somehow recognizably Japanese. Hence the popularity in Europe and
America of Yasumasa Morimura and Mariko Mori, two photo-based
artists whose work stars themselves. It's easy to pigeonhole them
as Japanese Cindy Shermans. On the other hand, in Tokyo's Nantenshi
Gallery, one of the city's best commercial venues for new art, I
chanced on a show of recent, and exquisite, sepia-toned prints of
eerily empty rooms by Ryoji Ikeda. Perhaps because there's nothing
particularly Japanese about their work, artists like Ikeda are all
but unknown outside Asia. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A national context &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Japan's high-speed bullet trains make day trips between major
cities simple. People in Nagoya can see anything in Toyko or Kyoto
and make it home for dinner. So the new Nagoya/Boston Museum of
Fine Arts has to be seen in a national context. Of course it also
exists in the smaller context of Nagoya itself. However drab that
city's image, there are other cultural attractions there. Ten
million people a year make the pilgrimage to Atsuta, the
second-biggest Shinto shrine in Japan, a complex that includes an
impressive museum housing 4,000 designated National Treasures _
swords, lacquerware, scrolls, and kimonos among them. The Tokugawa
Museum, established in 1935, survived the bombings in World War II,
was extensively renovated in 1987, and includes spectacular
displays of traditional arts. As opposed to the straightforward
lineups of objects in most Japanese museums, the Tokugawa mixes
media in vignettes that re-create tea houses, Noh stages, or rooms
in Nagoya's 17th-century castle. The presentation is world-class
and sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   There's a Nagoya City Art Museum, too, a decade-old example of
playful, postmodern, Lego-like architecture, filled with
20th-century collections that range from School of Paris paintings
to, rather improbably, works by the Mexican muralists, to major
pieces by contemporary masters including Anselm Kiefer and
Magdalena Abakanowicz. It turns out that the new Nagoya museum
isn't the only Boston art presence in town. Smack in the middle of
the City Art Museum's double-height lobby is one of the ``Hammering
Men'' of Jonathan Borofsky, a Boston native. He specializes in
giant, generic metal figures, which he's installed in countries the
world over. The blunt, unrelenting, mechanized gesture of the
Hammering Men suggests all the workers of the world rolled into
one. They're a global tribe, their presence in Japan symbolic of
that country's desire for full participation in the world of art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
