A7450 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$adv06-NYT     05-31 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$adv06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOSEPH SIANO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Canada for Children
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I wish to go to Newfoundland and Labrador this
summer with our son, who will be 18 months old. What child-friendly
activities are there? And do any hotels provide child care? _
Dorothy Bleiler, Englewood, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. Gillian Marx of the Newfoundland and Labrador Department of
Tourism, Culture and Recreation, who has two sons ages 1 and 3,
recommended several places.
</P>
<P>
   Bowring Park, Waterford Bridge Road and Cowan Avenue in St.
John's, has a swimming pool, a playground and a pond where you can
feed ducks and geese. Older children might enjoy climbing on the
statue of Peter Pan. Call (709) 576-6134.
</P>
<P>
   Salmonier Nature Park, a 40-minute drive west of the city, has a
boardwalk through a wilderness reserve and injured indigenous
animals that are being rehabilitated, like bald eagles, mink and
otter. Staff members provide programs for children. Open to Labor
Day. Free admission; call (709) 729-6974.
</P>
<P>
   The Fluvarium, on the shore of Long Pond in C.A. Pippy Park in
St. John's, provides a panoramic view of life in Nagles Hill Brook
through nine underwater windows. Call (709) 754-3474; admission
$2.72 (at $1.47 Canadian to the United States dollar), ages 4 to 14
$1.50.
</P>
<P>
   The Ocean Sciences Center of Memorial University, on Marine Lab
Drive, has a touch tank as well as harbor and harp seals. Telephone
(709) 737-3706; admission $3, students and seniors $2.40.
</P>
<P>
   If your son is up for nothing much more than a stroller ride,
Memorial University Botanical Garden, also in Pippy Park, contains
110 acres of cultivated and natural habitat, with an extensive rock
garden. Telephone (709) 737-8590; admission $1.40.
</P>
<P>
   As for accommodations with child care, Ms. Marx suggested the
Winterholme Heritage Inn, (709) 739-7979, in the center of St.
John's. There are efficiency units in this Queen Anne mansion, with
complimentary breakfast and baby-sitting for an extra charge.
Rates: $67 to $122 a night, plus tax.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Pacific Hotel Newfoundland, St. John's, (709)
726-4980, provides referrals to outside baby-sitting services.
Rates start at $88.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta St. John's, (709) 739-6404, also provides referrals
for child care. Doubles from $105.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the province, call (800) 563-6353.
</P>
<P>
   Dance in Spain
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be in northern Spain in August and would like to
attend fiestas with regional dancing in Navarre, Aragon and
Catalonia. What's on the calendar? _ S. P. Levine, River Forest,
Ill.
</P>
<P>
   A. The main event for folk dancing in the region during this
time is the Pyrenees Folk Festival, the first week in August in
Huesca in upper Aragon.
</P>
<P>
   In August, several towns have festivals dedicated to their
patron saints, with regional dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Aragon: This region is home to the jota, a bounding, leaping
dance done to fast rhythms. The Festival of San Lorenzo, in Huesca,
is Aug. 9 to 15.
</P>
<P>
   Catalonia: The sardana is usually danced in a circle in the main
square on Sundays. In Amer (12 miles west of Gerona), the Mayor's
Sardana, a ceremony that celebrates coexistence, is Aug. 16. Town
officials and citizens join hands in a long line, rather than the
usual circle.
</P>
<P>
   In Calella, on the Costa Dorada south of Barcelona (not the
Calella farther up the coast), there's a sardana contest each
Sunday in August.
</P>
<P>
   Sant Feliu de Guixols, on the Costa Brava, has its festival Aug.
1 to 4.
</P>
<P>
   Navarre: The jota is also danced here, but to a different tune.
The Feast of San Esteban at Vera de Bidasoa (near the French
border) is Aug. 3, and the feast of San Andres in Estella (about 25
miles southwest of Pamplona) is Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Tourist Office of Spain, 666 Fifth Ave., New York,
N.Y. 10103; (212) 265-8822.
</P>
<P>
   Dordogne Walks
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to go on a walking tour through the countryside
in the Dordogne, but I don't want to go during hunting season. Can
you tell me when that is? _ Kathleen Lobley, Indianapolis, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   A. The Dordogne, in southwest France, is known for peaceful,
rolling countryside filled with farms and vineyards, and hiking and
climbing are popular activities. The region's cuisine features
game: deer, boar, pheasant, partridge, quail and hare.
</P>
<P>
   They don't surrender voluntarily, though. According to the
French government Tourist Office in New York, (212) 838-7800, the
waterfowl season begins in mid-August. Starting around
mid-September, hunters pursue deer, rabbits and birds, and the
season runs to early January.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt to India
</P>
<P>
   Q. For a trip I'm planning later this year, I am interested in
cruise passage between Port Said, Egypt, and Bombay, India. What is
available? _ C.W. Layton, Baton Rouge, La.
</P>
<P>
   A. Cruise ships connect these two ports, but in the months you
mention _ November and December _ you'll have to combine parts of
two cruises (and pay full fare for both) or take segments of longer
voyages while paying the fare for the full trip.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Song of Flower, a Radisson Seven Seas Cruises
ship, leaves from Dubai on Nov. 9 and arrives in Bombay nine days
later after stops in Kuwait, Bahrain and Muscat. On the cruise
immediately preceding this one, the ship stops in Safaga, Egypt, on
Oct. 29, eventually continuing to Dubai. By booking early,
combining the two cruises and booking your own flights, you can pay
as little as $8,590 a person, double occupancy. You can contact
Radisson at (800) 285-1835.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can take part of a longer cruise. On Nov. 7, the Silver
Wind, a Silversea Cruises ship, departs Athens on a 16-day cruise
to Bombay. Along the way, it stops in Alexandria on Nov. 10, after
which it goes through the Suez Canal, followed by stops in
Sharm-el-Sheik, Aqaba, Djibouti and Bombay. But you must pay the
full Athens-Bombay fare, starting at $9,995 a person, double. Call
Silversea at (800) 774-9996.
</P>
<P>
   The Crystal Symphony, part of the Crystal Cruises fleet, leaves
Athens Nov. 3 and stops in Port Said on Nov. 7. From there, the
ports of call are Sharm-el-Sheik, Djibouti and Oman; it ends in
Bombay on Nov. 19. Again, you must pay the full Athens-Bombay fare,
starting at $4,825 a person, double. Call Crystal at (310)
785-9300.
</P>
<P>
   You may do better if you can be flexible about your travel
dates, or can go in the opposite direction _ Bombay to Port Said.
In any case, check with a travel agency specializing in cruises.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
