<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Debut for a Bridal Collection &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Because customers have been asking to order evening dresses in
white or ivory as bridal gowns, Barneys New York decided the time
was right to carry wedding dresses in its Madison Avenue store. The
idea was to have a designer who was exclusive to the store. Vera
Wang, whose bridal wear is carried in the Chicago and Beverly Hills
branches of Barneys, has her own store in New York, so she was not
a possibility. But Richard Tyler was. And so his first bridal
collection will make its debut in Barneys later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been toying with the idea of doing bridal for quite a
while,'' said Judy Collinson, an executive vice president. ``We
thought of Richard because he would be perfect. He manufactures in
the United States. His make is impeccable. And he's very good with
delivery, which is especially important for bridal.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler had a show of his bridal designs several months ago, and
Barneys secured the line exclusively for New York. It will be
housed in a room on the store's third floor with its own seamstress
and a veil maker.
</P>
<P>
   The dresses, in satin, silk tulle, taffeta, organza and lace,
range from unadorned columns to designs with beaded lace, quilting
or bustles. They include a sheath with three-dimensional roses, a
Cinderella-worthy strapless dress with a bouffant skirt of 12
layers of silk tulle, a halter with lace panels down the sides, and
a two-piece dress with a portrait collar. They are being made in
Tyler's Los Angeles workrooms.
</P>
<P>
   There is enough variety in the styling to appeal to brides of
different ages and degrees of sophistication, as long as they can
afford upward of $3,000 for a dress and can wait three months for
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Body by Starck
</P>
<P>
   Philippe Starck is at it again. After achieving fame for
designing hotels and lemon squeezers, he turned to fashion last
year with a one-piece dress-and-tights of nylon and spandex,
designed for Wolford and dubbed Starcknaked. More than 30,000 have
been sold. He has now come up with a version for summer called
Starcknaked Hot, which consists of a long strapless tube with
attached panties.
</P>
<P>
   Like the original dress, the new one can be worn in different
ways, at lengths from micro to maxi. It can also be pulled down to
the waist or hips to be worn as a skirt.
</P>
<P>
   The dress, in midnight blue, two shades of gray and a hot
orange, sells for $325; an accessory kit, consisting of a tube top,
long sleeves and a turtleneck, is $180. They are available at all
Wolford stores.
</P>
<P>
   But be warned: Because of the revealing fit of the stretch
fabric, only the daring are likely to dare.
</P>
<P>
   Paper Looks Back
</P>
<P>
   Paper magazine is celebrating its 15th anniversary this month
with a 24-page spread of fashion photographs from its archives, and
a monthlong retrospective to open on June 22 at the Holly Solomon
Gallery, 172 Mercer Street (Houston Street).
</P>
<P>
   As other unconventional publications have come and gone or
changed their formats (think of Details evolving from an indie
downtown fashion magazine into a mainstream men's-wear book now
owned by Conde Nast), Paper has continued to focus in an
idiosyncratic way on independent artists, designers and performers.
It has grown from a foldout black-and-white poster with a printing
of 6,000 to a 160-page bound, full-color glossy with 65,000
subscribers and a press run of 110,000.
</P>
<P>
   It began with $4,000 and a desire to produce something stylish
with content, said Kim Hastreiter, who founded the magazine with
David Hershkovits and continues to co-edit and publish it with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``David is the word person, and I'm the visual person,'' she
said. ``What Paper is about is finding creative people and pointing
to them. We promote independent culture and independent thought. A
lot of the people who work here are artists. We don't have
traditional journalists. We like people who are fanatical and
knowledgeable about different genres, and we teach them how to
write.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
