<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7454 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUTCH-FASHION-700&AMP;ADD     05-31 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUTCH-FASHION-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMIC TOUCH, BUT NO SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Haute couture, let's face it, is hardly anyone's idea
of a happening concern. Sure, one has the Miller sisters to hold up
as the inevitable example of new blood, and of course there is
Isabella Blow. Ms. Blow _ Izzy to her friends in London, where she
is a kind of muse _ is so crazy about couture that during the
semiannual showings in Paris she will change her outfit two or
three times a day.
</P>
<P>
   But apart from a few rich society figures and the ever-odd
English eccentric, everyone else is screaming ooh-la-la and running
to Gap.
</P>
<P>
   So why are all these fanatically cool people pouring into
Visionaire, the fashion publisher and art gallery in SoHo, to check
out the latest haute couture creations by a couple of Dutch
designers named Viktor Horsting and Rolf Snoeren?
</P>
<P>
   The two men are in a corner talking to Cecilia Dean, a
Visionaire editor who recently was named to the International
Best-Dressed List. And one can see why. Ms. Dean has on a white
pants suit by Viktor &AMP; Rolf, as their label is called. It looks
like any white pants suit, except that it is outlined with a wide
black ruffle, so that Ms. Dean seems to be popping perpetually out
of a dark space.
</P>
<P>
   When the designers showed their black-and-white collection of
stiff skirts and bouffant ruffs in Paris last January, they used
ultraviolet light to create the same effect. Everything white in
the room glowed, including the fashion editor's teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Now 3 of the 17 outfits from that collection are mounted in the
center of the Visionaire gallery. They're on Pucci mannequins that
are wearing ash-blond wigs that have been eccentrically combed out
by Danilo Dixon, a hairdresser, and about $1.2 million worth of
borrowed Vedura jewels.
</P>
<P>
   Standing near the door are Nicole Fischelis, the Saks Fifth
Avenue fashion director, and Lauren Ezersky, who has a fashion show
on cable television. Ms. Fischelis says: ``I wanted Viktor &AMP; Rolf
to do something for Saks. I think they're brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So all these things are not for sale?'' Ms. Ezersky
interjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because talent is so rare,'' Ms. Fischelis continues.
</P>
<P>
   One doesn't immediately learn the answer to Ms. Ezersky's
question, because more people keep trooping in. There is Diane Von
Furstenberg, the designer, and Christian Laboutin, the French
shoemaker, and Shalom Harlow, a model. Ronald van der Kemp, the
Dutch-born designer who's with Guy Laroche in Paris, is here, too.
So are Ruben Toledo, the illustrator, and his wife, Isabel Toledo,
a dressmaker. Someone has just introduced them to Horsting and
Snoeren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love your work,'' Toledo says to the Dutchmen, who have the
shellshocked look of a couple of people from Ohio who've just
stepped out of the Port Authority bus terminal at dawn. They trade
pleasantries, and Toledo nods and says, ``Yeah!''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Ezersky's question is intriguing. Even though Viktor &AMP;
Rolf represent what is optimistically called the ``new couture,''
and have shown their collections independently for three seasons in
Paris, though they will be on the official couture schedule next
month, not one client has bought a single outfit, which costs about
$12,000. That is a relatively small sum in the world of haute
couture, where a made-to-measure suit from Dior, without any
details to speak of, can run $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a client were determined to have a Viktor &AMP; Rolf
creation, she'd have to go to Amsterdam, where the designers are
based. Moreover, she'd have to be able to picture herself in the
clothes _ the very surreal collars rising up like Napoleon
pastries, the almost Victorian silhouettes.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, for their second collection, the one that put them
over with fashion editors and led to their New York invitation,
they created shirts that had literally been blown up with balloons
and confetti. The way the models' heads looked, small and bobbing
above these enormous inflated pigeon breast, it was almost the
reverse effect of seeing a pumped-up bodybuilder in a pair of tiny
briefs. It looked cartoonish.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, not many women can picture themselves in Victor
&AMP; Rolf's exaggerated silhouettes, and that's why the clothes
haven't sold. On the other hand, without commercial constraints,
the designers have been free to express themselves, and in a way,
their overblown shapes are a reaction to Dutch conventionality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashion doesn't hold a big value with Dutch people,'' says
Snoeren, who, like his partner, graduated in 1992 from the Arnhem
Institute for the Arts. ``It's all sportswear and second-hand
clothes.'' Horsting adds: ``In Holland, the mentality is you're not
supposed to want to stand out. We made our collections to be
noticed, but it was also a reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the comic brilliance of their second couture show,
Victor &AMP; Rolf have been embraced by the fashion world, especially
by those who look for connections between conceptual art and
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The July collection was really a break-through for us,'' said
Snoeren several days before the Visionaire party as he and
Horsting, both 29, had lunch at Balthazar. They were in town as
guests of Creative Time, an artists group, which had invited them,
along with avant-garde designers like Martin Margiela and Susan
Cianciolo, to be in a site-specific installation at the Brooklyn
Bridge Anchorage. For their exhibition, Horsting and Snoeren
planned to perch like birds in a large cage. ``It reflects the
fashion world,'' Horsting said. ``Who's watching who. Who's in,
who's out.''
</P>
<P>
   But to return to their breakthrough. Snoeren said: ``When things
are extreme, it's really easy to think it is a joke. Of course, for
us it was very serious. But people thought we were clowns.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest collection, their point proven, they moved to more
classic silhouettes. ``To show that we were making serious couture,
we did the first part of the January show in the dark and the
second in light,'' Snoeren said. ``It was like showing we had
conquered our demons and we're ready for reality.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Maybe. Although they seem committed to producing ready-to-wear
as soon as 2000, the only reality they've known is couture, which
even for established houses is a money-losing luxury. Horsting and
Snoeren said they have survived in the six years since finishing
school on a mix of government grants, museum sales and good will.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: In the last year they've been featured in dozens of
magazines, from Vogue to Composite in Tokyo. When Stephen Gan, the
Visionaire editor, decided to have a gallery in his new space on
Mercer Street, Viktor &AMP; Rolf were among the first designers he
thought of. ``They represent a new period of people craving fantasy
in fashion,'' Gan said.
</P>
<P>
   All this attention has been achieved without having a real
product. ``Fashion is not just about clothes,'' Horsting said. ``It
also deals with imagery and marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   His partner added, ``If the name is out there in the world, then
you can apply it to bags and T-shirts.''
</P>
<P>
   Horsting continued, ``You could say that for the last couple of
years our name was the only product we were working on.''
</P>
<P>
   This may sound disingenuous, yet look how successful a company
like Gucci has been using sex and celebrity to sell loafers. Even a
couple of Dutch novices can appreciate that. ``Did you see Julia
Roberts wearing our big blouse in Vanity Fair?'' Snoeren asked.
``She might be coming to the Visionaire party. That's what we were
told.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Anchorage event, with the pair in their bird cage (``The
first thing I can say is they're very brave,'' said Alex de Betak,
a fashion show producer for designers like Donna Karan), Susan
Cianciolo stood nearby and said that she actually enjoys the
commercial side of making clothes _ contrary to what people might
think of someone whose clothes have often been shown in art
galleries. ``I've a million ideas, and I'd like to offer things to
more people,'' she said. ``I just don't want to be me and my
studio.''
</P>
<P>
   van der Kemp of Guy Laroche had a different view. Maybe he was
jealous of Viktor &AMP; Rolf's freedom, he said at Visionaire, glancing
at a mannequin in a ruffled mantilla. ``Once you stop thinking this
way, you lose a lot of your identity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's an impossible situation. Nobody wants clothes.
They want Gap or Banana Republic, or they want something very
special.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
