<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7459 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FLEAS-ART-2TAKES-     05-31 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FLEAS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARTIFICIAL DOG BREEDS REAL FLEAS FOR RESEARCHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Kan., Colo.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREEVILLE, N.Y. _ ``Fleas,'' the textbook states, ``are highly
specialized parasitic insects belonging to the order
Siphonaptera.'' That order name tells it all: Fleas have a siphon,
a Draculian mouthpart that sucks the life blood from whatever
animal their genes have programmed them to latch onto. Or, failing
to find their predestined host, they will dine on any available
red-blooded creature.
</P>
<P>
   Fleas' habits would surely place them among the more repulsive
of living things. Upon landing on their victim, they proceed to
harass, extract blood, induce allergic reactions, introduce
infectious organisms and deposit their eggs on their unwelcoming
host.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny worm-like larvae emerging from the eggs feed
principally on the feces of their parents, who nourish the next
generation with partially digested blood.
</P>
<P>
   Disgusting, possibly, but not to Dr. Jay Georgi, an emeritus
professor at the Cornell University College of Veterinary Medicine,
the operator of one of the nation's few flea farms and the inventor
of a most improbable boon to scientific research: the artificial
dog.
</P>
<P>
   When his flea farm was going full-tilt, Georgi's freeze-dried
fleas were more than worth their weight in gold, fetching $40 a
gram ($1,200 an ounce), or 10 cents a piece live. Pharmaceutical
and pesticide companies bought them to develop flea-control
products and allergy shots.
</P>
<P>
   But the artificial dog _ in effect, a device in which fleas live
and reproduce _ has greatly reduced the farm's business. The
companies that made the farm one of the largest flea-suppliers in
the country bought his artificial dog instead, and bred their own
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgi does not mind. ``Most of the new products on the
market for controlling fleas were developed using my artificial
dog,'' he is proud to say.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, he keeps a ``small population'' of several hundred
thousand fleas alive and breeding for emergencies. ``You never know
when we'll get a call for fleas from some company or researcher,''
he remarked. ``We always have to be ready to fill an order.''
</P>
<P>
   A tinkerer by nature, Georgi invented the device that
revolutionized the flea-breeding business when the grant he had to
work on another costly parasite, the schistosome, was not renewed.
At the time, fleas for research were bred on live animals, mainly
cats and dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell's College of Veterinary Medicine, where Georgi worked
and authored a classical text on animal parasites, had six cats
that served as flea-breeders. And while the cats' flea production
was prodigious, the cats were not exactly thrilled and the
harvesting was tedious.
</P>
<P>
   Georgi thought he could come up with a device that would do
better. His artificial dog, modified and patented since his
retirement, is a transparent acrylic box, about 16 inches on a
side, with an electric heater to warm the fleas and the cow blood
they drink. Within the box are 25 cylindrical cages, each of which
can feed 300 reproducing fleas.
</P>
<P>
   The cages consist of an aluminum cylinder filled with blood and
covered with parafilm, an artificial skin through which the insects
feed. Their eggs and feces collect at the bottom in plastic dishes
filled with sand and ground-up dog food.
</P>
<P>
   Every other day, the adults are separated out by blowing on the
dishes, which sends them hoping about wildly. Then, using another
Georgi invention, the adults are sucked into a collector with a
modified vacuum cleaner. Eggs are then transferred to an incubator
where they hatch into larvae that dine on the blood-rich feces and
dog food, then pupate within silken cocoons surrounded by sand
grains where they metamorphose into adults _ wingless creatures
with strong spring-like legs that can propel them up to 7 feet
vertically or 13 feet horizontally, the equivalent of a person
jumping 250 feet up or 450 feet forward.
</P>
<P>
   Georgi figures that one artificial dog can do the work of 104
live ones. If need be, the parasitologist can raise 12,000 fleas in
a day with the artificial dog.
</P>
<P>
   But while he is proud of his invention, the fleas are what
really fascinate him. He marvels at their mouthparts, which are
horizontal, then squeezed vertically to make a perfect feeding
tube.
</P>
<P>
   Observing fleas through a microscope, Georgi produced a home
video of the fleas feeding and excreting and then mating, an act
entertaining enough to be in a flea circus. The male crawls beneath
the female and turns its tail end up to copulate.
</P>
<P>
   As with most other species, the males compete for females, and a
male in the mood will try its best to dislodge another male already
in a copulatory position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very fond of them,'' Georgi said. But, he admitted, ``No
matter how much you love them, you can get bored watching them.
They do the same things over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of warm weather means the height of flea season is
fast approaching. The creatures thrive at temperatures of 80 to 85
degrees, and humidity of at least 75 percent to 85 percent, said
Dr. Michael Dryden, a veterinary parasitologist at Kansas State
University in Manhattan. As a result, fleas are a year-round
problem in the Gulf Coast States, a summertime plague in the
Northeast and Midwest and a negligible presence in the Rocky
Mountain States.
</P>
<P>
   Adult fleas are about 1/16-inch- to 1/8-inch-long with dark
reddish-brown, wingless, hard-to-crush bodies and three pairs of
legs (the hind pair produce those incredible leaps). Their bodies
are flattened vertically or horizontally to allow easy movement
between the hair, fur or feathers of their hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide there are in fact about 1,350 different species of
fleas that specialize on various birds and mammals. Pet owners _
and those who bought homes previously occupied by a flea-infested
pet _ are most familiar with the cat flea, the flea that is usually
found on domestic dogs as well as cats.
</P>
<P>
   Adult fleas wisely select feeding sites where their hosts are
unable to scratch, typically the base of the tail and between the
shoulder blades. Given the opportunity, fleas could easily become
ubiquitous pests that inhabit every nook and cranny on earth. Under
ideal conditions, in just one month 10 female fleas can generate a
quarter of a million fleas in various life stages.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Pet owners struggling to get rid of fleas are often warned that
the parasite spends most of its life off the animal, and that
treating the animal's environment is as important as treating the
animal itself. However, thanks to a discovery in the late 1980s by
Dryden, it is now possible to control fleas without poisoning the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Dryden showed that once they sink into a blood supply, adult
fleas hang on to the animal for life. Even though the other stages
a flea's life cycle are spent off the animal, the new flea control
products, which include insect growth regulators and
skin-penetrating insecticides that are used only on the infested
animal, are able to interrupt the flea's life cycle by killing off
adult fleas when they seek their blood meal.
</P>
<P>
   Each fertile female lays about 15 to 20 eggs a day that lie
loosely on the animal's coat and drop off almost anywhere,
especially where the animal rests, sleeps or nests. Eggs can be
found in upholstered furniture, bedding, carpets and in crevices
and cracks on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   In two days to two weeks the eggs hatch into blind,
light-avoiding larvae, which molt twice within a week to several
months before spinning a cocoon. The adults form in the cocoon in
about five to 14 days. If conditions are right, they may emerge
right away, or they may remain in their silken womb for months
until they detect vibrations, pressure, warmth, noise or carbon
dioxide that indicate a blood meal is near.
</P>
<P>
   Adult fleas can live for a year without feeding, but will dig in
the moment a likely meal appears. That is why people are often
viciously attacked by hordes of blood-thirsty fleas when a family
returns home from a long vacation or someone moves into a house
that was empty for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Georgi said that one Cornell professor, upon returning from
vacation, would send his dog in first for a few hours to feed the
resident fleas before he entered the home. In warm climates, fleas
can live outdoors year-round. The so-called sand flea that people
encounter on vacation beaches is nothing more than a common flea
that is breeding outdoors in the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Fleas are more than annoyances. About 15 percent of dogs, cats
and people who are preyed upon by fleas develop an allergic
reaction _ a maddening itch at the site of the tiny red ``bite''
surrounded by a red halo or in some people a generalized allergic
dermatitis characterized by intense itching and swelling. A puppy
or kitten heavily infested with fleas can actually die of anemia.
</P>
<P>
   Before the new flea-control products arrived on the market
claiming to control flea allergy, the Heska Corp., a veterinary
biotechnology company in Fort Collins, Colo., was working on
allergy shots for flea-tortured pets.
</P>
<P>
   Using an adapted artificial dog, researchers collected spoonfuls
of flea saliva from the feeding membranes, identified the protein
allergens in the spit, cloned the genes that produce those proteins
and were preparing to test the effectiveness of desensitization
shots in cats and dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Grieve, the company's chief executive, said the project
was ``suspended, though not abandoned.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleas also spread disease, both to pets and people. Most common
in domestic animals and an occasional unfortunate human is the
tapeworm. Flea larvae, which have chewing mouthparts and
nondiscriminating appetites for anything organic, can feed on
egg-filled tapeworm segments that escape through the anus of an
infested animal.
</P>
<P>
   The eggs hatch into larvae in the adult flea. Then, when a dog
or cat swallows a flea in the process of grooming, the tapeworm
larvae are consumed and invade the animal's digestive tract.
Children too may get tapeworms after accidentally consuming parts
of tapeworm-carrying fleas.
</P>
<P>
   More serious ailments transmitted by fleas include bubonic
plague, a disease that is endemic in the American Southwest where
it is spread primarily by the oriental rat flea from rodent to
rodent and from rodent to humans, although 30 other flea species
can also transmit the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The oriental and northern rat fleas transmit murine typhus fever
among rodents and from rodents to people. Fleas are also carriers
of tularemia, a disease related to plague that originates in
cottontail rabbits in the east and jack rabbits in the west.
</P>
<P>
   For those interested in assessing the seriousness of an indoor
flea infestation, researchers offer this technique: Put on a pair
of light-colored trousers and tuck them into white socks. Then
enter the area in question for exactly one minute. If five or more
fleas have landed on the person's legs, the infestation is severe.
</P>
<P>
   Flea experts at Colorado State University say that chemical and
ultrasonic flea collars are ineffective at controlling fleas. But
the newer products, which include insect growth regulators and
insecticides that disperse in the animal's skin or get into the
blood, work far better than flea powders, shampoos and sprays in
keeping pets free of fleas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
