<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-GREECE-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURBULENT TIMES FOR TOURISM IN GREECE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 6) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With tourism throughout the Balkans suffering as a result of the
air war against Yugoslavia, it was perhaps inevitable that Greece
would be among the victims. But travel agents and tour operators
say that a bad regional situation has been made considerably worse
by a spate of terrorist attacks in and around Athens. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks the residence of the Dutch ambassador was
damaged by a bomb, and a rocket was fired at the German
ambassador's residence. Three western banks in the port of Piraeus,
just outside the capital, were also hit by rockets. A Greek woman
was killed by a bomb at the Athens Intercontinental Hotel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been left speechless,'' Dimitris Andoniou, president
of the Union of Greek Travel Agencies, said after the April 29
hotel bombing. ``First the war and now this. It will be many years
before we see American tourists.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the attacks have been attributed to a far-left group
bitterly opposed to the NATO operation in Serbia, which it
described in one statement as the work of ``euro-Atlantic assassins
and their chief, Clinton.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The State Department issued an announcement on April 29 ``urging
American citizens traveling to or residing in Greece to exercise
appropriate security precautions and avoid demonstrations.'' In
response, the Greek government's principal spokesman, Dimitris
Reppas, said: ``We do not think this initiative by the United
States is correct.'' He said it ``could create many problems,
especially for tourism in our country.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is big business in Greece. Last year about 12.5 million
foreigners came to Greece for holidays, a 10 percent increase over
the previous year, and spent nearly $7 billion. But growing numbers
of tourists are avoiding the country. Some Europeans are switching
to destinations in Spain or Portugal. British charter operators
have cut the prices of flights to Greece in an attempt to woo
customers back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Americans are also having second thoughts. ``We have
cancellations,'' said Michalis Ghiolman, an Athens travel agent who
specializes in arranging tours for visiting Americans. ``Even
Greek-Americans are afraid to come.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Northern Greece, which borders on Albania and Macedonia, has
been especially hard hit. Proximity to the war zone is one concern,
but environmentalists have also warned that the bombing of
pharmaceutical plants, oil refineries and fertilizer depots in
Serbia could release poisonous dioxins into the air. Some residents
of northern Greece have begun stockpiling food and water. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to published reports, half a million tourists have
canceled trips to northern Greece in recent weeks. The area is
especially popular with budget-minded travelers from Poland, the
Czech Republic and Hungary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cruise lines, which normally do a brisk business cruising the
Greek islands in the Aegean, are also hurting. Orient Lines, which
is based in Florida, recently sent letters to American travel
journalists inviting them to join a cruise from Athens to Istanbul
``to see for yourself that cruising the Greek isles is still a safe
and viable vacation option for summer/fall 1999.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The handful of terrorist attacks in Greece is having an effect
similar to that produced by a spate of attacks in neighboring
Turkey earlier this year. Visitors to both countries report feeling
quite safe, although some who have gone to Greece recently say they
have experienced disturbing instances of anti-Americanism.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opinion surveys show that Greeks are overwhelmingly opposed to
the NATO operation in Yugoslavia, and anti-NATO emotions are
running high. Many Greeks sympathize with the Serbs, with whom they
share the Orthodox Christian faith, and blame the United States for
conceiving and directing the bombing campaign aimed at Serbia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some recent protests in Athens have ended with the burning of
American flags. Major newspapers portray NATO as the perpetrator of
atrocities while giving little coverage to the campaign of ethnic
cleansing that Serbs are waging in Kosovo. A group of mayors on
Crete issued a statement saying that the 450 American military
personnel stationed there were no longer welcome and that their
safety could not be guaranteed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Burns, the American ambassador to Greece, urged
citizens of both countries ``to keep our disagreements rational, to
keep our disagreements proportional and to avoid demonizing each
other.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One travel agent in New York who arranges tours to both Greece
and Turkey, Suzanne Hall of IST Cultural Tours, said her Greek
business is slumping, though not as badly as her Turkish business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just had two new requests for tours to Greece, so maybe
things are starting to pick up,'' Ms. Hall said. ``But in general,
business is definitely off. The big problem isn't the hotel
bombing, which didn't get much coverage in the American press.
Kosovo is what they're afraid of. People are worried, and the
region as a whole is suffering.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
