<HEADER>
A7466 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-TRIANA-ART-2TAKES     05-31 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TRIANA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIANA SOUNDS NEAT, BUT IS IT SCIENCE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass., Wis.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As spacecraft go, it is small, inexpensive and normally would
hardly stand out among the dozens of satellites and probes NASA is
planning to send into space. But Triana, because of its unusual
origin and mission, has attracted a lot of attention. And it is in
trouble because of it.
</P>
<P>
   The goals of this simple satellite, designed to view the Earth
from afar, have become complicated by the reality of Washington
politics. The debate over whether the mission is a good idea or not
is muddled by the awareness of whose idea it was in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   Triana, in its earliest incarnation, is the brainchild of Vice
President Al Gore. In a speech on March 13, 1998, at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Gore challenged NASA to
build and fly an inexpensive spacecraft that would make continuous,
live pictures of the full, sunlit Earth from far out in space that
would be available to the world at all times via the Internet and
television.
</P>
<P>
   Weather and scientific satellites view the Earth all the time,
but they orbit so close that they only see a portion of the planet
at a time. Any ``whole Earth'' view has to be stitched together
from several images and none of these displays can be done in real
time.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that seeing the entire Earth against the blackness of
space at any time, which is not now possible, would inspire
environmental consciousness and encourage new educational and
scientific efforts. As the nation's classrooms and homes are
connected to the Internet and cable television, he said, the images
could arouse new feelings among millions of Americans about their
home planet.
</P>
<P>
   As White House aides tell it, Gore's idea came to him almost in
a dream. He awoke at 3 a.m. one day in February 1998, and thought
about a global view of Earth, they say, perhaps inspired by the
famous ``Blue Marble'' photograph of the planet taken in December
1972 by the returning crew of Apollo 17, the last moon mission. A
copy of the picture hangs in Gore's office.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also gave the Earth-watching project its name, after
Rodrigo de Triana, the lookout aboard Christopher Columbus' ship
who first saw the New World in 1492.
</P>
<P>
   After Gore told the NASA administrator, Daniel S. Goldin, about
the idea and asked if it was feasible, the agency made a quick
study of the proposal and concluded that it could be done for
between $20 million and $50 million. But after NASA asked for bids
on the project, it grew from a simple camera-in-space idea _
nicknamed by some the ``Gorecam'' or ``Goresat'' _ to a more
elaborate spacecraft that would also do environmental monitoring of
the Earth and the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, after an evaluation of nine competing proposals,
the agency selected one from the Scripps Institution of
Oceanography at the University of California at San Diego for a $75
million mission.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of just a video camera for taking pictures of the Earth,
the Scripps mission includes a multi-spectral imager that sees a
variety of wavelengths of light, from ultraviolet to near infrared,
to measure ozone, cloud height, the amounts of aerosols and
particulates suspended in the air, and other parameters.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes a radiometer for monitoring the solar radiation
reflected back into space by Earth and an instrument package for
monitoring solar events that could affect electrical equipment on
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``By no means is this the `Gorecam,''' said Dr. Francisco P.J.
Valero, director of the Atmospheric Research Laboratory at Scripps
and principal investigator for Triana. ``We wouldn't get into this
unless there is good, substantial science. We will be looking at
the planet in a way it has never been looked at before.''
</P>
<P>
   But as interest in Triana grew, so did opposition from some
space scientists concerned about diminishing NASA budgets and
politicians on Capitol Hill, particularly Republicans. NASA found
$35 million in its fiscal 1999 budget to begin the project, but ran
into renewed opposition this spring in trying to get $32 million
for Triana for the 2000 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   On May 13, the Republican-controlled House Science Committee
voted 21 to 18 along party lines to send a $41.2 billion,
three-year NASA authorization bill to the full House without Triana
financing. The measure included an amendment by Rep. Dave Weldon,
R-Fla., who called Triana ``a multimillion-dollar screen saver''
and ``tripe science,'' that shifted money for the project to other
research.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking against Weldon's amendment, Rep. Bart Gordon, D-Tenn.,
accused Republicans of attacking Triana in a partisan effort to
hurt Gore's presidential aspirations while ignoring the scientific
and educational uses of the program.
</P>
<P>
   On May 19, when the House considered the NASA financing bill,
Republicans attacked the project, with the majority leader, Dick
Armey of Texas calling it a ``far-out boondoggle'' and Rep. F.
James Sensenbrenner Jr. of Wisconsin, branding it ``the vice
president's late-night inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 259-168 to pass the measure without Triana
financing. Democratic leaders said they would ask their Senate
colleagues to reinsert money for Triana this summer when conference
committees of both houses meet to reconcile their spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, White House and NASA aides said Goldin might
recommend a presidential veto of a final agency spending bill that
did not include Triana.
</P>
<P>
   If Triana survives the budget wars, there is still discussion
among scientists on what the spacecraft will do and how valuable a
scientific contribution it can make.
</P>
<P>
   The spacecraft is scheduled for launching from a space shuttle
during a flight in December 2000. After a six-month journey, it is
to enter an orbit about a million miles from Earth at a point
called Lagrange 1. At this point, the gravitational pulls of the
Sun and the Earth balance one another, leaving a spacecraft to
match the Earth's track around the sun. There are several
spacecraft already at Lagrange 1, but they all face the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Triana would always have the sun at its back and its face toward
the sunlit side of Earth turning beneath it. There it would
constantly image the planet. Several times a year, Triana would
take detailed pictures of the far side of the moon, fully lighted
by the sun, as it passed between Triana's camera and Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Valero, the project's principal scientist, said Triana would be
the first craft to study Earth's energy balance and how it affects
climate. The planet absorbs energy from the sun that drives its
weather and climate, but it also reflects an unknown amount of
energy into space. The instruments would also track clouds and the
types of particles in them to see how they affect energy exchanges
in the atmosphere and how much potentially harmful ultraviolet
radiation reaches Earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have thought about doing science like this for years, and
now it's possible,'' Valero said. ``A lot of thought has gone into
these experiments. Science like this does not come out of a
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is disagreement about the project's worthiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you went to the scientific community and asked what is
needed most for Earth science, this would not be it,'' said Dr.
Richard S. Lindzen, a professor of earth, atmospheric and planetary
science at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. ``I don't see
a big benefit to science coming out of this. This is a strange way
to go about designing a project, starting with the vice president
having a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindzen said that if NASA wanted to devote part of its resources
to public relations, the agency might be justified in doing so. But
he said it should not call these projects ``science'' or devote too
much of its limited funds to them.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven C. Wofsy, a professor of atmospheric sciences at
Harvard University, says he was initially very skeptical about the
Triana proposal, but now says believes it may produce useful
science. He is not involved with the project, but serves on a
scientific committee that was briefed on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed by how carefully thought-out the experiments
were,'' Wofsy said. ``These people were determined to make
something out of it and they did. It's more than a world-cam, which
no one needs, and offers potentially unique results.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Donald Johnson, a retired professor of atmospheric sciences
at the University of Wisconsin who is now with the Universities
Space Research Association, says he can understand why some people
oppose Triana because of its political origins or its use of money
that could go to other projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes with some political baggage,'' he said, ``but it
still can be useful.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from any scientific payoff, he said, continued monitoring
of Earth can attract attention to the planet's problems globally
and be a useful educational tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some value in just making people aware of their
world,'' Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
