<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7469 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT &LR;      05-31 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MUSCLE SANDWICH  
 AUSTRALIA IN A EGGSHELL  
 NEW MOON FOR THE BARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's amazing what can be done with a little bit of Scotch tape.
Take, for example, the work of a team of researchers in creating a
kind of artificial muscle out of a piece of double-stick.
</P>
<P>
   It helps, of course, that attached to both sides of the tape are
sheets of single-walled carbon nanotubes, cylindrical molecules
with walls that are one atom thick. Carbon nanotubes, which were
discovered less than a decade ago, are among the star materials in
the growing research into development of molecular-scale
manufacturing devices.
</P>
<P>
   In the current research, reported in the journal Science,
scientists from Allied Signal and several universities put a
nanotube-tape-nanotube sandwich in an electrolyte (in one case,
simply a beaker of salt water) and applied a charge to one side.
</P>
<P>
   The nanotubes on the positively-charged side contracted, while
those on the negative side expanded, causing the whole sandwich to
bend. The result is a new kind of actuator, a device that converts
electrical energy into mechanical energy. It could have
applications in all kinds of microscopic devices.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers point out that the nanotube sheets, with their
array of countless numbers of the carbon cylinders, are akin to
muscles, which consist of millions of tiny fibers that contract
when an electrical signal reaches them from the brain. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The emu has not been kind to American ranchers. Many sank their
savings into raising the large ostrichlike birds in the hopes that
emu meat would catch on at the dinner table. It hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   But the emu, which is native to Australia, has been kinder to
researchers. Analyzing the proportions of carbon isotopes found in
fossilized emu eggshells dating to 65,000 years ago, scientists
have gained further insight into how the climate and vegetation of
Australia have changed.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, from American and Australian institutions, made
use of the fact that different climatic conditions produce grasses
with different levels of carbon isotopes, which are incorporated
into the eggshell when the grass is eaten and metabolized.
</P>
<P>
   Using fossilized egg samples from the Lake Eyre Basin, a huge
expanse of arid land in Australia, the researchers found that from
65,000 to 45,000 years ago, warmer-weather grasses linked to summer
monsoons predominated. These grasses disappeared in the last ice
age, from 28,000 to 15,000 years ago, when cold-weather types took
over.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who described their work in Science, found that
when warmer temperatures returned, about 10,000 years ago, the
warmer grasses did not return to previous levels. They suggest that
the burning practices of early humans may have affected how far
into the continent the monsoons penetrated.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread burning in what were then semiarid areas would have
modified the vegetation found, with desert scrub replacing trees
and shrubs. The vegetation change would, in turn, have reduced the
moisture transferred to the atmosphere, thus lessening the amount
of rainfall. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An 18th moon has been found orbiting Uranus, giving it a share,
with Saturn, of bragging rights in the category Planet With Most
Moons (mighty Jupiter, with 16, is third, followed by Neptune with
8, Mars with 2, and Earth and Pluto with 1 each).
</P>
<P>
   The new moon, which is only about 25 miles in diameter, was
actually photographed 13 years ago by the Voyager 2. Voyager had
already been credited with the discovery of 10 moons; a University
of Arizona astronomer poring over images from the mission found the
new one.
</P>
<P>
   The moon has yet to be named by the International Astronomical
Union. But most of the planet's other moons take their names from
Shakespeare (Desdemona, Oberon and Juliet being just a few). Given
how much in vogue the bard is these days, the trend seems likely to
continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
