<HEADER>
A7477 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      05-31 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: GUIDE FOR PARENTS IN HUNT FOR A SAFE SUMMER CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why does a tragedy always seem necessary to alert people to
consider safety issues that should be a matter of course? Such a
tragedy occurred last summer when 10-year-old Jeremy Scheinfeld of
New Rochelle, N.Y., drowned during an ill-conceived activity at an
upstate sleep-away camp.
</P>
<P>
   The incident took place during a game off camp grounds that
required him to jump into swirling water wearing hiking clothes and
shoes. Though he could swim, he became enmeshed in underwater
branches and could not free himself. It took 18 hours to locate his
body.
</P>
<P>
   The death has led Jeremy's parents, Jodi and Robert Scheinfeld,
to start a campaign to improve camp safety and to get parents to
look more carefully into the people to whom they entrust their
children during the summer and the camp conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Parents checking out summer camps for their children are likely
to delve into the camp's reputation, the kinds of activities
offered, the mix of children who attend, the attitudes of camp
personnel and the general atmosphere of the camp. But do they know
if the counselors are well trained, or whether fire extinguishers
are readily available in the bunks, or how well the camp is able to
deal with medical emergencies?
</P>
<P>
   Though most people would prefer not to think that a stay at camp
could involve a life-threatening illness or injury, the
Scheinfelds' experience is good reason to go to great lengths to
assure that children in camp will not be the victims of poor
judgment and avoidable injury and will return home healthy and
intact.
</P>
<P>
   The Scheinfelds have established a Web site outlining safety
guidelines for parents to consider when shopping for a camp. It is:
www.campsafetyguide.com
</P>
<P>
   It is not that camps lack safety requirements. The American
Camping Association, which accredits camps, lists 300 health and
safety standards, but only about 25 mandatory standards and an 80
percent score on the rest must be met to be accredited.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Hammond, the group's director of standards, says 2,300 to
2,400 camps are accredited, representing only one-quarter to
one-third of camps in this country.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain an operating permit, camps must meet state safety
standards, but there are no federal requirements. (In New York,
inspections are done by a county health officer.) If serious
injuries or deaths occur at a camp, the state health department is
supposed to be notified. But parents who want to know whether a
particular camp has had such problems do not have easy access to
state records.
</P>
<P>
   And so parents seeking information about a camp need to question
the director or other responsible person about things like
counselor training and credentials, safety of buildings,
precautions taken around water and access to emergency care.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the parents' job to be sure their children are
physically suited for the activities likely to be encountered at
the camp. Too often, the precamp medical examination is treated as
a bothersome formality.
</P>
<P>
   Why, many parents wonder, do perfectly healthy children have to
be checked out before engaging in camp activities that they are
likely to take part in at other times of the year as well?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the precamp physical is an opportunity to have a
child's health thoroughly assessed. For another, children at camp
may push themselves or be goaded to go beyond their bodily limits
when engaging in physically demanding group activities.
</P>
<P>
   Camp personnel should always be alerted to the recent or current
health problems of children in their charge. These might include
recent illnesses, injuries or operations; allergies and especially
food allergies, which can be life-threatening, chronic health
problems like asthma or diabetes and any physical limitations or
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Parents must also be sure to give permission to camp personnel
to provide emergency medical care, if needed, if the parents cannot
immediately be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Parents can consult the camping association's Web site, which
has a section that includes suggested questions to ask camp
directors, guidance on choosing a camp and a list of accredited
camps. The site is: www.acacamps.org
</P>
<P>
   Be sure the camp is accredited, but do not assume a camp is safe
even if it is accredited or if a parent or child previously
attended it or worked there. Ask to see the camp's written safety
plan, which must be filed with the state or county health
department and which describes staff qualifications and training,
camper supervision, safety requirements for specific activities and
fire safety and medical requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Ask how the staff is screened and trained. Are prospective
counselors checked for driving and criminal records and previous
employment history? Are their swimming skills tested? Do counselors
undergo a precamp training program (usually for six days) that
includes safety instruction and must they pass a test? Are all
counselors at least 18, and is the median age of counselors 21 or
more, as recommended by the camping association? What is the
camper-to-staff ratio? The younger the children, the fewer campers
should be in each counselor's charge.
</P>
<P>
   What percentage of counselors are trained and certified in CPR
or first aid? What arrangement does the camp have for medical care,
both on site and off?
</P>
<P>
   How are water-related activities supervised? Does the aquatic
director have at least three seasons of previous waterfront
experience, as required by New York State? Does the camp have a
water safety or progressive swimming instructor to assess the
swimming ability of each camper? How many lifeguards are there and
are they specifically trained for the types of swimming areas at
the camp?
</P>
<P>
   Is there a protocol for all off-site excursions? Will counselors
have a way of communicating for help if needed? Does a qualified
scout check out the path or activity before the children start out
(for example, a hiking trail may become treacherous after a rain)?
Must parents sign permission forms for these activities? Is proper
safety equipment used? Are children transported in safe vehicles
that have seat belts, and are they required to buckle up?
</P>
<P>
   Does the camp allow children to go into off-site bodies of
water? If so, has a government permit been issued that insures the
availability of lifesaving and safety equipment and qualified
lifeguards? Children should always wear bathing attire, not street
clothes, when entering water and life jackets when in boats.
</P>
<P>
   Does the camp maintain strict discipline for the staff,
including zero tolerance for drug and alcohol abuse and a staff
curfew? Has it fired counselors and for what reasons? Have there
been deaths or serious injuries, what happened and what has the
camp done to prevent a recurrence?
</P>
<P>
   If your inquiries are met with hostile responses, try another
camp.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
