<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYPOTHERMIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. If a body temperature of 107 degrees Fahrenheit is nearly
always fatal, what low body temperature is generally fatal?
</P>
<P>
   A. Medical literature contains few if any cases in which people
have recovered after their inner, or core, temperatures dropped
below 55 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``The Merck Manual of Medical Information'' says that
people with hypothermia should not be considered dead until they
have been warmed and still have no signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   Core body temperature is usually measured by electronic sensors
inserted into the digestive tract, often by way of the mouth or
rectum. It cannot be measured with an ordinary oral thermometer.
Hypothermia is considered to exist whenever the core temperature is
below 95 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Hypothermia occurs when the body loses heat faster than it can
burn fuel to replace it. How severe a person's reactions to low
temperatures will be depends on age and overall physical condition,
with the very old and the very young the most vulnerable; about 80
percent of hypothermia deaths occur in those older than 65.
</P>
<P>
   Age increases the risk for several reasons. The ability to
generate body heat declines because the heart rate is slower, blood
vessels do not contract as well, and the elderly often lose muscle
tone (which generates heat) and body fat (which conserves heat and
supplies body fuel).
</P>
<P>
   Exposed skin, cold air, cold water, cold wet clothing and
sitting on a cold surface that conducts heat away from the body all
greatly increase the rate of heat loss. Dehydration also adds to
the risks.
</P>
<P>
   The rates of chemical activity in the body are slowed by very
low temperatures. Eventually, the heartbeat and breathing may stop,
but even a very slow heartbeat and rate of respiration may maintain
vital body functions.
</P>
<P>
   Immediate treatment for hypothermia victims involves stopping
further loss of heat by wrapping the person in warm dry blankets.
Gentle handling is essential because jolts can cause fatally
irregular heart rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by postal mail to
Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43d St., New
York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to: Question(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of general interest will be answered in this column,
but requests for medical advice cannot be honored and unpublished
letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 1659EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7480 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-STREND-NYT &LR;      05-31 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-STREND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETES TEST STRENGTH AND ENDURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By LIZ NEPORENT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many adults, the mention of the president's Physical Fitness
Test conjures up images of sprinting between two chalkboard erasers
and doing sit ups to exhaustion. For those with fond memories of
this grade school gym class standard there is now a grown up
version of it called Strend, a challenging six-event contest that
is attracting more and more competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Strend is an acronym derived from the first three letters of
``strength'' and ``endurance.'' Each Strend competition includes
five upper-body strength events _ bench presses, pull-ups, military
presses, chin-ups and bar dips followed by a three-mile run. The
first Strend contest in 1992 was little more than a group workout.
There are now four to six events a year in several U.S. cities and
throughout Germany. A world championship features 50 competitors
and offers prize money for the top three men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors are allotted three minutes per strength event to do
as many repetitions as possible and then move on to the run. To
negate size and body-weight advantage, the weight that participants
use for the lifting exercises is based on a percentage of
individual body weight, which is officially measured a few hours
before the start of the competition. For example, Jennifer
Thompson-Tuzon, third-place finisher in the elite division at the
world Strend championship in October, was required to bench press
80 percent of her total body weight (120 pounds) as many times as
she could in the three minutes. ``I'd hoped I could do that much,''
said Ms. Thompson-Tuzon. She needed to complete a minimum of four
repetitions to prevent disqualification. She exceeded this by five
repetitions.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of a Strend competition is the athlete with the
highest Strend factor, a number calculated by adding the total
number of repetitions performed in the strength events and dividing
them by the three-mile run time. At the championship, Sonki Hong of
Walnut Creek, Calif., performed a total of 130 strength
repetitions, including 36 bar dips, and ran his three miles in
17:27, (5 minutes and 45 seconds per mile) for a world record
Strend factor of 7.449. At the same event, Peedi-Jean Saldania of
Honolulu established a new women's elite Strend factor record of
3.566. Ms. Saldania completed 78 strength exercise repetitions and
finished her run in 21:52 (7 minutes and 10 seconds per mile.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The philosophy of Strend is to maintain a balance between
muscular strength and aerobic endurance,'' said Carol Jaxon,
president of Strend Fitness Challenge, ``and unlike many other
sports, Strend makes an attempt to level the playing field.'' She
points out that the 29-year-old Hong weighs just 135 pounds and
that many of the other athletes outweigh him by more than 30
pounds. Also , factors like the hand placement on the pull-up bar
and the barbell are carefully controlled to take arm length into
account.
</P>
<P>
   The Strend Fitness Challenge is the brainchild of Edward
Bugarin, Ms. Jaxon's husband and a retired Army officer who was
once part of Delta Force, the elite anti-terrorist unit. The idea
for the competitions evolved from the fitness routine Bugarin used
to keep in shape for military operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to give those who practice both strength and
cardiovascular disciplines a way to compete against other like
athletes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The next Strend competition will be Saturday at Miramar Marine
Corps Air Station in San Diego, and the fourth Strend world
championship is scheduled for Oct. 16 in Honolulu. Strend is on the
Web at www.strend.com.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
