<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANGING UP ON BLOOD CLOTS WITH A NEW DRUG COCKTAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Mass., Wash., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adding a ``super aspirin'' to a standard clot-dissolving drug is
a more effective treatment for heart attacks than either drug
alone, according to an international study being published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs are alteplase, or Activase, and abciximab, or Reopro.
Each drug is marketed in this country but for separate uses. The
combination promises to spare many patients from angioplasty, a
procedure to widen blocked coronary arteries, or even from coronary
bypass surgery, experts said, citing the report in Circulation, a
journal published by the American Heart Association in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Heart attacks are the leading cause of death in the United
States and in other developed countries. Most heart attacks result
from blood clots that form after deposits of fat break open in the
lining of coronary arteries that nourish the heart, stopping blood
flow, destroying heart muscle and weakening the heart's ability to
pump blood. This, in turn, increases the risk of dangerous abnormal
heart rhythms and other complications.
</P>
<P>
   Alteplase, a standard drug often called TPA, can dissolve the
clots if given within a few hours after chest pain and other
symptoms of a heart attack begin. But sometimes, clots recur after
such drug therapy, largely from the clumping of blood cells known
as platelets.
</P>
<P>
   Abciximab prevents platelet clumping, and because it is more
potent than aspirin in doing so, abciximab is often called a
super-aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   The study is ``an important conceptual breakthrough'' in heart
attack therapy because the drugs attack clots in different ways,
said the lead author of the study, Dr. Elliott M. Antman of the
Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Abciximab weakens the structure of the clot by breaking up
platelet clumps and allows alteplase to penetrate more deeply into
the clot.
</P>
<P>
   Alteplase is a member of a class of drugs approved for treating
heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Abciximab, which is generally used in angioplasty procedures and
in cases of a chest pain condition known as unstable angina, does
not have broad approval for use against heart attacks. However,
doctors often use licensed drugs for unapproved uses, and many are
now expected to use the new combination for heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial in the same issue of the journal, Dr. J. Ward
Kennedy and Dr. Michael L. Stadius, both of the University of
Washington in Seattle, called the study ``a major contribution'' to
the management of heart attacks. While cautioning that additional
studies will be required, the Seattle cardiologists said that this
and newer combinations of drugs ``will likely prove to be
equivalent or superior to'' angioplasty and bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Antman said his team got the idea for the combination therapy
three years ago after it ``pieced together'' clues to its potential
use from animal experiments and from analyzing some clinical trials
in which a small number of patients happened to receive both drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Antman credited experiments conducted by Dr. Barry S. Coller,
then of the State University of New York at Stony Brook and now of
Mount Sinai Medical Center in Manhattan, as pivotal in starting his
team's study, which was conducted from March 1997 through July 1998
in the United States, Belgium, Canada, England, France, Germany and
the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   The study compared the ability of different amounts of the two
drugs, singly or in combination, to dissolve blood clots and
improve blood flow at 60 minutes and 90 minutes after they were
injected. A major concern was that a smaller-than-standard dose of
alteplase would be ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   But a combination of half the standard dose of alteplase and a
standard amount of abciximab improved blood flow in 72 percent of
the heart attack patients at 60 minutes and in 77 percent at 90
minutes. Alteplase alone eased blood flow in 43 percent of the
patients at 60 minutes and 62 percent at 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Both drugs are expensive. Alteplase costs about $2,000 for a
standard dose. Abciximab costs about $1,000. Although the immediate
savings balance out, there could be substantial longer-term savings
if the therapy reduces the need for angioplasty and bypass surgery,
Antman said.
</P>
<P>
   If widely adopted, the combination drug therapy would be only
part of the long-range treatment to prevent heart attacks. Patients
would also receive a drug to lower cholesterol in the blood and in
the fatty deposits in the arteries.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to test combinations of other drugs that are
now marketed or in development, Antman said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
