<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CENTENARIAN-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTION OF DETERIORATION WITH EACH PASSING YEAR IS A MYTH, STUDY
FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (The Science Times) 
(jt) 
 By PHILIP J. HILTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until recently, very few people lived to be more than 100. But
with the number of centenarians rocketing upward, statisticians and
scientists have begun studying them _ and challenging some of the
conventional wisdom about the very old.
</P>
<P>
   These are not necessarily people at the end of the line,
deteriorating into extreme age. Rather, many show patterns of
health that are as surprising as they are mysterious. For example,
the rate at which people die rises steadily from middle age up
through the 80s. But then, death rates decline. After age 110, the
death rate drops back to that for people in their 80s.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who make it past 90 or 95 are in robust health; as
a group, they are healthier than people 10 to 15 years younger. It
is as if those strong enough to make it to 95 are strong enough to
run a while longer. A substantial number of them stay healthy and
in command of their faculties until a short time before death.
</P>
<P>
   Those who reach 100 usually have had no dementia or serious
cognitive problems up through their mid-90s, said Dr. Margery H.
Silver, a leader of a Harvard University study of centenarians.
Contrary to previous studies, which suggested that nearly 100
percent of those reaching 100 should suffer dementia, the study
shows that after 100, up to one-quarter of the centenarians still
have no dementia. About 50 percent have mild to moderate dementia,
and an additional quarter have very severe dementia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways centenarians are healthier than people 20 to 30
years their junior,'' Dr. Silver and her colleague, Dr. Thomas
Perls, wrote in ``Living to 100,'' recently published by Basic
Books. ``Rather than accumulating damage, they were shedding it
like water from a duck's back.'' Perls and Dr. Silver are leading
the New England Centenarian Study at Beth Israel-Deaconness
Hospital and Harvard University Medical School, both in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   One of a number of studies of the extremely old, it is the only
so-called population-based study of people 100 and older. That
means it followed a natural population (in this case, 460,000
people in six towns in Massachusetts) and studied every person who
reached 100, checking factors like their conditions, incomes and
social status. Since the study began in 1994, a number of
interesting facts have emerged, including these:
</P>
<P>
   _Among the 169 centenarians, who have been extensively studied,
only three have had cancer.
</P>
<P>
   _A disproportionate number are women who never married.
</P>
<P>
   _No pattern of diet and exercise appears among the centenarians;
some are vegetarians, some eat lots of red meat; some are athletes
and some do nothing strenuous.
</P>
<P>
   _The only personality trait the subjects share is the ability to
manage stress effectively. As a group, they have experienced as
much stress as others, but they seem to have bounced back readily
from life's crises.
</P>
<P>
   _About 80 percent of those over 100 are women. But the
relatively few men in the group are far healthier than the women _
exactly opposite the situation at age 85. About 80 percent of the
men over 100 are healthy and mentally alert, while 80 percent of
the women have at least some dementia.
</P>
<P>
   _Among the women who are mothers, the ones who had children
after age 40 are disproportionately represented.
</P>
<P>
   _Medical expenses, which peak for those 60 to 69, drop for those
85 to 105. They get cheaper for society as they age.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7487 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CENTENARIAN-2NDTA     05-31 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CENTENARIAN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: they age.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What may be the most fundamental finding is not in the details,
but in the larger picture: some people live to extreme old age in
good health.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 50,000 centenarians in the United States now, up
from almost none at the turn of the century. Like the rest of
society, they have benefited from two great waves that extended
life expectancy: improved public sanitation, which increased
average life expectancy by 20 years, and the advent of antibiotics
and other drugs, which added another 10.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, demographers began to calculate the combined
effects of the growing population and the additional life span,
producing a gloomy ``standard model'' of aging that has prevailed
for 20 years. In this view, said Dr. Richard Suzman of the National
Institute on Aging, society might ``save people from dying, but
would not be able to cure them of chronic, disease.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus,'' Suzman said, ``there would be an accumulation, a
pandemic of people in worse and worse shape. This was a very
strongly held paradigm in gerontology.''
</P>
<P>
   The Centenarian Study challenges this view. The elderly are not
only living longer and are healthier, but there is something of a
mystery about why.
</P>
<P>
   James W. Vaupel, a demographer at the Max Planck Institute in
Rostock, Germany, who is involved in a Danish centenarian study,
noted last year in the journal Science that it had long been
erroneously assumed that there was a biological limit to longevity,
and that more and more people in a group died each year as they
approached it.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in a hypothetical group of 100 people, a certain
number die each year. That number increases to about 5 each year at
around age 65, 8 each year at 75 and 11 each year at 85. How is it
possible, then, that at age 90 the number remains 11 and at 100 it
drops back to 8? The studies show just that: The death rate levels
off in the 90s, and even appears to decrease after age 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decline in old-age mortality is perplexing,'' Vaupel said.
``What biological charter permits us to live long post-reproductive
lives?
</P>
<P>
   Scientists who study population figures were skeptical when
these numbers were first suggested. They suspected the sampling of
the very old was skewed. So Vaupel and colleagues ran tests to
check the idea. They figured that if the drop in mortality rate was
a real biological phenomenon, it should also appear among other
species.
</P>
<P>
   He started with fruit flies _ 2,706,967 of them to be exact. He
also followed the lives of 27,542 wasps, and about 650,000
parasitic worms. The pattern was the same across the species. Death
rates rose, peaked late in life, then dropped. Thus, while most
fruit flies die at age 30 days, a few hardy ones fly on. Of the 2.7
million he studied, 44 females and 18 males lived 100 days.
</P>
<P>
   To check one more possibility, Vaupel studied another complex
creature: the automobile. A car has died, he decided, if it is not
reregistered. He studied Chevrolets and Toyotas from the 1970 and
1980 model years. The pattern was there again: the ``death'' rate
peaked at about 10 years, then began to drop. The effect was not as
dramatic as in fruit flies, but it was there.
</P>
<P>
   The question is why? It may be partly a phenomenon of large,
complex systems of all kinds _ a few of the best made and best
treated can last much longer. With humans, that may mean
exceptional genes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably all have the genes to get us to age 85, if we take
care of ourselves,'' said Perls. ``But it may be that some of us
have supergenes, genes that protect us from cancers or Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kenneth Rockwood, a gerontologist at Dalhousie University in
Halifax, Nova Scotia, said the important factor, genetic or
otherwise, appeared to show itself early. Aging may be slowed even
at young ages, for example, with very late menopause, which occurs
among many of the women who become centenarians, suggesting they
are already aging more slowly by 50.
</P>
<P>
   Perls and Dr. Silver say they have found crucial evidence that
genes are a large part of living past 100 _ that extreme old age
runs in families. They have found several families with 10 or more
centenarians and many others over 90. Now they hope to find genes
that keep them healthy, perhaps by helping to ward off disease.
``Then maybe we can find some medications that will inhibit
negative gene products, or potentiate the positive ones,'' Dr.
Perls said.
</P>
<P>
   An example of what they hope to find is a human counterpart of
the fruit-fly gene HSP70. These proteins shield other cellular
substances from damage, and so as flies age, the more of this
protein they make, the longer they live.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we know that a substantial number of people can
remain robust and healthy through their 90s, at least, that should
change our attitude about old age,'' Perls said. ``It is no longer
a curse, but an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the centenarians studied in New England group was Anna
Morgan of Rehoboth, Mass. She remained so healthy in old age that
on her 100th birthday, she was not at home but rather was
testifying on health care before a committee of the state
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Just before she died at 101, she told researchers she had to
make all her own funeral arrangements before anything happened to
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my children to be burdened with all this,'' she
said. ``They're old, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
