<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, June 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of potent thunderstorms will develop across the middle
Mississippi, Tennessee and lower Ohio Valleys in response to the
lifting of humid air from the Gulf of Mexico by a jet stream
disturbance approaching from the central Plains. Some of the storms
will produce heavy rain. Severe weather is also possible in a few
of the storms, with isolated spots of large hail and damaging
winds. Burly, hit-or-miss thunderstorms will extend southwest into
portions of eastern Oklahoma, Arkansas and northeast Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Hazy humid conditions with scattered showers and thunderstorms
will extend from the central Gulf Coast to the western spine of the
southern and central Appalachians as a Bermuda high-pressure system
continues to pump tropical air into the East. Northbound tropical
air will also collide with a cool front across the eastern and
southeast Great Lakes region, setting the stage for hit-or-miss
thunderstorms with the potential for heavy rains across northern
Indiana, southern Michigan, extreme western New York and the St.
Lawrence River Valley in Quebec, Canada, the latter being at
greatest risk.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated, heavy thunderstorms associated with the leading edge
of the sea breeze will erupt across southern Florida. With moist
winds from the east importing juicy tropical air, rainfalls of 2
inches or more are possible in spots.
</P>
<P>
   Widely separated showers and thunderstorms will develop across
northern Washington and southern British Columbia as a pocket of
cold air 18,000 feet aloft destabilizes the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: June Gloom
</P>
<P>
   The high at San Francisco on Saturday was 54 degrees, tying the
city's record for the lowest maximum temperature for the date. The
daytime chill was caused by low clouds and drizzle associated with
a deep, cool and moist layer of marine air, which, on Saturday
spanned from the ground to 3,000 feet aloft. A marine layer gets
its name from the fact that coast-bound air acquires moisture and
the approximate temperature of underlying cool waters. With
cooler-than-average Pacific waters, the infamous ``June gloom'' of
recurrent morning fog and low clouds at the coast now appears to be
a safe bet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
