<HEADLINE>
CALL OF THE WILD IS EVER CLEARER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hiking is wildly popular these days, as are rafting and
bicycling. So Backroads, a travel company in Berkeley, Calif., did
not need a computer program to grasp that a combination would sell.
According to Megan Gaynor, a spokeswoman, these trips, begun only
in 1997, are the fastest growing in the company's catalog.
</P>
<P>
   These, like other physically rugged trips on horseback, bike,
raft and kayak, are starting to sell out for this season, mostly
because each trip has only a few spaces to begin with. But many
operators have dates still open for those willing to shop. Here is
a glance at a few trips, with suggestions for further looking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Triathlon of Sorts
</P>
<P>
   One of Backroads' multisport trips is ``Canadian Rockies
Kananaskis,'' for 20 people in two kinds of housing: tents and
cabins, or inns and lodges. The site for these trips, Kananaskis
(pronounced kah-nan-NANS-kiss) Country, is centered on the village
of Kananaskis, west of Calgary, Alberta, in an area of mountains,
lakes and forests.
</P>
<P>
   In the inn-lodge version, these six-day, five-night trips, all
meals included, cost $1,598 a person, double occupancy; the
double-occupancy cost is $898 in the tent-cabin version in areas
with coin-operated showers. Bicycles can be rented.
</P>
<P>
   In the tent version, the first day involves a 90-minute van ride
to the campground and a warm-up bike ride. The morning of the
second day brings a 20- or 25-mile bike trip _ participants pick
the difficulty _ and the afternoon, a raft trip with Class 1 to 3
rapids (6 is the most difficult). The next day brings an eight- or
nine-mile hike with a 1,600-foot climb. Bike trips and hikes occupy
the last two days.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the rugged schedule, Ms. Gaynor said that the
company let people drop out and ride after part of a day, but that
fitness was important.
</P>
<P>
   The tent trips leave on Sundays from July 4 through Aug. 29; the
Aug. 15 and July 25 trips are full; those on July 11 and 18 are for
families (children over 9 are allowed), and those Aug. 8, 22 and 29
for single travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The inn versions start July 25, with the last on Aug. 29. Those
on July 25 and Aug. 8 are for single travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Backroads, 801 Cedar Street, Berkeley, Calif. 94710; (800)
462-2848; www.backroads.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colorado on Horseback
</P>
<P>
   American Wilderness Experience in Boulder, Colo., is a broker
for tour companies and ranches. One of its component companies, the
Bear Basin Ranch in Westcliffe, Colo., a two-hour drive southwest
of Colorado Springs, offers five-day pack trips in the Sangre de
Cristo Mountains from mid-July to mid-September. Each trip
accommodates eight guests and two guides; one pack horse is
provided for each two riders.
</P>
<P>
   The participants should have riding experience and should be
prepared for activity above 11,500 feet, and for total lack of
facilities; Dave Wiggins, president of American Wilderness, said
that one mountain pass was above 13,000 feet. Three-person dome
tents are set up to accommodate one or two travelers, and pit
toilets are used.
</P>
<P>
   Most travelers come alone, he said, although families are
welcome. It is recommended that children be at least 16 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about accommodating vegetarians, Wiggins said, as did all
the others, that with notice this was not a problem. ``In fact, we
don't prepare much meat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The cost is $810 a person for five days and four nights.
Sleeping bags can be rented.
</P>
<P>
   American Wilderness Experience, 2820A Wilderness Place, Boulder,
Colo. 80301; (800) 444-0099; www.awetrips.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kayaking Off Maine
</P>
<P>
   The Maine Island Kayak Co. runs courses and trips, some of which
are demanding. Among them are five-day, four-night trips to
Penobscot Bay or the Fundy Isles. The company owner, Tom Bergh,
says both of these are for adults.
</P>
<P>
   Single-paddler kayaks are used, and tents and cooking gear are
carried along. The company supplies everything but sleeping bags.
</P>
<P>
   These trips accommodate six to eight travelers and two guides.
The paddling route is selected each day, with an eye on the
weather; camps are set up on various islands each evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Penobscot Bay trip, which starts on Little Deer Isle, may
involve paddling around Vinalhaven or Isle au Haut. The price is
$750 a person, and trips leave June 21, July 26, Aug. 23 and Sept.
13.
</P>
<P>
   Maine Island Kayak Co., 70 Luther Street, Peaks Island, Maine
04108; (800) 796-2373; www.maineislandkayak.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Down the Salmon River  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor Adventure River Specialists (OARS), in Angels Camp,
Calif., operates five-night trips on the Middle Fork of the Salmon
River in Idaho. These trips, which start every seven or eight days
all summer, accommodate 24 travelers and 6 guides, using dories,
boats with oars, rubber rafts and inflatable one- or two-paddler
kayaks. Participants may try various boats in Class 3 and Class 4
rapids, said Eric Grathwol, the marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   The trip is affected by the seasonal shift in the river,
Grathwol said: In May and early June, when the water is high, the
trip is demanding and the minimum age is 15. When the water is
calmer, in late June and in July, 9-year-olds are accepted.
Families tend to come in August, he said, and anglers in September.
</P>
<P>
   The price, including all equipment, in May, June, August and
early September is $1,509 a person; in July, $1,625. When the water
drops in September, the trips are shorter _ four days and three
nights, for $1,315.
</P>
<P>
   OARS, Post Office Box 67, Angels Camp, Calif., 95222; (800)
346-6277; www.oars.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mainly for Singles  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Outdoor Leadership School, or NOLS, has been in
business for 34 years and now has headquarters in Wyoming. Its
whitewater, horse-packing and rock-climbing courses in the lower 48
states are virtually filled this summer, although Tom Reed, a
spokesman, says there are waiting lists.
</P>
<P>
   This organization usually discourages couples and families
because it wants each participant to interact with the others, he
said. It also stresses good physical conditioning, and while there
is transportation back for participants who find that they cannot
cope, the organization does not give refunds to them.
</P>
<P>
   There are openings on two 20-day canoe trips on the South
Macmillan River in the Yukon Territory. The dates are June 22 to
July 12 and Aug. 1 to 20. The cost is $2,375 a person; participants
fly into Whitehorse.
</P>
<P>
   NOLS, 288 Main Street, Lander, Wyo. 82520; (307) 332-5300;
www.nols. edu. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five hundred outfitters and operators in 40 states and 50
foreign countries belong to a trade association, America Outdoors.
This organization maintains a database of its members at
www.americaoutdoors.org. This year's catalog should be out this
week.
</P>
<P>
   America Outdoors, Post Office Box 10847, Knoxville, Tenn. 37939;
(423) 558-3595.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
