<HEADER>
A7495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-40     05-31 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-400&AMP;ADDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS REFUGEES CROSS ALBANIA BORDER, NATO PLANES HIT NEARBY SERB
POSITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINI, Albania _ NATO planes bombarded Serbian positions in
southern Kosovo for much of Monday, dropping bombs only yards from
Albania's border, as refugees crossed over against a backdrop of
billowing black smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, America,'' Kadrush Demir, a 22-year-old farmer from
Kosovo, said approvingly after arriving in Albania, as yet another
explosion shook the town of Verbnice, over the border in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees _ among 200 or so who arrived in Albania on Monday
_ said none of them were hurt in the explosions, though several
bombs dropped only a few hundred yards away on what they said were
groups of Serbian soldiers near the border.
</P>
<P>
   Most the refugees appeared to be more of the men who reported
that they were imprisoned for several days or weeks by Serbian
forces. In the last eight days, about 2,500 men have crossed into
Albania saying that they had been held captive at a jail in
northern Kosovo. Nearly all reported that they had been beaten.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the men who crossed on Monday said that they had
been held in the southern city of Prizren. That suggests that the
Serbs may have broadened what aid officials here say is a
well-organized effort to extract information about the Kosovo
Liberation Army, the Kosovo Albanian rebel group fighting Serbian
forces, from men fleeing Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clearly now extremely systematic,'' said Rupert
Colville, a spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
``It's kind of a conveyor belt of brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   Demir said that he had been separated three days ago from the
women and children in a group fleeing toward the Albanian border
and taken, along with 40 other men, to a shoe factory in Prizren.
He said that they were not fed and were beaten often by Serbian
policemen, who demanded information about the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, without explanation, the men were all set
free.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us,'' he said, as he wolfed down bread and cheese,
his first meal in three days. ``They took our money. And they
didn't need us anymore.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Throughout the day, NATO planes thundered above the mountains
along the border between Albania and Kosovo, dropping dozens of
bombs on several villages within sight of the border. On the
Albanian side, people stopped by the side of the road, children
craning their necks, and cheered as bombs hummed down to their
targets and exploded.
</P>
<P>
   In the late afternoon, Albanian soldiers moved their border post
back several hundred yards after bombs exploded on the Kosovo side
nearby and machine-gun fire rattled from Serbian positions.
Albanian military officials said that the bombed villages appeared
to include Gorozhupe, Planeje, Verbnice and possibly Zhur.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian forces also traded gunfire with rebel forces on Monday
in the hills just across the Drini River from the border crossing.
Officials with the Albanian military and rebel officials said that
Yugoslav soldiers continued to lob shells into Albania, hitting
four villages in a reported transit area used by rebel fighters on
their way into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   No one was reported injured there on Monday; but two people were
killed last week when the same towns were shelled.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The nearness of the NATO bombing and other fighting to the
Albanian border _ and to 100,000 refugees living in the nearby city
of Kukes _ was further evidence of what officials say is an
increasing danger here.
</P>
<P>
   There have been two sniper attacks at the border crossing in
recent days, including one last week in which a Chilean sound
engineer was hit. On Sunday, Serbian forces fired two mortar shells
across the border here. They landed only 500 yards from the area
where refugees are processed.
</P>
<P>
   Colville said that the shooting and shelling episodes further
underscore the need for the the refugee agency's plans, which many
of the refugees here are resisting, to move the Kosovo Albanians
away from camps near the border to new camps in the south and west
of Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely of paramount importance that we try to empty
these camps as quickly as possible,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
