<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLACE-BOOK-REVIEW-N     05-31 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLACE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BRIEF INTERVIEWS WITH HIDEOUS MEN': CALLING THEM MISOGYNISTS WOULD
BE TOO KIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How to describe David Foster Wallace's new collection of
stories? You might say it's like being a therapist and being forced
to listen to one narcissistic patient after the next, prattle on _
and on and on _ about their neuroses and their explanations for
those neuroses and the rationalizations behind the explanations for
those neuroses.
</P>
<P>
   Or you might say it's like being locked in a room with a bunch
of speed freaks babbling to themselves nonstop on a
benzedrine-fueled high as they clip their toenails or cut the split
ends out of their hair.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in ``Brief Interviews With Hideous Men,'' all of
Wallace's remarkable powers of observations _ not to mention all of
his manic energy _ are trained not outward at the world at large,
as it was in his 1996 magnum opus ``Infinite Jest,'' but inward at
the convolutions of his characters' shallow psyches.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the people in this book are members of what might be
called Inward Bound, and nearly every story in this volume features
``an element of self-consciousness'' that ``now was itself an
object of focus, like some sort of diffraction or regress of
self-consciousness and consciousness of self-consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting book is an airless, tedious production, virtually
devoid of the wonderful descriptive powers on display in Wallace's
earlier fiction and reportial essays. Absent too, for the most
part, are his antic sense of humor, his uncanny ability to limn the
surrealness of contemporary life and his zingy, idiosyncratic
prose.
</P>
<P>
   One piece in ``Hideous Men'' reads like a parody of Nicholson
Baker, providing a minutely detailed account of the emotions going
through a 13-year-old boy's head as he dives into a swimming pool.
Two other stories _ a dying man's rant against his son and another
man's account of his father's career as a men's room attendant _
read like imitations of the early Martin Amis: they are animated by
a sophomoric voyeurism, and a fascination (and disgust) with bodily
functions.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the volume's other stories (or ``belletristic pieces,''
as Wallace pretentiously calls them) are discursive portraits of
relentlessly self-absorbed whiners, set down in an unappetizing mix
of psychobabble, scholarly jargon and stream-of-consciousness
riffs. Few of these characters are even given names, and they often
seem more like generic types than distinct individuals.
</P>
<P>
   There's ``the depressed person,'' a woman so immersed in the
fluctuations of her own self-esteem that she can spend hours
complaining about her own emotional pain to a friend who is dying
of cancer. There's a writer (perhaps a stand-in for Wallace
himself) who babbles on for pages about whether to level with the
reader about his post-modernist narrative strategies or whether
this impulse indicates an embarrassing need for approval.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a self-absorbed woman who is relieved to discover
that her husband is a ``Secret Compulsive Masturbator'' because it
means that his distraction in bed isn't a result of her own
inadequacy as a lover.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt these portraits are meant as sardonic commentaries on
our narcissistic, therapeutic age, but they are so long-winded, so
solipsistic, so predictable in their use of irony and gratuitous
narrative high jinks that they end up being as tiresome and
irritating as their subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of this volume consists of equally numbing
portraits of ``hideous men,'' who reveal in a series of interviews
that they are exemplary chauvinist pigs. One hideous man
rationalizes his womanizing, trying to turn the act of cruelly
dropping his girlfriend into a self-pitying disquisition on his own
inability to love.
</P>
<P>
   Another says he calls his deformed arm (``a itty tiny little
flipper'') ``the Asset'' because of its ability to evoke pity in
women he wants to seduce. And a third says he married a woman who
``had a good body even after she'd had a kid'' because it meant
she'd been ``pre-tested'': ``the kid didn't blow her body out, so I
knew she'd be a good bet to sign on and have kids with and still
try to have sex.''
</P>
<P>
   These men run the gamut from the annoying to the monstrous. At
one end of the spectrum are two Beavis and Butt-head adolescents
chortling (``Heh heh heh'') over a voluptuous target of seduction;
at the other is a maniacal psycho who suggests that gang rape, like
the Holocaust, isn't necessarily a bad thing because it might make
its victim ``more of a complete human being.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear just what point Wallace wants to make with these
boring, repetitious and frequently repellent profiles, aside from
the obvious one of examining the ways in which men can take
advantage of women. There is little subtlety or insight to his
portraits: his men are so uniformly misogynists, his women so
uniformly victims that the reader who didn't know better might
easily surmise that an angry radical feminist had penned them as
part of an ideological screed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed this entire volume represents a sharp falling off in
ambition, nuance and vision from Wallace's previous works of
fiction, books like ``Infinite Jest'' and ``The Broom of the
System'' (1986), which aspired to give the reader a hip, tactile
take on millennial America while daring to combine the latest
post-modernist hardware with an old-fashioned love of character and
storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   In an essay in ``A Supposedly Fun Thing I'll Never Do Again''
(1997), ``Fun Thing,'' Wallace mourned the loss of engagement with
deep moral issues that distinguished the work of the great
19th-century writers, and he took contemporary writers to task for
using the tools of irony and sarcasm to avoid commitment and risk.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Brief Interviews With Hideous Men,'' he is
guilty of exactly those failings. Only one story in this volume _ a
sad, little elliptical tale titled ``Church Not Made With Hands,''
which depicts a man trying to cope with his daughter's injury in a
freak swimming pool accident _ evinces the lure and dazzle of his
earlier work and hints at the capabilities of this immensely
talented writer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `BRIEF INTERVIEWS WITH HIDEOUS MEN'
</P>
<P>
   By David Foster Wallace
</P>
<P>
   273 pages. Little, Brown &AMP; Company. $24.
</P>
