<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lopez aims to live the dream of Open win
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's been stirring within her for about a month now.
When a U.S. Women's Open approaches for Nancy Lopez, so begins the
struggle. Can she maintain a balance of physical and mental
preparedness without becoming obsessed and overwhelmed by it all?
If so, can the most sentimental journey in women's golf move to the
non-fiction shelf?
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lopez wants a U.S. Women's Open as much John Elway wanted
a Super Bowl ring, more than Greg Norman covets a Masters title.
</P>
<P>
   And women's golf fans would like to see it happen.
</P>
<P>
   Chance No. 23 will come on Thursday in West Point, Miss., when
Lopez, the most famous carpooling Mom in Albany, Ga., strides down
the first fairway of the Old Waverly Golf Club hoping that her
karma, her ballstriking and her putting stroke might blend together
for a dream week.
</P>
<P>
   She's hoping that The Open that got away at Pumpkin Ridge two
years ago was not her last shot. She's hoping that she'll get to
stand over another 10-footer for a chance at the elusive USGA
trophy. She's hoping that a rush of tears that followed her missed
putt then, allowing a victory for England's Allison Nicholas, might
be felt this time without clenched teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me months to get over it,'' Lopez said during a
telephone interview. ``I thought about it every night. I went to
sleep every night thinking about it. I didn't think it would affect
me the way it did. I thought, `God, what's going on here?' It was
really a tough defeat. Usually, if I lose, I accept it and move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Move on? Yeah, right. Even two years later, when Lopez sees
Nicholas on the putting green or the practice range, she says in
jest, ``I kind of want to trip her as she goes by. . . . I pick on
her a lot, but she played like a champion and deserved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are Lopez still had Pumpkin Ridge on her mind last year,
when the Open was played at Blackwolf Run in Kohler, Wisc. In what
would become a tournament featuring Duke's Jenny Chuasiriporn and
Korea's Se Ri Pak, Lopez spent a nightmarish two days, missing the
cut by 10 shots with rounds of 77-83.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hated it,'' she said. ``It wasn't even fun. I was glad
I missed the cut so I wouldn't have to be 27-over by Sunday and
embarrass myself.''
</P>
<P>
   This week Lopez will be paired with Chuasiriporn, who makes her
professional debut, on a course where Lopez feels most comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Friends with owner George Bryan, she has played the course many
times during the last 10 years, occasionally by personal invitation
and annually in a charity event there.
</P>
<P>
   Will her experience provide an edge on a course unfamiliar to
many of the competitors?
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably,'' Lopez said, ``but I don't want to say that. . . .
I am excited about it, though. I have a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Although victimized by recent mental errors, Lopez has been
striking the ball superbly, tying for 15th at Corning last week in
preparation for an Old Waverly course that demands crisp iron play
to small greens. Her putting is much improved since a switch to the
cross-handed style a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Lopez is 42 years old. She has arthritis in her left knee,
``bone-on-bone'' from where cartilage was removed several years
ago. It happens to most people who spend 30 years twisting on a
knee, especially when combined with recent years of pounding on
treadmills and stairmasters. She's been taking glucosamine sulfate
instead of anti-inflammatories that are harder on the body. She
regularly exercises in her pool, lessening the strain on crucial
joints. She's into magnetic therapy to increase circulation, and
senses some positive results.
</P>
<P>
   When Lopez wore a brace on the knee last week, concerned viewers
watching on TV during the Corning Classic began calling in
remedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be a little more pressure I've put on myself
because I know there are only going to be so more Opens that I can
win,'' Lopez said. ``I'm getting older and I've got to face that.
My mind's not older, but my body is. I don't do pain too well. I'm
a real baby when it comes to that. Sure, I'm hurting and people ask
about my knee, but I don't want to think that I'm complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez has for the first time brought her three daughters to the
tournament site along with husband Ray Knight, who typically walks
every hole from behind the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to change my luck,'' Nancy said, ``and bring
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   54TH U.S. WOMEN'S OPEN
</P>
<P>
   _ Event: The 54th U.S. Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dates: Thursday-Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defending champion: Se Ri Pak.
</P>
<P>
   _ Television: Thursday-Friday, 3-7 p.m., ESPN. Saturday-Sunday,
3-6 p.m., NBC. Any playoff would be broadcast in its entirety by
ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   _ Site: Old Waverly Golf Club, West Point, Miss..
</P>
<P>
   _ Length: 6,431 yards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Par: 36-36--72.
</P>
<P>
   _ Format: 72 holes of stroke play.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cut: Top 60 and ties, plus anyone within 10 strokes of the
lead.
</P>
<P>
   _ Playoff: 18 holes starting at noon Monday, sudden death if two
players are still tied.
</P>
<P>
   _ Purse: $1.75 million ($315,000 to the winner).
</P>
<P>
   _ Noteworthy: An American hasn't won the Women's Open since
1994.
</P>
