<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mexico Sets Entry Fee For Most Tourists &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starting July 1, Mexico will begin charging foreign tourists 150
pesos, about $16 at recent exchange rates, to enter the country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tourists arriving by air or on land will be subject to the entry
fee. But tourists who declare that they intend to stay within 15.5
miles of the border and passengers from cruise ships who stay in
Mexico less than 72 hours will not be charged. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents say that the fee is unlikely to discourage
tourists planning lengthy trips to Mexican beach resorts or to
colonial cities, who expect to spend hundreds of dollars on their
vacations in any event. But people traveling to Mexico on modest
budgets, including thousands of Mexican-American families who
travel by car or bus from border states to cities in northern
Mexico to visit relatives, could feel the squeeze. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mario Sanchez, a spokesman for the Tourism Ministry, said that
the ministry was aware of the risks and was studying how to
minimize them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to discourage tourism or damage the tourism
industry,'' Sanchez said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He estimated that the measure would generate about $80 million a
year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Air passengers arriving in the United States must pay a $32.50
entry fee. Mexican applicants for a United States visa now pay a
$45 fee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sam Dillon &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the Earth With an Astronaut's Eye &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, people have looked up at the sky and watched the
stars and planets. This week the American Museum of Natural History
will present a view of the earth as it would look from the bay
window of a space shuttle in orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Opening Saturday, the David S. and Ruth L. Gottesman Hall of
Planet Earth is the first in a series of halls scheduled to open as
part of the Frederick Phineas and Sandra Priest Rose Center for
Earth and Space. Others, including the new Hayden Planetarium and
the Cullman Hall of the Universe, will open in early 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the attractions at the Hall of Planet Earth is a ``dynamic
earth globe'' eight feet across, onto which are projected, in a
12-minute loop, images of the rotating earth, showing such things
as dissolving clouds, then dissolving oceans to highlight the
topography. Other exhibits include 167 rocks from around the globe,
a model of a peak in Switzerland, ice core samples from Greenland,
and a sand model that illustrates how mountains are formed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the hall, visitors can see exotic black smokers _
chimneylike sulfide structures that grow along thermal vents on the
ocean floor and provide glimpses into communities where microbes
flourish and offer clues to the origins of life on earth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One interactive display allows visitors to explore ice core
records covering more than 115,000 years of the earth's climate
history, and another describes how carbon moves through the earth,
the atmosphere and salt rock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A number of videos _ including ``Various Views of the Planet''
and ``El Nino'' _ will run throughout the exhibit. An Earth Events
Wall will provide news and videos of such phenomena as earthquakes,
volcanic eruptions and hurricanes as soon as they occur. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suggested admission to the museum, which includes entry to the
Hall of Planet Earth, is $8, $4.50 for children, and $6 for seniors
and students. The museum is open daily. For information call (212)
769-5100.
</P>
<P>
   Alisha Berger &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Cotton Was King In New Orleans &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nights in 19th-century New Orleans were famously racy, notorious
for drinking, dancing and gambling; by day there was more serious
business _ most notably cotton. Before the Civil War, the city was
one of the busiest cotton ports in the world; boatloads of cotton
poured into the city and created the wealth that built many of the
mansions that still grace the Garden District. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cotton in all its permutations _ from plants, lush fields, tired
pickers, and plantations to art that the crop inspired _ can be
seen in an exhibition at the Historic New Orleans Collection, a
small French Quarter museum with extensive archives, through July
10.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 90 items in the exhibition are photographs of
steamboats and of grand houses built by rich plantation owners and
cotton factors, illustrations of machines that processed the
harvest, portraits of people prominent in the cotton world,
examples of the paper trail generated by cotton trading, ephemera
from the New Orleans 1884-85 World's Industrial and Cotton
Centennial Exposition, and five panels of a popular 19th-century
form of art known as pasties, removed from the walls of the Nitta
Yuma plantation house near Vicksburg, Miss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Nitta Yuma pasties are collages of cut silhouettes placed in
a painted landscape centering on scenes of slaves returning from
the cotton fields. The work was done by a traveling artist, William
Henry Brown, who visited the plantation in the early 1840s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The show, titled ``The Fabric of History: The Cotton Industry in
New Orleans, 1835-1885,'' can be seen Tuesday through Saturday from
10 a.m. to 4:30 p.m., 533 Royal Street, (504) 523-4662. Entry is
free. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frances Frank Marcus &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Setting Sail for San Francisco &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As part of the celebration of the 150th anniversary of the
California Gold Rush, a parade of barques, schooners,
square-riggers and other tall ships from around the world will sail
under the Golden Gate Bridge and into San Francisco Bay on July 2,
beginning at about 1 p.m. It will be one of the largest collections
of tall ships to converge on San Francisco since the Gold Rush,
when a virtual armada bore thousands of miners to California. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The United States Coast Guard training ship Eagle will lead the
parade, which will feature ships from Japan, Ecuador, Colombia,
Canada and Indonesia, as well as other United States tall ships and
historic vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty tall ships, most of them reproductions of 18th- and
19th-century ships, will participate. The majority are training
vessels carrying cadets. The largest ship will be Japan's 361-foot,
four-masted barque, Kaiwo Maru. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ships will dock along San Francisco's waterfront near
Fisherman's Wharf, from Pier 27 to the Hyde Street Pier, and will
be open for free public tours from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. on July 3 and
4. On July 5 some of the ships will participate in a race to Long
Beach, Calif., that will begin 10 miles out to sea and cover 400
miles.
</P>
<P>
   All the ships in the San Francisco parade will be on view to the
public in Long Beach from July 8 to 12 and in San Diego from July
13 to 18. Information: (415) 556-0115. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
