<HEADER>
A7509 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN-COX     05-31 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latest conflict with Chinese to play out in U.S. elections
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Depending which has been in or out, China has long
been a field of political opportunity for both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who lost China?'' was a rallying cry for Republicans riding
the anti-communist wave of the early 1950s. Only a few years later,
John F. Kennedy used the crisis over Quemoy and Matsu, two small
islands between the mainland and Taiwan, to question American
military readiness in the 1960 presidential campaign. (Though
unknown to the American public at the time, that passing emergency
also helped generate the frictions between China and the Soviet
Union which Richard Nixon would later exploit to make his historic
overture to the Chinese.)
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to say what impact last week's release of the Cox
Report on Chinese nuclear espionage will have on next year's
presidential election, but it seems bound to play a central role,
by a kind of centrifugal force of events: Drop a bomb on Belgrade
and it hits the Chinese embassy. Follow the list of names in the
Cox Report _ Wang Jun, Johnny Chung, Charlie Trie _ and they
connect back to the campaign finance scandal.
</P>
<P>
   You can judge a book by its cover _ to a certain extent at least
_ and by its method of delivery. Multiple copies of the
three-volume report, bound in black and printed on glossy paper,
were express-mailed to newsrooms around the country last week.
</P>
<P>
   This departure from the plain-brown style of nearly all
congressional reports, including last year's articles of
impeachment, hints at the political impact which House select
committee chairman Christopher Cox and other Republicans intended
it to have.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion of finger-pointing which has followed the
publication of the report make it more difficult to determine what
real implications the report's findings have for the nation's
military security. An analyst for the Cato Institute, a libertarian
think tank which maintains its independence from both parties, was
critical of the report for its lack of clarity on this question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really uncertain as to what's been stolen, or what's the
impact of this,'' said Ivan Eland, Cato's director of defense
policy studies. ``Even with a worst-case scenario, this needs to be
placed in context.''
</P>
<P>
   In Eland's view, the lapses outlined in the Cox Report do not
represent ``a quantum leap in threat.'' Any breach involving
nuclear weapons is a grave matter, however, and the report's
finding that the leaks go all the way back to the 1970s adds to the
uneasiness.
</P>
<P>
   The assertion by the Chinese government on Monday that the
nuclear secrets are already available on the internet and in
libraries is not terribly comforting, either.
</P>
<P>
   Only weeks after the Chinese government stood by as a mob
surrounded the U.S. embassy in Beijing, chanting ``Death to the
long noses,'' a government spokesman dismissed the Cox Report's
claims that Chinese businessmen and students were used as spies as
``typical racial prejudice.'' The government condemned the
congressional resolution on the anniversary of the Tiananmen
massacre, claiming the Chinese people _ presumably excepting the
Tibetans _ now enjoy ``unprecedentedly extensive human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder the report packs such a political wallop.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
