<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7513 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-PAGERS-COX     05-31 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-PAGERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth Mobility adds pager to portfolio
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth is scheduled to announce today that its
interactive pagers will be sold by the unit that sells wireless
phone service, a move aimed at boosting both.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement between the two BellSouth units offers something
to both: BellSouth Wireless Data's already hot pager will get a
boost from the phone unit's sales force, while BellSouth Mobility
gets another way to make its service stand out in a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The interactive pager is the only truly national service offered
by BellSouth, whose local phone turf is the nine-state Southeastern
region. Unlike one-way pagers that receive messages, the
interactive pager permits the user to type responses that can be
received _ when all goes well _ within seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The BellSouth service competes directly with SkyTel, which is
being purchased by Mississippi-based MCI WorldCom. BellSouth claims
its pagers use a faster technology than SkyTel's.
</P>
<P>
   The interactive pager is marketed by New Jersey-based BellSouth
Wireless Data, mostly through dealers. However, it also will be
offered through PageNet, one of the nation's leading paging
companies, using both companies' names, said John Kampfe, spokesman
for BellSouth Wireless Data.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth Mobility offers wireless phone service through the
Southeast as well as in three other cities. The unit has sometimes
been faulted as a regional player in a matchup against national
players such as Sprint, Nextel and AT&AMP;T. Those companies can offer
lower out-of-town and long-distance rates because _ so the logic
goes _ they can save money by keeping traveling customers on their
own networks.
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth of late has responded to that challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The company now has ``one rate'' plans aimed at high-spending
mobile professionals. BellSouth has also added Portico, ``virtual
assistant'' software that can route and respond to messages.
</P>
<P>
   Kristie Madara, BellSouth Mobility spokeswoman, said the
addition of the pager is aimed at giving the company more services
to offer each customer and is more than just an attempt to give the
service a national presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Portico, it's a great differentiator in the marketplace
where carriers are starting to look alike. I certainly think it
will give us a competitive advantage. It's another product that
meets the needs of a particular group of customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The pager can be purchased for $359 or rented for $20 a month.
The basic service costs $25 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Pagers and wireless phones are seen as providing different
services. BellSouth believes they will sometimes appeal to
different users, while some users will carry both.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things I can deal with without dialing a
phone,'' Madara said. ``Cell phones ringing in a meeting can be
very distracting, but (with an interactive pager) I can type back a
message and nobody in the room even knows I am doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The interactive pager has also been known to let two people in a
meeting send each other messages.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
