<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7514 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIAONE-DIGITALTV-CO     05-31 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIAONE-DIGITALTV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MediaOne rolling out digital TV in Georgia
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MediaOne will begin offering digital television for
the first time today, beginning with a small group of its customers
in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The service, to be called MediaOne Digital NexTV, will be
available to about a third of MediaOne's 95,000 subscribers in Cobb
County. It will offer 222 channels of music, premium movie services
and pay-per-view programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the next step in bringing customers the
products and services they've said they want,'' said Ellen
Filipiak, vice president for MediaOne's Southeast region. ``Our
customers want to control what they're watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is only the second market in which MediaOne, the
nation's third-largest cable operator, has begun to offer digital
television. The service was first rolled out in Detroit last year.
</P>
<P>
   Digital television requires a new network, which MediaOne has
been building in metro Atlanta for years. About 36 percent of the
operator's Atlanta system, which serves 570,000 subscribers, has
been rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving full steam ahead,'' said Filipiak, who added that
the pace of reconstruction will pick up in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The new network offers three next-generation services: digital
television, telephone service and high-speed access to the
Internet. So far, MediaOne has signed up 5,000 telephone customers
and 3,000 for Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   None had yet been offered digital television, which features
sharper pictures and 100-plus new channels. That will begin
changing today.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne has finished installing the first equipment necessary
to send digital television signals. This part of MediaOne's system
already is able to offer telephone service and Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled next to receive digital television service are Clayton
County and parts of the city of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne is in the process of buying Time Warner's Cobb system,
but the deal has not been completed.
</P>
<P>
   NexTV is a choice and is priced higher, at $41.95 per month. For
that, subscribers will receive all 70 regular channels, 40 channels
of music, 40 pay-per-view channels and 72 channels dedicated to
premium movie services such as HBO.
</P>
<P>
   There are, for example, eight different channels of HBO. This
configuration offers subscribers greater choice concerning when to
watch a show on a premium movie channel.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
