<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7518 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-588(2     05-31 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-588(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIVES OF TIANANMEN DEAD CALL FOR CRIMINAL INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM with DAVID CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Ten years after army troops and tanks were used to
smash pro-democracy demonstrations in Tiananmen Square, more than a
hundred relatives of the dead have petitioned the government to
open a criminal investigation of the responsible officials.
</P>
<P>
   Like previous demands for an inquiry into one of modern China's
most traumatic events, this one is certain to be rejected by the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time, the victims' relatives have tried to use
China's nascent legal system for redress. And they see this as the
opening round in a new push for answers to what their documents
call the ``bloody slaughter'' of June 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives, who are working closely with a dissident group
and lawyers abroad, say that if the Chinese legal system fails
them, they will seek an international legal forum, like a U.N.
tribunal or a court in a sympathetic country, that will investigate
the government's actions of June 1989 and assess individual blame.
</P>
<P>
   In two documents handed in to the national prosecutor's office
in the last two weeks, tailored to China's criminal code, the group
asserts that former Premier Li Peng should be investigated as the
``primary suspect'' in the killings. Li _ remembered for his angry
exchanges with students and his televised announcement of martial
law in May 1989 _ is today the No. 2 leader of the ruling Communist
Party and chief of the national Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Several military officers and former Beijing city officials are
also cited for their roles in what the petitions describe as a
planned campaign to shoot students and others, violating criminal
laws against ``intentional killing'' and ``intentional injury.''
</P>
<P>
   The petitions were signed by 105 people who live in China,
including close relatives of people killed in 1989 as well as
several people who were seriously wounded in the army attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the actions of Li Peng and other people
constituted a genuine crime and nothing less,'' said Ding Zilin, a
retired professor whose 17-year-old son was killed the night of
June 3, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ding, a relentless critic of the government over the last
decade and chief organizer of the victims' families, spoke Monday
by telephone from her Beijing apartment on the campus of People's
University. Since early May, she said, the police have not allowed
her or her husband to leave the campus, on threat of immediate
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The new petitions, while repeating demands that Ms. Ding and the
relatives' group have made in previous public appeals, represent
their most formal effort yet to put China's legal system on the
spot over the 1989 killings. But China's courts have never acted
independently in cases that are politically sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   The petitioners' strategy, worked out with lawyers here and in
the United States, is to exhaust domestic legal options as the
first step toward a campaign for an international inquiry into the
events. They have been inspired, for instance, by the Spanish
arrest warrant for Gen. Augusto Pinochet, the former Chilean
dictator, that led to his detention by Britain long after his
alleged crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The victims' group is working closely with a dissident group in
New York, Human Rights in China, which will coordinate the
international legal campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the Tiananmen massacre was a crime against
humanity,'' Xiao Qiang, executive director of Human Rights in
China, said in a telephone interview. ``This is just the first
step,'' he said of the petitions delivered in Beijing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The human rights group plans to release further details on
Tuesday at a news conference in New York.
</P>
<P>
   As corroborating evidence in their appeal, the relatives' group
provided names and details of 155 people who were killed and 65
people who were wounded in the attacks by the army and the police
on June 3 and 4, 1989. ``Not one was engaged in any violent
behavior,'' the group says of those listed. ``They were all
innocent victims of the massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of people who died in the crackdown has never been
disclosed, but it is believed to total several hundred at least.
The new list of victims, though far from complete, is the longest
ever publicly compiled.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party has firmly refused to reconsider its verdict
that the raucous 1989 demonstrations, in which hundreds of
thousands of students and other citizens marched or camped on
Beijing's central square, were a ``counter-revolutionary'' movement
that had to be crushed for the sake of China's stability and
development.
</P>
<P>
   Li, the central target of the new petitions, appears to be
securely in power today, a key spokesman for more conservative
elements in the Communist Party. The group's decision to cite Li
and other living officials as targets for criminal indictment
assures a hostile reaction from the Communist Party and the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Western and Chinese experts believe that the final decision to
use military force to clear students from Tiananmen Square was made
by Deng Xiaoping, the paramount leader who died in 1997, and that
the military operations were directed by Yang Shangkun, who died
last September.
</P>
<P>
   But the new petitions say Li, as premier, bore major
responsibility for the killings because of his role in declaring
martial law, because he ``failed to stop the cruel killings of
civilians,'' and because he ``tried to cover up these crimes,''
praising the army for its achievements in the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the attacks on unarmed civilians ``systematic and
organized,'' the petitions say several military leaders should be
held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   The first petition calling for a criminal inquiry was delivered
on May 17 by Zhang Xianling, 62 and Su Bingxian, 64, both mothers
of young men shot dead on June 4, 1989. They took the petition to
the front gate of the Supreme People's Procuratorate, the agency
that prosecutes crimes. Eventually an official emerged and took the
document, they reported, promising an answer that has not come.
</P>
<P>
   On May 24, the same two women delivered a second document
providing more details of the group's demands to guards at that
same gate.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone Monday, officials in the information
section of the Supreme Procuratorate said they had no knowledge of
the petitions and could not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ding and other organizers of the victims' group know that
they are pushing the authorities to the limit, risking arrest and
prison. Working with exiled dissidents against the interests of the
Communist Party is often declared a major crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since my son died in 1989, there's nothing more that can scare
me,'' Ms. Ding said Monday. ``I do what I choose to do according to
my own conscience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
