<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-MARLINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McGwire quietly returns to South Florida
 &HT;    By Dan Graziano
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ So, Mark McGwire and the St. Louis
Cardinals come to town today. Remember the last time that happened?
It was last September when McGwire electrified South Florida and
all of baseball by hitting his 56th, 57th, 58th and 59th home runs
of the season in two games at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The sold-out stadium was rocking, and fans were blissfully
risking their health by diving all over (and under) the outfield
tarps to retrieve the precious home-run balls.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that? Well, this isn't going to be quite the same.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, McGwire played, despite missing Saturday's game in Chicago
after being hospitalized for treatment of a staph infection in his
right leg. But, attendance figures for the four games are expected
to be in the 20,000s _ good compared to the Marlins' typical
weeknights, but nothing approaching the sold-out fiestas of last
season. And they won't be taking the tarps off the upper-deck seats
in left field.
</P>
<P>
   They have nearly sold out the left-field club seats, which is
the location from which the Marlins' radio broadcasters will call
the game. They've sectioned off part of the section in left and are
calling it ``Home Run Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any giveaways, but we are highlighting the fact
that Mark McGwire will be coming to town for his only visit of the
season,'' said Mark Geddis, director of marketing communications.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the Marlins will show a short video
presentation in tribute to McGwire's accomplishments here last
season.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has played only six games at Pro Player Stadium in his
career, but he's hit six home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of guys in baseball who have that threat, but
their home runs don't go 700 feet,'' Marlins interim manager Fredi
Gonzalez said. ``If they're solo home runs, I wouldn't mind
watching a couple. If we win 10-2 and he hits two solo homers,
that's fine.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Graziano writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
