u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-DROUGHT-ART-57     05-31 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DROUGHT-ART-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO DECLARES 10 PARCHED STATES DISASTER AREAS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORREON, Mexico _ Maria Torres Garcia turned on a faucet in her
home one recent morning and watched a little trickle run into the
bucket she uses to collect water during the few hours a day when
water still flows into homes here.
</P>
<P>
   Later the same day, Mrs. Torres raised her umbrella _ to shield
against the sun, since it has not rained in Torreon since last
August _ and trudged a mile or so away to the Nazas River _
actually to its parched bed, since the water dried up completely in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   There, Ms. Torres joined a throng of 6,000 other Roman Catholics
who gathered to pray for relief from a withering drought that is
killing livestock, draining reservoirs and forcing hundreds of
towns across northern Mexico to limit their consumption of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father, grant to us and to our fields the water we need,''
Mrs. Torres said, repeating with thousands of others a common
prayer led by Archbishop Jose Trinidad Medel Perez, who presided
over the Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In Torreon, a city in Coahuila state, 600 miles north of the
capital, and all across the country's arid north, Mexicans have
been praying for rain. Late last week, the federal government
declared 10 northern states, covering about half the country,
disaster zones because of the drought.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have explained the mounting water shortage as one of
the vagaries of nature, since for several years rainfall has been
lower than usual in northern Mexico. But Torreon residents, and
several experts as well, contend that deforestation, wasteful
irrigation and water-intensive industrial processes ill-suited to
an arid region, have worsened the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Torreon faces Gomez Palacio, in the state of Durango, across the
Nazas River. Together with Lerdo, Durango, the cities form a single
metropolis of 1 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Jose Gomez, the manager of Torreon's municipal water
system, said that punching thousands of deep wells in the region to
irrigate fields of alfalfa and other cattle-feed crops has consumed
so much water since the 1950s that the aquifers under Torreon have
dropped hundreds of feet. The water table fell 30 feet just in the
last year, Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico's water shortage is worsening because of bad
policies,'' he said in an interview during a regional water
conference, held in a Torreon hotel hours before the evening Mass
at the Nazas River. ``The water's been wasted. That's why we have a
crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference brought state and municipal officials from
Durango, Coahuila and Zacatecas states together with ranchers and
businessmen to discuss strategies for confronting the water crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The conference reflected an increasing sense of urgency among
local and federal officials about the severity of the country's
water problem. Some prominent business leaders and
environmentalists have begun to criticize the distorted utility
price structures that encourage the waste of water and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   During the water conference, Ulises Adame de Leon, Durango's
minister of agriculture, described uncontrolled logging that he
said was leveling forests all across Mexico's mountainous northern
watersheds, which act as funnels to replenish the region's
underground aquifers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine the destruction,'' Adame said. ``Hundreds of
trucks are carrying logs out of those mountains every day. If we
don't act, the cutting is going to turn our watershed into a desert
in 10 years.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sen. Adolfo Aguilar Zinser, from Mexico's Green Party, has been
speaking out about the dangers of continuing deforestation and its
relation to the water scarcity.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, federal officials have issued repeated emergency
declarations about the drought up north, which has become entangled
in the politics of an emerging presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his last acts as interior minister before resigning to
seek the presidential nomination of Mexico's governing party,
Francisco Labastida Ochoa signed proclamations declaring the states
of Durango, Coahuila, Chihuahua, Sinaloa and Sonora to be disaster
areas.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition parties cried foul because the governors of all
five states are from the governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party, while other states suffering from drought but governed by
opposition parties were not included.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Ministry said the five states were extended
disaster aid first because they had requested it first. But after
days of criticism, the Interior Ministry gave disaster aid to
Zacatecas, whose governor belongs to the opposition Party of the
Democratic Revolution, as well as to San Luis Potosi, also led by
the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they made a political mistake and then corrected
themselves,'' Ricardo Monreal, the Zacatecas governor, said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Later last week, the Interior Ministry also declared the states
of Baja California Sur and Nuevo Leon, both governed by the
opposition, and Tamaulipas, led by the governing party, to be
disaster zones. The federal aid is intended to help farmers keep
herds of cattle and sheep alive by providing forage, and to help
the states improve their conservation infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   But some Torreon residents took matters into their own hands. In
one working-class neighborhood where water runs from household taps
only from about 5 a.m. to 9 a.m. weekdays, residents became
irritated over the apparent waste of water by a factory that washes
enormous amounts of denim fabric used in making jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Until new drainage pipes were installed recently, the factory's
used water ran through an open channel, where it was visible to
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a river of water, running blue,'' said Rogelio Garcia
Triana, a sign maker who lives near the factory, and who also
attended the open-air Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood residents surrounded the plant recently in an
attempt to close it down, but dispersed after police arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think it's fair for a plant to waste water when our city
is so dry?'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   At the makeshift altar, a priest from a Torreon parish, the Rev.
Manuel Chavez, urged worshippers not only to issue a plea for
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's also ask forgiveness for what we've done to a world that
was once perfect,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
