<HEADER>
A7522 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-TAX-CUT-COX     05-31 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-TAX-CUT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vouchers debate halts vote on tax-cut package
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State lawmakers appeared well on their way to
approving about $2 billion in tax cuts Sunday until the dreaded
``voucher'' word arose, grinding progress to a halt in the House
and Senate, which both faced a midnight deadline to complete
substantive work on proposed laws.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats opposed to using tax-funded vouchers for private
school education late Sunday said they believed that a tax credit
proposal added to a bill meant to give $506 million in business and
tax credits was an attempt to create a voucher-type program.
Vouchers for private school tuition have been a heated topic in the
Legislature this year. Opponents have blocked all attempts to
attach such programs to several proposals this year and killed two
voucher-program bills in House and Senate committees.
</P>
<P>
   Senate lawmakers earlier Sunday approved the business and sales
tax-cut bill without debate on the voucher issue. But officials
from one Senate office said the same language opposed by House
Democrats was reviewed and judged not to create a voucher program.
Senate lawmakers, however, briefly stalled their debate on a $3.9
billion school finance proposal, including local school property
tax cuts, teacher pay raises and new education spending, to await
House action on the business and sales tax-cut bill. They later
approved the education bill, sending it to the governor, who is
expected to sign it into law.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Dunnam, D-Waco, said he supports the other programs in
the tax-cutting measure known as Senate Bill 441. But he said he's
opposed to any program that allows public money to go to private
schools. The proposal before the House was a House-Senate
compromise reached Friday on plans to cut taxes by $506 million
over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is an end-run to vouchers,'' Dunnam said.
</P>
<P>
   With Monday reserved for minor and technical adjustments to
already-passed bills, lawmakers could either vote for Senate Bill
441 or let it die at their midnight deadline Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Paul Sadler, D-Henderson, chairman of the House Education
Committee, did not allow a vote on a voucher bill in his committee
this session. He tried Sunday night to convince fellow lawmakers
that the proposed tax credit for before- and after-school programs
did not amount to publicly paid private school educations.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, Texas corporations could get tax credits for
donations made to various institutions that offer before- and
after-school programs. The donations could be used for constructing
or remodeling a building for the program; purchasing equipment,
supplies and food for the program; or operating the program,
including administrative and staff costs.
</P>
<P>
   Voucher opponents, including Rep. Sylvester Turner, D-Houston,
said the program may not require the state to give up tax income
for private school tuition, but ``these tax credits do cover
everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner said private schools could be among those institutions to
which corporations could donate money and get tax credits. He added
the state indirectly would be subsidizing the cost of private
school costs, allowing those schools to reduce tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said donations to private schools could be eligible for
the tax credits. But he added that the building, equipment,
supplies and other costs paid by the donations would primarily have
to go to the before- and after-school programs in order to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it is not is a voucher for tuition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   in addition to the tax credit for before- and after-school
programs, the bill would give corporations tax credits for research
and development costs; capital investments and job creation in
counties with high unemployment and low per-capita income; and
investments in their employees' child-care costs. The bill also
would exempt from the state business franchise tax any corporation
that makes less than $150,000 in gross annual income. Only
corporations pay the franchise tax.
</P>
<P>
   While the education and tax bills had promised to be the
crowning jewels of the 1999 session, lawmakers passed scores of
other legislation Sunday as well. They included:
</P>
<P>
   _Requiring candidates and political action committees to file
campaign finance reports electronically.
</P>
<P>
   _Allowing the Texas Department of Criminal Justice to track some
repeat sex offenders after their release from prison. The agency
would identify the offenders who pose the greatest risk and require
them to wear electronic tracking devices and attend treatment
programs.
</P>
<P>
   _Requiring governments to prove a compelling interest to enforce
laws that would limit the practice of religion. The Texas Religious
Freedom Restoration Act has been a priority for Bush, who is
expected to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   _Requiring public school students to take more state
standardized tests and pass comprehensive exams to get a diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Austin city officials were relieved by the death of several
proposals to restrict its land development rules. One proposal
killed was Senate Bill 938, filed by Sen. Ken Armbrister,
D-Victoria, which would have prevented Austin from enforcing its
water-quality rules in its extraterritorial jurisdiction in Hays
County.
</P>
<P>
   The other bill, by Rep. Harold Dutton, D-Houston, would have
required a city to have identical water-quality rules in every part
of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Juan B. Elizondo Jr. writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
