<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7523 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRITICS-NOTEBOOK-2TAK     05-31 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRITICS-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT EXTRA MUSICAL INGREDIENT, FRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The amateur soprano has reasons to fear Beethoven's
Missa Solemnis. Professional choristers don't take it lightly
either. It is the inner segments _the Gloria, the Credo and parts
of the Sanctus _ that make palms sweat and throats turn dry. The
high Bs, B flats, As and Gs keep coming, incessant, like battering
rams.
</P>
<P>
   The height is manageable, for a time. Sopranos by definition
live a good part of their lives above the G-clef staff. It is the
relentlessness and the duration of these attacks. Facing difficulty
like this comes in stages, much like the familiar ones for facing
death: fear, disbelief, anger, acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, in most amateur performances of the Missa Solemnis I
have heard, sopranos get the hard parts right and do less well
elsewhere. It is hard to explain, but perhaps fright unleashes a
new level of psychic energy, extruding the best from us in a
survive-or-die environment.
</P>
<P>
   Beethoven was deaf as a post when he wrote the Missa Solemnis,
but like any complete musician, he heard inside his head what he
was writing on paper. The high-flying passages are just one item in
a catalog of daunting peculiarities.
</P>
<P>
   There are especially the Missa's fugues, spit out at great
speeds in twisted, dense, crossing lines. Needed is a a kind of
breathless, teeth-grinding vigilance: one slip, and derailment is
upon you.
</P>
<P>
   At last Thursday's performance of the Missa Solemnis at Avery
Fisher Hall, Kurt Masur had all the virtuosity he needed. The New
York Philharmonic gleamed; the New York Choral Artists and the
American Boychoir knocked down one scary passage after another. It
was very impressive and almost too easy. This is not easy music.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Beethoven make things so hard for the rest of us? Mozart
and Liszt wrote music that likes to be played, though both are
difficult in their separate ways. One explanation says that
Beethoven was mad (which he must have been). Another is that he
didn't care (he said as much, famously, to a complaining violinist
about another piece): Beethoven wanted an effect, and it was up to
the performer to realize it.
</P>
<P>
   Another answer is that deafness had so isolated him from the
tactile and practical world of performing that the concerns of the
musician became remote from his thoughts. Composers in fact often
hear their music faster than performers do, probably because for
them the connection of thought to sound is direct, without the
middlemen that the listener requires: no violins to scrape, pianos
to pound or high notes to attack.
</P>
<P>
   A machine on the drawing board runs unimpeded. In motion,
friction comes into play. It slows things down.
</P>
<P>
   This might be why the metronome speeds that Beethoven later
attached to his pieces seem fast to us, so fast that the composer's
metronome has been accused of malfunction. Or are these tempos what
he really wanted? The better we get at playing the string quartets,
for example, the more quartet players argue for the latter, but we
won't ever really know.
</P>
<P>
   The more paranoid among us say that Beethoven knew precisely
what he was doing and that fear and physical strain were calculated
parts of the musical message. It happens elsewhere in his later
music, one example being the finale of the ``Hammerklavier'' Piano
Sonata, written five years earlier than the Missa Solemnis.
</P>
<P>
   So great is the effort to negotiate this monster of a movement
that palpable effort, even among well-developed piano virtuosos,
becomes part of the musical experience.
</P>
<P>
   It is the well-established struggle factor that makes
performances by people like Maurizio Pollini somehow inauthentic.
Pollini sails through the difficulties of the ``Hammerklavier''
with so little perspiration and apparent apprehension that we
barely recognize the music as Beethoven's.
</P>
<P>
   Impossibility has a history in the annals of musical
performance. One of the more famous examples is the Tchaikovsky
Violin Concerto, which was declared unplayable by those who tried
it first. ``Not possible,'' said the bassoonist first faced with
the nervous, whining opening of Stravinsky's ``Sacre du
Printemps.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are those who think that Brahms left out some of the
tortuous inner detail of his B Flat Piano Concerto when he played
the earliest performances. (Pianists still do, but won't admit it.)
Rubinstein adored the piano music of Albeniz and with his cleverly
self-deprecating charm didn't mind confessing that some of the
composer's bizarre complications were left on the cutting room
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet unplayability has less to do with the limits of human hands,
arms, legs, mouths and throats than it does with old cultures
meeting new ones. Musicians trained in Eurocentric conservatories
are simply not prepared for the fanatical, repetitive exactitude of
some Minimalist music.
</P>
<P>
   European music gives, bends, stretches and contracts according
to gravitational pulls of harmonic change; a lot of contemporary
music does not.
</P>
<P>
   Liszt and Mozart embrace what traditional training teaches us
and then challenge its limits. Liszt brooks not the slightest
blemish in phrasing; Mozart raises Czerny, Hanon and the dreary
tradition of scales and arpeggios to sublime heights.
</P>
<P>
   Tchaikovsky and Stravinsky heard new sounds within them and had
to go against received wisdom. Among their first jobs was to
persuade musicians that their methods were not as unnatural as they
seemed.
</P>
<P>
   And anyone who has wrestled with the physical problems of music
making, and taught others ways of dealing with them, knows that
persuasion is the operative noun. The conquering virtuoso, bulging
with muscle, is a dangerous image.
</P>
<P>
   If we are wise, we remember Plato's myth of creation, in which
the universe is fashioned not by fiat or force but by seducing the
elements of chaos. In much the same way, we woo the muscles,
tendons or vocal cords. We comfort them, soothe their anxieties and
explain.
</P>
<P>
   I wish that ``we'' were more inclusive. How else can one explain
the explosion of on-the-job injuries suffered by musicians of every
kind? Learning by brute will has done terrible things not only to
the quality of the music produced but also to the minds and bodies
of those who are producing it. And it is practiced everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Other impossibilities turn out to be seductive acts by
persuasive composers. Debussy, that most subtle of score-writers,
often writes piano passages on three staves instead of the usual
two, placing the notes so far apart that two hands can't possibly
reach all of them.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, of course, is the sustaining pedal. With it can
come the lingering, echoing wash of sound from keys no longer
touched.
</P>
<P>
   But Debussy does not just tell you to use the pedal; a few of
those electrocardiogram-like squiggles placed underneath could do
that. He teaches you. First lesson: Musical scores are not
operator's manuals with instructions about what body part to put
where. Scores are visual maps of what the composer wants people to
hear. Second lesson: Think for yourself and listen. Are you hearing
as you play what the map says?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some impossibilities are simply impossible. One finds
them in freshman conservatory classes where aspiring composers
still don't know what particular instruments can and cannot do.
Beethoven, a marvelous orchestrator in his earlier years, seems
sometimes to have miscalculated in later music. Those ``mistakes''
are the subject of many a conductor's furtive editing.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimate unplayability is offered by Schumann, who writes on one
page ``as fast as possible'' and on the next ``faster.'' Don't ask
me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
