<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7535 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAIL-TRAFFIC-ART-2NDT     05-31 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIL-TRAFFIC-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: this properly.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The change was a long time coming. Back in 1976, Congress, with
much fanfare, created the government-controlled Consolidated Rail
Corp. out of the bankrupt Penn Central Railroad and five other
struggling lines in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1980s _ after a huge infusion of public funds to
replace or rebuild its aging locomotives, rolling stock and track,
over $7 billion all told, and repeated rounds of cost cutting and
job cuts _ the railroad showed stirrings of life.
</P>
<P>
   In this period, various attempts were made to sell Conrail,
either to a private company or to the public. Norfolk Southern was
once close to a deal, but it lost out when Conrail's unions and
managers fought back and forced a sale through a public offering.
</P>
<P>
   The government's 85 percent stake was finally sold to the public
in March 1987 for $1.9 billion, while its unions kept 15 percent.
Since then, the railroad and its shareholders have prospered, with
hefty profits and a sharply rising stock price. It has been a major
force in getting shippers to send their freight on intermodal
trains _ which carry containers or easily transferable truck
trailers _ rather than trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Thus CSX and Norfolk Southern will be dividing up a robust
competitor, one that has played a big role in helping sustain some
basic industries in the Northeast economy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A major goal of shippers and other groups in the Northeast was
to have two railroads compete for Conrail's customers, and the
breakup achieves that.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz Russell, director of policy and planning for the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey, said his agency had favored
dividing Conrail to insure ``that the region not end up with
another monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the agency and other groups were also able to persuade
both railroads to help revive some rail service in the various
marine terminals in the port of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there is practically no way to get goods across New
York Harbor except by truck or barge. A short line called the New
York Cross Harbor railroad has reached an agreement with Norfolk
Southern to help it build up the use of barges, which will move
containers, taken from rail cars, between the Greenville yards in
Jersey City and the Red Hook section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Also, some tracks on Staten Island's North Shore Line are being
restored with the help of the New York City Economic Development
Corp. This will enable containers to be moved by rail, by both
railroads, between New Jersey and docks in Staten Island. It will
also link the docks with trains that can go anywhere in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The New York region now lags behind other major cities and ports
in moving freight by rail. But these changes, Russell said, will
help change that. Huge containers now moved by truck will soon be
carried by rail, easing road congestion and lowering costs.
</P>
<P>
   Some shippers have already seen their rates fall by about 5
percent, he added, as the two railroads compete to sign up
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, of CSX, estimated that of Conrail's $3.5 billion in annual
revenues, about $1 billion came from what the railroads term
``jump-ball customers'' _ which, because of track layout, could
theoretically be served by either railroad.
</P>
<P>
   The two rivals have been fast off the mark. Between them, he
estimated, their sales staffs have signed up shippers representing
about 80 percent of that $1 billion by offering discounts of
roughly 6 percent to 8 percent. And in the push to compete with
trucking, many others could get discounts, too.
</P>
<P>
   Even after such rate cuts, he said, the railroads will be able
to turn a profit. That would be good news for stockholders, since
both railroads added greatly to their debt load to buy Conrail. CSX
stock is roughly where it was two years ago, while Norfolk Southern
shares are up slightly. CSX closed at $46.9375 on Friday, and
Norfolk Southern closed at $32.875.
</P>
<P>
   One big change is that with more extensive track networks, both
railroads will offer more routes on which a single train can make
the whole journey _ from, say, Atlanta to Chicago or Bangor, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   While containers generally arrive about a day later by rail than
if they were moved by truck, the rates offered by railroads are
about 15 percent lower, creating a strong incentive to switch.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Conrail did provide some competition for trucks, in
many cases ``there will be competitive service where none existed
before,'' said Tom Finkbiner, the vice president for intermodal
trains for Norfolk Southern.
</P>
<P>
   There has been little outcry from truckers, and some, seeing
rate cuts as inevitable, are even cooperating with railroads.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, everyone has been poised for Tuesday, when one of the
most complex transitions in railroad history will take place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're satisfied that they have done a superhuman effort of
planning,'' Rastatter of the transportation trade group said.
``We're waiting with our fingers crossed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
