<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-ELECT-NYT &LR;      05-31 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL IN SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ There was a last-gasp volley of
election salvos on Sunday night, the closest that South Africa's
second post-apartheid election campaign has come to a debate.
</P>
<P>
   The government-owned television network, which controls three of
the country's five stations, tried to set up a debate. But
President Nelson Mandela's heir apparent, Thabo Mbeki, declined to
take part.
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing the governing African National Congress
likely to win the vote on Wednesday in a landslide, Mbeki no doubt
saw little need. Instead, the network gathered representatives of
five parties for what turned out to be a raucous discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki's stand-in as the party's representative, Essop Pahad,
faced tough questioning on the economy, crime and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Tony Leon, the fast-talking leader of the liberal
Democratic Party, who showed off the quick tongue for which he is
known. On the subject of corruption, he said, the ANC has failed to
show much leadership. ``Under this government,'' he said, ``obeying
the law looks like a second option.''
</P>
<P>
   Pahad shot back, albeit a bit feebly, ``One can never take that
man seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heavyweight: Mandela
</P>
<P>
   Though Mbeki has been an energetic campaigner, crisscrossing the
country highlighting his party's achievements, it often seems that
it is the 80-year-old Mandela who is assigned the tougher
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela has not hesitated to talk to angry white farmers who
have been plagued by crime, traditional leaders who feel ignored
and mixed-race voters, who have never felt that the ANC had their
interests at heart.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an often grueling pace, Mandela seems to revel in his
campaigning, often recalling his humble background and always
urging South Africans to unite behind his party.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, at a shopping center in the mixed-race neighborhood
of Eldorado Park outside Johannesburg, he was busy reminding
potential voters of all the mixed-race people in the Cabinet and in
other major posts when his microphone went dead.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, he pressed on. ``You can hear me,'' he told the
crowd. ``I used to shout at the sheep to get them to come home.''
</P>
<P>
   A Sly Poster
</P>
<P>
   Although South Africa has many advertising agencies that compete
to produce witty poster and magazine ads, the advertising for this
election has been stultifyingly dull. Most posters have
straightforward, rather lumpish slogans like ``Vote ANC'' or
``Fight Back _ Vote DP'' or ``Fight Crime Now _ Vote IFP.''
</P>
<P>
   The exception has been the National Party, which ran this
country for 47 years and still has a formidable campaign machinery.
Its posters change frequently. And some are not subtle: ``Hang
Murderers and Rapists _ Vote NP'' reminds voters that the party
favors the return of the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But its slyest poster has been simple: ``Mugabe Has
Two-Thirds,'' a reference to the ANC's desire to win a two-thirds
majority in Parliament. The slogan counts on the voters' knowing
that President Robert Mugabe of neighboring Zimbabwe, once the
widely admired leader of a liberation movement, has become a
virtual dictator over a riot-torn country on the edge of
bankruptcy. Mugabe's party has 147 parliamentary seats out of 150.
</P>
<P>
   A Neighborhood's Hope
</P>
<P>
   The Greenfields neighborhood on the outskirts of Johannesburg
was once a sign of all that has been accomplished by the ANC. The
neighborhood did not even exist in 1994, when the first multi-race
national elections were held. Now, what was once a bleak hillside
is dotted with neat rows of modest pastel-colored homes.
</P>
<P>
   But look closely, and some of the new houses have already been
burned out. Installation of electricity and running water have
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The area has become a casualty of the political campaign. The
governing party's supporters have clashed there with supporters of
the new United Democratic Movement, started by Bantu Holomisa, a
former ANC official who was expelled for insubordination. Only last
week, a police officer patrolling the area was killed by sniper
fire.
</P>
<P>
   So far, more than 40 ANC supporters from Greenfields have taken
refuge in three tiny rooms at the back of a police station several
miles away. In one room no bigger than a sauna, 19 women and
children sleep piled up on the floor. Their stacked blankets reach
to the ceiling during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many of the displaced feel they are better off than they
were before the 1994 elections. At least now, they own homes. Most
believe fervently that the ANC will take care of them when the
elections are over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, my house _ the doors and windows have been ripped
out,'' said Nkululekao Duka, 32, who before the last elections was
living in a squatter camp. ``But they have promised they will put
security there. They will solve the problem. I believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   A Lesson in Soweto
</P>
<P>
   The students at Anchor High School in Soweto were gathered last
week in the auditorium _ a graffiti-filled room with a peeling
linoleum floor, broken windows and only a handful of chairs _ for
voter education.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the students are well into their 20s. In the years
leading up to 1994, Soweto was in many ways ground zero for the
liberation struggle _ and youngsters, often at the forefront of the
movement, missed out on school.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are back. But the schools are a mess. There are no
textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing about where to get his identification papers and
how he should go to hear what the candidates had to say, Freddy
Tebogo, 23, walked away with a shrug. ``They say, `Youth, you must
vote,''' he said, ``but then they give us nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   First World or Third?
</P>
<P>
   In a shopping mall in Johannesburg, Tony Leon was weaving his
way through the crowds, asking for votes, shaking hands, engaging
in impromptu debates over the merits of the death penalty and, of
course, admiring babies.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign workers walked behind him, stuffing Democratic Party
pamphlets into hands already busy with shopping bags. In short, it
could have been a campaign stop almost anywhere in America.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the vote-getting looks like this. South Africa is a
country that is both First World and Third World.
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, Senzo Mchunu, the deputy secretary for the ANC
in the province of KwaZulu/Natal, was standing in a field in the
remote village of Ndlangubo waiting for a plane to fly overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get to places like this can be very difficult for our
campaigners,'' Mchunu said. ``Some of the people around here, if
they see campaigners, they are very suspicious. They think, `Ah,
they are here to take our land or our wives.'''
</P>
<P>
   So for three days the party conducted a sort of crop-dusting
operation in which a small plane swooped in on clusters of huts to
unload thousands of pamphlets.
</P>
<P>
   How effective the tactic was is unclear. Many of the villagers
who came to greet Mchunu while he waited said they could not read.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-48     05-31 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS BOMBING CONTINUES, INDIA AGREES TO TALKS WITH PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(kd) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Even as India continued bombing what it calls
a Pakistani-sponsored band of 700 guerrillas occupying a frigid
swath of Indian territory, Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee
Monday agreed to hold talks with Pakistan about this ``warlike
situation'' in the contested state of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The talks, which are yet to be scheduled, will take place in an
atmosphere of deepening mistrust between two bitter adversaries,
who conducted tit-for-tat nuclear tests a year ago and matching
tests of missiles able to carry nuclear warheads in April.
</P>
<P>
   On India's side, the mistrust has become very personal.
</P>
<P>
   At the invitation of Pakistan's prime minister, Nawaz Sharif,
Vajpayee in February took the inaugural ride on a new bus service
connecting New Delhi and Lahore, Pakistan. The two men embraced and
promised to seek solutions to the issues that divide them,
including the status of Kashmir, which India claims as one of its
states and whose people Pakistan says should be allowed to decide
whether to join India or Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Monday, Vajpayee recalled his bus trip to Lahore in
describing his sense of betrayal now. As the head of the Hindu
nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, which has been hawkish on
India's relationship with Pakistan, Vajpayee's hand of friendship
to Pakistan had been seen here as a sign of hope that decades of
hostility might finally ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started the bus service to Lahore, it was to improve
relations,'' Vajpayee said. ``I went as an emissary of peace. I
have told the Pakistani leadership that it seems that while I
talked peace with you, you were preparing to attack our borders. We
still believe in peace, but you cannot clap with one hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians and Pakistanis have such diametrically opposed
viewpoints it is difficult to see how talks between their foreign
ministers here in New Delhi will produce any convergence.
</P>
<P>
   Where the Indians see Pakistan-backed terrorists grabbing Indian
territory, the Pakistanis say they see indigenous Kashmiri freedom
fighters seeking their right of self determination, with no
financial support from Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   And just as adamantly as India has accused Pakistan of
committing an act of aggression against India, Pakistan has charged
India with provoking tensions by using air power in Kashmir so
close to the heavily fortified cease-fire line.
</P>
<P>
   Tariq Altaf, a spokesman of Pakistan's Foreign Office, said
Monday that Pakistan has asked India to stop the air raids and to
agree to neutral monitors or U.N. observers at the cease-fire line,
known as the line of control, which divides Indian and
Pakistan-occupied portions of Kashmir. These are all steps that
India has ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret that India continues to obstruct all moves aimed at
peace and defusing tension at the line of control,'' Altaf said
Monday in Islamabad.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pakistani officials have said Pakistan will protect its borders.
Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad on Sunday told The News, an
English-language daily in Pakistan, ``We will not hesitate to use
any weapon in our arsenal to defend our territorial integrity'' _ a
fearsome statement from a new nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
   Altaf said Monday that Ahmad had not meant to suggest that
Pakistan would use nuclear weapons, only that Pakistan would not
hesitate to defend itself as it did when it shot down two Indian
jet fighters that crossed over the cease-fire line into
Pakistan-held Kashmir on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   India maintains that one of the jet pilots accidentally strayed
across the line after developing engine trouble, while the other
pilot was just trying to help his comrade. India accused Pakistan
of murdering one of the pilots with gunshots to the head and heart
_ a charge Altaf called ``absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that the conflict over Kashmir could turn into a wider
war, the United States and the United Nations, among others, have
encouraged India and Pakistan to seek ways to calm things down.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the two nations are clearly talking past each
other. Pakistan, which proposed the talks, has asked for measures
that India has said are not even on the table _ stopping the air
raids, or agreeing to a role for the United Nations in settling the
Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee said Monday that while India was prepared to meet with
Pakistan, India's determination to drive out the guerrillas hiding
in the rugged Himalayan mountains on the Indian side of the
cease-fire line was non-negotiable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
