<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7540 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARE-INTERVIEW-ART-2T     05-31 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARE-INTERVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYWRIGHT DAVID HARE TAKES ROLES OF PERFORMER AND REPORTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He came upon the notion of a monologue about Israel,
David Hare explained, when it became clear to him that the Holy
Land far exceeded the possibilities of conventional fiction. It is
a perception that has only been reinforced by what has happened
since he took his one-man play, ``Via Dolorosa,'' onto Broadway,
including the stunning defeat of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The thread of the play, more a lecture by a thoughtful British
intellectual, is a lament for Yitzhak Rabin, a survey of the land
of Israel at the moment when its course is abruptly changed. So the
election four years later of Rabin's hand-picked protege, Ehud
Barak, amounted to a historical reversal, an event with such
dramatic force that Hare was stunned by the thin American
television coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes historically clear that the intention of the
Israeli people was to go in the direction that Yitzhak Rabin took
them, that they'd been in a waiting room for four years,'' he said.
``There's a feeling now that Barak will resume the direction Israel
was going in the early 1990s, that there has been a needless
delay.''
</P>
<P>
   If David Hare the reporter watched in awe, David Hare the
playwright was a bit uneasy. The play, after all, is about a
specific time, and with the election that moment was now history.
The burst of press publicity only made the audiences more informed,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made no accommodation to any event since I wrote the
play,'' he said. ``Yes, it's a piece of journalism: to use that
awful phrase, a snapshot. But it's about profounder themes, themes
of the human soul. So it wasn't necessary every time to change the
detail.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to explore these themes through a straight, direct
report, stripped of any theatrical technique, was really a process
of elimination. Hare originally set off for Israel on an assignment
to write about memories of the British mandate, but aside from the
scarcity of these, he arrived at the moment when the assassination
of Rabin rudely lifted the curtain on all the profound conflicts
and drama of the country. Stagecraft simply seemed redundant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came back with a simple journalistic zeal to say this isn't
what you think it's like, it's like something else. And that
excitement _ the reporter's excitement of `You may think you know
about this, but you don't' _ is what carried me through,'' Hare
said in a conversation at his New York pied-a-terre, a spacious
loft in the East Village.
</P>
<P>
   There is something suspect, albeit pleasing to a reporter's ear,
when the best-represented playwright on Broadway finds there are
themes that defy his art, subjects to which only journalism can do
justice. Yet anybody who has been in Israel knows it is a place
that wrenches the soul in a way fiction simply cannot.
</P>
<P>
   There is the overwhelming presence of religion, to which nobody
reacts in the same way. There are the conflicts, in which nobody
can remain neutral. There is the beauty, the sun, the desert, the
danger, and the extraordinary compactness of the place, which
prevent even momentary escape. This is stuff that begs to be told
as it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a feeling that I didn't want it to be, as it were,
conventional fiction,'' Hare said. ``And the minute I thought about
scenes of enactment, I became depressed because I knew that they
would be acted by English Jewish actors who would bear no
relationship to Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israelis are not, they really are not, like Jews who've been
living in North London for 30 years or 40 years. And the
Palestinians would have to be played by, you know, an Egyptian
actor, maybe a light-skinned Pakistani, maybe if we were lucky a
Lebanese, you know. And they would not be anything like the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as if the more important the subject, the more
gratuitous the conventional approaches of fiction seem. And, you
know, in my view the greatest writer about the Holocaust was Primo
Levi. It's barely fiction at all. I don't mean there isn't art.
There is immense art, and there is immense imagination. But finally
Levi's claim to greatness is that you believe that it is true, and
that he's managed to encompass every aspect of it by the greatness
of his imagination. For what he's bringing you is something you
believe to be the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Hare first played with the idea of having a real Israeli and a
real Palestinian join him onstage to present their separate
versions of reality alongside his own. But then he realized that
even this attempt to reduce the story to its elemental components
would be a lie, because for a Palestinian writer even to step on
the same stage with an Israeli would be to imply a rapprochement
that does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thus in the end Hare is alone on the stage of the Booth Theater,
in slacks and white shirt-sleeves, a somewhat awkward and slightly
bemused Briton talking about his visit to Israel. No plot, no
intermission, no actors, no dialogue, no costumes: nothing at all
between the storyteller and his audience except the footlights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pushing Broadway as far as it can be pushed,'' Hare said
with a dollop of pride. And it is a push that Lincoln Center
Theater, producer of the play, might not have risked with a lesser
playwright than Hare, who has had two other shows on Broadway this
season, ``Amy's View'' and ``The Blue Room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand before you as the reporter, and you have to decide
whether I'm an honest reporter or not,'' he said. ``And if you're
convinced that I am honest, then I think that you will listen to me
in a way that you wouldn't have listened to a fiction where scenes
are made. Does that make sense?''
</P>
<P>
   It does make sense to a reporter. But Israel arouses such
passions that simple honesty is not always enough to avoid
nastiness. There is a story Henry A. Kissinger tells about his
first meeting with Golda Meir, by then the former prime minister of
Israel, at which she told him that she expected the United States
to be evenhanded in the Middle East. ``She said that meant we had
to agree 100 percent with Israel,'' Kissinger continues. ``At the
time I thought she was kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   Hare was in Israel long enough to understand that, and one of
his more powerful passages is his meeting with American settlers in
the West Bank, to whom he assigns the names Danny and Sarah Weiss,
``whose American-type home is littered with Delta timetables and
yesterday's copy of The New York Times.'' It is here that Hare
comes face to face with the core of Jewish zealotry, the immutable
belief that the lands of Judaea and Samaria are the God-given
property of the Jews, and only the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few places where my antagonisms or my sympathies
show, and plainly the settlers were, for me, a disturbing people to
meet, because to live as they seemed to, or as they pretend to,
with no conception of the future, is a very peculiar way to live,''
Hare said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet like so many other outsiders who have listened to the
impassioned arguments of the settlers, he cannot dismiss them:
``One of the most powerful lines to me in the play is when Sarah
says, unless we stay here, we have no chance at all. I'm not just
talking about the Holocaust, but you will find in every moment in
Jewish history whenever there's a moment of safety, persecution
started again. And that is a very difficult argument to deal with,
isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Inescapably the play has had some minor disruptions during
performances _ walkouts, loud comments and the like _ but not on
the scale that Hare or the producers feared. He recalled a fax he
received from Salman Rushdie asking whether Hare really planned to
stage the play in New York. ``And he said this wonderful thing, he
said being a persecuted writer isn't all it's cracked up to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not frightened about scrutiny,'' Hare said. ``I've thought
quite long and hard about what I want to say in this play. And if
it means that every single sentiment that I produce is put minutely
under an ideological microscope, that's fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
