<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROARING RETURN FOR KENNY BRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The third time proved to be the charm for Kenny
Brack.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Brack arrived from Sweden and had his debut in
the Indianapolis 500 ruined by a crash on the warmup lap that wiped
out him and the rest of the starters on the fifth row. Last year,
he returned as part of A.J. Foyt's stable and qualified fast enough
to join teammate Billy Boat, the pole-sitter, on the front row. He
led 23 laps, the third-best total in the race, but finished sixth
after running out of fuel on Lap 88 and barely making it back into
the pits.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Brack was the unwitting beneficiary of Robby Gordon's
fuel problems, as the CART driver ran out of gas with one lap to
go, delivering the 33-year-old native of Arvika, Sweden, his first
Indy 500 victory and Foyt, a four-time winner as a driver, his
first triumph as a car owner.
</P>
<P>
   Brack gained a greater appreciation for Foyt's four Indy 500
titles. ``It's very hard to win a race like this race, because
there are so many unknowns,'' he said. ``You don't know how the
car's going to handle, you don't know what's going to happen with
other drivers, if there's going to be lots of overtaking, and
there's so much risk involved that you have to calculate correctly
all the time. So you have to really have a lot of knowledge and so
forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this year we picked up a lot of good things. I've been
watching the videos, I've been taking notes and doing research for
two or three months and going through things just to know what I
could expect here. We planned for this, the team planned well, and
I think you get a little lucky _ if you prepare well.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day when a huge crowd turned out to bid farewell to Arie
Luyendyk, the 45-year-old pole-sitter whose 15th and final Indy 500
ended in a Turn 3 wall crash on Lap 117, the torch seemingly was
passed from the Flying Dutchman to Brack, who was described by
Michael Buffer during driver introductions as ``the Swede with the
need for speed.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Brack and runner-up Jeff Ward were the only
ones out of seven drivers who led at least a lap to make it to the
finish. Brack led four times for a total of 66 laps, the most of
any driver, while Ward led once for three laps before Brack's
daring Turn 1 pass on Lap 154.
</P>
<P>
   Brack adhered to his plan to play it cool, keep pace for the
first 100 laps, then give chase and go for it all in the last 10
laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't in a hurry all day,'' Foyt said. ``We were going to
run our own race. If we had to get reckless in the end, then we
would. I didn't want to take chances of eating our tires up. It was
just one of those days where everything worked in our favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when the leaders pitted under caution with about 30
laps to go and Gordon stayed on the track to move up to the lead.
As Brack gave chase and Foyt kept a vigil in the pits, they knew
that Gordon's 35-gallon tank would run dry before he could take the
checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt Robby should have run out before he did,'' Foyt said.
``Last year we tried to stretch it and we got ourselves in trouble.
But I told Kenny I didn't want second.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt's wishes were granted when Gordon's car sputtered with one
lap to go.
</P>
<P>
   The result was one of the oddest of couples in Victory Circle:
Brack, the quiet, unassuming road racer from Sweden who watches his
diet as carefully as he measures his words; and Foyt, the sometimes
brusque but always outspoken car owner from Houston with a
voracious appetite for life and anything with a high caloric
content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody laughed when I brought a foreigner to America, but I
brought him to Texas (to live) and he's not too bad,'' Foyt said of
Brack, who won three races in a row last year to deliver his car
owner an Indy Racing League championship. ``He's a good racer.''
</P>
<P>
   While Foyt has a reputation for going through drivers at Indy
the way George Steinbrenner does managers at Yankee Stadium, Brack
has settled into an easy working relationship with Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been good so far, no bad moments,'' Brack said. ``Sure,
A.J. calls a spade a spade. I'm not as outspoken as he is, but I
think I tell it like it is.''
</P>
<P>
   So whom was Brack happier for? Foyt, for winning his first as an
owner and fifth overall? Or himself, for winning his first?
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy for both of us,'' Brack smiled. ``I think more for
me. He has won it four times already. So I am happier for myself.
It has been very special to me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Energizers Motorsports chief mechanic Steve Fried, who was
critically injured when he was run over on pit row during the race,
remained in critical but stable condition in the intensive care
unit at Methodist Hospital in Indianapolis. He was awake and
responding to those around him, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   Energizer team management has decided to have crews don helmets
at the next Indy Racing League event June 12 at Texas Motor
Speedway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
