</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUCTIONS-ONLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY ENTREPRENEURS ARE ON INTERNET AUCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERVILLE, Mass. _ The poster in the antique shop was more than
a century old. Produced for the Union Pacific Railroad, it
encouraged New Englanders to take scenic train trips across the
grand vistas of the western United States.
</P>
<P>
   To Shannon Aaron of South Boston, it was ideal eBay bait, the
sort of collectible that would surely find a buyer on the popular
Internet auction site. So Aaron paid $25 for it, and posted an
offer on eBay to sell his find to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, a railroad buff in Montana bought the poster for
$700, or 28 times what Aaron had paid. ``I had a collector who said
he'd been waiting all his life,'' Aaron says. ``It was the cap of
his collection.''
</P>
<P>
   A knack for making this kind of deal has changed Aaron's life.
He no longer edits a local antiques magazine or works in somebody
else's knickknack shop. Instead, he's found a career tracking down
valuable antiques and collectibles and reselling them on the
Internet's hottest auction site.
</P>
<P>
   And he's not alone. An industry of entrepreneurs has sprung up
around auction sites like eBay. The sites enable anyone to start an
Internet business in minutes and to sell goods around the world.
And as the most popular such site, eBay is a favorite storefront
for these independent business people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly growing, as more and more people find out how
easy it is,'' said Kevin Pursglove, an eBay spokesman. Pursglove
won't say how many people have turned eBay auctions into a
full-time job, but confirms that the number is ``significant.''
</P>
<P>
   So significant that eBay has set up a special Power Sellers
program for regulars who sell more than $2,000 of goods per month.
Power Sellers get a special logo attached to their eBay Web
auctions, to tell potential buyers that the seller is a
trustworthy, respected member of the eBay community. There are
other perks, too: Those who sell $25,000 a month or more are
assigned a personal eBay account specialist to provide technical
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron won't say how much he takes in as an eBay auctioneer,
except that it's a lot. ``I make more money than I've ever made at
any job I've ever had,'' he declares.
</P>
<P>
   The eBay site was created in 1995 by Pierre Omidyar to buy and
sell the Pez candy dispensers that his wife loved to collect. But
it rapidly expanded into an on-line auction house for all manner of
merchandise. For people looking to empty their attics, eBay can
provide a cheap and simple alternative to garage sales and
newspaper ads. Because it uses an auction format, sellers often get
exceptional prices for items they once thought of as little more
than junk.
</P>
<P>
   Profits for eBay come from listing and transaction fees charged
to the seller. The company earned $2.4 million last year, but its
market capitalization is a stunning $22 billion. That's why many
other firms are trying their hand at the Internet auction business.
The on-line bookstore Amazon.com Inc., for instance, is spending
millions to promote its new auction service. But for now, eBay is
far ahead of the pack, with about 8 million visitors every month.
</P>
<P>
   Many serious entrepreneurs try to peddle goods over the
Internet. But there's the challenge of learning how to design a Web
site, or the expense of hiring a professional to do the job.
Besides, with millions of Web pages on the Internet, it's difficult
to attract visitors to any one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Now many of these businesspeople are simply auctioning their
goods on eBay or one of its competitors. It's relatively easy to
post a description of the product, and even a photograph. And eBay
draws about 8 million visitors from around the world each month,
boosting the odds that the goods will sell. The seller can set a
minimum price, and if a bidding war breaks out, an item can end up
selling at a far higher price than it would at an ordinary Internet
storefront.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you need is two obsessed people,'' said Michael Agostino
of Quincy. The 32-year-old Web site designer supplements his income
by selling rare compact discs on eBay under the name
``thelimelight.''
</P>
<P>
   Agostino is astounded by the prices some music fans cheerfully
pay. ``I sold a Mariah Carey CD single for $120,'' he recalls. Then
there's Carmen Electra, Baywatch girl, former wife of basketball
star Dennis Rodman, and erstwhile singer. ``She actually recorded a
CD with Prince before her Baywatch days,'' says Agostino. ``I found
it in a used CD store for like two bucks and I sold it for 80
bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   The community of people making a living off sites like eBay
sites doesn't stop with auctioneers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   During the California gold rush, some people got rich selling
picks and shovels to miners. In the same spirit, some eBay
entrepreneurs specialize in selling products to professional
on-line auctioneers.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schlicht of San Mateo, Calif., has created a software
program called AuctionPoster that makes it easy to list dozens or
hundreds of items on eBay. The 27-year-old software engineer had
gotten into the eBay habit, auctioning about 10 items a week. Each
item required a separate posting on the eBay Web site, and Schlicht
found the process tedious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was taking me 20 minutes to post an auction on eBay for
something that's only going to sell for $10,'' he said. So Schlicht
wrote a program to automate the process. Then he realized he could
sell the software to other eBay regulars.
</P>
<P>
   AuctionPoster is a subscription service that costs $29.95 a year
for unlimited use. Schlicht also provides a Web-hosting service for
people who want to display pictures of their merchandise on the
eBay site.
</P>
<P>
   Schlicht says his earnings from AuctionPoster in the last two
months have outstripped his salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very close to doing it full time,'' he says. But Schlicht
clings to his day job, worried that eBay might eventually offer a
competing service that would reduce demand for his product.
</P>
<P>
   The on-line auctioneers are so far having only a slight effect
on traditional retailers of collectibles. Andy Papertsian, owner of
Bay State Coin Co. in Boston, says he's forced to sell coins,
trading cards, and other collectibles at lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always hearing, `Well, I can get it cheaper on the
Internet,' '' says Papertsian. ``I'm being compared, not just to my
competitors on the street, but to some nebulous eBay in the sky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
