</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOOKING AT THE WHOLE EARTH AGAIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This summer is the 30th anniversary of the moon walk, and is
also the 30th anniversary of the first man-made photograph of our
whole planet from space, as taken by an astronaut on  &LR; an &LR;  Apollo
mission. The photograph came to grace the cover of the Whole Earth
catalog, as a reflection of the vision of  &UR; Stewart Brand &LR; , who
created the catalog, and founded the WELL in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Brand recalled the other day that in 1966, to ``get people
going'' in favor of space travel, he'd given out buttons that said,
``Why haven't we seen a photograph of the whole Earth?''
</P>
<P>
   The classic shots taken three years later ``weren't photographs
taken by robots on a satellite,'' says Brand. ``They were taken by
homesick astronauts looking toward the Earth from the moon.'' The
change in people's perception of themselves in the cosmos was like
that ``when mirrors got really good,'' said Brand, ``when people
could really see themselves. ... We saw a planet, but we saw
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, after the image was used on the cover of Life
magazine and all sorts of ads, ``it just became the classic image
of the world. It became as strong as the mushroom cloud, and
eventually displaced it, as fear of Armageddon was replaced by a
sense of the wholesome Earth and the age of space travel. What's
interesting is that the same rockets that were going to deliver the
bombs were going to deliver us to space. One was a message of
destruction and the other was a message of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand has just published ``The Clock of the Long Now'' (Basic;
$22), which he says is about ``making a hasty world safe for haste
by tending to the slow things.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAKING CARE OF YOUR INTERIORS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Casting its discerning eye on the calendar, Elle Decor magazine
asked a group of people it described as ``style-setters'' the big
question: ``How is decorating changing as we head into the next
century?''
</P>
<P>
   Some of their thoughts:
</P>
<P>
   ``I love color,'' said  &UR; Louise Grunwald &LR; , who is described as a
philanthropist, ``although all my rooms seem to be beige or
white.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never get tired of period rooms,'' antiques dealer
 &UR; Merrill Stenbeck  &LR; revealed, ``but I've never had the urge to sit
down and read a magazine in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Decorator  &UR; Mica Ertegun &LR;  took a harsh view of ``pretty ... not a
word that ranks high on my decorating list,'' she said. ``It equals
mediocrity.'' Magazine editor  &UR; Cristina Greeven &LR;  disagreed in the
strongest terms: ``I couldn't imagine sleeping in a bedroom that
wasn't pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, said Grunwald, ``A woman's decorator, like her
hairdresser, has always been her shrink.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORLD O' WOMEN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - In Oslo,  &UR; Anne-Mette Smette &LR; , 58, is keeping a bird's egg
between her breasts in hopes of incubating it. The abandoned egg
was found by a farmer last week, and hens refused to accept it for
hatching.
</P>
<P>
   - A Berkeley woman received a flyer about the Women's Goddess
Festival (in Occidental in July), addressed to her ``or current
goddess'' at her address.
</P>
<P>
   - If  &UR; Bernadette Peters &LR;  leaves the New York revival of ``Annie
Get Your Gun,'' reports the New York Daily News, the producers are
thinking about replacing her with  &UR; Dolly Parton &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   - Historian  &UR; Terence O'Donnell &LR; , whose New York Times quote was
gleaned by  &UR; Ken Maley &LR; , described San Francisco as one of the three
West Coast sisters: ``San Francisco grew up as the debutante,
Seattle the tart and Portland the spinster.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - A foot-square sample of granite sent by the Cold Spring
Granite Co. to prove to The Chronicle its ``beauty, complexity and
durability,'' arrived smashed into 10 pieces.
</P>
<P>
   - The teen magazine Twist provides the backstage menu of
Aerosmith (brown rice, corn, organic beets and baked potatoes) and
 &UR; Britney Spears &LR;  (cheese grits, barbecue, chocolate chip cookie
dough ice cream, Cap'n Crunch cq &LR;  and Froot Loopscq &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Al Sharpton &LR;  has hired a personal trainer, says the New York
Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Come, but please don't cry when you lose.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  -  &LR; New York columnist  &UR; Jimmy Breslin  &LR; advising &UR; Hillary
Clinton &LR;  on a run for a New York seat in the Senate, quoted in U.S.
News &AMP; World Report.
</P>
