<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTANDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ON THE NEWSSTANDS
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newspaperman Philip True, an American based out of Mexico City,
made a one-way trek into Mexico's last great wilderness last
December, fascinated by the unspoiled land of the Sierra Madre
Occidental and the intact culture of the Huichol Indians. Two weeks
later he turned up in a shallow grave. Atlanta writer Paul Kvinta
retraces True's journey for Outside ($3.95) and discovers that True
may have been blind to one important fact: This was a culture that
did not want to be discovered.
</P>
<P>
   EYE OF RAGE: Images can hasten war, Charles Paul Freund points
out in Reason ($2.95), discussing the role that broadcasts of
atrocities have played in American humanitarian expeditions in
Somalia, Haiti and, today, in Kosovo. Freund argues that what
starts out as a mission of mercy inevitably brings political
entanglements, and opines that ``when we do choose to act, it
should be in full appreciation not only of mercy's limits but of
its consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   LEARNING PEACE: A violence-prevention program called Second Step
that is taught in Decatur, Ga. schools and in Forsyth County, Ga.'s
Midway Elementary School receives attention from Life ($3.99) as a
viable way to silence the gunfire disrupting American schools.
Kennedy Middle School in Eugene, Ore., experienced a shooting last
year, and Second Step has reduced the number of Kennedy students
getting into trouble because of aggression and hostility, Life
reports
</P>
<P>
   GOT MILK? Swedish researcher Catharina Svanborg set out to
determine why breast milk is so effective at warding off bacteria.
But when she started mixing breast milk with cancer cells seven
years ago, she saw the cancer cells falling apart _ in her words,
``committing suicide.'' Breast-fed babies are nine times less
likely to develop childhood lymphoma than bottle-fed babies, and
Svanborg thought she might have found out why. More than that, she
imagined isolating the compound in breast milk that kills cancer
cells and creating an across-the-board antidote. Discover ($4.99)
reports on her mom-and-pop research center in Lund, Sweden, and her
search for the grand cure.
</P>
<P>
   GOT BLUEMILK? Emory Magazine features the independent arts
magazine bluemilk in the spring issue. Bluemilk was started by
Emory University grads Chris Hansen, Richard Hermes and Ben Tran,
along with Tulane University alumnus Chris Kowalski, and has been
graced by writings from such Emory profs as Frank Manley and John
Stone. In the same issue, Emory Magazine pins a clever headline on
a piece about neuroscientist Thomas R. Insel, who studies
pair-bonding among fuzzy brown rodents in an attempt to find out
``Why do voles fall in love?''
</P>
<P>
   IMPROBABLE DEVICES: Disregarding the pesky fact that these
machines are beyond the realm of possibility, Popular Mechanics
($2.95) offers the spec sheets on the Droid Control Ship, Queen
Amidala's Royal Starship and other vehicles that speed through
``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.'' ``We lift the hood
and pull back the access panels on the most amazing land- and
spacecraft George Lucas has ever imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
