<HEADER>
A7564 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-2NDTA     05-31 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BEIJING: in Beijing.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The human rights group plans to release further details on
Tuesday at a news conference in New York.
</P>
<P>
   As corroborating evidence in their appeal, the relatives' group
provided names and details of 155 people who were killed and 65
people who were wounded in the attacks by the army and the police
on June 3 and 4, 1989. ``Not one was engaged in any violent
behavior,'' the group says of those listed. ``They were all
innocent victims of the massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of people who died in the crackdown has never been
disclosed, but it is believed to total several hundred at least.
The new list of victims, though far from complete, is the longest
ever publicly compiled.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party has firmly refused to reconsider its verdict
that the raucous 1989 demonstrations, in which hundreds of
thousands of students and other citizens marched or camped on
Beijing's central square, were a ``counter-revolutionary'' movement
that had to be crushed for the sake of China's stability and
development.
</P>
<P>
   Li, the central target of the new petitions, appears to be
securely in power today, a key spokesman for more conservative
elements in the Communist Party. The group's decision to cite Li
and other living officials as targets for criminal indictment
assures a hostile reaction from the Communist Party and the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Western and Chinese experts believe that the final decision to
use military force to clear students from Tiananmen Square was made
by Deng Xiaoping, the paramount leader who died in 1997, and that
the military operations were directed by Yang Shangkun, who died
last September.
</P>
<P>
   But the new petitions say Li, as premier, bore major
responsibility for the killings because of his role in declaring
martial law, because he ``failed to stop the cruel killings of
civilians,'' and because he ``tried to cover up these crimes,''
praising the army for its achievements in the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the attacks on unarmed civilians ``systematic and
organized,'' the petitions say several military leaders should be
held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   The first petition calling for a criminal inquiry was delivered
on May 17 by Zhang Xianling, 62 and Su Bingxian, 64, both mothers
of young men shot dead on June 4, 1989. They took the petition to
the front gate of the Supreme People's Procuratorate, the agency
that prosecutes crimes. Eventually an official emerged and took the
document, they reported, promising an answer that has not come.
</P>
<P>
   On May 24, the same two women delivered a second document
providing more details of the group's demands to guards at that
same gate.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone Monday, officials in the information
section of the Supreme Procuratorate said they had no knowledge of
the petitions and could not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ding and other organizers of the victims' group know that
they are pushing the authorities to the limit, risking arrest and
prison. Working with exiled dissidents against the interests of the
Communist Party is often declared a major crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since my son died in 1989, there's nothing more that can scare
me,'' Ms. Ding said Monday. ``I do what I choose to do according to
my own conscience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
