<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7565 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DROWNING-COX     05-31 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROWNING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rescue attempt in suburban Atlanta turns tragic
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ None of Thomas Robinson's grieving relatives expressed
surprise Monday that ``Cowboy'' gave his life trying to save a man
whose canoe had capsized in Joel's Lake near Lithonia, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   They said the 39-year-old Robinson, who drowned trying to swim
back to shore Sunday night, helped anyone at any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always did stuff like that,'' his sister-in-law, Carlotta
Harrell, said. ``He'd help out folks he didn't know. He'd give away
his last dime. He'd find jobs for people who needed one.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson died trying to save the life of Dwayne Evans, 33, who
also drowned. Police say Evans was fishing with two other men on
Sunday. According to the DeKalb police report, Evans was playing
around in the boat and it flipped over. None of the three men were
wearing life jackets, Fire Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a father of four, was a former deputy nicknamed
``Cowboy'' because he loved horses. A former rodeo rider, Robinson
owned several horses.
</P>
<P>
   He founded one of Atlanta's first horse-drawn carriage
companies, which caters to tourists downtown. He also loved driving
his Harley-Davidson and was a member of a local motorcycle club.
</P>
<P>
   About 7:30 p.m. Sunday, Robinson was out in the yard when a man
came running up from the lake, saying a canoe with three fishermen
had capsized. Robinson immediately called his wife, Kenya, on the
couple's two-way radio and told her to dial 911. Robinson then
sprinted down to Joel's Lake.
</P>
<P>
   At the lake, Robinson dove in to try and save Evans, Harrell
said.
</P>
<P>
   As Kenya Robinson waited for fire and police personnel to arrive
at the house, her husband called back on the two-way radio, asking
her to bring him some dry clothes and some towels.
</P>
<P>
   When she asked if he had been able to save the third man,
Robinson said, ``No, I'm not a lifeguard,'' said Robinson's
mother-in-law, Brenda Harris, who heard the call. She added:
``Those were the last words we heard him say.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson apparently dove back in the lake one last time but
never made it back to shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave up his life trying to save someone else,'' Harris
said. ``It doesn't surprise me whatsoever. ... But he was the sole
bread-winner for his wife and four children. We've just got to
figure out what to do now.''
</P>
<P>
   Divers found Robinson's body 50 to 75 feet from shore at about 9
p.m. Sunday and pulled Evans' body from the lake about 11 a.m.
Monday, DeKalb Fire Battalion Chief Bobby Wade said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrell, Robinson's sister-in-law, criticized DeKalb County
police and fire officials for not immediately jumping in to try and
save Robinson when they arrived at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   But Wade said DeKalb Fire officials did not want another
fatality. ``If we had jumped in, one of us might have ended up just
like Mr. Robinson,'' Wade said.
</P>
<P>
   One firefighter saw Robinson struggling in the water and threw a
fire hose toward him, but Robinson was unable to reach it, Wade
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
