<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOX-TIGERS-DISPUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGRAVATION BOILS OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The day had already turned sour on the Detroit Tigers
when relief pitcher Matt Anderson threw his last pitch of what was
for him a long afternoon in a short time span.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Anderson and the Tigers, the pitch plunked Red
Sox first baseman Mike Stanley just below the shoulder blade.
</P>
<P>
   Home plate umpire Chuck Meriwether took about a second to
determine that the pitch, which came on a 3-and-2 count, had been
intentionally thrown at Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was gone, and the ejection set off Tiger catcher Brad
Ausmus, who went from disbelief to rage in a heartbeat, and that
set off Tiger manager Larry Parrish, who sprinted onto the field in
a futile effort to protect his catcher from being tossed.
</P>
<P>
   But all Parrish could do was voice his own outrage and disbelief
at something that enraged the Tigers as much as turning a 6-1 lead
into an 8-7 loss did.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, of all,'' Parrish said, ``to think that he was throwing
at anybody with a 3-and-2 count is ridiculous. The way he was
pitching, he couldn't have hit anybody if he wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson faced four batters, allowing a two-run pinch-hit home
run to Jason Varitek, a single to Nomar Garciaparra, and a two-run
home run to Troy O'Leary before plunking Stanley, so he no doubt
would have been gone anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the way he departed that angered the Tigers. Adding
to their frustration was that Meriwether was behind the plate nine
days ago when Detroit and Cleveland got into a ``beanball'' war
that led to ejections and suspensions. Those things can be
particularly frustrating for a team playing as poorly as the
Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Making things worse was watching Red Sox closer Tom Gordon nick
Damion Easley with a pitch in the top of the ninth without any
action from Meriwether.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be consistent,'' said Ausmus, who conceded that he
deserved to be tossed for his reaction. ``If they can come out and
warn him before the ninth, and then he hits Damion Easley with
nothing happening is embarrassing for the umpires. Especially when
a week ago the same crew is working the Cleveland series and C.J.
Nitkowski was suspended and thrown out for two games and didn't hit
a guy. There's no consistency. There's no question in my mind that
Tom Gordon was not trying to hit Damion Easley, but he should have
been thrown out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ausmus also conceded that he was not in the best of moods even
before Stanley was hit. Watching his team blow another lead, on a
91-degree Monday afternoon, contributed to his irritation.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I was just flabbergasted they would throw Matt
Anderson out,'' said Ausmus. ``But then the first words out of my
mouth were the kind you couldn't play on television before 11:30 at
night and probably after it as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck generally does a good job. He works his ass off. Today
he mad a bad decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Tigers sat around after the game and watched a
replay of Anderson hitting Stanley. Some suggested that Meriwether
actually bumped Parrish in their face-to-face confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was trying to hit anybody,'' said Parrish. ``But if you
are consistent, Tom Gordon deserved to be thrown out as well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just an aggravating day,'' summed up Ausmus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
