<HEADLINE>
MIDLIFE HITS LINCOLN CENTER WITH CALLS FOR A FACE LIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Across Lincoln Center's 18-acre expanse, granite
paving blocks are spider-veined with cracks. Missing tiles mar the
reflecting pool that frames Henry Moore's signature sculpture. An
uncomfortable crush of patrons often jams the undersize lobby of
the Metropolitan Opera House, and its metal ceiling is turning
green from oxidation. Calls for sweeping renovations of Avery
Fisher Hall and the New York State Theater are growing more
insistent.
</P>
<P>
   As it celebrates its 40th birthday, Lincoln Center for the
Performing Arts, the world's most successful arts complex, is
showing its age. Officials are weighing a vast fund-raising
campaign to address the wear and tear and other gnawing problems,
from shortages of backstage space to troubled acoustics to
underground leaks.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign could run into the hundreds of millions of dollars,
making it the largest arts initiative in the city in years.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys of the needs of the Metropolitan Opera House and of
Avery Fisher Hall, home of the New York Philharmonic, indicated
that renovating those two buildings could cost more than half a
billion dollars. A committee led by Roy Furman, vice chairman of
the center's board of directors, has been asked for a report by
this fall on capital needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this effort is going to be looking at things 40 years
old whose useful life has run out and need to be replaced,'' said
Nathan Leventhal, the president of Lincoln Center since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Coming four decades after Lincoln Center's groundbreaking in May
1959, the internal review is described by officials as a midlife
stock-taking, a way to figure out what it would take to bring the
complex's performance halls up to 21st-century standards and to
keep enticing audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues Lincoln Center faces is how to mount a major
new capital drive without interfering with the fund raising of its
constituents, from the Metropolitan Opera, halfway through a $200
million drive to double its endowment, to Jazz at Lincoln Center,
which is pressing to raise about $70 million for its first
performance hall.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the thinking is expansive. One member of the
Philharmonic's board, Rita E. Hauser, suggested rebuilding almost
every performance hall. ``They all served a wonderful purpose,''
she said. ``But if I had my druthers, other than the Met, I'd take
them down.''
</P>
<P>
   The buildings are not under landmark protection, but because
they were part of a federally aided urban renewal project, any
changes to their exterior would face government and community
review.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by a coalition of esteemed architects, Lincoln Center's
melange of arched facades, clad in luminescent but vulnerable
travertine, bears the scars of patchwork repairs and deterioration.
(Kimball J. Beasley, an engineer at Wiss Janney Elstner Associates,
said that travertine, a type of limestone, was particularly
susceptible to pollution.)
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, the center has spent nearly $25 million on
repairs and maintenance, not including such capital projects as the
continuing $30 million reconstruction of the performing arts
library. Its endowment is $142 million. For all this, said Joseph
Volpe, the Met's general manager, ``The condition of the plaza is a
disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Met, the Philharmonic and Jazz at Lincoln Center,
the 13 constituents of the center are the New York Library for the
Performing Arts; the School of American Ballet; the New York City
Ballet; the New York City Opera; the City Center of Music and
Drama; the Juilliard School; the Film Society of Lincoln Center
(which runs the New York Film Festival); the Chamber Music Society
of Lincoln Center, and the Lincoln Center Theater. The constituents
include Lincoln Center itself which, in addition to managing the
complex, presents 350 events a year, from the Mostly Mozart
festival and Great Performers to the Lincoln Center Festival in the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   An Avery Fisher study, sponsored by the Philharmonic and the
center, has not been publicly released. But executives familiar
with the report said it recommended three options: upgrade the hall
with a largely cosmetic face lift ($20 million); overhaul it in a
major modernization ($100 million), or recreate it in an expansive,
innovative way, including a new stage and sound system ($200
million). The hall, which had acoustic problems that were addressed
by a $30 million effort in the 1970s, is still dealing with cramped
concourses and a poor restaurant layout.
</P>
<P>
   At the New York State Theater, Martin J. Oppenheimer, who is the
board chairman, said that the house, built for ballet, has
shortcomings for its opera component: ``Is it adequate for opera?
Yes. Have we made improvements? Yes. Do we hope for something even
better? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater, executives said, lacked adequate space for
workshops and rehearsals, for storage of sets backstage and for
cooking food to serve at receptions; caterers must carry the food
across the plaza from Avery Fisher Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Randall Bourscheidt, the master plan coordinator for the State
Theater, said that a minimal upgrading of the facade and windows
had been estimated at $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Opera is in far better physical shape. For its
silver anniversary at Lincoln Center in 1990, the Met undertook 82
capital projects totaling about $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said James H. Naples Jr., the house manager, a crush of
patrons was often a problem in the lobby because the design was
shortened by 40 feet to save money. As with other buildings at
Lincoln Center, the Met's travertine facade shows its patches.
</P>
<P>
   Since completion of the initial Lincoln Center plan in 1969, at
a cost of $184 million, the biggest project has been the $180
million construction, from 1988 to 1992, of the Samuel B. and David
Rose Building and the Walter Reade Theater, along with additions to
Juilliard.
</P>
<P>
   Many within the complex consider the prospective effort of a
piece with the master plan laid out more than 40 years ago by John
D. Rockefeller III, who led the campaign for the center. ``We are
not building for just '56 or '57 or '58,'' he said. ``We are
thinking of something that will last for generations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
