<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW BAD DO THINGS HAVE TO GET? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The letter from the woman began, ``Two and one-half
years ago, my formally considerate, loving, obedient 15-year-old
son walked in the door and informed me that he didn't have to do
anything I said anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   She was determined to prove him wrong.
</P>
<P>
   She sought help from family, friends, counselors, the police,
the juvenile probation department, the courts. She's seen her son
arrested, hauled before judges, ordered to perform community
service, placed on probation and on house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   She's watched him ignore it all, and her, with no real
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never would have believed it,'' she said last week. ``But
now, after all this time, I realize that when he came into the
house that day and said he didn't have to listen to me anymore, or
to anyone else, he was right.''
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking about a gang-banger. Her son hasn't robbed a
convenience store or assaulted a police officer or organized a
major drug ring. It would be easier if he had. Those kids we know
how to deal with. We treat them as adults and put them away.
</P>
<P>
   We identify them in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   But not this kid. His mother, Cindi, won't have a last name in
this article, and the boy won't be named at all because, as yet,
his crimes don't warrant it.
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem. &QL; 
Learning lessons &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the two years he's been acting out this way,'' Cindi
says, ``he's learned that he can disregard the rules and defy
authority. And get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been involved in vandalism, shoplifting, loitering, curfew
violations and drug use. The juvenile courts have placed him on
probation and house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ignores it, or gets around it,'' Cindi said. ``And when I
turn him in, the probation people get annoyed and say, `Let us do
our job.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her son's been ordered to perform community service, and hasn't.
He does what he wants.
</P>
<P>
   His parents are divorced. He's gone to live with his father and
with other relatives. It never lasts long.
</P>
<P>
   ``He eventually acts with them as he does with me,'' Cindi said.
``And they throw him out.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's juvenile probation department knows all about the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Cherie Townsend, director of Juvenile Court Services, said,
``He's done things and been faced with increasing consequences. We
don't believe we're letting him skate. I know, by now, the mom
would probably like for him to be detained. The reality is that our
detention centers are very overcrowded.'' &QL; 
No room in jails &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We don't have room for all our violent juvenile offenders, let
alone for kids like Cindi's son. It leaves a struggling mother with
few options. She doesn't have the money to send her boy to one of
those tough-love wilderness experiences, or any other expensive
private program. He wouldn't agree to go, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society hasn't figured out what to do with him,'' she said.
``He's not bad enough yet, I guess. So, instead of preventing him
from becoming that bad, we choose to just wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherie Townsend says prevention programs work, but need to be
expanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just kids who need help, these days,'' she says.
``It's families. We need more resources to help families deal with
these types of issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, if Cindi's boy kills someone in a car accident
or a fight, it'll be Cindi we blame. Blaming parents is a national
pastime. It's easy. It requires little thought, and even less
money.
</P>
<P>
   Cherie Townsend believes this particular boy still can be
helped. He has another probation violation hearing this week. Maybe
something productive will come of it, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Cindi isn't as optimistic. Her boy turns 18 in less than six
months, and will either move out or be asked by his mother to
leave. It's something she wants us to think about because she
figures there are a lot of kids like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no respect for the law,'' she said. And no sense of
responsibility. And no fear of reprisal. And he's about to become
an adult. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at at ed.montini(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
