<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7577 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-METREON-SFCHRON &LR;      05-31 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METREON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Welcome to Sonyland   By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Metreon, which opens in San Francisco next month, is being billed
as a cross between a high-tech shopping mall and a theme park. But
it's also a four-story, 350,000-square-foot marketing vehicle for
Sony Corp.
<P>
   Almost every square foot of Metreon promotes the Tokyo company's
far-flung holdings _ from its music-recording arm, which includes
the Epic label, to its film studio, Columbia TriStar Motion Picture
Group, to its computer games, high-definition televisions and
boom-boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy works on many levels: Sony will sell consumer
products in the high-profile PlayStation and Sony Style stores.
Behind the scenes, it will showcase business technologies _ such as
a DJ sound system in Jillian's restaurant that Sony hopes to sell
to nightclub developers and other corporate clients. Throughout the
complex, Sony hopes to build its image as a cool, cutting-edge
company.
</P>
<P>
   If the experiment works, observers say, Metreon could be as
effective a branding vehicle for Sony as Disney World is for Walt
Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   Sony plans to roll out other Metreons around the world if this
one proves successful.
</P>
<P>
   If Metreon fails, Sony will have bungled an $85 million
investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``A virtual showroom for Sony makes tremendous sense,'' said
Mike Moriarty, an entertainment-retail consultant with A.T. Kearney
in Chicago. ``If they want to keep their leading-edge image, they
have to maintain a leading-edge position in new technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Metreon's blatant brand-marketing elements include 15 Sony
cinemas, some of which will &LR;   &LR; show Columbia TriStar pictures, and a
huge Sony IMAX theater for 3-D movies.
</P>
<P>
   But most of Sony's salesmanship is understated.
</P>
<P>
   Sony recordings will be played as background music throughout
the mall. The PCs running Microsoft software in the Microsoft store
will carry little Sony tags, as will the headphones in Hear Music's
listening stations.
</P>
<P>
   Sony technology is behind the 110-foot video wall in the
Discovery Channel Store, Melvin the talking robot in an educational
attraction called Why Things Work, and the computer server that
lets Hear Music patrons listen to thousands of CDs.
</P>
<P>
   A Metreon debit card that visitors can use instead of cash was
developed by Sony. Games in a futuristic arcade called the Airtight
Garage were created by Sony. Even leftover Sony computer parts have
become a design element _ tiny chips and other computer innards are
pressed into Metreon's concrete walls.
</P>
<P>
   Metreon will even showcase a technology that is still on the
drawing board: decorative, 12-foot ``wings'' floating above the
lobby will one day be outfitted with thin HDTV screens, although
Sony is still trying to figure out how to make monitors that are
long and thin enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to expand the definition of entertainment,'' said
Tom Sugiyama, general manager of Sony's location-based
entertainment division. ``We're taking advantage of our hardware
and also taking advantage of our content, like movies, games and
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony's goals are twofold: to strengthen the Sony image as ``a
company that offers a new kind of lifestyle'' and ``to make money
by merging these kinds of entertainment'' into a profitable
shopping center, said Sugiyama.
</P>
<P>
   But will a visit to Metreon really influence a visitor's buying
decision months later, when he or she is shopping for a boom box in
Walnut Creek or Topeka, Kansas? That's something nobody knows for
certain, including Sony officials, Sugiyama admits.
</P>
<P>
   For Metreon to be an effective brand-builder, the Sony name must
be reasonably conspicuous, said Moriarty. If visitors skip the
cinemas and PlayStation and Sony Style stores, they could miss the
Sony connection.
</P>
<P>
   Company decision-makers opted not to call the center Sony
Metreon because they didn't want visitors to arrive with
preconceived ideas, said Sugiyama. Yet consumers are unlikely to
use it's official name, ``Metreon, a Sony Entertainment Center.''
So the Sony name could get lost.
</P>
<P>
   The name issue aside, consultant Pat Esgate said Metreon seems
unique and cool enough to burnish Sony's image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe (Metreon visitors) will be more likely to buy Sony
products, just as I'm sure there's an impact when people go to
FootLocker after they've visited NikeTown,'' said Esgate, who runs
Esgate &AMP; Associates in Nyack, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   There are two requirements for retail entertainment venues like
Metreon to be a success, said Moriarty: ``continuously refreshable
content and continually refreshable consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   If Metreon succeeds in attracting 2.5 million out-of-town
tourists per year _ half of its projected annual traffic of 5
million _ the ``refreshable consumers'' should be taken care of.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Swinney, president of Sony Development, said merchandise
selections at Sony Style and other stores will be frequently
refreshed. Same with the games in Airtight Garage and the exhibits
in the Way Things Work, a multimedia attraction that uses gears and
levers to teach children (and their parents) about physics and
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the applications developed for Metreon, such as the
debit card and arcade games, were not designed for resale to other
companies, although they may be used in future Metreons. Their
function is to make Metreon a fun and unique experience that
shoppers associate with the Sony name.
</P>
<P>
   But other Sony technologies used in Metreon are intended to make
money through sales to other businesses. Even before the doors open
June 16, Sony will have sold $10 million of its own electronic
components, like video monitors and projectors, for use in the
center, said Swinney.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sony developed a server with San Francisco music
retailer Hear Music that will let patrons listen to thousands of
CDs at listening stations around the store.
</P>
<P>
   Hear Music, which will occupy part of the Sony Style store,
intends to buy servers to install at its four other outlets, in
Berkeley, Palo Alto, Santa Monica and Chicago, as well as in future
locations around the country.
</P>
<P>
   In existing stores, Hear's listening stations are equipped with
CD changers, which are slow to switch between songs, &UR;  &LR; break down
easily, and can play only up to 10 CDs per station. In addition to
playing thousands of CDs at the touch of a button, the Sony server
lets patrons read articles and music recommendations at 11
interactive stations in the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a quantum leap for us,'' said Don MacKinnon, president of
Hear, who is also a fan of Sony headphones and other equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Hear won't give preference to Sony recordings and in fact the
contract between the two companies states that it cannot be asked
to do so, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Swinney expects Sony to recoup its initial investment in Metreon
within seven years. If its bet pans out, of course, the ultimate
payoff will be much greater.
</P>
</TEXT>
