<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Tuesday, June 1, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Stewart Slavin at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   LA-MEMORIAL (Los Angeles) _ Canoga Park may not be Staff Sgt.
Andrew Ramirez's hometown, but San Fernando Valley residents gave
the released POW a hero's welcome during its annual Memorial Day
parade Monday. By Yvette Cabrera. (Will move in the ``n''
California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   IRON-BUTTERFLY (Malibu, Calif.) _ Los Angeles County coroners
might determine as early as Tuesday if the skeletal remains found
in a heavily-wooded Malibu canyon over the weekend are those of
Iron Butterfly bassist Philip ``Taylor'' Kramer, who disappeared
four years ago. By David Greenberg. (Will move in the ``n''
California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-BOX-OFFICE (Los Angeles) _ The Force will clearly be with
moviegoers for several more months at the nation's multiplexes,
where it continues to dominate business and break records. ``Star
Wars Episode 1: The Phantom Menace'' showed impressive staying
power with an amazing $64.8 million at 3,023 theaters during the
Friday through Monday Memorial Day holiday weekend. By Dave McNary.
(Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   BELMONT-TOXIC (Los Angeles) _ Lax practices by contractors and
Los Angeles school district officials allowed oil-contaminated soil
to be used in site preparation for construction of the costliest
school in U.S. history, a Daily News investigation has found. By
Greg Gittrich. (Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a''
national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   ART-SCAM (Los Angeles) _ Amid guns, stolen stereos and bags of
drugs that fill up the LAPD evidence room is what appears to be a
famous Renoir painting. It is not. Rather, it is a meticulous fake
seized from a Los Angeles art dealer who tried to sell it for
$350,000 to a local collector, police say. With Los Angeles'
growing affluence and love affair with art, comes crime. By Troy
Anderson. (Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national
news files.)
</P>
