<HEADER>
A7582 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEER-KAN &LR;      05-31 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAWN RAISED WITH HUMAN ASSIST CREATES QUANDARY IN SMALL TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINN VALLEY, Kan. _ The tale of Pretty Girl, an orphaned deer
that paces alone in a tiny petting zoo after having the run of this
small community, sounds like a Disney story waiting for a happy
ending.
</P>
<P>
   All looked lost for the spotted fawn in July 1996 when children
said they came upon coyotes devouring its mother in northern Linn
County.
</P>
<P>
   The children plucked the fawn from the wild and delivered it to
Mary Perkins' small yellow house on the edge of the private
community of Linn Valley Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins was the natural choice.
</P>
<P>
   Since moving to Linn County from Roeland Park in 1986, she had
kept a trough just outside her back yard, where deer would gather
for regular feedings. She watched as opossums dined from her cat's
dish on the back porch, and she put out food for any sort of hungry
stray that wandered the community.
</P>
<P>
   She had even raised another fawn from a bottle until a
neighborhood dog that ate in her yard frightened it off.
</P>
<P>
   So Perkins stocked up on baby formula, bought bottle nipples
from the local co-op and raised the fawn, which she named Pretty
Girl, in her back yard.
</P>
<P>
   When the animal grew big enough, it regularly hopped Perkins'
fence to explore the neighborhood, nibble at landscaped yards and
try to pal around with residents.
</P>
<P>
   It is illegal to keep a wild animal. Charlie Ward, a regional
supervisor with the Kansas Department of Wildlife and Parks, said
that what kept Perkins in the clear is the same thing that has
doomed Pretty Girl to her 35-by-65-foot pen at Linn Valley Lakes.
The deer was free to come and go from Perkins' yard like a wild
animal, but it chose to wander about town and try to play with
people like a pet.
</P>
<P>
   The way Perkins tells the story, Pretty Girl was an oversized,
graceful version of Mary's Little Lamb.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor little thing would follow anybody anywhere, she was
so tame,'' Perkins said. ``She wanted to go to church. She'd follow
people while they walked up to the mailbox and back.''
</P>
<P>
   That is true, say others in Linn Valley, which became a city in
November. But the qualities that Perkins found so endearing in
Pretty Girl _ wandering into houses, stretching on her hind legs to
snack on tall plants, rearing up in play _ upset some of Perkins'
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha Carpenter, 7, likes to pet Pretty Girl in the zoo, but
she was afraid to play outside when the deer ran loose. Last spring
her brother, Josh, 11, tried to run the animal off with a broom so
the little girl could play in peace. The deer reared up and
scratched Josh's face, said his mother, Sue Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins ``did it a favor, saving it, and that's wonderful,''
Carpenter said, ``but you can't keep an animal that's hurting
people.''
</P>
<P>
   She told Larry Dwyer, general manager of the Linn Valley
Property Owners' Association, who called Wildlife and Parks for
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing was just getting too big. When it was a fawn, it
wasn't much of a problem,'' Dwyer said. ``The choices were either
round her up and put her in the pen, or destroy her. And she'd been
like a pet to a lot of people around here, so we didn't want to put
her down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like that deer.''
</P>
<P>
   So Pretty Girl's freedom ended in April 1998, while Perkins was
in the hospital with heart problems. Linn Valley officials took the
deer and locked it in the largest pen of the community's small
petting zoo. Ward said Perkins agreed to have the deer confined,
but Perkins insists she'd never consent to locking up a creature
that had grown up in such freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them when they put her in there that she'd be better
off dead,'' Perkins said. `` &UR; `I'd shoot her right now, if I had a
gun,' I told them. They don't want her to have a good life.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty Girl is being neglected in the petting zoo, Perkins and
her supporters say.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the deer and animals in the other pens had fresh
straw, food and water. But Perkins said that the animals usually
lived in mud and that the area was spruced up after a reporter
asked about it. The deer had mud halfway up its legs, and its water
bucket looked as if it had been lifted from mud recently and placed
on drier land. Fresh straw was spread over deep mud outside the
deer's corrugated metal shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Mills, a Wildlife and Parks conservation officer who
routinely checks on the deer's living conditions, said the zoo was
taking proper care of the animal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been up there that the deer didn't have food and
water,'' Mills said. ``All you have to do is look at the deer and
know that it's had plenty to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins' daughter, Marija Fitzpatrick of Fontana, thinks
captivity has instilled such a fear of humans in Pretty Girl that
the deer could be released into the wild and never bother anyone
again.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the zoo suggests that is unlikely. Pretty Girl stays
on the perimeter of the pen to be close to visitors as they walk
around. She enjoys being scratched and is especially fond of
touching humans' noses with her own in a sort of deer kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty Girl would not last long in the wild, said Ward, the park
department supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first hunter that came along would've popped it, because
it would've thought it was a friend,'' Ward said. ``I wish we
could've gotten to it sooner so we could've released it into the
wild. But because it was hand-raised, it was ruined.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins thought she had found a happy ending to the story a few
weeks ago, when she invited someone with plenty of land to take
Pretty Girl so the animal could run free again. But they found a
truck backed up to the zoo's fence, blocking the deer's way out.
</P>
<P>
   That is because officials caught wind of the plan, and only
someone with a permit can take the animal. Perkins and her
supporters hope to find someone with enough land to make Pretty
Girl happy and the right paperwork to satisfy the state.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter enjoys looking at the deer at the petting zoo, but
finding a better home for the animal sounds like a good idea to
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``That animal doesn't belong caged,'' Carpenter said. ``But at
the same time, it doesn't belong in a community with small
children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
