<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-JUDAISM-ART-825(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDAISM'S REFORM MOVEMENT REASSESSES TRADITIONS OF FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, N.Y., Calif., Pa., Texas)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw&AMP;lh) 
 By NADINE BROZAN and GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For Maron Waxman, practicing Judaism has been a
series of deepening experiences. She began lighting Sabbath candles
after her children were born, in the 1970s. In the next decade, she
started studying Hebrew. And from once having attended synagogue
only infrequently, Ms. Waxman has been going twice weekly of late,
Friday nights and Saturday mornings. She also serves as president
of the Stephen Wise Free Synagogue, a Manhattan congregation
affiliated with Judaism's Reform movement.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent airplane flight, she worked on a transliteration of
Hebrew prayers for members of her congregation who do not read that
language. Taking a break, she opened a book of Jewish short
stories. ``This is not what I would have been doing on a plane five
years ago,'' said Ms. Waxman, who is director of special publishing
at the American Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   Yet her closer attention to her faith's traditions is by no
means untypical among members of the Reform movement, Judaism's
largest liberal branch and one that is now undergoing some major
internal shifts.
</P>
<P>
   More than a century ago, Reform leaders declared practices like
wearing skullcaps and prayer shawls and using Hebrew in services to
be dated relics of the past, and emphasized instead a focus on
social ethics and a highly cerebral approach to the faith.
</P>
<P>
   But in a symbolically resonant gesture, Reform's rabbinic arm,
the Central Conference of American Rabbis, in Pittsburgh last week
adopted a document that encourages the movement's members to
explore traditional rituals.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbis' statement _ known as the Pittsburgh Principles _ is
advisory, far from binding in a movement that values individual
autonomy. But by commending study of the mitzvot, the sacred
obligations that include traditional rituals that are required in
more conservative branches of Judaism, the rabbis positively
acknowledged a trend among many of the 1.5 million Reform Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The mitzvot (Hebrew for commandments) are wide-ranging, covering
religious and social practices in Judaism. The Talmud counts 613
mitzvot in all, of which one, for example, would be the wearing of
tefillin, the small leather boxes, containing four passages of
Scripture, worn on the forehead and arm during morning prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking for guidance, for assistance, for help in
understanding what the Reform movement stands for,'' said Rabbi
Richard Levy of Los Angeles, the conference's immediate past
president, who wrote the draft statement on which the document is
based. ``The Pittsburgh Principles will help them understand
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The shift occurs amid growing public interest in ritual,
evidenced by a boom in books on prayer, meditation and other
aspects of religious tradition. Even the Latin Mass has made a
comeback in some Roman Catholic dioceses.
</P>
<P>
   The greater interest in tradition among Reform Jews is something
the movement's leaders attribute to several factors _ the
widespread spiritual searching going on in the United States, a
longing among liberal Jews to connect with their roots, and a
heightened interest in traditional practices among Reform rabbis,
who since 1971 have been required to spend a year of study in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Sheldon Zimmerman, president of Hebrew Union
College-Jewish Institute of Religion, said the desire of many to
reconnect with religious tradition came amid a decline in
anti-Semitism in the United States in which the larger society less
frequently reminds Jews of their identity. ``The question today is,
why be Jewish?'' he said. ``No other generation has had to answer
that question.''
</P>
<P>
   At Hebrew Union, Zimmerman said he saw some people studying to
be rabbis and cantors who had enrolled partly ``to find themselves
Jewishly.'' And during the study year in Israel, he said, many
students discover traditions that become important to them, ``like
wearing a prayer shawl, covering their heads, experimenting with
keeping kosher.''
</P>
<P>
   But interest in tradition is evident among lay people as well.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Paul Menitoff, the conference's executive vice president,
said he measured the change in Reform's culture by comparing what
he saw at two national meetings of the Union of American Hebrew
Congregations, the Reform movement's synagogue arm, that occurred
22 years apart in Dallas. At the first, in 1976, one had to look
``long and hard'' to find anyone wearing a skullcap at Sabbath
services. But at the meeting that took place there last year, he
said, at least half of those attending wore a head covering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a change in the sociology of what we're all
about,'' Menitoff said. ``Our parents and grandparents were coming
to this country and trying to become Americanized. They wanted
their kids to be as American as apple pie, and they did a very good
job.'' Members of the younger generations are now searching for
their roots, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of change can be found in many synagogues. Leonard
Gordon, a lawyer who arranges investments in companies that make
advanced medical devices, said he grew up six decades ago attending
a Reform synagogue in Cleveland where the rabbi kept ``secretly
kosher'' and no one wore a skullcap. Now, attending the Jewish
Center of the Hamptons in Easthampton, N.Y., he has started Torah
study (in English) and has been increasing his knowledge of Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, when Rabbi Peter Rubinstein was interviewed
for the job of senior rabbi at Central Synagogue in Manhattan, the
search committee asked if there was anything in particular it
should know about him. He replied that he wore a skullcap and
prayer shawl when he led services. The committee told him that
rabbis at Central did not do such things, he recalled. ``I said,
`You had better have a long discussion, not about me, but about who
you are as a Reform synagogue. Reform Judaism is about the ability
to make a decisions _ now you are telling me that we may not have a
choice.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Rubinstein got a call from the committee saying
that wearing a skullcap was not a litmus test; he was soon hired.
</P>
<P>
   At the Stephen Wise synagogue, where Ms. Waxman is president,
Rabbi Gary Bretton Granatoor said a ``remarkable transformation''
was going on, involving an increase in the use of Hebrew in
services, a greater level of singing and chanting by congregants
and a deepening interest among adults in religious education.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, some lay people want to handle duties, like
visiting the sick, that an earlier generation left largely to the
rabbis and cantors. ``There is a group in the synagogue called
Morei Derech, which means role models, and they are lay people
taking on responsibilities that in the past many congregants felt
professionals had to do,'' Granatoor said. ``That is exactly what
mitzvot is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet much of the embrace of tradition by Reform Jews is occurring
in the home, too.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Sue Ann Wasserman, associate director of the department of
religious living at the Union of American Hebrew Congregations,
said she maintained a kosher kitchen in her home, a practice begun
in her college years at Brandeis University. ``I wanted my daily
life to feel Jewish, to feel significantly Jewish,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wasserman said she would ``bend'' her dietary rules a bit
outside her home. ``I see it as a way of balancing my desire to
make friends of people in all faiths and communities,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, her department is developing a wallet-sized
card listing various traditional blessings, to be spoken at meals
or on other particular occasions. That such a thing would be in the
works, she said, is a sign of the times within the Reform movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are bringing their Jewishness out in public,'' she
said. ``Part of this whole trend really shows how comfortable Jews
are in America, how secure we are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
