<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   YELTSIN NAMES REFORMERS TO TOP ECONOMIC POSTS
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin placed two familiar and reform-minded
fiscal experts in top economic posts, but after a week of brutal
infighting among his closest advisers the question of who really
controls his latest Government seemed no clearer than before.
Yeltsin appointed Viktor Khristenko, a deputy prime minister until
last August's fiscal collapse, to the new post of First Deputy
Prime Minister for macroeconomics and financial policy. He also
named Mikhail Zadornov, the finance minister until this month, as
the government's special negotiator with the International Monetary
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   A CHILL ON FOOD REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   A series of state libel laws that were aimed at protecting the
makers of agricultural products from food scares is putting a chill
on the continuing debate about what the public should eat. Food
producers say they need protection against irresponsible claims,
but critics say the laws cut off debate on health issues.
</P>
<P>
   SPECULATORS BORROW YEN
</P>
<P>
   The spread between Japanese and higher American interest rates
has recently been widening, tempting speculators to borrow yen at
bargain-basement prices, convert them to dollars and invest them in
United States Treasury bills. The idea is to sell the bills later
on, pocket most of the interest payments and then repay the
low-interest yen debt.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT OFFICIAL TAKES SABBATICAL
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Myhrvold, Microsoft's chief technology officer, will take
a yearlong sabbatical to pursue his own scientific research and
travel, the company announced. Several news organizations reported
that Myhrvold was leaving after a falling out with Microsoft's
president, Steven Ballmer. Microsoft executives said the reports
were inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARKETS REOPEN
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets in the United States are open Tuesday; they
were closed Monday in observance of Memorial Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
