</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-MILITIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI-BACKED TROOPS START TO WITHDRAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ Troops from an Israeli-backed militia began withdrawing
Monday night from the northern-most fringe of the Israeli-occupied
``security zone'' in South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The pullback by the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army was seen as a
significant retreat from Hezbollah guerrillas waging a war of
attrition to end Israeli control of the south.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear whether the move could also be a step to the
wider Israeli withdrawal promised by Israel's newly elected Prime
Minister Ehud Barak from the nine-mile wide swath that Israel
occupies along the Lebanon-Israel border to protect itself from
hostile incursions.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 p.m. Monday night, three of the SLA's armored personnel
carriers, three aging tanks, and two trailer trucks transporting
heavy equipment formed a convoy exiting Jezzine.
</P>
<P>
   And as the exodus got under way, the people of the predominantly
Christian village were left fearing possible reprisals from
fighters of the Shiite Muslim Hezbollah, or ``Party of God.''
</P>
<P>
   The commander of Israel's South Lebanon Army, General Antoine
Lahd announced Monday that the phased withdrawal from Jezzine would
begin that night and continue over the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Lahd, a 70-year-old renegade Lebanese army officer, has been
sentenced to death for treason by the Beirut government for
commanding the 2,000-man strong militia since it was established in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters at his home in Marjayoun: ``The situation in
Jezzine could not handle any more deaths. Our aim in being in
Jezzine was to protect its people and we hope the government will
do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah has ratcheted up its attacks and proven a dogged and
determined opposition to the Israeli occupation. It often plants
roadside bombs around Jezzine and seriously wounded the militia's
senior Jezzine commander and killed one of his senior officers this
year. Five SLA militiamen have been killed and 34 wounded in the
fighting since January.
</P>
<P>
   Lahd conceded to reporters that his militia's morale had been
``battered'' but said he had offered to relocate the troops to
homes inside the occupation zone.
</P>
<P>
   But dozens of militiamen are switching sides, pledging
allegiance to the Lebanese government and vowing to remain in
Jezzine even if they face treason charges, according to Edmund
Rizk, a former member of parliament from Jezzine and a leader of
the town.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Monday night, Rizk said he had been
urging militiamen in the area to turn themselves in to the
authorities and assuring them that the Lebanese government and the
Lebanese Army would ensure ``Lebanese law is there to protect the
citizens of Jezzine.''
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah guerrillas see the SLA troops -- whose uniforms have
Hebrew writing on them and who receive monthly stipends from the
Israeli government-- as religious infidels and traitors.
</P>
<P>
   The pullback of SLA forces in Jezzine, observers say, will be an
important test of the Lebanese army's ability to preserve the rule
of law and to control Hezbollah's guerrillas in a town formerly
controlled by the Israeli-backed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah leader Sayyed Hassan Nasrallah vowed Sunday that his
forces would not enter Jezzine or use it as a base for launching
further attacks on the SLA and Israeli forces.
</P>
<P>
   But Nasrallah has made it clear that he believes militiamen who
collaborated with Israel should be tried in Lebanese courts.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah has offered amnesty to militia members who surrender,
but Nasrallah said, ``Those who serve the enemy until the last day
and have not renounced their collaboration when the enemy drops
them should not benefit from the amnesty.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said fears that Hezbollah would move quickly to apprehend
and execute milita members were ``exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Lahd reiterated Monday that even though he faces the death
penalty as a collaborator with Israel that he has nothing to fear
from an Israeli pullout of southern Lebanon because he is a citizen
of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   The same cannot be said of the several thousand Christian
residents who live in Jezzine and are widely viewed as
collaborators by Hezbollah. Their fate remains uncertain, as does
that of tens of thousands of Lebanese residents living in the
security zone whose husbands or sons supported, or as many claim,
were coerced into fighting with the SLA.
</P>
<P>
   The move out of Jezzine comes at a potentially critical moment
in the long war of attrition between Hezbollah and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In his election campaign, Israel's Prime Minister-elect Barak
promised to remove within one year the roughly 1,000 Israeli troops
stationed in the the self-proclaimed ``security zone'' that it has
occupied since 1985 to protect against border attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
