<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BANGED-UP EWING LUMBERS ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ His quadriceps and shoulders are the newest
additions to the list of injuries that have riddled Patrick Ewing.
They are just two more parts of an aging 36-year-old body that will
require extra attention, tape, ice, heating balm, Ibuprofen, what
have you from the medicine cabinet when Ewing leads the New York
Knicks against the Indiana Pacers Tuesday night in Game 2 of the
NBA Eastern Conference finals at Market Square Arena.
</P>
<P>
   They will go along with the aching ribs Ewing hurt in Game 2 of
the first-round series against the Miami Heat, the right wrist he
broke last season, and the sore Achilles' tendon that has bothered
him all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how hurt I am,'' Ewing said with a smile Monday,
refusing to divulge exactly what was ailing him.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, Ewing proved to be a big pain in the neck to
the Pacers as he led the Knicks to a 93-90 victory, snapping
Indiana's streak of 12 consecutive playoff victories at home. Ewing
grabbed 10 rebounds and scored 16 points in 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you read that right.
</P>
<P>
   Forty minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most minutes logged by any player on either side.
</P>
<P>
   That had Pacers coach Larry Bird shaking his head after Monday's
workout. Bird was amazed that Ewing could perform as well as he did
with the injuries he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick Ewing is hurt and he played 40 minutes Monday,'' Bird
deadpanned. ``Rik Smits has been hurting all year, and if we played
him 40 you wouldn't see him for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Was it a case of an aging warrior wanting to go out on his
shield?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is, but he's playing and that's all that
matters,'' Bird said. ``Patrick is a friend of mine, but I don't
want to hear about how hurt he is, because he played 40 minutes.
That's a lot of minutes for a guy who's hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pacers guard Mark Jackson, a former Knick teammmate of
Ewing's, ``He's milking it. If a guy who takes shots and makes
shots and then hobbles around . . . well, I just wonder when the
limp is going to disappear, like Keyser Soze.''
</P>
<P>
   Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy could only shrug when asked about
Ewing's health.
</P>
<P>
   ``It amazes me, too,'' he said. ``It's showing a tremendous will
to win and heart. And I know that it doesn't surprise Mark because
he's played with him.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ewing has aged, and as the injuries have mounted for the
former Cambridge Rindge &AMP; Latin and Georgetown star, the Knicks
have had to refocus their strategy of making him the focal point of
their offense.
</P>
<P>
   No longer are the Knicks cast in Ewing's lumbering image.
</P>
<P>
   This season, they have reinvented themselves as something of a
transition team, with a rotation of hyperquick guards including
Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell, who has provided a burst of
energy off the bench as the sixth man. Houston led the Knicks in
scoring Sunday with 19 points while Sprewell had 16 off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came down to crunch time, there was Ewing, hobbled
as ever, making 4 of 4 crucial free throws in the final 51.3
seconds to enable the Knicks to salt away Game 1, neutralizing
Indiana's home-court advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy was asked if there was any thought about giving Ewing
some rest at the end of Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``None _ zero,'' he said. ``He's finishing games. We want him in
there at the end of games.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not unlike a baseball manager coming out late in the game
to inquire about his ace on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what do they always say?'' Van Gundy asked. ``It's always,
`I'm fine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But wasn't Ewing tired?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, everybody is tired,'' Van Gundy said. ``Fatigue is a
part of it, but that's what makes him a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Van Gundy knows it is not in his best interest to expose
his aging center to 40 hard minutes of combat against the league's
elite centers. That is why Ewing has been insulated by a strong and
athletic frontcourt that includes power forwards Larry Johnson and
Kurt Thomas and a bench rotation of Chris Dudley and Marcus Camby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, because Patrick is so hobbled, we can't ask him to
play the top centers in the league for more than a few minutes at a
time in any game,'' Van Gundy said. ``But because of his great
heart and will to win, he'll give you what he can.''
</P>
<P>
   But now that the eighth-seeded Knicks are in the Eastern finals,
three victories from a berth in the NBA Finals, Ewing is prepared
to sacrifice his body in the quest for an elusive title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to get to the next level,'' Ewing said.
``And if we have the opportunity, then we have to try and seize it.
Whether it comes this year, or next year, my goal every year is to
win a championship. I think about it a lot. That's the only thing I
want to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what price his body has to pay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
