<SLUG> BC-LEGISLATURE-MOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATORY MOOD ENVELOPS TEXAS CAPITOL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ From high anxieties over the fate of pet bills
to the euphoric giddiness of sleep deprivation, the final days of
the 76th Texas Legislature rocked like an emotional roller-coaster
that ground to a halt Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the final days before allies and adversaries ultimately bid
each other farewell, a celebratory mood enveloped the Capitol as
strains of mariachi music rose through the rotunda.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators gave a standing ovation to Gov. George W. Bush at a
fajita lunch under a blue-and-white striped canopy on the front
lawn of the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like the flame and you all are the moths,'' Bush told
reporters as festivities began and a clutch of television cameras
followed his every move. As photo opportunities go, this one proved
ample with Bush working the crowd of state politicians and national
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's human nature when people are excited about the potential
prospect of their governor running for president to basically try
to say that everything has presidential overtones,'' said Bush's
spokeswoman Karen Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think if the sun comes up tomorrow someone will probably
say it's because Gov. Bush is running for president. We all know it
would have come up tomorrow anyway, but ... ''
</P>
<P>
   In certain respects, partisan clashes were more apparent during
a session that careened between powerful feelings on hate crimes,
parental notifications for teens seeking abortions, school vouchers
and tax-cutting zeal.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the previous session, however, this one had no match for
the infamous Memorial Day Massacre of 1997 when Rep. Arlene
Wohlgemuth, R-Burleson, killed the remaining bills on the day's
calendar in retaliation for the same fate on a parental
notification bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of partisan activity, more so than I've ever
seen. But in the end people seemed to be in good moods, happy to be
going home and proud of their accomplishments,'' said Rep. Elliott
Naishtat, D-Austin, chairman of the House Human Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   When the Texas House reconvened after lunch, female members of
both parties joined ranks to put their sometimes puffed-up male
colleagues in place. They gathered around Speaker Pete Laney,
D-Hale Center, hoisting cigars and then proceeded on their ``cigar
strut'' through the chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get even with the guys,'' Wohlgemuth said.
</P>
<P>
   Goofiness was in high gear, too, as Rep. Bob Hunter, R-Abilene,
distributed a list of little-known facts about House members.
Several, one discovers, have celebrity connections.
</P>
<P>
   The bespectacled Anna Mowery, R-Fort Worth, once jitterbugged
with Larry Hagman of ``Dallas fame. Naishtat once had a date with
Leslie Gore, famous for the pop tune, ``It's My Party and I'll Cry
if I Want To.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Wolens, D-Dallas, who was accused by an anti-abortion
lobbyist this session of ``hoodwinking'' colleagues, does turn out
to have some talent at sleight of hand. Wolens, 48, performed a
magic act for President Lyndon B. Johnson as a kid back in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Other facts might better have been left untold. Leticia Van de
Putte, D-San Antonio, takes ``long, hot, soothing bubble baths''
and watches the Public Education Committee on television. Dawnna
Dukes, D-Austin, admits to having one birthmark shaped like an
angel and another like a hamburger. And, does anyone really want to
know that Toby Goodman, R-Arlington, claims to have once kidnapped
a buffalo?
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the session, talk buzzed about the fact that
conservative Republican Rep. Talmadge Heflin of Houston had refused
a haircut since last July when he didn't like the results. The
hefty-bodied Heflin with fading blonde locks touching his
shoulders, however, looked more like something out of the
Elizabethan era than the hippie one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another reason for them to harass me,'' he said.
``They always found plenty, so it's no difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of lawmakers sported new looks, whether by design or spoof.
Rep. Ron Wilson, D-Houston, spent much of the session wearing dark
glasses in both chambers.
</P>
<P>
   The photogenic Republican Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, however, wasn't
so sure he liked being shown wearing lacy ruffles and disco-dancing
garb as ``Austin Perry'' in a movie poster with '60s slogans such
as ``Groovy Baby'' _ a takeoff on the Austin Powers movies. Perry
offered Monday that the look comes about 30 years too late.
</P>
<P>
   Perry wasn't the only politician whose image underwent brilliant
transformations by Mark Loeffler, aide to Sen. Mike Jackson, R-La
Porte, who runs a company called Quantum Graphics. For a look at
``Senate Wars: Vouchers II, The Phantom Menace,'' starring Bush and
Republican Sens. Florence Shapiro of Plano, Teel Bivens of Amarillo
and Bill Ratliff of Mount Pleasant, visit the Web site at
www.onr.com/user/leff/images/movies.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, who was at the forefront of several legislative
skirmishes, also shows up on Cameron Diaz's body in a slinky little
dress. She gets top billing in ``There's Something about Flo'' _ a
story about men and commitment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
