<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7609 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIANANMEN-ANNIVERSARY     05-31 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIANANMEN-ANNIVERSARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 YEARS LATER, HINTS OF MORE FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Ten years since tanks rumbled and fired down the
Avenue of Everlasting Peace, killing at least hundreds of
reform-minded protesters, China is in many ways a freer place than
it was _ thanks to the same ruling party that crushed those who
dared to demand change.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the anniversary of the June 4, 1989, massacre,
most Chinese people prefer not to talk about it, children too young
to remember are not told what happened, and democracy activists
remain exiled, jailed or under surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities made sure there would be no significant memorials on
the anniversary by hauling off at least 50 dissidents in the last
few weeks, cutting off reception of most foreign and cable TV
channels, ordering news blocked to pager systems and computer
networks, and boarding up Tiananmen Square with the excuse that it
needs renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Even without such measures, after a decade of anti-June 4
propaganda and steady changes in everyday life, it is unclear how
many would have taken the chance to commemorate the date.
Dissidents still committed to ideals of political freedom say that
the masses support them, but that the government terrorized them
into silence in 1989 _ and has bought their quiescence with
gradually rising incomes.
</P>
<P>
   But those are not the only reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the demands of the student-led demonstrators in
Tiananmen Square _ with the notable exceptions of democracy and
full political freedoms _ have been met in the last decade by a
Communist Party resolved on doing what it must to keep its
half-century hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   Loyalty once inspired obedience to the party. But the days of an
unquestioning Chinese public cut off from other influences are
over, and the Tiananmen massacre exposed a brute force that shocked
many party members who had been true believers. For a variety of
reasons, the leadership has had to change with the times.
</P>
<P>
   The Tiananmen Square protesters _ who at their peak drew 1
million to the streets of the capital and millions more in about 80
cities nationwide _ were demanding not only democracy, but
practical reform: a more accountable government, a crackdown on
corruption and nepotism, a halt to inflation, a purge of
conservative leaders, the freedom to choose one's job, and greater
freedom of ideas. In differing degrees, they have gotten most of
those demands, making the movement a backdoor success, despite its
brutal suppression.
</P>
<P>
   At Beijing University, the hotbed of student activism, many
young people today echo the thoughts of a 20-year-old life sciences
student surnamed Chu, who reflected recently on the upcoming
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what students wanted 10 years ago, we have gained
since then. Economically, China has turned a planned economy to
more of a market economy, and our system is more connected to the
global economy. Politically, we have . . . more freedoms and
rights. The government is doing anticorruption work, making
reforms, and working hard,'' Chu said. ``I cannot say everything is
perfect, but we are going in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   It is often forgotten that Tiananmen protesters did not demand
the overthrow of the government, and even many dissidents say they
would prefer the Communist Party to reform itself to ensure smooth,
peaceful change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the government had some ability to change and would
have to reform because of pressure from the people,'' said Jiang
Qisheng, a former June 4th student leader at People's University.
Jiang spoke with the Globe two days before he was detained,
apparently in a pre-anniversary sweep of dissidents, and his family
says he has been incommunicado since May 18.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International has documented 241 people still imprisoned
for June 4th activities, but said the true figure is much higher.
And a Hong Kong human rights group estimated that 2,000 are still
in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Its intolerance for dissent notwithstanding, the government has
reformed in many ways in the aftermath of the crackdown. The party
launched a tough antigraft campaign _ the original demand of
Tiananmen protesters _ that has punished hundreds of thousands of
officials in the last decade, with some even sentenced to death.
People are no longer assigned jobs, inflation was reined in, and
ideas and books that do not openly flaunt party authority are
generally tolerated. Most important, most wallets are fatter.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the price of these changes has been a tacit agreement not to
question the party, and to accept its view that limits on freedom
ensure stability and are in China's best interest. It is an
oft-repeated scene here that China would have followed the former
Soviet Union _ political and economic chaos _ if Tiananmen
protesters had introduced democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang insisted, however, that there are ``potentially more
people to support the movement today, but they wouldn't come onto
the streets now, (except) maybe if the economy collapsed. First
they'd come for jobs, then for democracy. People do want more
money,'' he added, ``but they want more freedom, too. The two are
not contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   The government, meanwhile, has undertaken some reforms that are
boosting its legitimacy, but which in time could undermine its
authority. It has modernized the legal system, retired laws against
``counterrevolutionary'' crimes, and given citizens leeway to sue
if they face official abuse. Village elections have been gradually
introduced nationwide, bringing the power of the vote and a
more-accountable government to an estimated 600 million of China's
1.3 billion citizens _ even though for now, most candidates remain
party members. Beijing signed the UN charter on civil and political
rights, and although it is not observing it yet, it might have to
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   There are continual fits and starts, however, as the government
wrestles with how much freedom is too much. Internet access is
widespread in urban China, but Web sites perceived as
controversial, including the Boston Globe's, are often blocked.
Ideas can be discussed freely at home, but magazines that delve too
much into politics are censored or shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Dissidents were allowed last year to register the China
Democracy Party _ the first opposition party since the communist
revolution. But the party was soon outlawed and its three top
leaders sentenced in summary trials to 11- and 13-year prison
terms. Three other Democracy Party leaders were allowed to campaign
for local Beijing elections to the National People's Congress last
fall, but they say authorities followed them and confiscated their
brochures.
</P>
<P>
   Due to halting progress, however, the public seems less likely
to run to the ramparts for June 4th-style ``radicals.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is not to say that 10 years after Tiananmen, China is a
nation of satisfied customers. On the contrary; there are more
protests than ever before, though none as big or as potentially
destabilizing as the Tiananmen movement.
</P>
<P>
   Academics, labor leaders, and independent groups record nearly
daily protests across China, most related to livelihood issues.
There are tens of millions of jobless, pensioners without support
checks, farmers locked in land and resource disputes, and peasants
fighting high taxes. And there are those who hate the government,
but most are too terrified to protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so afraid of the government, we don't want to say
anything about politics. We're weak, we're scared,'' cried a
64-year-old food vendor, dropping to her knees and sobbing..
</P>
<P>
   The woman's friend said she was beaten by authorities during the
Tiananmen demonstration. Because of legal freedoms granted since
the protest,the woman is trying to sue for damages in local court.
But in a sign of lingering official paranoia about dissent and a
free press, the woman's conversation was monitored by two
plainclothes security officers following this reporter around town.
</P>
<P>
   Surveillance of dissidents has increased before the anniversary,
with some detained or kept under house arrest and others followed.
About 10 plainclothes officers trailed two leaders of the banned
China Democracy Party and the wife of a jailed founder of the party
to a recent lunchtime interview _ and arranged with the restaurant
for a special room to be used. But that did not stop the dissidents
from speaking their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the current government could reform itself, that would be
best,'' said Zha Jianguo, 48, a vice chairman of the outlawed party
and a Communist Party cadre until he quit over June 4th. ``As soon
as people are not scared and pressured by the government, they will
stand up and ask for democracy. Maybe in three years, maybe five
years. Definitely within 10 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
