<HEADLINE>
BUSH HONORS MEDAL OF HONOR WINNERS FROM TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In comments both patriotic and presidential,
Gov. George W. Bush told a Memorial Day audience at the Texas State
Cemetery on Monday that America owes its heroes a commitment to
preserve what many of them died for.
</P>
<P>
   While a campaign consultant shot video footage that may later be
used in his White House campaign, the governor dedicated a monument
to 83 Medal of Honor winners from Texas and presented a special
citation to the survivors of a fallen World War II hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``New threats are replacing old enemies. Unstable dictators seek
weapons of mass destruction. Regional power grabs become global
crises,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is still America that preserves the peace. Our nation
still determines the future of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Several national reporters covered Bush's appearance, which came
on the last day of a mostly successful legislative session and may
have been a warm-up for the Republican governor's first
out-of-state presidential campaign trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I begin to move around, I'm going to start talking about
foreign policy, how the military relates to diplomacy, the need to
make sure that we have a strong and vibrant military,'' Bush told
reporters later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can either seize the moment as we head into an uncertain
century, or we can shirk from duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is scheduled to begin a campaign swing to Iowa and New
Hampshire on June 12, is still developing his foreign policy
credentials. Just last week, he jumped into an international
controversy by criticizing the Clinton administration's response to
reports of Chinese spying.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the governor said he was honored to ``shake the hand
of freedom's heroes'' and remember how liberty has been ``measured
in young lives that ended so suddenly, so tragically, so very far
from home.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States needed a ``clear military mission in
times of crisis'' and must resolve ``never to multiply our missions
while cutting our capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush posthumously presented the Texas Legislative Medal of Honor
to First Lt. Jack Llewellyn Knight, a Texas Army National Guard
officer from Garner in Parker County, who was killed in Burma in
1945.
</P>
<P>
   Bush presented the medal to Knight's brother, Bill Knight of
Mineola, and sister, June Knight Campbell of Weatherford.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
