<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN NAMES TWO REFORMERS TO TOP ECONOMIC POSTS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin placed two familiar and
reform-minded fiscal experts in top economic posts on Monday, but
after a week of brutal infighting among his closest advisers the
question of who really controls his latest government seemed no
clearer than before.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin appointed Viktor Khristenko, a deputy prime minister
until last August's fiscal collapse, to the new post of first
deputy prime minister for Macroeconomics and Financial Policy. He
named Mikhail Zadornov, the finance minister until this past month,
to be the government's special negotiator with the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Both appointments seemed to have been sought by Yeltsin's latest
prime minister, Sergei Stepashin, who has been locked in a bitter _
and losing _ battle with rival political forces to place loyalists
in senior government jobs. Many of the jobs with direct control
over money and fiscal policy appear to have been filled not by
Stepashin's allies, but by people tied to Boris Berezovsky, the
supposed billionaire businessman and an on-and-off intimate of the
Yeltsin family.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Stepashin's own future seemed in some doubt last Friday
when his highest-ranking appointee, Zadornov, abruptly quit the
macroeconomics and fiscal policy post. Zadornov said that Yeltsin
had refused to give him the authority he needed to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   That sparked a weekend of furious and nearly unanimous attacks
on Yeltsin, in which he was accused of handing the keys to the
treasury to Berezovsky's clique and of sacrificing his own place in
history as the father of Russian democracy.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Stepashin tried to declare the entire affair over,
saying, ``There will be no more sudden resignations.'' Yeltsin's
spokesman, Dimitry Yakushkin, called speculation over the power
struggle an ``absolutely artificial polemic'' and said the new
appointments should put an end to it.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview on Monday with the newspaper Izvestia,
Zadornov seemed to suggest that a struggle for control not only
existed, but had yet to end.
</P>
<P>
   With Stepashin's appointment to succeed Yegeny Primakov as prime
minister, he was quoted as saying, ``here was a unique chance to
resolve the political crisis and begin effective work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But subsequent events have nullified the political
achievements,'' he said. ``It is Stepashin who is preventing the
situation from sliding into deeper crisis, the end of which no one
can now foresee. We are under the impression of only one, albeit
tumultuous, week. Final assessments and conclusions should not be
made hastily.''
</P>
<P>
   With the completion of Stepashin's Cabinet, analysts said, the
question now becomes which of the government's top economic
advisers will end up with the lion's share of authority.
</P>
<P>
   Khristenko shares that power with another first deputy prime
minister, Nikolai Aksyonenko, who formally is in charge of
industrial policy but who already has said that he will exercise
full control of economic policy. Aksyonenko, until recently the
railways minister, is regarded by political handicappers as an ally
of Berezovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcements should please Western lenders, who are
still trying to negotiate repayment of billions of dollars in
Russian and Soviet debt as well as new loans intended to keep
Russia afloat until its economy improves. Zadornov already has been
handling the major negotiations with the International Monetary
Fund. Khristenko is experienced in international finance as well,
having served as Russia's representative to the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   One experienced western financial analyst, Charles Blitzer, the
director of emerging markets research for the London office of
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, said the appointments, while
comforting, may not matter all that much in the long run because
Russia has little choice but to adopt economic reforms. The
alternative would be to default on even more of its worldwide
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, I'm not sure it makes any difference,'' he said.
``Russia's going to do its best to meet the terms the IMF sets out
regardless of who's running the negotiations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
