u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLOTS-DRUGS-BOS &LR;      05-31 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOTS-DRUGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUPER ASPIRIN' BOOSTS CLOT-BUSTING THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new regimen for treating heart attacks promises to rescue
thousands of patients for whom the current clot-busting therapy
does not work.
</P>
<P>
   Adding a ``super-aspirin'' drug called abciximab to the standard
clot-dissolver, dubbed TPA, boosts the chances of restoring normal
blood flow within the stricken heart by 67 percent, according to a
large international study being published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the new treatment represents the biggest
advance in heart attack treatment since clot-busting drugs came
into routine use 15 years ago. Such drugs interrupt a heart attack
in progress by breaking up the clump of platelets and proteins that
has shut off blood flow to a region of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of clot-busting therapy, technically called
thrombolysis, has revolutionized heart attack care by rescuing
heart muscle from certain death. Not only has this reduced
immediate mortality from heart attacks, but it has left survivors
with less-damaged hearts.
</P>
<P>
   But the best clot-dissolving therapy restores normal blood flow
only about half of the time, and even then, new clots form in 5 to
10 percent of patients. The double-drug therapy raised the success
rate to nearly 80 percent within 90 minutes of treatment onset.
</P>
<P>
   The study results ``have opened a new era'' in the treatment of
heart attacks, Dr. J. Ward Kennedy and Dr. Michael L. Stadius of
the University of Washington declared in a commentary on the
research in the American Heart Association journal, Circulation.
</P>
<P>
   The authors estimate that the new double-drug treatment will
save 20 additional lives for every 1,000 heart attack patients who
receive it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one-two punch is much more successful,'' said Dr. Elliott
M. Antman of Brigham and Women's Hospital, who was the study's
principal investigator. ``Not only are a higher proportion of
arteries being cleared, but the arteries are being opened faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Speed is critical in minimizing damage to heart muscle
threatened by a coronary clot, Antman noted. ``The amount of muscle
salvaged is one of the most important factors in determining how
well a patient will do in terms of mortality and risk of subsequent
heart attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The research project goes by the acronym TIMI-14 because it is
the fourteenth major report from a study called Thrombolysis in
Myocardial Infarction. It involved 888 heart attack patients at 63
hospitals in North America, Britain, the Netherlands, France, and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Participants received an array of clot-busting drug treatments.
The one that worked best used half the standard dose of TPA, also
called alteplase, along with an infusion of abciximab, which goes
by the brand name ReoPro. The study was funded by Eli Lilly Inc.,
and Centocor, which make alteplase and abciximab, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   An hour after the drug treatments were started, 72 percent of
patients receiving both drugs had normal blood flow restored in the
clogged artery, compared to 43 percent of those receiving TPA
alone. After 90 minutes, the two-drug group had a 77 percent
success rate compared to 62 percent for those getting only TPA.
</P>
<P>
   The double-drug treatment achieved a success rate nearly equal
to the ``gold standard'' of acute heart attack treatment, an
artery-clearing procedure called balloon angioplasty. But the drug
treatment does not require highly skilled angioplasty teams at the
ready, so it may be more widely used than angioplasty ever could
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for some major centers to embrace'' the
TPA-ambicixmab treatment, reserving angioplasty for heart attack
patients with underlying bleeding disorders or other reasons why
they should not have the drug therapy, Kennedy and Stadius wrote in
their editorial.
</P>
<P>
   The new evidence may also lessen the need for more hospitals to
develop angioplasty programs, at least on the basis of their
usefulness in treating heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Antman said the drug combination is more effective because
abciximab precisely targets platelets, sticky, disk-shaped blood
cells that make up a major part of blood clots. On the other hand,
TPA works on a clot protein called fibrin.
</P>
<P>
   By attacking both clot elements, the drug combination seems to
dissolve it more completely and quickly.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, TPA has the undesirable effect of activating
platelets, which may explain why some heart attack patients develop
new clots after the initial one is dissolved. Abciximab, a highly
specific artificial antibody, blocks this process by inhibiting
platelet activation.
</P>
<P>
   Aspirin, which is widely used in heart attack care, also blocks
platelet activiation. But abciximab is much more potent, which is
why the drug is often called a ``super-aspirin.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of the two-drug treatment opens the door to a range
of new, experimental drug combinations to clear coronary clots even
more effectively, Kennedy and Stadius said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
