<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7618 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      05-31 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX COME FROM BEHIND TO TAME TIGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's too bad for the Red Sox that May is over. There
hasn't been this much fun around Fenway Park since 1986. You know,
the one they still call, ``That Championship Season.''
</P>
<P>
   If you were among the 27,883 in attendance or near a television
set Monday, you probably got a lot of enjoyment out of the Old
Towne Team's 8-7 victory over the Detroit Tigers. Can you remember
the last time the Red Sox overcame a 6-1 deficit with three home
runs, then held off the visitors with a magnificent rescue by the
oft-maligned bullpen?
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have won four in a row, went 20-8 in May, and increased
their lead in the American League East to 1 1/2 games over the
Yankees, who lost to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   What happened Monday should be ample evidence that this is a
team we are going to enjoy the next couple of months. The three
home runs, each of which came with a man on base, were off the bats
of Brian Daubach, Jason Varitek, and Troy O'Leary, none of whom
figures to break any slugging records. O'Leary's blast in the
seventh inning broke a 6-6 tie. Is there anything that could make
the Fenway Faithful happier?
</P>
<P>
   How can you lose when your starting pitcher has his left
shoulder nearly pulled out of the socket while fielding a ground
ball in the second inning, then demands to be left in? Mark
Portugal's wisdom in the situation could be questioned but not his
courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of weird stuff out there today,'' said
Varitek, whose homer also came in the seventh, as a pinch hitter,
and tied the game at 6-6. ``But we kept plugging away. Tip your hat
to the bullpen: Pat Rapp, John Wasdin, Mark Guthrie, Derek Lowe,
and Tom Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough day for Portugal. You have to admire a guy who
gets his shoulder thrown out of the socket on a ball hit back to
him and he stays in the game. That shows you how much of a
competitor he is and how much we're going to need him down the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this luck? After O'Leary's homer, Mike Stanley came to the
plate knowing that the Tigers have not hesitated to pinch inside
lately, but when he got hit on a 3-and-2 pitch by Matt Anderson, it
was the Tigers who lost two players and manager Larry Parrish
because of it. All were thrown out by plate umpire Chuck
Meriwether, who had seen a similar act in Cleveland last week
involving the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're probably thinking about what happened in Cleveland,''
said Meriwether. ``I'm not. Every game is different. I make a
judgment on a situation as it happens right then.''
</P>
<P>
   Said crew chief Jim Evans: ``Our response is because there was
provocation _ two home runs given up. If not, maybe a warning at
that time would have been sufficient. But in that situation, you're
going to have a further incident in the game if you don't do
something at that point. You've got to take action right there. If
he wasn't throwing at him, it's a bad time to let one get away
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley said pitches that stray are not uncommon after home
runs. He expected one right away, but not on 3 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what he was thinking,'' said Stanley. ``It's
tough to say. It was just the decision by the umpire that it was
intentional. I was on my heels with the first pitch. I didn't know
what was going on. But after that, maybe that one got away from
him.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Sox began May, they were 11-11 and struggling to find
an identity. The lineup was not set. Injuries to Nomar Garciaparra
and Gordon made you wonder whether this would be a .500 club all
year. But they reeled off their first 20-victory month since 1996,
doing major damage at the expense of Anaheim, Texas, New York, and
Cleveland, all teams with playoff ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to come from behind and score 6-7 runs against
major league pitching,'' said Daubach, whom Varitek was pinch
hitting for and who was the first person to greet Varitek in the
dugout. ``But we kept playing hard every inning and didn't give up.
We peck away and peck away and then we got a couple of home runs
for the win.''
</P>
<P>
   The game-winner by O'Leary went to left field and got an assist
from the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the wind was blowing out,'' said O'Leary, ``and I was
just hoping it was to the wall. The next thing I knew, I looked up
and it was out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were happy to peck away. But the big damage was done by
Varitek. I got in there and the wind was blowing out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some strange things early and we fell behind,''
Williams said. ``But we fought back, tied it, and went ahead. We're
resilient. The big middle innings by Rapp picked us up and gave us
a chance to get our offense going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
