<HEADER>
A7619 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-REHAB-2TAKES     05-31 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-REHAB-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REHAB CLINICS IN DOCTORS' OFFICES RAISE LEGAL QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Creative entrepreneurs and some doctors are seizing
on a change in Medicare rules to establish part-time rehabilitation
clinics in doctors' offices, an arrangement that critics say comes
dangerously close to violating fraud, abuse and kickback laws.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, trying to save money for Medicare, Congress
changed the rules governing physical therapy and similar services
provided to people with a wide range of illnesses and injuries. The
revision limited the amount that Medicare would pay for each
patient's treatment and established a fee schedule that took effect
this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the change had a surprising, unintended consequence.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, health care businesses seized on the new
rules as a way to make money by increasing the numbers of patients
being treated in doctors offices even though the per-patient fees
were not as lucrative as before. The businesses sent unsolicited
invitations to doctors across the country, proposing to establish
part-time rehabilitation clinics in their offices.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors did not have to do anything but provide office space
for a few hours a day, three days a week. In return, they were
told, they would receive up to $3,000 in ``monthly compensation,''
payable ``upon receipt from Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrangements, described by one Democratic congressman as
``too good to be true,'' show why it is difficult to control
Medicare costs. In this case, while the fees per patient were
limited, enterprising businesses found a way to provide more
services to more patients in the fast-growing Medicare market. They
simply followed the old maxim that when prices are cut, make up the
difference in volume.
</P>
<P>
   D. McCarty Thornton, chief counsel to the inspector general of
the Department of Health and Human Services, which runs Medicare,
said he had received reports of the new arrangements cropping up
around the country. Thornton said the government was investigating
such arrangements because some of the proposals raised ``serious
questions under the federal fraud and abuse laws, in particular the
anti-kickback statute.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, it is a crime to pay, solicit or receive anything
of value in return for the referral of Medicare patients, or for
buying or leasing any goods or services under Medicare. A separate
law says that if a doctor has a financial relationship with a
company, the doctor may not refer patients to that company for any
``designated health services,'' like physical therapy, occupational
therapy or speech-language pathology services. Those are the very
services provided in outpatient rehabilitation clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies involved in the growing business is Senior
Health Care of Savannah, Ga., which in a solicitation letter
invites doctors to ``participate in an exciting program offered
through Medicare.'' The company says it is careful to keep its
program within legal limits, employing experts in Medicare payment
policy to ensure that it is acting properly.
</P>
<P>
   In its solicitations, the company proposes to use the doctor's
office as an ``off-site location'' for a clinic known in the
Medicare law as a comprehensive outpatient rehabilitation facility,
or CORF.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to chiropractors in various states, Dr. John P.
Olevnik of Senior Health Care said: ``The benefit for you is that
for every month you provide the CORF with a minimum of five new
patients to treat in your office, I will reimburse you $21 per
square foot for the space I use. Up to a maximum of $3,000 per
month.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Health Care said, in other materials made available to
doctors, that it was ``currently in the process of securing CORF
licenses nationwide.'' Such outpatient clinics are not new, the
company said, but in 1999, for the first time, they ``will be
allowed to make a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   By accepting this proposal, Senior Health Care said, doctors can
expand the range and scope of services available to Medicare
patients, ``at absolutely no cost'' to the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Stroke victims, people who have fallen and broken a hip, and
people severely injured in auto accidents are among those who could
benefit from the services of such clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Health Care said it worked with a Florida company, Total
Health Care Consulting, to set up the clinics in doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``A single CORF license can have 100 or more off-sites'' in the
same state, the companies tell doctors. ``Only the primary (main)
CORF facility will be subjected to a certification inspection. The
off-sites have no inspection.''
</P>
<P>
   Total Health Care Consulting said in an information package for
doctors that it intended to set up comprehensive outpatient
rehabilitation clinics in all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Health Care contends that its arrangement complies with
the law because it pays doctors ``fair market value'' for the space
it rents from them. And it says it does not require the doctors to
send patients to the clinics operating in their offices _ even if
some solicitation letters suggested such a link.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are well aware of the law,'' said Benjamin S. Eichholz, a
co-owner of Senior Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTION TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers and medical groups are advising doctors to be
careful. The Florida Chiropractic Association sent a bulletin to
its members urging them to ``use caution in responding to any
solicitations'' from companies that wanted to rent space in their
offices.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Downing, executive director of the California
Chiropractic Association, said doctors should ``seek the advice of
a lawyer familiar with Medicare, unlawful referral and general
health care issues before signing any contract or rental
agreement.'' And the American Podiatric Medical Association told
its members to exercise ``extreme caution.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., said: ``The incentive for gross
overutilization of services in these kinds of deals is enormous.
Implicit in the deal is the message, `Doctor, you can make a lot of
money by renting spare office space to me, but I will have to keep
busy _ through referrals of your patients for rehab and physical
therapy.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John B. Collet Jr., a podiatrist in Ventura, Calif., said
that he had initially agreed to let a rehabilitation clinic rent
space in his office, but that he now wanted to wait until the
federal government clarified the legality of such arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is perilous,'' Collet said. ``I don't want to get into a
conflict of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract does not appear to require Collet to send patients
to the clinic. But, he said, after he signed the document, it
became clear to him, in discussions with owners of the clinic, that
``I'd be a source of patients for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, Medicare generally paid 80 percent of the
``reasonable costs'' that outpatient clinics incurred in providing
therapy and other rehabilitation services to Medicare patients.
Federal auditors examined the claims and could deny payment for
costs deemed to be excessive.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, as a result of the Balanced Budget Act of 1997,
Medicare began using a fee schedule like the one used to pay
doctors. Clinics that hold their costs below the fees paid by
Medicare can keep the difference. Congress saw this as a way to
control costs, since Medicare payments would be fixed in advance.
But some businesses see it as a new opportunity to make profits.
</P>
<P>
   Literature sent out by Senior Health Care tells doctors: ``This
is a win-win situation for all involved. The patient can get needed
therapy without having to travel to a hospital or rehab center, and
the off-site receives compensation for providing space for the
therapist to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Under such an arrangement, according to material from Total
Health Care Consulting, health care providers can ``receive a
rental rebate'' while expanding services to their patients.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Health Care says it uses the services of Carlos A.
Carrero and Jorge L. Narvaez to help bill Medicare. The two men
used to work at Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Florida, the local
Medicare contractor, which reviews and pays Medicare claims on
behalf of the government. Their company, based in Jacksonville,
Fla., offers advice on Medicare billing techniques to clients in
Florida, Georgia, Ohio, Texas and other states.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Carrero, a former auditing manager at Blue
Cross and Blue Shield, said: ``As a taxpayer, I congratulate the
government for investigating the outpatient rehabilitation
facilities. If the contract or the rent is in exchange for
patients, I have to agree 100 percent with Stark. That's a no-no.
If anyone is offering to pay rent as compensation for the referral
of Medicare patients, that's a questionable practice, to say the
least.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1, the new limits on Medicare coverage of therapy
services took effect. There is a limit of $1,500 a year on physical
therapy for each beneficiary and a separate $1,500 limit for
occupational therapy services, which enable people to take care of
themselves and engage in productive activity.
</P>
<P>
   Karen A. Monson, director of Medicare benefits integrity at Blue
Cross and Blue Shield of Florida, said some clinics had found
``ways to circumvent the limits.'' For example, Ms. Monson said,
they may provide physical therapy, but bill Medicare for
respiratory therapy, which is not subject to an annual limit.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Monson did not identify any of the clinics but said her
office was looking into this practice.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ms. Monson said, some clinics provide physical
therapy to the same patient at more than one site, so it is
difficult for the government to keep track of expenses incurred by
that beneficiary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
