<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PENTAGON-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO BOMBING HELPS KOSOVO REBELS IN BATTLE FOR STRATEGIC MOUNTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Unmoved by signs that President Slobodan Milosevic
of Yugoslavia might be prepared to negotiate a settlement, NATO
carried out withering new air strikes across Yugoslavia on Monday,
seizing on a day of clear weather to attack targets from the
capital to the increasingly tense border with Albania.
</P>
<P>
   NATO jets, including American A-10s, carried out a series of
strikes against Yugoslav army units that NATO said were trying to
repel an offensive by the Kosovo Liberation Army, the Kosovo
Albanian separatist rebels, along Kosovo's southwestern border.
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO has not coordinated its attacks with the rebels,
NATO spokesmen in Brussels said the strikes effectively aided the
rebels' efforts to seize a strategic mountain, Mount Pastrik, which
straddles the border between Yugoslavia and Albania.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO spokesman, Col. Konrad Freytag, said that Yugoslavia's
Serbian-led army had massed troops and weapons and had been driving
the rebels off the mountain's slope and toward Albania on Sunday.
On Monday, the low-flying A-10s, designed to find and destroy tanks
and other armored weapons, attacked the site of the Serbian
buildup.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO aircraft are taking advantage of this opportunity to
attack the now more prominent concentration of Serbian war
machinery,'' Freytag said.
</P>
<P>
   With clear skies and new authority to expand the air raids, NATO
has conducted some of the most sustained attacks since the bombing
began 69 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav capital, Belgrade, endured a heavy night of
bombardment late Sunday and early Monday that knocked out an
electrical tower. On Monday night, two more towers were struck,
once again plunging the city into darkness. Yugoslavia's official
news agency reported air strikes across the country again on Monday
and Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesmen said on Monday that the alliance had conducted
323 combat strikes in the previous 24 hours, the fourth straight
day that American and NATO aircraft had flown such a large number
of raids.
</P>
<P>
   The intensification of the attacks has coincided with still more
instances of NATO bombs and missiles killing civilians. A day after
striking a heavily used bridge near an open air market, killing at
least nine people, NATO strikes on Monday hit a hospital complex in
the Serbian city of Surdulica, killing 17 civilians and wounding
43.
</P>
<P>
   Freytag said NATO aircraft had successfully attacked a military
barracks and an ammunition storage area in Surdulica, but he said
he could not confirm any attack on the hospital complex.
</P>
<P>
   Western journalists went to the scene and reported seeing both
bodies and evidence of damage to the hospital buildings. On Monday
night, official Yugoslav news reports said NATO missiles hit an
apartment building in another city, Novi Pazar, killing at least 10
people.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has repeatedly expressed regret for the deaths of
civilians, but on M Monday, its chief spokesman, Jamie Shea,
sounded increasingly frustrated with the criticism of NATO's
mistakes, saying the bombings would go on undeterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been engaged in this because the government in
Belgrade has been deliberately targeting large numbers of its own
civilian population for months,'' Shea said. ``We have made it
clear that we would have preferred to solve this through other
means, except the use of force, but we are not going to be
deterred, having started to do this, until our objectives are
met.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest raids, NATO said, its aircraft also struck highway
bridges at Vladicin, Varvarin, Bare and Donje Trnjance, airfields
at Nis and Ponikve, and army barracks in six cities, including
Belgrade and Surdulica. NATO also continued to attack radio and
television towers.
</P>
<P>
   The clear weather has apparently improved the alliance's success
against Yugoslav forces still operating in Kosovo. NATO reported
destroying significant clusters of heavy weapons in Kosovo, among
them 12 tanks, seven artillery pieces and six armored personnel
carriers, including those involved in the fighting against the
Kosovo Liberation Army around Mount Pastrik.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fighting between the Serbian forces and the rebels has
intensified in recent days. The rebels, whose numbers have
reportedly grown to as many as 15,000, have tried to take advantage
of NATO's air raids to harass the battered Serbian units and,
increasingly, to carve out territory for use as supply routes. Shea
said on Monday that the rebels had moved into three towns cleared
of Serbian forces by NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Pastrik is a strategic position, with a commanding view
from the city of Prizen to the Djakovica Valley, areas hotly
contested by the rebels. NATO officials say that Serbian artillery
and tanks had used the position to attack rebel strongholds and
concentrations of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said the rebels were ``indirect beneficiaries'' of NATO
attacks on the Serbian positions on Mount Pastrik.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a clear objective here of striking at the Yugoslav
forces wherever they are in Kosovo,'' he said. If the rebels ``are
able to benefit from that, so be it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
