<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHINA DETECTS RACISM IN U.S REPORT ON SPYING  (mk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China on Monday issued its broadest attack yet on the
congressional report that says China stole nuclear and missile
technologies, calling the document a tissue of half-truths,
conjectures and lies.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference, the information minister of China's State
Council, or Cabinet, used an Internet hookup to illustrate his
point that detailed information on American nuclear weapons was
readily available from public sites on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The minister, Zhao Qizheng, alternated between outrage and
ridicule as he called the allegations of spying absurd and racist.
</P>
<P>
   In its assertion that China has engaged in decades of successful
military espionage, Zhao said, the report relied on ``terms of
conjecture like seemingly, presumably, if, perhaps, probably and
perhaps in the future,'' while offering no substantive evidence of
theft.
</P>
<P>
   The contention that American security was endangered by all
types of Chinese visitors, including scientists, students and
executives, is ``a great slander against the Chinese nation and is
typical racial prejudice,'' Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
   Like other officials in recent days, the minister portrayed the
report, from a committee led by Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., as
the latest blow by hostile groups in the United States who are
trying to sabotage Chinese-American relations. Zhao took pains to
describe Chinese progress in military technologies, saying,
``During the years when the United States imposed an all-round
blockade and used nuclear blackmail against China, China relied on
its own efforts to develop atom bombs, missiles, satellites and
other sophisticated national-defense technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the report concern American companies' hiring Chinese
rockets to launch commercial satellites. The report says the
companies, eager to prevent failures, gave China militarily useful
information on rocket guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Zhao said that when China entered the commercial launching
market in 1990, it had already successfully launched 20 satellites
of its own and had little need of outside advice for its own secret
rocket designs. He also questioned the military value of
information that could be gleaned from commercial launchings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commercial satellite launches require only an economical and
rational guidance system with moderate precision,'' he said,
``instead of the high-precision guidance system needed for
ballistic missiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhao said China had never stolen secrets from American weapons
laboratories and asserted that important performance information on
the seven types of American warheads that are involved in the
spying case had ``long been openly published in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   To buttress the point, a Web page of the Federation of American
Scientists (http://www.fas.org) was shown on a screen as an
operator scrolled through it, displaying technical descriptions of
American warheads and missiles.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Internet sites like that nor books that Zhao cited
offer the secret design details at the center of the most serious
espionage charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
