u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ETHICS-EDUC-2TAKES(TR     05-31 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHICS-EDUC-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHING VALUES WITHOUT TAKING A PAGE FROM THE BIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Md.)  (lh) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's public schools, which taught the Bible routinely
for generations but retreated from explicitly moral education in
the individual-rights boom of the 1960s, are under growing pressure
to offer ethics instruction to provide safe learning free of
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   While the pressure on schools has been building through the
1990s because of the increase in the numbers of working parents and
concerns about the influence of television and music, recent school
shootings and last week's Supreme Court ruling on sexual harassment
by students have given the issue a new urgency, educators say.
</P>
<P>
   School administrators say they understand the need for such
instruction but worry that their legal protections are unclear,
their resources limited and the need to improve academic standards
already nearly all-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of School Boards says there has been a
notable rise in ``character education'' in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend now is that there is no one else to turn to for the
teaching of right and wrong so the schools are being asked to take
it on,'' said Samuel G. Sava, executive director of the National
Association of Elementary School Principals. ``But everyone is
concerned about getting sued for infringing on the prerogatives of
the family. No one knows where the limits are.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is that much of what passes for education in values
today amounts to the promotion of high ideals. These might include
caring and responsibility, taught, say, by hanging posters, naming
weekly or monthly themes or labeling hallways, like
``Responsibility Lane.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet many educators say that because there is so little of such
basic value re-enforcement at home or elsewhere in society, such an
approach makes a difference.
</P>
<P>
   La Jolla Elementary School in San Diego offers an example. Anne
Slattery Howard, a parent, said that two years ago she urged the
school to focus on character and morals. Now each month bears a
theme. September was ``courtesy month,'' February was ``caring
month,'' and activities and projects were geared around those
values.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had many parents come up to me and say they are
extremely grateful for the program,'' Ms. Howard said. ``Because we
have moved away from extended families and children are often not
at the top of the list of parents' priorities, there is no one
there to discuss with kids how to behave. The schools must fill
in.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The principal of La Jolla, Patricia Dibos, said that when the
program began, there was debate over what to call it. ``Virtues''
and ``values'' were rejected as too shaded by religion and open to
objection by parents. So the program is called ``interactive
skills.'' No one has complained.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Schools across the country have taken other approaches. Buck
Lodge Middle School in Adelphi, Md., was honored for its approach
last year by the Character Education Partnership, a nonprofit
group. For two years, the program at Buck Lodge worked by defining
a virtue on Monday, then devoting Tuesday to the telling of
positive and negative experiences related to that virtue. On
Wednesday, a guest from the community explained how the virtue was
important and could be applied at work. On Thursday, historical
figures who exemplified the virtue were discussed. On Friday,
students presented projects.
</P>
<P>
   The school has altered the program but still incorporates
virtues into its daily and weekly activities. It also encourages
students to do volunteer work, like making sandwiches for the
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   But there is competition for limited resources. Under
legislative and public pressure, schools are working vigorously to
raise academic standards. And while well-behaved students may make
for a better learning environment, which probably produces higher
achievement, trying to improve academic standards and create
programs focused on character is not proving easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is about competition and the other is about cooperation,''
said Gordon M. Ambach, executive director of the national Council
of Chief State School Officers.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, schools act in loco parentis, as stand-in parents,
during the school day. But courts have told educators that they may
not foster religion and have made it clear that the young have
legal rights and protections, which reduce institutional authority.
</P>
<P>
   And schools and their counselors have an even bigger job,
psychologists say, because the growth of managed health care has
reduced the availability of routine mental health services for
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Last week's Supreme Court decision poses a complex question: Can
students be taught how to avoid sexual harassment without being
taught about sex?
</P>
<P>
   Debra W. Haffner, president of the Sexuality Information and
Education Council, a nonprofit group, says the answer is no.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't talk about inappropriate sexual behavior until you
help young people deal with sexuality as a whole,'' Ms. Haffner
said. But she acknowledged that most schools did not see it that
way and that the court's ruling would not change that.
</P>
<P>
   In its 5-4 decision, the court said that schools may be held
liable for failing to stop a student from severely sexually
harassing another student. Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, writing for
the dissent, said the ruling amounted to labeling puerile behavior
_ teasing, grabbing, offending _ as sex discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, writing for the majority, says
liability will result only when harassment is ``so severe,
pervasive and objectively offensive that it effectively bars the
victim's access to an educational opportunity or benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Esther F. Schaeffer, executive director of the Character
Education Partnership, a six-year-old nonpartisan coalition in
Washington that promotes the teaching of values, said opinion
surveys showed that Americans overwhelmingly want their schools to
teach basic values like honesty, respect and responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schaeffer said other research showed how acute the need was.
She said teen-agers had been asked how many hours they spent
watching television, in school and engaged in meaningful
conversations with their parents. Over the course of a year, the
teen-agers said, they were spending 1,500 hours watching
television, 600 hours in school and 33 hours in conversation with
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is awareness all around of these other influences on the
young,'' Ms. Schaeffer said. ``Parents need some help to equalize
the situation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of public moral education say the Supreme Court may
have banned prayer in schools but it had never insisted that
schools be neutral on values. In fact, they say, former Chief
Justice Warren Burger made clear in a 1986 case about high school
student speech that the opposite was true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools must teach by example the shared values of a civilized
social order,'' Burger wrote in Bethel School District vs. Fraser,
a decision often quoted by advocates of education that includes
values.
</P>
<P>
   Objections about the nature of public moral education used to
come most often from liberals who objected to the conservative
Christian bent they detected. But in recent years it has come more
from conservatives who say schools are promoting values like
feminism and one-world government, noted Jay P. Heubert, professor
of education at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in every state, the Character Education Partnership
says, there is some form of character education, often using a mix
of private and public money. The Department of Education began a
pilot program four years ago to finance such projects. Now 28
states get federal assistance for values projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
