<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS BEAT METS, 5-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thirty minutes after the Mets had lost their
season-high fourth consecutive game, a 5-3 decision to the
Cincinnati Reds on Monday afternoon, their clubhouse was almost
deserted, the sign of a struggling team.
</P>
<P>
   Most players had showered quickly and left Shea Stadium. Not Al
Leiter. He stayed and answered questions about another bad outing,
his first start in 11 days: 5 runs on 7 hits, including 2 more home
runs in 7 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are many things the 33-year-old left-hander cannot
explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should have been seven innings, two runs,'' Leiter said.
``It's that close. I can't explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter (2-5) is not the only one grasping for answers. The Mets
(27-24) had no hits and no base runners after the third inning. The
most alarming question might be why the team's starters, which had
the fourth-best earned run average in the National League last
season (3.74), are near the bottom of this season (5.53) when
almost all of the pitchers are the same.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the Mets starters are 18-21. Only one of the five
pitchers who opened the season in the starting rotation has an era
of less than 5.00 _ and that is Masato Yoshii (4.94), who began the
season as the team's fifth starter and was one shellacking away
from being demoted to the minor leagues a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   And Leiter? After allowing solo homers on Monday to Greg Vaughn,
in the fifth inning, and Pokey Reese, in the seventh inning, for
the game's final two runs, Leiter has surrendered 9 home runs in 62
innings this season and has a 6.39 era.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Leiter allowed only eight homers in 193 innings _
tied with Kevin Brown among starters for the lowest number allowed
in the league, and which was one big reason Leiter went a
career-best 17-6 with another career-best 2.47 era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've given up more homers than I would like, that's for
sure,'' said Leiter, who was rewarded with a four-year, $32 million
deal after last season and anointed the ace of this year's staff.
``The bottom line is we lost and I gave up five runs in seven
innings. But I felt I threw better than that, if that makes
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to make any sense of Leiter's season. After a rocky
spring and his first three regular-season starts, Leiter had
allowed two runs in 131/3 innings over his next two starts when it
was determined that he had a sprained left knee. Over his next four
starts, Leiter allowed 24 earned runs in 22 innings.
</P>
<P>
   And then Manager Bobby Valentine noticed something different in
Leiter's motion as he pored over videotapes. Last season, when
Leiter was pitching well, he exploded through his follow through
with his left (back) leg. Since the sprain, however, Leiter had
been following through as though his back leg was tied to the
pitching rubber.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter was held out of a start and he experimented with a new
taping method on his sore left knee. On Monday, both Valentine and
Leiter said that he had much more explosion with the leg. And
Leiter _ who broke a half-dozen Cincinnati bats with his pitches _
said he did not feel unusual soreness from the new knee wrap.
</P>
<P>
   But even though Edgardo Alfonzo hit a solo home run in the first
and Bobby Bonilla _ in his first game back from the disabled list _
and Brian McRae belted consecutive solo homers in the second to
give the Mets a 3-1 lead, Leiter could not hold it. He had escaped
a bases-loaded, no-out jam in the second with only one run allowed.
But Sean Casey singled in two runs in the third to tie the game at
3-3.
</P>
<P>
   And after left-handed reliever Ron Villone came on for Brett
Tomko with runners on second and third and two out in the third and
threw three straight strikes past Robin Ventura (who struck out
four times on Monday), the Mets did not record another hit. Villone
(1-0) retired the first 12 batters he faced before walking Luis
Lopez on four pitches with two out in the seventh. And then
right-hander Scott Williamson came on and struck out pinch-hitter
Benny Agbayani to end the threat, before pitching two more perfect
innings for his sixth save.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Valentine liked enough of what he saw of Leiter to
say, ``He was four or five pitches away from having probably a
complete game shutout, so we'll build on that.'' But the results
were pretty much the same.
</P>
<P>
   Another rough outing, another loss, another five days spent
trying to explain. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
