<HEADLINE>
KUERTEN, THE FAVORITE IN PARIS, HAS VISIONS OF A NO. 1 RANKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ These days Gustavo Kuerten is a vision in black and
lime, no longer cloaking his lanky frame in the blue-and-yellow
dazzle of his national flag the way he did when he became a Grand
Slam champion here two years ago. But there seems little dispute
that the blood pulsing through his veins is still the color of red
clay.
</P>
<P>
   Kuerten, the Brazilian who chose the French Open as the site for
his first career title in 1997, is back in the hunt, except that
this time around not only is he the favorite to claim the title,
but he could also earn the No. 1 ranking as a personal bonus prize.
</P>
<P>
   With the major museums in Paris closed by a strike, the best
place to see artistry Monday was Court Suzanne Lenglen at Roland
Garros, where Kuerten defeated Bohdan Ulihrach, 6-4, 6-4, 6-1, and
was the only headliner for the sparse men's Round-of-16 program.
Kuerten zipped through his match with typical nonchalance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if I was a product, I would be difficult to sell,''
joked Kuerten.
</P>
<P>
   But Kuerten, 22-3 on clay this season and riding his cushion of
topspin like a magic carpet, is anything but a hard sell. According
to Ulihrach, the only player left in contention with a prayer
against the Brazilian is Andre Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Kuerten would need to win the final against ninth-seeded Marcelo
Rios, not the 13th-seeded Agassi, to reap sufficient bonus points
to also seize the top ranking. But he said he was not looking
beyond his quarterfinal with 100th-ranked Andrei Medvedev, the
Ukrainian who spoiled Sampras' French Open in Round 2 and Monday
downed Arnaud DiPasquale, 7-6 (7-5), 7-6 (7-3), 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm ready to go out on court and really show a lot
of good tennis, let the guy respect me more, just go in like a
favorite and win the match, too, not only win on paper,'' said
Kuerten, whose searing crosscourt backhand was so accurate it dug a
hole in the corner of the court. ``I have to win against the next
guy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A banner day for Brazil was guaranteed when Kuerten's buddy, the
54th-ranked Fernando Meligeni, upended 14th-seeded Felix Mantilla
of Spain, 6-1, 5-7, 7-5, 7-6 (7-1) in a 3-hour-7-minute slugfest
that concluded with a flimsy netted backhand after Meligeni reached
match point with another frantic scramble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have Armada Espanola, but we have Armada South
America now,'' said the 28-year-old Meligeni after reaching his
first Grand Slam quarterfinal in animated fashion. ``I don't know
if I am good enough to win the tournament or good enough to lose in
the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just get in the court, try my best, hit the ball harder, run
like a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Kuerten, the 142-pound Meligeni is slight by tennis
standards. ``You don't need to be Schwarzeneger to play tennis,''
Meligeni said.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Corretja, seeded sixth, accomplished what his comrade,
Carlos Moya, the French Open's defending and now deposed champion,
could not: He reached the final eight.
</P>
<P>
   Corretja advanced with a 6-2, 6-3, 7-5 victory over Stefan
Koubek, the 22-year-old left-hander who has dislodged Thomas
Muster, the 1995 champion, as Austria's top player.
</P>
<P>
   Corretja struggled with mononucleosis before the event began and
pronounced himself barely recovered from a bout with food poisoning
on the eve of Monday's match against the inexperienced Koubek, who
made 88 unforced errors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
