u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-ECON-NYT &LR;      05-31 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUICK RECOVERY MAY UNDERCUT SOUTH KOREA'S QUEST TO BAIL OUT BANKS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ South Korea's efforts to enlist foreign capital and
expertise in an overhaul of its rickety financial system have
become bogged down in, of all things, the country's stunning
recovery from economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Financial Supervisory Commission, the financial
watchdog charged with cleaning up South Korea's debt-laden
financial institutions, announced that it had extended negotiations
over the final terms of the sale of Seoul Bank to HSBC Holdings PLC
until June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both parties agreed that more time was needed, as due
diligence of the bank took longer than initially expected,'' the
commission said in a statement, referring to the need for the buyer
to do more research.
</P>
<P>
   The tortured negotiations stand in stark contrast to the rest of
the optimistic news sweeping the country and are thus fast shaping
up as a litmus test of the government's resolve to continue to push
reform now that pressure in the form of imminent economic collapse,
a sinking currency and a crashing stock market has faded.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also delayed for a third time the sale of Korea
First Bank to a group of investors led by Newbridge Capital Ltd., a
private equity group backed by two U.S. financiers, David Bonderman
and Richard C. Blum.
</P>
<P>
   Both banks were nationalized as part of a $57-billion bailout by
the International Monetary Fund in December 1997 when Korea
teetered on the brink of default.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions have changed markedly since then. Today, Korea's
economy is growing beyond all expectations, and its stock market
hits post-crisis highs nearly every day, as foreign investors
register their approval of the government's reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is improving, people are feeling better and the
sense of urgency is not as great,'' said Jeffrey D. Jones, the
president of the American Chamber of Commerce in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, Jones said, the economic improvements do in fact
reduce the need for foreign capital, although Korea is still eager
to obtain it. ``When you don't see that sense of urgency, that can
be seen as a step back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining the drive to change ways of doing business that are
decades old, however, is critical, not only in Korea but across
Asia. Japan's seemingly intractable economic decline stands as a
stark reminder of the perils of staving off the problems rather
than moving aggressively to eradicate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's maybe the biggest challenge Korea in particular and the
rest of Asia in general faces, not lapsing back,'' said Wilbur
Ross, a high-profile turnaround strategist at Rothschild Inc. He
was recently appointed by the Korean Ministry of Commerce, Industry
and Energy as the ``Honorary Economic Ambassador'' to the APEC
Investment Mart being held in Seoul this week, an offshoot of the
Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation forum that is aimed at enticing
foreign investors to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   He remains bullish on the region, as he will demonstrate in a
speech to the conference on Tuesday that will stress the importance
of following up capital enhancements to financial systems with a
complete overhaul of management practices.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Ross, like many other foreign executives who have
shuttled between their home countries and South Korea over the last
year, said he had definitely encountered changes in attitude among
people there. ``The first place you see it is in the cab drivers,''
he said. ``They're more abrupt, less courteous than a few months
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, at least in so far as the demeanor of cabbies is
any indicator, there has been a pronounced swing back to old
habits.
</P>
<P>
   There may be some political motivation for Monday's delays.
Parliamentary elections are coming up on Friday, and the government
is afraid of a public backlash against the ruling party should it
conclude the deals before voters go to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Supervisory Commission has spent 43.9 trillion won
of taxpayer money (about $37 billion) so far to recapitalize
financial institutions, and politicians from the ruling party are
worried that voters will be shocked to see how comparatively little
money the government gets for the two banks.
</P>
<P>
   The delays, however, raise the taxpayers' bill. After it
postponed the deal for Korea First, the government was forced to
put in another $2.5 billion of capital _ in addition to the
intangible costs of dampening investor sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Both bank deals have foundered over price, with the government
insisting that the banks' assets are worth more than the
prospective buyers are willing to consider. However, Jones said
that he believed that HSBC's acquisition of Seoul Bank would
ultimately be completed.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier this month, price scuttled a deal for Korea Life
Insurance, which the commission was trying to sell to a foreign
buyer. Metropolitan Life, the big American insurer, spent several
months and roughly $2 million poring over the books only to
conclude that the government would never entertain a bid at a price
Metropolitan Life considered reasonable, according to one person
familiar with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Axa, a large French insurance company, apparently came to the
same conclusion. Neither company even tendered an offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of foreign buyers came to Korea at a very early stage,
talked to companies when they were at the very bottom and walked
away with plans to buy that were bargains,'' said Kristine Li, an
analyst who follows Korean banks for Lehman Brothers in Hong Kong.
``But Korea has recovered so quickly, just in the last four months,
and everything, including the perception of the values of assets,
has changed quickly, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Although its efforts to lure foreign capital into the banking
system have been delayed, the Financial Supervisory Commission has
pushed through extensive changes in the financial system. Banks are
cutting up to 30 percent of their employees, and the number of
banks has shrunk, from 27 to 17. About 20 percent of bank branches
are being phased out, and new managers are gradually entering the
top ranks of decision makers. ``I don't think any other country has
done or could do as much as they have in terms of cleaning up the
banking system,'' Ms. Li said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
