<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: INDIANS ARE PUTTING THE YANKEES ON THE ALERT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's nothing on the Yankees' uniforms to indicate
that they are World Series champions. Just the intertwined ``NY''
on the chest, each player's number on the back, and a small ``5''
on the left sleeve to memorialize Joe DiMaggio's death. It's as if
nothing needs to be said about the Yankees' 24th World Series
reign.
</P>
<P>
   On the right sleeve of the Cleveland Indians' road grays is a
red logo identifying the ``AL Central Champs,'' which they've been
for each of the last four seasons. But it's all they have to brag
about.
</P>
<P>
   That logo is more of a reminder of what the Indians haven't done
than what they have. Although they were in the World Series twice,
they lost both times _ to the Atlanta Braves in 1995, to the
Florida Marlins in 1997. In the American League playoffs the other
two years, they lost to the Baltimore Orioles in 1996 and to the
Yankees last year.
</P>
<P>
   But this is 1999, and as June begins, the Indians were
baseball's best team.
</P>
<P>
   They arrived at Yankee Stadium Monday with a 32-16 record and a
.300 team batting average, scoring nearly seven runs a game.
</P>
<P>
   If the playoffs were beginning now, the Indians would be opening
against the wild-card Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't just beat you,'' Joe Torre was saying prophetically
before Monday's opener of a three-game series, ``they put you in a
trunk and drive you away somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   After only two innings, the Yankees and Orlando ``El Duque''
Hernandez were in a trunk on their way to a 7-1 loss. Manny Ramirez
hit a two-run homer. Jim Thome hit a grand slam into the Yankee
bullpen in left-center field. Not that the Indians dared to gloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice, but it's early,'' said Thome, the big first
baseman. ``This don't mean a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But it did mean something. It meant that the Indians, who don't
play the Yankees again until mid-September in Cleveland, alerted
the Yankees that they mean business. Thome especially. On the pitch
that turned last year's American League Championship Series, Thome
had struck out with two on against El Duque in the sixth inning of
the Yankees' 4-0 victory in Cleveland that squared the playoff at
2-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the same pitch, a changeup, but that one was a little
in,'' Thome said, referring to the one he missed in Game 4. ``This
one was out over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hargrove, the Indians' manager, wasn't about to gloat,
either. After the Indians had been swept by the Red Sox in a
three-game series over the weekend in Cleveland, he was ``just
happy to win'' a game.
</P>
<P>
   But some of his players understood the significance of serving
notice on the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's always important,'' said Dwight Gooden, once a
Yankee. ``Players always downplay it, but I think it's important to
try to send a message.''
</P>
<P>
   Richie Sexson, their designated hitter, insisted that the
Indians weren't thinking about ``trying to beat'' what the Yankees
did last year in winning 125 games while sweeping the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thinking,'' Sexson said, ``about what we have to do to
beat the Yankees this year.''
</P>
<P>
   As good as the Indians have been so far this year, they surely
will try to get even better. Before Monday's game, their staff had
a 4.73 earned run average, seventh among AL teams. That ERA will be
good enough to dominate the AL Central, but to improve their
chances in the playoffs, look for the Indians to seek an
established stopper.
</P>
<P>
   For two years now, the Indians have talked about obtaining Curt
Schilling from the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   And if Schilling isn't available this time, they might pursue
David Wells, the former Yankee who is now an unhappy 5-5 with a
6.30 ERA for the Toronto Blue Jays, who don't seem interested in
negotiating a three-year extension on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   If the Indians were to acquire Wells, that would be the Yankee
fans' worst nightmare _ going against the Boomer in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, of course, was traded to the Blue Jays for Roger Clemens,
who Tuesday night will be trying to find holes in the Indians' big
bats. But just the thought of Clemens' fastball had Hargrove
wincing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' the Indians' manager said, ``that'll be fun, won't
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's why the Yankees made the deal for Roger Clemens _ to
make sure the Indians just keep wearing that ``AL Central Champs''
logo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
