<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7653 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-INDIANS-T     05-31 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-INDIANS-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' PRAISE OF THE INDIANS HAS A HOLLOW RING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Through grins, the New York Yankees acknowledged that
they were thoroughly outplayed by the Cleveland Indians Monday.
They conceded their own failures, the poor performance of Orlando
Hernandez and their lack of clutch hitting. Nobody suggested that
the Indians didn't earn their 7-1 victory before 46,605 at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Yankees also think that Manny Ramirez's bat made a
very funny sound when he stretched to hit a low pitch for a
monstrous two-run home run in the first inning. Many Yankees think
Ramirez's bat is packed _ illegally _ with cork.
</P>
<P>
   Asking umpires to check a bat for a foreign substance can be
considered an act of war, and in recent years the Yankees and
Indians have shared a respectful rivalry; the Yankees did not
challenge the legality of Ramirez's bat in his subsequent plate
appearances, in the first game in their three-game series. ``It
looks like sour grapes if you say you lost because of the corked
bat,'' one Yankee said. ``They're a good team, and they beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees think they have strong circumstantial evidence
of cork against Ramirez and the Indians, who have been involved in
bat controversies before. When Albert Belle played for Cleveland in
1994, he was suspended for 10 days for using a corked bat _ the
Yankees reliever Jason Grimsley was with the Indians at the time _
and according to American League lore, the Indians' bat rack was
once full of corked bats, pieced together in a secret room in
Jacobs Field (perhaps by a carpenter named Bigfoot).
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez would not discuss whether his bat was corked. ``Not
right now,'' he said cordially when a reporter approached. He then
turned away and ignored questions that followed.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's home run was preceded by a long delay. Roberto Alomar
pulled a long fly down the right-field line and began trotting to
first base, assuming he had hit his seventh home run. But after the
ball crashed into the upper deck, near the foul pole, Larry Young,
the first-base umpire, waved his arms to indicate the ball had
sliced foul. Alomar thought otherwise, protesting to Young and then
to the home-plate umpire, Al Clark, that the ball had glanced off
the foul pole for a homer. Indians Manager Mike Hargrove replaced
Alomar in the debate. Hernandez stood on the mound and waited as
Hargrove argued with Young.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez waited. Hargrove went to argue with Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez waited, bending on the mound to stretch his legs, to
combat boredom. Hargrove escorted Clark to first base, to engage in
a three-man panel over whether the ball was fair or foul. Hernandez
waited. If not for the fact that it was Memorial Day, millions of
shares would have exchanged hands on Wall Street in the time it
took for Young and Clark to inform Hargrove that Alomar's fly had
gone foul.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, finally tired of the delay, but
just as he went to the top step of the dugout, Hargrove turned and
walked slowly back toward the Indians' dugout, accompanied part of
the way by Clark. Hernandez waited, and good things did not come to
him.
</P>
<P>
   He walked Alomar. ``Maybe, by staying out there long enough,''
Alomar said, ``it took away from his concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   With a two-ball, two-strike count on Ramirez, Hernandez tried
three times to throw fastballs past Ramirez; he fouled off each
one. Hernandez then spun a slider low and away, and Ramirez reached
out and, with his weight off his back leg and his bottom hand
pulling the ball through the strike zone, he flicked his wrists.
</P>
<P>
   Boom. The ball rocketed toward center field, carrying and
carrying, flying over the wall. Estimated distance: 412 feet. Some
of the Yankees exchanged glances over the fact that Ramirez had
been able to hit a low pitch so far and over the sound of the bat
meeting the ball. ``It just didn't sound right at all,'' said one
Yankee, who, like the others discussing their corked-bat theory,
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next was Exhibit C: Ramirez stopped at second
base, not realizing he had hit the ball out of the park. ``He
couldn't believe he hit the ball that far, either,'' another Yankee
said.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Tschida, the second-base umpire, told Ramirez he had hit a
home run, and Ramirez continued on his way. In his next at-bat,
several Yankees said, Ramirez used a different bat. ``The bat he
hit the home run with, it was more worn and it looked like he'd
been using it for a while,'' said a Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Leading by 2-0 after the first inning, the Indians added five
runs in the second. With runners at first and second and two out,
Hernandez covered first on a grounder to Tino Martinez and dropped
the throw, loading the bases. Ramirez laced a grounder past the
mound _ and it hit Tschida's right foot before it got through the
infield. The ball was ruled dead, and Ramirez was credited with a
single, all runners advancing one base. Chuck Knoblauch, the
Yankees' second baseman, was sure he would have had a play on the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Then Hernandez flipped a changeup to Jim Thome _ the same pitch
Hernandez struck out Thome with in the American League Championship
Series last year in a pivotal situation _ and Thome whacked it over
the wall. ``They got two extra outs in that inning,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees took full blame for their loss and gave the Indians
all the credit. And they will be watching, and listening, when
Ramirez comes to bat Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
