<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7654 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MEMORIALDAY-ART-NY     05-31 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MEMORIALDAY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERANS PAINED BY PUBLIC'S APATHY TOWARD WAR DEAD
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fifty-five years later, Murray Gaile vividly
remembers the 123 days that he spent surviving at Anzio, in the
Allied invasion of Italy in 1944. As a mortarman, he supported Army
Rangers who were scythed down by German gunfire on one of the
bloodiest beachheads of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were with them when they got wiped out,'' said Gaile, whose
own unit, the 83rd Chemical Battalion, lost 381 men before it
reached Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But as Gaile, now 75, watched Memorial Day ceremonies on the USS
Intrepid in Manhattan on Monday, bitterness weighed on him as much
as the American and French military medals tugging on his shirt.
``Today, they don't even know what Anzio was,'' Gaile said. ``Most
people aren't interested.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went for many veterans at the smattering of parades and
commemorations on Memorial Day, a holiday better known these days
for barbecues, beach trips and bargain sales than for selfless
courage. Parade routes that spill over with crowds on holidays like
Thanksgiving and St. Patrick's Day had mostly casual tourists
Monday, as continuing sunshine drove temperatures into the high 80s
and many more New Yorkers to the parks and seashore.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer Americans called to serve their country, the ranks of
veterans who turn out in New York and elsewhere has dwindled, and
with them the spirit of a holiday that once saw thousands of men
and women marching down Fifth Avenue in midtown Manhattan or the
Grand Concourse in the Bronx to cheering crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Memorial Day was created after the Civil War ``for the purpose
of strewing with flowers or otherwise decorating the graves of
comrades who died in defense of their country during the late
rebellion,'' according to the order of May 5, 1868, creating
Decoration Day, as the holiday was first called.
</P>
<P>
   John Logan, commander in chief of the Grand Army of the
Republic, pledged, ``If other eyes grow dull and other hands slack,
and other hearts cold in the solemn trust, ours shall keep it well
as long as the light and warmth of life remain in us.''
</P>
<P>
   His general order remains an implicit rallying call for veterans
who turn out on the last Monday of May, if only to maintain faith
with their dead comrades and each other. ``I'm nothing,'' said
George Arnone, a 54-year-old social worker who served as a Marine
in Vietnam in 1965-66 and attended the Intrepid ceremony. ``I owe
my life to a bunch of guys who aren't here. I can't lose sight of
what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   In upper Manhattan, the Rev. Kevin Devine celebrated Mass for
the war dead Monday at the Roman Catholic Church of the Good
Shepherd in the Inwood neighborhood. Afterward, Devine, who spent
18 months in Vietnam as a chaplain in the 4th Infantry Division,
donned his Army uniform to march up Broadway with other members of
Inwood Post 581 of the American Legion. A few pedestrians stopped
to applaud and cheer the men, who had to ask their color bearers,
wearing desert camouflage, to slow down in the wilting heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to remember everyone who gave their life,'' Devine
said as he limped along. ``We'd like to think that everyone
remembers them, but we're grateful that many do.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Hoare, 34, a Marine who served in the 1991 Persian Gulf
war, was marching in remembrance of his cousin of the same name, a
Marine lieutenant killed in Vietnam in the battle for Hue in 1968.
``We're going to continue the tradition as long as possible,'' said
Hoare, a portfolio manager for Chase Manhattan Bank and commander
of Post 581. ``Let the word get out that the people of northern
Manhattan have not forgotten and will never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an occasion for some ordinary-looking New Yorkers to
confess to extraordinary exploits.
</P>
<P>
   Bronislaw Bartkowski, 75, was one of 16 veterans who showed up
at a memorial ceremony Sunday at Veterans of Foreign Wars Post 3427
in Flushing, Queens. An Army sniper in World War II, Bartkowski
said he weighed barely 98 pounds when he dragged six wounded
American soldiers to safety, then killed five Nazi SS soldiers and
captured their tank. ``My legs were shaking so much I couldn't hold
my rifle,'' Bartkowski recalled. ``Then I heard my mother's voice
whisper to me, `You have to do it.''' His heroism earned him the
Medal of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   But Post 3427, to which Bartkowski belongs, has not participated
in a march since 1995. ``You can't have a parade with 20 men,''
said the post's commander, James Moglia, 52, who was an Air Force
technician at Ben Hoa, Vietnam, in 1969-70.
</P>
<P>
   In Bay Ridge, Brooklyn, Salvatore Grasso, 75, marched wearing a
red blazer identifying him as a former American prisoner of war. He
lost seven toes to frostbite in a German prison camp during the
winter of 1944-45, he said, and has not missed a Memorial Day
parade since.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cunningham, 77, who was captured during the Battle of
the Bulge in 1944, conceded that the marching bothered his feet
because frostbite had claimed all his toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's especially bad that people have forgotten about Memorial
Day because Memorial Day is for the dead guys,'' Cunningham said.
``Turnout is going down. Interest is going down. It's been a long
time since these guys saved the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
