<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- May 31, 1999 -- NY-MEMORIALDAY, 5-31 --
Murray Gaile holds a portrait of himself after coming back from
fighting in Europe during World War II, during Memorial Day
ceremonies aboard the Intrepid Sea Air and Space Museum on Monday.
Gaile's unit, the 83rd Chemical Battalion, lost 381 men before it
reached Germany from Anzio, Italy, during the war. ``Today, they
don't even know what Anzio was,'' Gaile said while commenting on
the low turnout during the ceremonies. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LONDON -- May 31, 1999 -- USBROKERS-LONDON -- Simon
Benarroch, an Edward Jones employee, greets visitors at the opening
of the American investment firm's first London office. The
calculation that Britain is ripe for a personal investment boom
underpins this newest American sortie into Main Street Britain by
the company that seeks a niche between high-priced financial
advisers, low-cost discount brokers and banks. (Jonathan Player/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- May 31, 1999 -- RUM DISPUTE, 5-31 -- A
ruling by Judge Shira Scheindlin, seen in her chambers, denied
trademark rights to Cuba's most famous rum, Havana Club. Many
American companies, fearful of losing their trademark rights in
Cuba, are lobbying for the repeal of the law on which the ruling
was based. With the exception of Bacardi-Martini U.S.A., the U.S.
subsidiary of Bacardi Ltd., which contends that it holds the rights
to the Havana Club name, just about everyone seems unhappy with the
ruling. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- May 31, 1999 -- DUTCH-FASHION-2, 5-31 --
Dutch designers Rolf Snoeren, left, and Viktor Horsting at
Visionaire with Cecilia Dean, who is wearing one of their
creations. Even though Viktor &AMP; Rolf represent what is
optimistically called the ``new couture,'' and have shown their
collections independently for three seasons in Paris, though they
will be on the official couture schedule next month, not one client
has bought a single outfit, which costs about $12,000. (Barbara
Alper/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- May 31, 1999 -- DUTCH-FASHION-2, 5-31 --
Members of the Dutch fashion team, Viktor Horsting, right, and Rolf
Snoeren in a bird cage at a Brooklyn Bridge Anchorage installation.
Even though Viktor &AMP; Rolf represent what is optimistically called
the ``new couture,'' and have shown their collections independently
for three seasons in Paris, though they will be on the official
couture schedule next month, not one client has bought a single
outfit, which costs about $12,000. (Linda Rosier/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PARIS -- May 31, 1999 -- DUTCH-FASHION-1, 5-31 -- A
Victorian touch from the Dutch fashion team of Viktor Horsting and
Rolf Snoeren: a tuxedo with a gazar ruff, shown in January. Even
though Viktor &AMP; Rolf represent what is optimistically called the
``new couture,'' and have shown their collections independently for
three seasons in Paris, though they will be on the official couture
schedule next month, not one client has bought a single outfit,
which costs about $12,000. (Jean-Luce Hure/New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) TORREON, Mexico -- May 31, 1999 -- MEXICO-DROUGHT, 5-31
-- A procession for a Mass celebrated last week in the northern
Mexican city calling for rain. Some 6,000 Roman Catholics gathered
to pray for relief from a withering drought that is killing
livestock, draining reservoirs and forcing hundreds of towns in the
region to limit their consumption of water. (Keith Dannemiller/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) SKOPJE, Macedonia -- May 31, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-2,
5-31 --Besa Berisha, left, an ethnic Albanian refugee from Kosovo,
says goodbye to relatives before boarding a flight to the United
States last week. If there is an overwhelming sense that emerges
from a walk through the squalid refugee camps of Macedonia these
days, it is despair. Kosovars are giving up on their dream of
returning home soon and are increasingly desperate to go abroad.
(Andrew Testa/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 31, 1999 --
LINCOLN-CENTER-FUNDRAISING-2, 5-31 -- Beverly Sills, chairwoman of
Lincoln Center, and Nathan Leventhal, its president, during a
recent interview. As it celebrates its 40th birthday, Lincoln
Center for the Performing Arts, the world's most successful arts
complex, is showing its age. Officials are weighing a vast
fund-raising campaign to address the wear and tear of decades and
other gnawing problems. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 31, 1999 --
LINCOLN-CENTER-FUNDRAISING-1, 5-31 -- Cracks on the sidewalk
leading to Lincoln Center. As it celebrates its 40th birthday,
Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts, the world's most successful
arts complex, is showing its age. Officials are weighing a vast
fund-raising campaign to address the wear and tear of decades and
other gnawing problems. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) EASTHAMPTON, N.Y. -- May 31, 1999 -- HAMPTONS-FORVER-2,
5-31 -- Roland Eisenberg co-owner of the Blue Parrot bar and
resteraunt, a reknown eatery frequented by celebrities. Propelled
by a bull market and fueled by celebrity sitings, change is
rippling as never before across the Hamptons, and it is challenging
traditional defenses that have long served to protect the Hamptons
Way of Life, many locals say. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) EASTHAMPTON, N.Y. -- May 31, 1999 -- HAMPTONS-FORVER-1,
