intellectual about the land of Israel at the moment when its course
is abruptly changed. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) EASTON, Conn. -- May 31, 1999 -- CT-TRAINDEATHS-FUNERAL,
5-31 -- Anibal Aguirre Toledo, left, and his sister Jenny Aguirre
Toledo, children of Julia Toledo, embrace during their mother's
burial service on Monday. Julia Toledo and four of her younger sons
were killed by an Amtrak train last week. (Angel Franco/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MORINI, Albania -- May 31, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA, 5-31
-- Ethnic Albanian refugees enter Albania at the Morini border
crossing as smoke billows in the background after a NATO airstrike
just over the border in Kosovo on Monday. NATO planes bombarded
Serb positions in southern Kosovo for much of Monday, dropping
bombs only yards from Albania's border. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SENOKOS, Macedonia -- May 31, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
5-31 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kovacevc, near Kacanik, in
southern Kosovo, at a camp on Sunday. The group walked for two days
to reach the Macedonian village of Odri where they sought refuge in
the local mosque. However Macedonian police transported them to
this camp. (Andrew Testa/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PORTLAND, Ore. -- May 31, 1999 -- SCI-STEROIDS, 5-31 --
Drs. Diane Elliot, left, and Dr. Linn Goldberg of Oregon Health
Sciences University recently completed a program aimed at reducing
steroid use among young athletes. Girls with an interest in the
lean muscular look are turning increasingly to steroids, say
prominent researchers in field. Meanwhile, use among boys also is
increasing. (Shane Young/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- May 31, 1999 -- MEMORIAL-DAY-FLOATER, 5-31
-- Dave Tolsen, an honor guard with the United States Park Police,
stands in front of the Vietnam Memorial while a military honor
guard presents the colors at the start of Memorial Day ceremonies
on Monday. In an address on the century's final Memorial Day,
President Clinton asked Americans to reconsider their ambivalence
about the military conflict in Kosovo and said: ``Remember why many
of the people are laying in these graves out here.'' (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
