<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-TRAINDEATHS-ART-NY     05-31 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-TRAINDEATHS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
500 MOURN FAMILY OF 5 KILLED BY TRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRUMBULL, Conn. _ Julia Toledo de Urgiles lay in her coffin with
her youngest son, Pedro Andres, 3. Two other sons, Jose Francisco,
10, and Angel Gabriel, 6, shared one, too. Carlos Enrique, 11, had
his own. On top was a white T-shirt he had won from a drug abuse
prevention program, but had not had a chance to collect before his
sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   The three gleaming white coffins were placed side by side, the
two that held the remains of Jose, Angel and Carlos adorned with
the black and red scribblings of friends and relatives in English
and Spanish: ``We will miss you,'' ``We love you,'' ``We will
always remember you.''
</P>
<P>
   As the three coffins were lowered into the earth after a funeral
attended Monday by 500 friends and relatives, the mystery behind
their deaths was buried, too.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday at 2:20 a.m., Mrs. Urgiles, who had immigrated from
Ecuador 18 months ago, and her four young children were struck and
killed by an Amtrak train just west of the train station in
Fairfield. Mrs. Urgiles was dashing across the tracks to get one of
the boys when the train hit them, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is sure why they were out there in the middle of the
night or where they were going, but on Monday those questions
weighed on the minds of mourners and caused tension among family
members.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Mrs. Urgiles', Olga Leiva, said she believed that
Mrs. Urgiles was headed to Fairfield University, where another son
and her sister were working a late shift for the janitorial company
that employed Mrs. Urgiles.
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, Mrs. Urgiles had moved out of a Bridgeport
apartment owned by her sister, Maria Toledo, and into an emergency
shelter for homeless families. Friends said she was under the
mistaken belief that her relatives were plotting to take custody of
her children. Several said she had been depressed lately. A few
days before her death, after she complained of headaches and
hearing voices, the friends said they took her to a mental health
clinic, where a psychologist spoke with her and scheduled a
follow-up visit for later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wasn't feeling well,'' said Clodomiro Falcon, a family
friend and a former leader of their Spanish-speaking Mormon
congregation. ``She had suffered a lot in the past because of
domestic issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Urgiles was in the process of divorcing her second husband,
Carlos Urgiles, who is the father of the four boys killed with her.
She had two other children from a previous marriage: a son, Anibal
Aguirre, 20, who lived with her in Bridgeport, and a daughter,
Jenny Aguirre, 21, who lives in Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   The Urgileses had immigrated following Mrs. Urgiles' sister, who
converted from Roman Catholicism to the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints. But Urgiles stopped attending Mormon services
within a few months, and friends of Mrs. Urgiles' said religious
differences may have played a role in the deterioration of their
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Friends said Mrs. Urgiles had filed a complaint with police last
year accusing Urgiles of abusing her and threatening the children.
(Police said Monday that the records office was closed and that
they could not immediately confirm the report.) Urgiles returned to
Ecuador shortly afterward, but he denied in interviews Monday that
he intended to harm anybody, and said he returned to his farming
village in Ecuador because he was having trouble adjusting to life
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The strains in the family were evident. Urgiles, upon his
arrival in New York on Friday night, declared his intent to bring
his family home for burial, but after a meeting Saturday with
officials of the Ecuadorean Consulate and Mrs. Urgiles' family, he
agreed to let the funeral and burial proceed in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   At a private memorial service before the funeral, Urgiles, 52,
buried his head in his hands and wept as he said a blessing over
the coffins, each of which was topped with a spray of white
carnations.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family, I hope you can appreciate my terrible pain and that
I will think of you always, that I will never forget you,'' Urgiles
said.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Romero, secretary of the Ecuadorean Association, a
Stamford group with several dozen members, said the Urgileses were
typical of many of her compatriots who, sponsored by relatives,
have begun streaming into southwestern Connecticut to take service
industry jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
