<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     05-31 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: EWING, SMITS AND PLAYING WITH PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   af)  
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS, Ind. _ Larry Bird has heard all about Patrick
Ewing the Warrior, Patrick Ewing playing so hurt he should be in
traction in an emergency ward, Patrick Ewing so bruised and beat up
that he appears to have been run over by shoppers at a
bargain-basement sale. Larry Bird says he's buying none of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of hearing about how hurt Patrick is,'' the Pacers'
head coach said Monday. ``I don't think he's hurting that bad.
C'mon. He played 40 minutes last night. If Rik Smits played 40
minutes you wouldn't see him again for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   If it is true, as Patrick Ewing had said before the
Knicks-Pacers Eastern Conference final series, that ``This is
war!'' then the day after Game 1 and the day before Game 2 at
Market Square Arena here was a matter of splitting hairs, or,
rather, medical reports regarding the opposing centers.
</P>
<P>
   But as their relative or fanciful health goes, so might well go
the series.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bird believes that a contused Patrick is a con job. And
that the sore Achilles' tendon, the battered ribs, the throbbing
thigh, the knees and shoulder and feet that need to be iced in
wraps and buckets after each game is all as phony as a four-dollar
bill. Or maybe he just doesn't want his players to suffer sympathy
pangs for the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ewing not only played 40 minutes in the Knicks' 93-90
victory over Indiana in Game 1, but he also played superbly, though
not perfectly, scoring 16 points, and hitting all eight of his
free-throw attempts. They included four in the last 30.6 seconds of
the game, and twice broke a tie to put the Knicks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Smits is playing with a broken toe. ``Sometimes,'' he said,
``it's so hard for me to move it feels like I'm standing in
cement.'' He also played 26 minutes in Game 1, before fouling out
with 87 critical seconds left in the last quarter, scoring 12
points and taking down 6 rebounds, 4 fewer than Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Smits was having a tough offensive night _ he scored no points
in the first half _ when in the fourth period he seemed
resuscitated. He hit a hook shot, two jump shots and a pair of free
throws _ blowing by Ewing on a drive from the top of the key and
stopping only when Ewing grabbed him _ before committing his sixth
foul, with his team up by 3 points, 87-84.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just Smits' scoring at this juncture that was
significant, but how Ewing was forced to guard him and was no
match. He looked either fatigued, hobbled, old or simply
out-skilled. Perhaps all four _ and the last since Ewing's forte
has never been footwork on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of Patrick's physical condition,'' said the Knicks'
head coach, Jeff Van Gundy, ``we can't ask him to play the
top-scoring centers for more than a few minutes in a half.''
</P>
<P>
   But had Van Gundy down the stretch considered removing Ewing if
Smits had not fouled out?
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy's eyes grew steely at the question. ``None! Zero!'' He
cooled, and explained: ``He's finishing games. Playing in pain and
fatigue is part of his greatness. At the other end, he made a
basket to cut their lead to three'' _ with 2:20 left in the game _
``and then he hit those free throws. But I felt he has to defend
better. We've talked about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, though, must be given credit for the heart and will he
has played with this season, these playoffs. He is obviously in
agony, but it is subverted for his lust, at age 36, to win a
championship and quiet his critics. Even the most rabid Knick fans,
however, have been distressed over the 13 years he has played in
New York when all his sweat on the court sometimes went for naught
because he was not as good a passer, defender, rebounder or team
player that he could have been had his heart and will been in it
fully from the start.
</P>
<P>
   As Van Gundy talked with the press after practice Monday, a
voice from a passerby said an expletive to say hello.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ewing, smiling broadly. And Van Gundy, laughing, answered
with an expletive greeting and added, ``for making your free
throws, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy had said that he had ``talked with Patrick about
making his free throws at the end of games'' and ``I told him one
out of two wasn't good enough, he had to make 'em both.'' He added,
self-deprecatingly, ``Now that's coaching,''
</P>
<P>
   He paused for a moment, his thoughts seeming to follow the
departure of this player he clearly has such respect for.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yeah,'' he said, referring to Bird's remarks in doubting
Ewing's infirmities, ``and Smits doesn't have a broken toe,
right?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
