<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YEN-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      05-31 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEN-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING YEN AGAINST DOLLARS IS AGAIN TEMPTING THE RISK TAKERS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the main culprits in the global financial crisis of 1997
is sneaking back into the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   The spread between Japanese and higher American interest rates
has recently been widening, tempting speculators to borrow yen at
bargain-basement prices, convert them to dollars and invest them in
U.S. Treasury bills. The idea is to sell the bills later on, pocket
most of the interest payments and then repay the low-interest yen
debt.
</P>
<P>
   If the yen does not turn against the borrower _ and most
forecasts are saying that it will not _ it is an easy, if perhaps
esoteric way to make money.
</P>
<P>
   But the play, known as a ``carry trade,'' has not caught fire
yet the way it did two years ago, traders and analysts say, in part
because speculators are still smarting from their losses after it
backfired in 1997 and again in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   If this bet does go mainstream again, though, it could weaken
the yen and buoy the U.S. bond market, helping to keep interest
rates lower than they would otherwise be.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Barbera, chief economist at Hoenig &AMP; Co., argues that
if the yen carry trade does catch on again, it could make the
Federal Reserve's goal of slowing economic growth here more
difficult. ``The yen carry trade shows that global capital flows
can be at odds with domestic economic circumstances,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the trade _ besides a large enough difference in
interest rates _ is the performance of the currency that the
borrowing is done in. It has to remain stable or weaken against the
currency that the bonds are bought in. If the borrowing currency
suddenly rallies, the cost of paying off the loan rises. A sharp
currency rally can quickly make the carry trade a big loser.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Asian investors took low-interest loans in yen or
dollars and invested at higher rates at home, for example, in
Thailand. Last year, the carry trade was focused on borrowing in
Japanese yen and investing in U.S. Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   But when the yen suddenly rallied against the dollar and other
Asian currencies in May 1997, that carry trade blew up in the
speculators' faces. The rush to get out involved the selling of
local currencies, like the Thai baht, to convert to yen and dollars
to pay off the loans. And that selling marked the beginning of the
rush that forced the devaluation of the Thai currency in July,
which in turn marked the beginning of the Asian, and eventually
broader, financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, speculators began to get out of the yen carry trade
as the Russian financial crisis came to a head in August. The
flight accelerated after the near-collapse of Long-Term Capital
Management, the American hedge fund. The selling of dollars to buy
yen and pay off the yen loans helped send the yen soaring 29
percent against the dollar in two months. After that the
interest-rate spread narrowed, closing the door on the carry trade.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last two months, the spread between American and
Japanese interest rates has widened again _ to a high of 4.42
percentage points on 10-year notes, a big enough difference to make
the strategy attractive once more. With yields that much higher in
this country, as long as the yen does not significantly strengthen
against the dollar, it will be very profitable to borrow in Japan
and invest the proceeds in the bond market here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that it is now the time to put the trade
back on,'' said Jeremy P. Fand, senior foreign exchange strategist
at BankBoston. Yet he said he did not think there are nearly as
many bets on now as there were in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for this reluctance, in addition to the memory of
recent losses, is that market players realize there is much more
risk of an adverse currency move. In 1997, for example, the Thai
baht's value was pegged to the dollar, making the trade appear much
less risky. In contrast, given the sharp fluctuations of the yen
against the dollar over the last year, the currency risks are much
greater. The yen, after falling 8.6 percent this year, has gained
almost 3 percent in the last week and a half, trading on foreign
spot markets late Monday around 121.50 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is investors' wariness about the prospects for
emerging markets and U.S. stock markets in the wake of the Federal
Reserve's announcement that it would now lean toward a policy of
higher interest rates. With stock selloffs still fresh in their
minds, some traders may be reducing their exposure to risky bets,
including the yen carry trade.
</P>
<P>
   James Kemp, the head of foreign-exchange sales and trading for
North America at Citigroup, suggested that the yen's recent rise
reflected this cautiousness. ``People are in risk-reduction mode,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A strategist at a prominent hedge fund, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity, agreed. ``People are playing, but they are
taking their profits right away,'' the strategist said, adding,
``That is why you are going to see a lot of spikes up and down in
the yen.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the rally in the yen could set up another run into the
carry trade. While the interest rate spread has narrowed a little,
to 4.17 percentage points on Friday, the last day of bond trading
before Monday's holiday, the yen, many forecasters think, is most
likely to reverse course, weakening to a level of perhaps 130 to
the dollar. And if that turns out to be true, the lure of the yen
carry trade could prove irresistible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
