<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO MUSEUM REOPENS AND TUTANKHAMEN REIGNS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Oriental Institute reopened to the public this
past weekend after three years of reconstruction, allowing
museumgoers to come face-to-face _ or rather face-to-knee _ with a
colossal statue of Tutankhamen that was made the centerpiece of the
new Egyptian gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The $10.1-million renovation and expansion was undertaken mainly
to safeguard more than 300,000 artifacts, including one of the
largest Egyptian collections in the United States, from this city's
unforgiving climate. Scholarly work at the 80-year-old institute, a
research division of the University of Chicago that specializes in
the ancient Near East, continued during construction.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian gallery was the first to reopen, coincidentally
while ``The Mummy'' is playing in 48 theaters around Chicago. Other
galleries, focusing on Mesopotamia, Sumer, Persia, Palestine,
Israel, Anatolia and Nubia, are to open over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each gallery will have a monumental focus,'' said Dr. Emily
Teeter, the curator of the Egyptian gallery. Gesturing to
Tutankhamen, she added, ``You can't get much more monumental.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17-foot-4-inch quartzite pharaoh is believed to be the
largest Egyptian statue in the Western Hemisphere, Dr. Teeter said.
About 3,320 years old, it is one of a pair that were excavated by
an Oriental Institute team in 1930 at Medinet Habu in Luxor. The
other one, in better condition, remained in Egypt. They are the
largest known representations of Tutankhamen.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the statue was once relegated to the sidelines in another
gallery near a 16-foot-long, human-headed, winged bull from the
throne room of Sargon II, a Neo-Assyrian king from the eighth
century B.C. Tutankhamen was so close to a wall that it was almost
impossible to read the hieroglyphs on its back pillar.
</P>
<P>
   Moving it down the hall to a commanding position in the new
gallery took six weeks. The statue was cut apart between the hips
and thighs, the dividing line between original and reconstructed
material, because it was too high for doorways.
</P>
<P>
   A four-legged steel framework on a concrete foundation was built
in the basement directly below the statue to support its estimated
weight of five to six tons. When the statue was re-erected, it
cleared the ceiling beam above it by an inch.
</P>
<P>
   To Dr. Teeter, it was worth the effort to be able to see the
rose-colored figure from all angles. ``I love the curve of the hips
and the width of the shoulders and the roundness of the head,'' she
said. ``It's so massive, yet so sensuous. It's like a different
statue.''
</P>
<P>
   Admiring the newly visible back pillar, she read a column of
hieroglyphs: ``Beloved of him _ possessor of diadems _ ruler of
happiness, I guess it is _ djeser kheperw Re setep en Re _ holy are
the manifestations of Re, the one selected by Re. These are pretty
highfalutin names. These guys were not modest at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The hieroglyph mentioning Re, the sun god, refers to the Pharaoh
Horemheb, who reigned from 1321 B.C. to 1293 B.C. and appropriated
the colossal statue by chiseling his name over that of his
predecessor, Aye. It is widely believed that Aye in turn had
appropriated the statue from  &UR; his &LR;  predecessor, Tutankhamen,
because its facial features resemble other representations of
Tutankhamen.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it actually resembled any of them would hardly have
mattered to ancient Egyptians, Dr. Teeter said, because
inscriptions _ not likenesses _ identified statues as representing
one king or another.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing about 800 objects out of a collection of more than
35,000 artifacts from the Nile Valley, Dr. Teeter said one goal was
to find things that ``people could relate to,'' like a mummified
chicken and a child's linen tunic.
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, 12-year-old Shaneira Brandon, who came with seven
family members from the west side of Chicago for her first visit to
the Oriental Institute, passed right by King Tut, drawn instead to
a 10-inch-long baby crocodile mummy.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny crocodile from between the fourth and first centuries
B.C. exemplifies the kind of delicate object that could not have
been displayed before the installation of climate control. Other
such artifacts include clothing, shoes, metal tools and papyrus
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Decades of exposure to pollution and widely varying humidity
have taken a toll on the collection. In the worst cases, involving
inscribed stones or pottery shards known as ostraca, salt layers
formed beneath the ancient paint, causing the decorated surface to
flake off.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Teeter said there was not much permanent damage. ``The
desire for climate control was to arrest future damage,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
