<SLUG> BC-DUAL-DONATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME EARLY CAMPAIGN DONORS PLAY THE ODDS IN BOTH PARTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif.)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Alfonse M. D'Amato and Charles E. Schumer faced
off last year in New York's divisive Senate race, David G. Lambert
decided to take a side. Make that two sides.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, Lambert, a managing director of the Goldman
Sachs Group in New York, gave $1,000 to Schumer, the eventual
winner. Six months later, he pulled out his checkbook and gave
$1,000 to D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Lambert is at it again. As fund-raising gears up for
the 2000 presidential contest, he is among the contributors who
have donated both to the presumptive front-runners of the
Democratic and Republican parties, Vice President Al Gore and Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas. Lambert has given $500 to each of them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being hopefully associated with a winner, early
financial supporters also often get the best seats at the
Inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the people whose contributions will be remembered by
the candidates, and that's what you want when you make a
contribution,'' said Paul Hendrie, the communications director at
the Center for Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan campaign finance
research group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for donors to give to multiple candidates
within a party, and already, for 2000, prominent Democrats and
Republicans have given the maximum donation of $1,000 each to more
than one primary candidate. For example, Eppie Lederer, the advice
columnist known as Ann Landers, has given both to Gore and his
Democratic rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   More unusual are the so-called pragmatic donors who split their
contributions among Republican and Democratic contenders. ``If you
really believed in the candidate,'' Hendrie said, ``you wouldn't
turn around and give to his opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   An analysis by the Center for Responsive Politics of Federal
Election Commission records for the first three months of 1999
reveals only 18 contributors who have given to both Gore and Bush.
As the election season progresses, there are certain to be many
more.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, more than 250 donors gave the maximum to both President
Clinton and former Sen. Bob Dole, the Republican candidate, in the
primaries, commission records show.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the Gore-Bush donors agreed to be interviewed last
week, many on the condition of anonymity. Their comments shed light
on the increasingly complex interplay between money and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Several donors said their contributions had little to do with
the candidates and much to do with personal ties to campaign
solicitors. The Bush-Gore list is an affluent one, including
Lambert of Goldman Sachs; William Tiefel, president of Marriott
Lodging, and Michael Kassan, president of Western International
Media, the largest advertising media firm in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the donors described themselves as pragmatists who
wanted to be with a winner. But most donors explained their
contributions in other ways. Some simply admired both Bush and Vice
President Gore and said dual donations served primarily to advance
the best candidate in each party.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the dual contributors described themselves as
political moderates who disliked seeing Washington torn apart by
partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are outstanding men,'' said Michael D. Goldberg,
president of On-Care, a cancer-treatment company south of San
Francisco. ``Both of them would make excellent presidents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
