A7672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANNIVERSARY-AD-COLUMN     05-31 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANNIVERSARY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DDB WORLDWIDE: HOPING TO BUILD ON A LEGACY OF 50 YEARS OF
INNOVATION  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When is an anniversary not just an anniversary but
the start of an ambitious brand image campaign? When it is
commemorated on Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago on Tuesday, an agency named Doyle Dane Bernbach
opened its doors in midtown Manhattan with 13 employees and
billings of $500,000 or $600,000 (memories vary). From those modest
beginnings emerged a shop that grew to 15,000 employees and
billings of $14 billion. But more importantly, it revolutionized
advertising with distinctive creative and operational approaches
that still resonate a half century later.
</P>
<P>
   The successor agency to Doyle Dane, DDB Worldwide Communications
Group, is capitalizing on the anniversary as a way to help burnish
its reputation and stand out from myriad competitors. There is a
particular focus on the achievements of William Bernbach, the
copywriter recently described by the trade publication Advertising
Age as ``the single most influential creative force in
advertising's history.''
</P>
<P>
   By reminding everyone of the contributions of Doyle Dane _ as
seen in refreshingly low-key, entertaining campaigns for
advertisers like Alka-Seltzer, Avis, Chivas Regal Scotch whisky,
Cracker Jack, El Al, Levy's rye bread, Ohrbach's department store
and especially Volkswagen _ the celebration is meant to promote DDB
as the keeper of the flame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to reclaim the Bernbach legacy,'' said Keith
Reinhard, chairman and chief executive at DDB in New York, a unit
of Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernbach belongs to the industry and to the world,'' he added.
``But he belongs to us first.''
</P>
<P>
   The Doyle Dane heritage ``represents a brand equity we should
leverage,'' Reinhard said, ``but a forward thrust is more important
than a retrospective.''
</P>
<P>
   (In the interest of full disclosure, it should be noted that
this columnist played a minuscule role in the history of Doyle
Dane, spending the summer of 1971 working in the agency's
mailroom.)
</P>
<P>
   A centerpiece of the celebration on Tuesday is the dropping of
``Needham'' from the name of the agency, which had been DDB Needham
Worldwide Communications Group since 1986. That's when Doyle Dane,
battered by account and personnel losses after the death of
Bernbach in 1982, merged with Needham Harper Worldwide, a
Chicago-based agency known for more prosaic work for mainstream
marketers like McDonald's. The merged agency did not truly jell for
six to eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any merger putting two cultures together is rough,'' said
Reinhard, who had headed Needham Harper, ``but we didn't know it
would be that rough.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency, by renaming itself DDB, is accelerating a process
that started in 1994 at various offices; for instance, BMP DDB
Needham in London became BMP DDB.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a marketing decision,'' Reinhard said, to play up ``an
important defining and differentiating part of our agency brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Needham Harper traced its roots to 1925, with the founding of
the Maurice H. Needham Co. But with the emphasis on DDB, similarly
elaborate hoopla next year to commemorate a Needham 75th
anniversary is about as likely as, well, the reopening of
Ohrbach's.
</P>
<P>
   The Doyle Dane celebration that DDB is orchestrating includes
giving away 315,000 postcards in cities around the world that
reprint familiar print advertisements for products like Chivas
Regal, the Volkswagen Beetle and the New York Lotto; compiling
lists of the 50 best commercials and print ads produced since 1949;
sponsoring exhibits at museums, and taking group portraits of DDB
employees at what are now 206 offices in 96 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhard has taped a tribute to Doyle Dane to be shown on
Tuesday at every office; he is joined by Maxwell Dane, 93, the sole
surviving co-founder (Ned Doyle died in 1989). And DDB will hold a
party for creative executives at the International Advertising
Festival this month in Cannes, France; Reinhard is president of the
festival's jury.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, only one agency could possibly warrant such a lengthy
list of celebratory events. The war waged by Bernbach and Doyle
Dane against Madison Avenue's conventional wisdom was fierce,
passionate _ and ultimately successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernbach invented `modern advertising,''' said John Hegarty,
chairman and creative director at Bartle Bogle Hegarty in London, a
creatively focused agency in which a DDB rival, the Leo Burnett
Co., owns a minority interest. ``Our debt to him is incalculable.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bernbach, as the creative spark at Doyle Dane, insisted
that advertising could be effective without insulting the
intelligence of consumers. The agency proved that bold assertion
with respectful, low-key campaigns infused with cheeky,
self-deprecating humor. At Doyle Dane, copywriters and art
directors were paired to produce more efficient creative teams. The
agency brought a new humanity _ and credibility _ to ads by
diversifying casts to include ethnic Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle Dane itself was widely staffed with Americans of different
ethnic backgrounds, who often had found themselves unwelcome at the
white-shoe agencies of the era. Scores of those employees went on
to found risk-taking, rule-breaking agencies of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, there's a dispersion of creative talent at 10 to 20 great
agencies,'' said Diane Rothschild, a former Doyle Dane creative
executive who is president at Grace &AMP; Rothschild in New York.
``Then, the talent was all in one place.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Doyle Dane creative alumnus, Roy Grace, chairman at
Grace &AMP; Rothschild, said he welcomed the renewed interest in Doyle
Dane at DDB Needham.
</P>
<P>
   ``A horrible mistake was made when they changed the name'' after
the merger, he said. ``It was like changing the name of
Coca-Cola.''
</P>
<P>
   Was there any inkling on June 1, 1949 among the workers in a
walkup office at 350 Madison Avenue that they were starting an
agency that one day would be compared to the world's most famous
brand?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pretty excited,'' Phyllis Robinson, a copywriter at
Doyle Dane, recalled last week. ``There was a great sense of
adventure and freedom, that we'd have great fun without having a
boss peering over our shoulder telling us, `You can't do that kind
of work.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill used to say, `If we really do this right, we could have a
$2-million agency,''' Ms. Robinson said. ``We felt pretty confident
we would succeed, at least up to Bill's goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, she added, chuckling, ``he didn't believe he had
ever said that his goals were so modest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
