A7674 &Cx1f; kan-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY-IOWA-KAN &LR;      05-31 1503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-IOWA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY'S RUN AT GORE IS MAKING STRIDES IN IOWA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALLTOWN, Iowa _ The man with the perfect resume has himself
in the perfect position.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley _ Princeton graduate, Rhodes scholar, basketball
star, author and three-term U.S. senator _ is the insurgent
candidate for the Democratic presidential nomination. But now
Bradley finds himself with only one person to beat _ Vice President
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people will be surprised by how well he does in
Iowa,'' said Jim Beres, a Gore backer who listened to Bradley speak
for an hour Monday in a park shelter here in Marshalltown. ``It's
sort of a stealth candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not for much longer. Bradley has been enjoying a media
boomlet because of his unusual standing. Never before has a
presidential race without an incumbent come down to only two
contenders so early in the nomination process.
</P>
<P>
   And with Gore struggling recently, the focus on Bradley has
intensified.
</P>
<P>
   Though defeating the vice president will be a herculean task,
few political observers count Bradley out. He stands to be the lone
beneficiary of ``Clinton fatigue,'' the sentiment that many voters
are tired of the Clinton administration _ and Gore by extension _
after eight turbulent years. It helps that Bradley's own ethics
record is spot-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worry with Gore is how much of Clinton's problems will
settle on his shoulders,'' said Jim Harrison, a lifelong
Marshalltown resident who also listened to Bradley on Monday. ``You
can't separate Bill Clinton from Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Expectations will be Gore's constant worry. He has to win early
primaries big. He has to raise money in multiples of whatever
Bradley brings in. Any better-than-expected showing by Bradley will
be portrayed as a sign of Gore's vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, 55, has his own share of doubts to overcome. He is a
steady but uninspiring speaker known for telling long stories with
sometimes confusing conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is much more of a contemplative figure than someone who is
a crowd-pleaser,'' said Ross K. Baker, a political scientist at
Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's own political history does not offer much confidence
about his ability to win the White House. In 1990, in his last
re-election race for his Senate seat from New Jersey, Bradley
narrowly survived an upset bid by Republican Christine Todd Whitman
even though he outspent her 12 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways Bradley does not offer much contrast to Gore. Both
are the antithesis of back-slapping pols. Both are prone to deep
thoughts and stiff presentations. When it comes to criticism of the
Clinton administration, Bradley offers a mild rebuke of Clinton's
welfare-reform bill. He is somewhat more outspoken about the
president's failure to outline clearer military objectives in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley asserts that his own life experiences are more varied
than Gore's and that the vice president is prone to caution.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley does not get much tougher than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the built-in advantages Gore has as vice president, the
question is whether Bradley's low-key, gentlemanly way of
campaigning is enough to distinguish himself and score a
breakthrough,'' said Dennis Goldford, a Drake University political
scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley insists that he is the outsider candidate of ``big
ideas.'' His outsider status, however, has been questioned because
his 18-year Senate career ended only in 1997. And Bradley has been
maddeningly vague about how he would take his ``big ideas,'' such
as improving race relations and reforming health care, and
transform them into public policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about intellectual abstractions. This isn't a
senior thesis at Princeton,'' said David Axelrod, a Chicago-based
Democratic consultant who backs Gore. ``This is about real life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley promises more details by fall. The early stages of the
campaign, he says, are about offering himself as a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in the Senate, my kind of leadership was to take
big, complex issues like taxes, international trade and
international finance and put a structure of reform around those
issues and then push for that reform,'' he said in an interview
Monday. ``Or I would take issues that were volatile, like race, and
try to play to our better angels.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday in Marshalltown, a city of 25,000 about 30 miles
northeast of Des Moines, Bradley was charming but, as usual,
low-key. In the park shelter before about 40 people, he spoke for
20 minutes, and then sat on a picnic table and fielded questions.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke quietly in almost a pastoral manner that some onlookers
said exuded sincerity. He drew laughter by recounting how he got
picked off first base in a key Little League baseball game years
before in Ottumwa. Bradley's team from Missouri wound up losing by
one run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since that day I've dreamed of coming back to Iowa and
winning one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked afterward whether he could motivate the country with such
a mild demeanor, Bradley said he could rise to the occasion when
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's rhetoric, and there's communication,'' Bradley said.
``The key is to communicate well.''
</P>
<P>
   As he left, Bradley signed autographs and posed for pictures, as
he does at almost every stop. Although his NBA career ended in the
mid-1970s, his celebrity endures, fueled by books that relied on
his basketball days and, less so, on his 18-year Senate career.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who hails from Crystal City in eastern Missouri, has
spent most of his life in the public eye. As a star basketball
player at Princeton, he was a celebrity when he was barely old
enough to vote.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up two years of pro basketball to accept the Rhodes
Scholarship and, after turning pro, spurned millions of dollars he
could have earned in endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate he developed a reputation as an original thinker
on major issues. He was known to listen carefully to others and,
when possible, incorporate their thinking into his own proposals.
</P>
<P>
   /{The National Journal/} hailed Bradley for his work on what may
have been his crowning achievement, the momentous 1986 tax reform
that lowered rates and closed loopholes. /{The Journal/} called his
work a ``stunning achievement,'' particularly for a member of the
minority party with little seniority.
</P>
<P>
   ``At each stage of the tax-reform debate, Bradley was there,
quietly encouraging others, avoiding the spotlight but offering
advice and lobbying key members,'' the publication said.
</P>
<P>
   For years Bradley has been considered a probable presidential
candidate. But in 1988 he said he wasn't ready. His tough 1990
Senate race, in which Bradley refused to criticize Democratic Gov.
Jim Florio's tax increases, kept him out in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when Bradley announced his retirement from the Senate,
some thought he was done with politics for good. But last fall,
Bradley said he looked in the mirror and decided he was ready.
</P>
<P>
   Back then the Democratic race appeared to be anything but a
one-on-one duel. Sen. Paul Wellstone of Minnesota was going to run.
So was Richard Gephardt, the House minority leader from St. Louis,
and Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and Sen. John Kerry of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But then, certainly awed by the challenge of facing Gore, they
all backed out.
</P>
<P>
   His sole-competitor status is not the only thing propelling
Bradley's campaign. In the first three months of the year, he
raised a respectable $4.3 million, far less than Gore's $8.9
million, but more than expected. He has said repeatedly that he
will raise the benchmark total of $20 million to $25 million to run
a competitive race.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's strategy is hardly a secret. The trip to Marshalltown
was part of a three-day campaign swing to Iowa, his ninth, that
began in Sioux City on the western border. His trip to Marshalltown
was his second of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bradley is to make a breakthrough, he has to do it in Iowa
and New Hampshire, or it's good night, Irene,'' Goldford said about
the states that conduct the first two major presidential tests.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the front-loaded primary schedule favors
front-runners and affords challengers little opportunity to break
out.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Gore, Bradley can move around Iowa and New Hampshire with
relative ease to do the type of person-to-person ``retail''
campaigning that voters demand. As the sitting vice president, Gore
must drag along a security entourage that limits his mobility.
Gore, for example, recently had breakfast with the mayor of Osceola
in his modest, brick-and-siding home while his 14-vehicle motorcade
waited outside.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he welcomed the chance for voters to size him up.
But whether voters see a winner or another Adlai Stevenson, the
deep-thinking Democrat who lost twice to Dwight Eisenhower in the
1950s, remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``How it all wears is hard to say,'' said Fred I. Greenstein, a
Princeton University political scientist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
