<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL DEVALUATION CHANGES THE TRADING BLOC PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ For generations of Argentines, the
quality of the meat they produce has been not just a source of
pride but part of their national identity. So it is not hard to
imagine the consternation that greeted a recent piece of news: The
country is now importing meat from Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil may be on its way to recovery from the crisis that in
January forced the government to devalue the national currency by
40 percent. But the fallout from that move has turned things
topsy-turvy in neighboring countries and created new tensions and
exacerbated old ones between Brazil and its partners in the trading
bloc known as Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1991, Mercosur is the world's third-largest trading
bloc, after the North American Free Trade Agreement and the
European Union. Since Brazil's $800 billion economy is more than
double the combined gross national product of Argentina, Paraguay
and Uruguay, the other Mercosur members, the sharp drop in the
price of Brazilian goods as a result of the devaluation has
generated considerable turbulence, both economic and political, in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian president Fernando Henrique Cardoso is scheduled to
meet on June 7 with Carlos Menem, his Argentine counterpart, in an
effort to resolve their differences. The timing is important
because the leaders of Mercosur and other Latin American countries
are scheduled to meet with the European Union nations here late in
June to discuss economic integration.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of Brazilian meat exports to Argentina has been
largely symbolic. But the more substantive matter of steel has
become a flash point between the two countries after Argentina, in
response to a complaint by a local producer, activated a mechanism
in April that requires Brazilian steelmakers to pay a bond that
will be forfeited if it is determined they have been selling steel
at prices below cost, an unfair trade practice known as dumping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some uneasiness about the process of calculating and
determining the margins of dumping,'' Luiz Felipe Lampreia,
Brazil's foreign minister, said about the decision. He described
talks with Argentina about the issue as ``very negative,'' adding
that ``it seemed to us that a decision had already been taken, that
the Argentine side wasn't willing to listen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Argentina, in the midst of a presidential campaign in which
trade relations with Brazil are an issue, is hardly alone in being
affected by the spillover from Brazil's economic problems. Uruguay
normally sends one third of its exports to its northern neighbor,
but the devaluation has caused sales of textiles, wool and grains
to Brazil to sag by 20 percent, a blow that contributed to a
one-day general strike in Montevideo in May.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Paraguay, the smallest and weakest member of the
group, called for a renegotiation of membership terms and benefits
after a popular uprising forced a change of government in March.
``Paraguay and Uruguay should without a doubt have some privileges
and concessions,'' in order to bring about ``a much more balanced
integration,'' the country's new president, Luis Gonzalez Macchi,
said recently.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in Brasilia in April, Cardoso praised his
counterparts for their ``understanding and sympathy'' during
Brazil's recent travails and said that Mercosur was ``fundamental,
a top priority'' to Brazil. But he gave little indication that his
government was willing to make concessions on the key issues
dividing the trade group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a deficit with Argentina, and we never complained,'' he
said, in a reference to the unfavorable trade balance of about $6
billion his country incurred between 1995 and 1998. ``This is
incidental,'' he added, and does not reflect a structural flaw.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil also appears to have parted company with its Mercosur
partners on the issue of how and when to enlarge the group. Chile
and Bolivia have already been granted associate member status as a
first step to full participation, but there has been resistance to
granting similar standing to the remaining Andean countries.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Cardoso's government has begun a crash effort to
negotiate bilateral trade agreements with Colombia, Ecuador, Peru
and Venezuela, members of the Andean Community. In doing so, Brazil
has ignored Argentine assertions that Mercosur policy is to pursue
trade ties with outside countries as a bloc, not individually.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis here has also brought out into the open a
long-submerged debate about what sort of currency policy Mercosur
should adopt. In January, Brazil responded to the speculative
pressure on the real by allowing its currency to be freely bought
and sold in the foreign-exchange market. Argentina, in contrast,
has since 1991 adhered to a policy of parity between its peso and
the American dollar, a step that has imposed enormous fiscal
discipline on the previously unruly Argentine economy but clashes
with the new Brazilian approach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
