<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-ART     05-31 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDS SENDS THE MESSAGE: HE'S RELIABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS, Ind. _ On practice floors and inside the coach's
office, Chris Childs and Jeff Van Gundy have yelled at each other
like two drivers arguing over a fender bender. No disagreement has
been major, no damage has been irreparable.
</P>
<P>
   Three years and all those volatile moments have helped them
understand each other a little more.
</P>
<P>
   As their relationship has unfolded, the trust that has developed
between them is as subtle as the difference between Childs'
bellyache on Sunday and his bellyaching of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the fourth quarter in Game 1 of the Eastern
Conference finals, Childs, who had been a tireless defender on Mark
Jackson for the bulk of first half, was feeling sick to his
stomach. One or two years ago, his teammates and his coach might
have rolled their eyes as if to say, Here we go again, another
fragile moment for Childs. And the team and coach would have turned
to Charlie Ward.
</P>
<P>
   No more. Not after a year in which Childs played through nagging
ailments. Not after a season in which he sent a message to his team
and coach that they can rely on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the fourth quarter started, I was bent over with my
stomach, and then Jeff looked at me like: `Hey, don't pull that
junk. You play better when you're sick,''' Childs said Monday after
the Knicks practiced in preparation for Game 2 at Market Square
Arena on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a respect thing. Jeff knows that I'm going to go out
there and give 150 percent. And I know that I can go out there, and
if I do make a mistake but I'm doing it hard, he's not going to
worry about it. Before, it wasn't like that. Before, I was always
looking over my shoulder and wondering about what he was
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Childs knows. During a critical stretch of the fourth
quarter, Van Gundy leaned on Childs, one of the best on-ball
defenders in the league, to come through and guard Jackson in the
post. Usually, it was one-on-one. But when help did arrive with 3
minutes 25 seconds left in the game, Jackson slipped a pass to Rik
Smits for a jumper that gave the Pacers a 4-point lead. The Knicks
called a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so upset, I slammed the ball down,'' Childs said. ``I
went into the huddle, and I said: `Don't come and help me. If Mark
Jackson scores on me, I'll take the blame.'''
</P>
<P>
   Childs was on the spot. Using his broad body, Jackson bumped and
backed Childs into the paint on two consecutive possessions. Each
time, as he tried to whirl around Childs, he missed short jump
hooks. The Knicks capitalized with points at the other end and took
back the lead. At that moment, the situation the Knicks worried
about before this series began _ Jackson's impact in the post _ was
diluted by Childs' physical defense in Game 1. That's the way it
appeared to many, though Jackson wasn't among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you consider that great D, then I'm happy for you,''
Jackson said after the Pacers practiced Monday, less than 24 hours
after he finished Game 1 with 11 assists but shot just 1 for 8 from
the field. ``Good try by him. He played me straight up, and they
didn't want to double. I missed two jump hooks that I usually knock
down. It doesn't matter what kind of grabbing or holding is going
on in there, that's my strength. I'm going to get to the spot I
want to get to, and I'm going to get the look I want to get. Last
night, they didn't drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's response to Childs is not new. Thanks to the $24
million deal he signed three years ago, Childs has a Jaguar among
his cars and an all-white suit in his closet of style, but credit
has been hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like Mark was standing there, shooting the ball by
himself,'' Childs said. ``We pressured him early on. He might not
have had the legs that he usually has if he wasn't getting worked
by me and Charlie. If he says he was just missing them, I say,
Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Childs is never short on clever responses. But three years ago,
for once, he didn't know how to react when he arrived in New York
and was labeled the point guard of the future. Guys like Jackson,
they were part of yesteryear. But when Childs stepped on the floor,
it was like stripes on plaid. Once a playmaker with a green light
in New Jersey, he was unable to blend his wilder side with the
team's more conservative system.
</P>
<P>
   Childs resisted change, rebelled a little and complained at
times. And a divide developed between him and Van Gundy. As Childs
puts it, ``We've had the same relationship as he and John Starks
did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I coach people better the more time we go along,'' Van Gundy
said. ``With Chris, he has a strong personality, as I do, and there
was a natural head-butting. Now, I think it's evolved into
something that's good and workable.''
</P>
<P>
   It has worked because Childs agreed to accept a backup role
before the 1997-98 season began. But it was ego deflating. And at
times, it seemed an irritable Childs was more likely to sit out
with aches and pains than he was to play through them.
</P>
<P>
   But with time, any doubts about his durability have ceased. With
a flair for the dramatic, he can still limp and wince and groan on
cue with the best of them, but Childs doesn't allow pain to get in
his way of running an up-tempo second unit that has given his
run-and-gun style new life.
</P>
<P>
   The additions of Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby are like
wings for Childs. He can fly now, just like he always wanted to.
That approach sent the Pacers backpedaling in vain in the first
half of Sunday's game, when the Knicks scored 18 of their 22
fast-break points. While the Knicks were running, they were also
keeping tabs on the Pacers' dangerous transition game and protected
the 3-point line as well as they have all season.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks gave up just three 3-pointers to a Pacer team that
usually feeds its transition game with open shots from the
perimeter. For the game, the Pacers had just 8 points on the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we did a good job getting back,'' Pacers forward
Dale Davis said. ``We gave up a lot of transition baskets, and we
can't afford to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy said Childs had had a great year. ``And I think it
comes from accepting who he is as a player, where he is in his
career and what he needs to do in order for our team to be
successful,'' Van Gundy said. ``He's been terrific.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
