<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-TRAILBLAZER     05-31 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-TRAILBLAZERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO TAKE ITS TIME, AND GAME 2 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ore.)  (mk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Once it became close, the San Antonio Spurs knew
they had it won.
</P>
<P>
   Recovering from an 18-point deficit, the Spurs defeated the
Portland Trail Blazers by 86-85 Monday night before 35,260
delirious fans at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Spurs a 2-0 lead in this four-of-seven-game
Western Conference championship series, which will resume Friday in
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs won a game they never led until the final moments.
That was when Sean Elliott made an unfathomable 3-point shot from
the right baseline with 9 seconds remaining. The 3-pointer was
Elliott's sixth in seven attempts and came with the 6-foot-11-inch
Rasheed Wallace flying at him.
</P>
<P>
   As in Game 1, Portland had a chance for the victory, but shots
by Jimmy Jackson and Walt Williams fell short, giving the Spurs
their sixth victory in seven games this season against the Blazers.
All of the Spurs' victories have been decided in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very confident down the stretch,'' said David Robinson,
San Antonio's longtime leader. ``We've proved it time and time
again that we can win close games, so for us that's a good thing if
they are close games and come down to execution.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott scored 22 points to follow Tim Duncan's game-high 23,
and Robinson added 14 points as all five Spurs starters scored in
double figures. Arvydas Sabonis led Portland with 17 points, Damon
Stoudamire added 15 and Wallace scored 13.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Grant put the Blazers ahead by 74-63 on a smooth
turnaround jumper over Duncan with nine minutes remaining, but the
Spurs countered with their second big run of the half, this one a
9-0 surge. In a half of spurts, Portland put together the next one
behind a 3-pointer and slick spin move in the post by Jackson.
Wallace wrapped two jumpers around a jumper by Avery Johnson to
make it 82-74 with less than three minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   When Stoudamire followed a basket by San Antonio's Mario Elie
with a jump shot that made the score 84-76 with two minutes left,
the Spurs seemed dead. But Johnson, shooting with confidence
despite a terrible start, nailed a baseline jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Then Elliott got his fifth 3-pointer and Robinson stole the ball
from Wallace, leading to two free throws by Elie. Suddenly the
Blazers' lead was down to 1 point with 33 seconds on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Stoudamire took an ill-advised jumper on Portland's next
possession, but after Walt Williams grabbed the rebound, he made
one of two free throws to make it 85-83 and set up the drama at the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Just when Portland seemed ready to crash, especially with
Wallace and Grant on the bench with four fouls, another turnaround
occurred, and the Blazers regained control. Sabonis and Stoudamire
began scoring again, the Spurs turned cold and Portland pulled away
to lead by 67-60 heading into the final period.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers' grabbed their 48-34 halftime lead by running their
offense through Sabonis. With the slow-moving veteran using every
facet of his versatile game _ shooting, rebounding and passing _
Portland dominated the Spurs with a well-balanced attack.
</P>
<P>
   Though he shot poorly, making just three of 10 attempts, Sabonis
led the way with 9 first-half points while also notching five
rebounds and four assists.
</P>
<P>
   Keyed by the play of Sabonis, their 7-foot-3-inch center, the
Blazers enjoyed a surprising advantage in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   Running a seemingly endless supply of large bodies at San
Antonio's Duncan and Robinson, the Blazers outrebounded the Spurs
by 24-17 in the first half and had nine offensive rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   If it wasn't Sabonis using his bulk to battle the Spurs' big
men, it was Wallace, Grant, Jermaine O'Neal or Kelvin Cato.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace and Grant were as productive as Sabonis before foul
trouble sent them to the bench in the second quarter. Wallace had 7
points, and Grant matched his Game 1 scoring output with 8 points
and four rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, who scored all of his first-half points in the opening
quarter, teamed with Sabonis to total 15 points in leading the
Blazers to a 31-20 advantage after one quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers' offense was incredibly efficient, as they shot 57
percent against one of the top defensive outfits in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs seemed to be in for a boost when Grant was whistled
for his third foul just two minutes into the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But with Cato on the floor, the Blazers didn't miss a beat as
they ran to a 39-22 lead midway through the quarter. If Grant's
absence wasn't enough inspiration for San Antonio, then it seemed
that Wallace's would be. But when Wallace committed his third foul
and joined Grant on the bench with 6:42 left in the half, the Spurs
still could not take advantage, getting no closer than 11 points
before the break.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan led all scorers with 11 points, but it was quiet
production, largely because he only had two rebounds to go with it.
Robinson's 8 points and three rebounds also seemed minimal. With
San Antonio's big men unable to rule, the Spurs' horrific outside
shooting became huge.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose touch has always been a question mark, missed
four wide-open jumpers and two driving layups.
</P>
<P>
   Jaren Jackson, the reserve turned sharpshooter in the semifinal
victory over the Los Angeles Lakers, was no better, missing all
five of his shots, and Elie was just one for three. Only Elliott
provided anything on the perimeter, hitting two 3-pointers in
scoring 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
