<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES01-CO     05-31 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz's return means move for Chen
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Rookie pitcher Bruce Chen is expected to return to AAA
Richmond today when John Smoltz is activated from the disabled list
for tonight's start. Chen made two starts in which he kept the
Braves in contention but didn't make enough of an impression for
the Braves to reconsider their decision to use Odalis Perez as the
fifth starter.
</P>
<P>
   Perez is coming off his best start of the year on Friday night
in which he flirted with a shut out against the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Chen allowed six earned runs in 12 innings, four on the grand
slam by Gary Gaetti in his first inning in his first start. He ran
into trouble in the first inning of his second start, this time
with his location but escaped without allowing a run. He received a
no decision after holding the Brewers to two runs in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know I can pitch here,'' Chen said. ``There's nothing I
can do about (the decision) but go back to Richmond. I have to keep
working, getting more starts. Other than that, I think I'm fine. I
don't think I have to develop, I just need the opportunity.
Hopefully I opened some eyes, that people will say the kid is
ready. If (another injury) happens, I'll be the first one they call
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz ready
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz reports that the 15 days off has served him well and he's
ready for today's start against the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have waited three more weeks and I don't think it
would have done me any good,'' Smoltz said. ``You never know how
your elbow is going to react. I know I can pitch when it ain't
great, that's the comforting thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss waits
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Walt Weiss had toyed with the idea of getting back in
the lineup on Monday but manager Bobby Cox thought he needed a day
or so to make absolute sure his sore left quadriceps was ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel it some,'' said Weiss, who strained it running
out an infield hit in Milwaukee. ``(Cox) wants me to go out there
100 percent, so there's no chance of going backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss said he ran at 50 percent on Sunday and planned to push
himself to about 85 percent in his workout Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The times he gets frustrated about sitting, all Weiss has to do
is think about last year when quadriceps and hamstring injuries
limited him to 96 games, his fewest since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the one who wasn't smart at times,'' Weiss said. ``Every
day I keep wanting to get back in there, but last year is a good
reminder.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive lapse
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have played some uncharacteristically flawed defense
this season, never more evident than over the weekend when a pair
of errors led to two losses to the Dodgers. Through 50 games last
year the Braves had committed only 21 errors. This season through
50 games, they've had 41.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's one of those things,'' said first baseman Brian
Hunter, who was responsible for one of them against the Dodgers.
``You don't hit for a while, you don't pitch well for a while,
we're in a slump making errors. The last couple have hurt us.
Hopefully guys will crack down. I'll take groundballs, just like I
always do. To me, it was just a decision I made (to go for a double
play), not a physical (mistake).''
</P>
<P>
   Angel Pena's line drive took a hop Hunter wasn't expecting and
bounced through his legs. It wound up costing the Braves two runs
in a 2-1 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could have knocked it down we would have been out of the
inning easy,'' Hunter said. ``In that situation, I should have
knocked the ball down.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko's error on Sunday, trying to catch a high throw from
Chipper Jones, cost the Braves a 5-4 extra inning loss.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko (6) and Hunter (2) have combined for eight errors at
first base, compared to Andres Galarraga's five through 50 games
last year. Weiss has nine errors in 42 games. He had 12 in 96 games
last year. Chipper Jones has five errors in 48 games, he had 12 in
158 last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves finished first in the National League with a .985
fielding percentage last year. Right now they rank sixth in the
National League with a .978 fielding percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rely an awful lot on playing flawless defense, and when we
don't play good defense behind (Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine) we're
going to get beat,'' Jones said. ``It's going to happen to some of
the best players in the game...Are we worried? No.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
