<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROCKIES-CO     05-31 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROCKIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves best Rockies 3-1
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Remember that 20-5 doozy the Braves won at Coors Field
last month? Remember who started for Colorado?
</P>
<P>
   Rockies right-hander Pedro Astacio is one man who's like to
forget, and planned to use Monday night to do it.
</P>
<P>
   In a place he'd been uncharacteristically effective against the
Braves _ he's 2-0 at Turner Field against the team that's beaten
him more times than any other in baseball (11) _ Astacio pitched
stingier, the way he has for his last four starts.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves beat him anyway, using three hits and two runs
batted in by Brian Jordan, a key RBI hit by Ryan Klesko in the
sixth and a strong pitching effort of his own by Kevin Millwood to
pick up the 3-1 win and even their record to 2-2 on this homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood, who was pitching on three days rest for the second
time in his career in preparation for John Smoltz's coming off the
disabled list today, did some gutsy pitching to pull out his fourth
consecutive win.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood mixed stretches of dominance with shakiness, but for
the most part pitched like the most formidable Braves starter in
the absence of Smoltz that escaped him in his last outing against
the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   He clutched a 2-1 lead after allowing a solo home run to Vinny
Castilla in the fourth inning, loading the bases in the fifth and
using a Castilla popup to get out of it. He retired the next six
batters he saw and got a little more breathing room with a Braves
run in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Take Rockies pitching out of the Rockies and it hasn't looked so
bad. Colorado pitchers had a 2.57 ERA in the first seven games on
this trip through Houston and Philadelphia, riding a streak of a
club record 17 scoreless innings coming into Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves squelched that by taking a 1-0 lead four batters into
the game, 2-0 two innings later, but left a pair of runners on each
time on consecutive outs by Javy Lopez and Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves weren't raking Astacio this time, just picking at him
with infield hits and grounders sneaking up the middle. The 2-0
lead came on five singles, both after Bret Boone reached, moved to
third on Chipper Jones singles and scored on Jordan hits.
</P>
<P>
   Astacio pitched three more innings this time (6) against the
Braves than the start in Denver, allowed one fewer hit (7) and
three fewer runs (3). Still the same nemesis though. Jordan had two
RBIs and a run scored in the April game on a two-run home run, two
RBIs and a run scored this time on a pair of singles.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Remlinger came in in relief of Millwood, and John Rocker
was brought in for the 9th inning. Rocker got his 10th save of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
