u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-INDIANS-RAMIREZ-N     05-31 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-RAMIREZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: RAMIREZ RAISES BROWS BEHIND HIS (HOT?) BAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Poor Manny. His friends have abandoned him. The large
groups who used to sit in the upper stands on the third base side
of Yankee Stadium do not go there anymore. At least that is what he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be the same because some of my friends don't
go to the ball park anymore,'' Manuel Aristides Ramirez said
Saturday of the Cleveland Indians' impending visit to New York.
``They're working.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monday was a holiday, so who among Ramirez's Washington
Heights friends was working?
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, after he reignited the Indians' volatile offense
with a two-run home run in the first inning and set the tone for a
7-1 Indians victory, Ramirez still insisted his friends had not
been among the 46,000 fans at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't like me anymore,'' he said Monday, then laughed.
</P>
<P>
   At that very moment, two young men sat at Ramirez's locker in
the visiting clubhouse. They wouldn't say much _ ``He doesn't like
me to talk about him,'' one of them said _ but they acknowledged
they were his friends and one said, ``A lot of Dominicans were here
today.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ramirez, a Dominican Republic native who grew up and lives in
New York, chose to remain mysterious about his New York fans, he
also raised suspicion about the bat he used to hit the home run.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Yankees suspected that the bat had more than wood
in it _ cork, to be descriptive _ citing Ramirez's unusual reaction
to the home run and his decision to use a different bat in the
second inning, when he rapped a two-out run-scoring single off an
umpire's foot ahead of Jim Thome's grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   If they are correct about the cork, would that illegal aid taint
the two-month performance that has made Ramirez the chief rival of
Derek Jeter for the American League Most Valuable Player Award? Not
if Ramirez abandons the bat and no one ever establishes that he
produced most or at least some of his major-league-leading 63 runs
batted in with that sticky wicket.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez does not talk much about his hitting or anything else
for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't speak English well, not enough to do an
interview,'' said Omar Vizquel, the Indians' shortstop and an
articulate and delightful Venezuelan. ``That's what he says. That's
his excuse. But he can say so many nice things.''
</P>
<P>
   Another member of the Cleveland club attributed Ramirez's
reticence to shyness. But in what apparently was his first and only
interview of the season, Ramirez last Saturday talked briefly about
his 1999 hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year,'' he said softly, ``I think I'm more lucky. I'm
getting hits at right time. More runners are on base. Sometimes I
bring them in; sometimes I don't. I just try to be patient. It's
still early. A lot of things can happen. I'm not trying to get a
big head. I just go out and play and whatever happens happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Ramirez has been a corking good hitter
throughout his six-year major-league career. In his previous four
seasons, he batted .310 and averaged 34 home runs and 113 RBIs a
year. Last year he established career highs with 45 home runs and
145 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   His home run and umpire-aided single Monday raised this season's
average to .350, fourth in the league, and kept him well ahead of
other hitters in the RBI race. By comparison, he has more RBIs than
any pair of Yankees except Jeter and Chili Davis, who combined have
knocked in 66 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manny may have the most pure sweet swing,'' Mike Hargrove, the
Indians' manager, said. ``You watch him take batting practice, and
it doesn't look like he's swinging hard, and the ball jumps off his
bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove, it should be noted, offered that observation before
the Yankees' suspicions surfaced and later wasn't around to address
that issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got tremendous power to all fields, which is a huge
advantage'' _ his home run cleared the center field fence _ ``and
he's a very good off-field hitter,'' the manager continued. ``He
can pull the ball, but if you stay out away from him too long he'll
hurt you in that direction, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove said that Ramirez had developed one flaw this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times he's overswinging,'' he said. ``I've very rarely seen
Manny do that before. Usually he swings very controlled and
measured. It's a good swing; it's a good, powerful, quick swing
when he does that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why he does it. I think Manny wants to hit the
ball out of the ball park when he does that. I also think Manny
knows himself better as a hitter now, knows the pitchers better and
gets into a good count when he knows he can hit this ball hard and
he gets the pitch that he wants and he overswings. All hitters do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, remarkably, has become more than a one-dimensional
player. The Indians generally agree that he has improved
tremendously in right field and adequately on the bases.
</P>
<P>
   As a base runner, with some help from Roberto Alomar, he has
become more focused and more aggressive. Running with greater
confidence, Ramirez has become a two-base runner instead of one who
stops at each base along the way, Hargrove said.
</P>
<P>
   The manager also said Ramirez had made himself one of the better
right fielders in the league, covering a lot of territory and
possessing an above-average arm, above-average accuracy and a quick
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to work a little bit every day,'' Ramirez said. ``I take
fly balls and ground balls. I think that has helped me a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the question remains. Has cork helped him a lot, too?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
