A7689 &Cx1f; tad-z
b a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-CARNIVAL-LAW-COX     05-31 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-CARNIVAL-LAW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carnival ride inspection bill goes to governor
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A year after a 15-year-old girl was thrown to
her death from an amusement park ride at the Austin-Travis County
Livestock Show and Rodeo, Gov. George W. Bush is poised to sign
legislation that would allow police to inspect and immediately shut
down unsafe rides.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos, D-Austin, and Rep. Terry Keel,
R-Austin, filed the legislation in response to the death last
spring of McNeil High School student Leslie Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Under current Texas law, ride operators must be able to prove
that they have insurance and that the ride is inspected at least
once a year. Insurance companies can choose their own inspectors,
as long as they meet certain standards of education and experience.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would supplement that system by allowing law
enforcement officials to inspect and immediately shut down unsafe
rides. Under current rules, law enforcement officers or Texas
Department of Insurance officials must get a court order to close a
ride.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also would stiffen sanctions for failing to comply
with the insurance and inspection rules, making jail time a
possibility in addition to fines.
</P>
<P>
   Keel called the new law ``probably the best in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a careful balance in the bill to promote
safety without overregulating private industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say the bill is weak because, unlike many other
states, Texas would not use state inspectors to ensure ride safety.
Others have questioned whether police officers will have the
expertise to recognize safety risks.
</P>
<P>
   But Keel insists that the new system is preferable to relying on
state inspectors, who wouldn't be able to inspect rides every day.
He noted that riders and police officers are always present, and
that most safety problems _ such as a broken lap bar or an
intoxicated operator _ are obvious to everyone. Senators added a
provision to the bill requiring signs notifying riders of their
right to contact a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of federal regulations, amusement park rules vary
greatly from state to state. Arkansas and Florida use state
inspectors to check rides at every setup, while Hawaii uses state
inspectors every six months. Nevada leaves it up to city code
inspectors. Missouri and North Dakota have no safety requirements.
Some states perform inspections but do not require insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
