<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7694 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEGISLATURE-TEXAS-HNS     05-31 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGISLATURE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LAWMAKERS END `GOOD LEGISLATIVE SESSION' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
and JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ &UR;  &LR; The Texas Legislature gaveled to a close Monday
for the last time this century, ending a session that focused on
letting the good times roll with tax cuts, big teacher pay raises,
children's health insurance and other laws designed to make Texans
feel like they are sharing in the state's economic bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been a really good legislative session,'' said
Gov. George W. Bush, who as a GOP front-runner stood to gain from
legislative success. ``Texas is a better place because of the last
140 days.''
</P>
<P>
   The 76th Legislature passed more than 1,340 bills this session _
from the grand (electric and telephone service deregulation) to the
minutiae (setting weight standards for loaves of bread). But those
that got the most protracted attention seemed to focus on sharing
Texas' economic vitality.
</P>
<P>
   A package of tax relief bills promise consumers and businesses
half a billion in tax reductions over the next biennium, and a
school funding bill will give the biggest boost in history to
public school funding. The school finance package will trigger an
estimated $1.35 billion in property tax reductions and offer every
teacher a one-time pay raise of $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we did ... we took the surplus, and we invested
it in the future of Texas,'' said House Speaker Pete Laney, a
Democrat from the Panhandle. He was referring to the lawmakers'
decision to devote $3.8 billion of the state's record $6 billion
surplus to public schools and universities.
</P>
<P>
   In their final day, before calling a close to business at 6:19
p.m., Texas senators spent more than four hours engaging in Academy
Award-length speeches, for fellow Sen. Gregory Luna, D-San Antonio,
who missed most of the session hospitalized; for Senate Secretary
Betty King for her 22-year tenure; and for Houston Democrat Rodney
Ellis, who was elected president pro tempore of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The title will make Ellis acting governor whenever Bush and Lt.
Gov. Rick Perry are out of state. It also means that if Bush is
elected president and Perry ascends to the governor's office, Ellis
would preside over the Texas Senate until the body elects a new
lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Given Bush's travel plans as he heads to Iowa and New Hampshire,
sites of the first two presidential primaries, Ellis may assume
those duties before long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush needs to do what he needs to do in New Hampshire,''
Ellis said, adding that Perry should take his family on a long
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, who has guided 278 bills into law during his five terms
in office _ 90 of them this session _ said he would head back to
Houston to spend some time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I've got to go back and face Pampers,'' he said, a
reference to his infant son.
</P>
<P>
   But senators also praised Perry for his freshman session at the
podium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You came in as a rookie and you followed an icon (former Lt.
Gov. Bob Bullock),'' said Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   This session also marked the first time in the 20th century that
Republicans held a majority of seats in the 31-member Senate and
had a Republican at the helm as lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, said he believed partisanship was kept under
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a very successful legislative session because we had a
Republican lieutenant governor and a Democrat speaker work
together,'' he said. ``We had a successful legislative session
because we had a Democrat committee chairman carry a significant
piece of education reform, teacher pay and tax cuts. We had people
from both parties come together to do what was right for Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only a few weeks ago, however, that members of the Senate
were locked in a rancorous partisan fight over a hate-crimes bill
that could not be salvaged. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Act, sponsored by Ellis and Rep.
Senfronia Thompson, another Houston Democrat, identified specific
groups, including homosexuals, for protection from crimes of
prejudice. A law now on the books is so vague it is virtually
unenforceable, according to experts. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; For the first time ever, the tougher hate-crimes bill passed
the Texas House, winning the vote of one of the most conservative
members of that body _ Rep. Warren Chisum, R-Pampa. But it failed
in the Senate in a struggle so emotional and bitter it temporarily
shut down that chamber for most of one day. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Rep. Paul Sadler, D-Henderson, called the bill's failure a
defining issue of the session.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had victims on one side of that issue and hatred and
bigotry on the other. If you chose the latter, it says a lot about
the party you represent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More partisanship flared just 48 hours before the session ended
when the Republican-led Senate fought with the Democrat-controlled
House over how to spend the last $47 million in the school finance
package. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The Senate wanted the money to go to tax cuts; the House, whose
negotiations were led by Sadler, wanted it to go to early childhood
education programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans did almost all the compromising, but Democrats
refused to give an inch. In the end, a hasty projection of $100
million more in revenue by the state comptroller saved the day.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the extra education funding and tax cuts, other
spread-the-wealth bills sent to the governor include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A government-funded health insurance program for 500,000
low-income children under the age of 19.
</P>
<P>
   _ A $100 million college scholarship to send about 20,000 high
school graduates whose families earn less than $25,000 to college.
</P>
<P>
   _ Creation of permanent endowments to fund health care programs,
including county and hospital district indigent care, and
anti-smoking campaigns _ initiatives made possible by the first
payments to the state from tobacco companies in a $17.3 billion
lawsuit settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the Legislature also passed the most significant
change in abortion laws since the procedure was legalized more than
two decades ago by passing a law that will require doctors to
notify parents when their minor daughters seek an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   A major blow to Bush and Republican leaders was a pilot project
to allow public schoolchildren to attend private schools at
taxpayer expense. Despite intense pressure from proponents and
support by the governor, the issue never made it to the floor of
either house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked hard on the voucher issue. It just wasn't meant to be
this legislative session,'' Bush said Monday. ``I believe it's
(vouchers) an idea that frightens certain people.''
</P>
<P>
   The House finished its business Monday with a whimper, approving
a few corrections to major bills and scores of minor resolutions.
Members bid one another good-bye, signed each others' souvenirs and
praised the session's legislative output.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was maybe more partisanship present,'' acknowledged
Laney, the House speaker and a legislator since the 1970s, ``but it
probably didn't play as big a role.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
