u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLLUTION-STATES-ART-     05-31 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLUTION-STATES-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFORT TO CUT WIND-BORNE CHEMICALS FACES LIKELY COURT CHALLENGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Pa., Mich., Maine, N.H., R.I., Mass., Vt., Conn.,
N.J., Md.)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Northeast begins its smog season _ when sunshine, warmth
and pollution combine to sting eyes and strain lungs _ state
environmental officials from Maryland to Maine are reeling from a
series of court rulings that have derailed federal plans to cut the
flow of air pollution across state borders.
</P>
<P>
   New York and other states in the region find themselves down to
their last defense tactic against smog-causing chemicals drifting
downwind from coal-fired power plants in the Middle West and the
South, but even that tactic is likely to face court challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the federal Environmental Protection Agency formally
accepted petitions from New York, Pennsylvania and the six New
England states requesting a federally imposed cleanup of dirty
power plants in states that send nitrogen oxides and ozone _ the
components of smog _ east on the wind. Petitions from New Jersey
and Maryland are still under review.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Clean Air Act, after receiving such petitions, the EPA
can order sharp cuts in pollution at specific power plants or other
sources. The petitions are a ``legal hammer'' of last resort
against out-of-state polluters, said John Cahill, New York's
commissioner of environmental conservation. This is the first time
the EPA has accepted petitions of this sort, officials with the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
   But the petitions are certain to be challenged in the courts by
the same coalition of state governments and industry groups that
gained the favorable court rulings against other aspects of the
EPA's plans for reducing smog. Environmental officials from Middle
Western states and power industry spokesmen say the EPA's strict
new standards for smog are not supported by science.
</P>
<P>
   A result of legal challenges is likely to be further delays in
ending smoggy summers in the Northeast, according to various state
officials and private environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big polluters are succeeding in delaying rules that would
prevent a lot of sickness and death in this region,'' said David
Wooley, a law professor at Pace University who has been providing
legal advice to a coalition of 18 private environmental
organizations contributing briefs in the court fights.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the 1999 smog season is off to an early start.
New York state environmental officials on Saturday issued the first
ozone advisory of the year, with levels in several parts of western
New York rising above the federal safety threshold of 80 parts per
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeastern states have long contended, and the
environmental agency concurs, that plumes of nitrogen oxides from
old coal-fired power plants in the Middle West and South contribute
to eye-burning haze and lung problems along the eastern seaboard.
In the presence of sunlight, the nitrogen compounds produce ozone.
Ozone, in turn, can irritate the lungs and eyes, contributing to
asthma and raising death rates in the elderly and infirm. The
nitrogen oxides also contribute to acid rain.
</P>
<P>
   To solve the problem, the EPA required 22 states last fall to
file plans by September for sharply reducing emissions of nitrogen
oxides.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, in 1997, the agency issued new limits for ozone that
were far lower than the previous standard. That drew immediate
legal challenges from power companies that relied on coal and
states with older, dirtier power plants.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over long-distance air pollution has intensified in
the last few years as the electric power industry has begun opening
up to competition.
</P>
<P>
   States with many older, coal-fired power plants, like West
Virginia and Michigan, have much cheaper electricity than areas
with newer, cleaner power plants, like the Northeast, and they want
to keep that competitive advantage, industry executives and state
officials in both regions say.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, several state environmental officials said, after
several years of relatively constructive negotiations and
cooperative research among the states to reduce smog, talks have
stalled and the battleground has shifted to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The latest court rulings on federal smog controls came on May 14
and May 25 in the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia. In the first, two of three judges on a panel ruled that
the EPA had not adequately justified the need for a strict new
standard for ozone. The same ruling overturned new standards for
soot particles. The EPA was invited to return to court to
substantiate the numbers it chose. That decision was hailed by
industry groups and denounced by private environmental
organizations and the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   In the second ruling, three judges, including the two that
rejected the EPA's ozone standard, said states could hold off on
filing the plans for pollution cuts until the merits of the federal
requirements for nitrogen oxides were argued.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the rulings are likely to delay federal programs to
sharply cut levels of nitrogen oxides and ozone in the eastern half
of the country, Carol Browner, the EPA administrator, said in a
telephone interview on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The agency planned to return to court this summer with a new
argument in support of its pollution standards, Ms. Browner said.
``We're going to continue to look at how to provide the relief to
downwind states.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell Harding, the director of Michigan's Department of
Environmental Quality, said Friday that the courts acted
appropriately because the EPA could identify no ``bright line'' for
health effects of ozone that separated safe levels from hazardous
ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there's no clear human threshold, then picking a number
becomes a policy call,'' Harding said. He added that setting policy
is the responsibility of Congress, not the agency.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting for appeals to play out, he said, Michigan plans
to proceed with a nitrogen-cutting proposal and still intends to
reduce its output of the smog-causing chemicals, but to a less
stringent standard than that sought by the EPA. ``We know we have
some culpability in Michigan,'' Harding said, ``but it's way, way
less than what they're talking about.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``My view is that EPA is in deep trouble, and they know it,'' he
said. ``It's a house of cards that Carol Browner has built on
politics and bad science, and it's falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior EPA officials said the agency's smog standards had
nothing to do with politics and were a result of hundreds of
scientific studies and comments from states and industry.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shinn, the New Jersey commissioner of environmental
protection, said there was plenty of evidence from studies in New
Jersey backing the need for the strict ozone standard set by the
EPA.
</P>
<P>
   He said New Jersey had commissioned a study of asthma attacks
treated at a Morristown hospital and found that admissions rose 30
percent on days when ozone levels topped 60 parts per billion _ not
even a level as high as the federal standard of 80 parts per
billion.
</P>
<P>
   He added that half of the ozone measured in the state has been
shown to be a result of pollution carried on wind from the west.
Shinn has an ozone meter in his state car, he said, and often keeps
it running to track smog levels as he crisscrosses the state.
``I've found high levels in real rural areas _ in places where it
just shouldn't be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If transport is 50 percent of our problem,'' Shinn said, ``no
matter what we do to cut emissions here, we can never guarantee
healthy air for our residents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
