<HEADLINE>
CRAIG GOT PAST ERRORS TO LEAD TROJANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wouldn't have been a career-breaker for Beau Craig, USC's
freshman third baseman who is going to switch to catcher next year.
But Craig knew it would be a long summer if his mistakes cost the
Trojans a chance to defend their national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have felt like the (jerk) on the team,'' Craig said.
``I would have been the guy that blew it. I'm always pretty hard on
myself. I've never had the perfect game. Things stick out in my
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig's two throwing errors, which led to USC's 4-3 loss to
Pepperdine on Sunday, became footnotes. The Trojans, pushed to a
final game to advance to this weekend's ``super regional'' at
Stanford, came back to beat the Waves 12-7 in the second game and
win the first-round regional at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a good thing, that my teammates picked me up,'' said
Craig, who contributed as much as anybody in USC's clinching win.
He went 3 for 4 and was flawless on two chances.
</P>
<P>
   Even after his earlier miscues, Craig was fearless. He told
shortstop Seth Davidson he was going to go after every ball hit to
the left side of the infield. An All-State catcher in high school,
Craig fielded dozens of ground balls last week to prepare for the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of stuff coming my way,'' he said. ``We're
playing better teams and better hitters. I'm not going to get much
of a break over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig's ability to hit _ his batting average is fifth-highest on
the team _ has kept him in the lineup. When starting catcher Eric
Munson broke his hand early in the season and missed 21 games,
Craig moved back behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Mike Gillespie is appreciative of what Craig has done
this season and the way his freshman rebounded Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Craig) should be proud of the defense he played,''
Gillespie said.
</P>
<P>
   __ No surprise: As expected, the NCAA announced Monday that
Stanford will host USC in a three-game series to determine a spot
in the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   USC (36-24) and Stanford both put in bids to host the super
regional, but the Cardinal (46-13) are the nation's No. 6 seed and
the NCAA indicated that seedings were important for determining
second-round sites.
</P>
<P>
   Munson, who hit two home runs Sunday and was selected the
outstanding player in this past weekend's regional, doesn't care
that the games are at Stanford, where USC won two of three games
from the Pac-10-champion Cardinal in April.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans and Cardinal have played 323 times but never in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely always a tough series,'' Munson said. ``We'll
have to play our best baseball to win.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Little big man: The regional All-Tournament team included
four Pepperdine players but not sophomore outfielder Austin Evans,
who batted .450 (nine for 20) with eight runs scored and four RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Being left out hasn't bothered Evans, a 5-foot-8, 155-pound
former walk-on who became the Waves' starting center fielder and
leadoff batter in the middle of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Evans' parents, Bob and Shary, flew to Los Angeles from their
home outside Austin, Texas, to see their son play. It was the first
time they had seen him in a college game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When coaches (in the past) saw him initially, they saw his
size, not his ability,'' said Bob. ``Austin knew what he could
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Shary: ``His (high school) coach would always put him down.
He never got any respect because he was small.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who graduates in December, a year and a half ahead of
schedule, is one of eight underclassmen who started Sunday's final
game for the Waves, who finished 46-16.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine gained at least one out-of-area admirer after pushing
USC to the brink this weekend _ Virginia Commonwealth head coach
Paul Keyes. The Waves beat the Rams 12-5 Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell they've got a lot of character,'' Keyes said. ``I
enjoyed watching them play. . . . Just a well-schooled team.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The old college try: Harvard went two-and-out at USC, marking
the first time in three years the Crimson didn't win a playoff
game.
</P>
<P>
   Although none of the seven teams from the Northeast won a
regional this year, Harvard head coach Joe Walsh said teams from
the East get a bad rap at playoff time for receiving bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are some good Northeast teams that are home,''
Walsh said last week. ``The thing we (Harvard) can't overcome is
the lack of scholarships. Most of these guys have a couple jobs
during the season.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Around the horn: Cal State Fullerton, the national No. 3
seed, won its regional at Notre Dame but is on the road again this
weekend. The Titans play at Ohio State in a super regional. . . .
Long Beach State was swept in two games by host Texas A&AMP;M Sunday
and was eliminated in the first round. Senior outfielder Termmel
Sledge (Granada Hills) went 5 for 10 in the two games for the
49ers, who went to the CWS last year. . . . USC pitching coach John
Savage said he is not a candidate for the head job at Cal and he is
supporting Cal assistant David Lawn for the job. Long Beach State
head coach Dave Snow, whose son Casey played at Crespi, is rumored
to be interested in going to Berkeley.
</P>
</TEXT>
