<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-WARHERO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PEARL HARBOR AND A DEBT STILL UNPAID 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Hawaii, Fla., Utah, N.J.)  (lh) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As always, Memorial Day took Leonard Purifoy back to
Dec. 7, 1941, back to Pearl Harbor, back to the boundless realm of
terror and the cold iron touch of death.
</P>
<P>
   Purifoy was a sailor in Hawaii that fateful day when Japanese
fighter planes attacked the United States fleet there. It took his
battleship, the Utah, 10 minutes to capsize after being torpedoed.
</P>
<P>
   Some people can live a lifetime in 10 minutes. This young man
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared and I was running,'' said Purifoy, now 80, a
retired mechanic living in Jacksonville, Fla. ``I thought the ship
was about to blow. I got out just in time. I guess I wouldn't have
if I wasn't so scared. I imagine I'd have been on the bottom with
the chief.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief was Chief Watertender Peter Tomich, and Purifoy
believes he was the last person to see him alive.
</P>
<P>
   Tomich, 48, was in charge of the Utah's engine room. While
others scrambled to get off the ship, he raced below deck to keep
the boilers from exploding and to make sure crewmen got out safely.
Most did, but 64 were killed, including the chief. He is among 58
sailors entombed to this day in the Utah's rusty hulk.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, he was posthumously awarded the Medal of Honor, the
nation's highest decoration, for ``extraordinary courage and
disregard of his own safety.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes this more than just another old war story is this:
</P>
<P>
   No one ever received Tomich's medal. It is, in fact, the only
Medal of Honor in the last century never to have been presented to
someone, whether the person being honored or relatives.
</P>
<P>
   It has bounced from one display case to another, first on a
World War II destroyer called the Tomich, then in the Utah state
capitol building. Later, it went to the Navy Museum in Washington,
where it lies in a storeroom.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, a Navy spokeswoman said, is that the authorities
have never found ``definitive proof'' that Tomich had any
relatives. Back in the 1940s, she said, a man he had listed as next
of kin, a cousin living in Los Angeles, could never be found.
</P>
<P>
   But the New York Naval Militia, which has taken the Tomich case
under its wing, insists that the real problem is the Navy itself:
It and bureaucratic sloth.
</P>
<P>
   If the Navy has uncovered no proof, the New York militia says,
it is because it has done nothing to find it. Worse, the New
Yorkers say, Navy officials keep shrugging off evidence that Tomich
indeed has kin: distant cousins in the Balkans who would be
delighted to receive his medal.
</P>
<P>
   Rear Adm. J. Robert Lunney knows, because he has tracked them
down himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all so frustrated over why our government doesn't
recognize their family,'' said Lunney, a Westchester lawyer who is
staff judge advocate for the Naval Militia, which for those
unfamiliar with it is equivalent to the Army National Guard. It
became involved because Tomich had once lived in Queens and had
joined the Army at Fort Slocum, N.Y., before switching services and
enlisting in the Navy from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   This is a tale that gets a little messy. We are talking,
remember, about the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The cousins, Lunney said, are Croatians from a village called
Prolog, an outpost of the Austro-Hungarian empire when Tomich was
born in 1893. Now it lies in western Bosnia. All the same, family
members are Croatian. One is a Croatian army officer.
</P>
<P>
   They use the name of the larger clan to which they belong:
Tonic. After Petar Tonic journeyed to America (becoming a citizen
in 1918), his name took new shape. Any child or grandchild of
immigrants will recognize the process by which Petar became Peter
and Tonic became Tonich, morphing later into Tomich.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting Prolog in 1997, after talking with villagers and
studying well-kept local records, Lunney became convinced that,
Tonic or Tomich, all belong to the same family. ``They're all so
proud,'' he said. ``And all they want is some acknowledgment that
the medal should be presented to them. It would be fine if it then
comes back here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   You might be wondering why any of this matters after so many
years. You might as well ask Leonard Purifoy why Memorial Day
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the right thing to do for a man who gave his life
for this country,'' said Rear Adm. Robert A. Rosen, commander of
the New York Naval Militia. ``It's a matter of honor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
