<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DEBT-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN ARREARS DEEPENING ON DEBTS TO FOREIGN GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ On Wednesday, Russia will default on roughly $900
million in interest payments on debt it owes the so-called London
Club, a group of major foreign banks and investors that lent money
to commercial entities of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Reneging on debt may be a grave transgression, but most London
Club lenders have shown little rancor or surprise at Russia's
failure to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Although a splinter group of U.S. creditors is threatening suit
against Russia, the London Club as a whole seems hesitant to act.
It could restructure the debt with the Russians, or it could get
tough and call in the full amount, accelerating a default. Yet
because of a host of considerations, the creditors have instead
chosen to look the other way as a bankrupt Russia falls deeper into
arrears.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's likely to happen after June 2 is that Russia will
remain in default and not get called on it,'' Charles Blitzer, the
chief international economist with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette,
said.
</P>
<P>
   When its economy collapsed last August, Russia unilaterally
annulled obligations on a range of debt, including a default on $40
billion of treasury bills. Besides its own loans, Russia had also
inherited the former Soviet Union's debts to foreign governments
and private lenders. After the crisis, Russia said it would honor
foreign debt it had accumulated after the fall of the Soviet Union,
which includes Eurobonds, loans from the International Monetary
Fund and a few other instruments. But the Russian government
maintained that it lacked the resources to pay the Soviet debt.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the June 2 default surprises few people because Russia
is already in arrears on $300 million it owed the London Club in
December 1998. All told, Russia has fallen behind on about $1.2
billion of about $30 billion in Soviet-era debt it owes the London
Club.
</P>
<P>
   When Russia did not pay last year, that debt was automatically
rolled over under the terms of its London Club contract. But some
creditors also called for a vote to accelerate default, which means
the whole sum comes due immediately. That measure failed, but it is
likely that a newly formed association of investment funds, the
U.S.-based Russia London Club Portfolio Managers Inc., may again
demand such a vote once a 15-day grace period passes after the June
2 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the commercial banks in the London Club are mistaken
about the sentiment among creditors this time,'' said Marc Helie,
managing director of the New York investment management firm
Gramercy Advisors and chairman of the association, whose members
hold about 10 percent to 15 percent of the total London Club debt.
``I think now many other creditors will vote for an acceleration of
default.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of the vote, the emergence of the investor
association alone shows how fractured the London Club is, which may
help explain its hesitancy over Russia. About half of those holding
London Club debt are investment funds, according to Helie. Yet the
bank steering committee that actually negotiates with the Russians
is drawn from major lenders like Deutsche Bank AG, J.P. Morgan &AMP;
Co. and Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. Helie and others say that because these
banks want future business with Russia, they may be unwilling to
pressure the government on the London Club arrears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The London Club has objectives beyond Soviet debt, such as
bilateral debt, underwriting of new securities, all of which would
tend to dilute their focus on these debt securities,'' Helie said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The varied business goals of the creditors and their access to
the Russians themselves affect how they view Russia's ability to
pay. Some argue that Russia could pay, at least partly, but is
unwilling to, because it knows that for the time being it can get
away with delaying tactics. They note that in mid-May, Russia
scraped together about $330 million in interest on bonds issued
against another package of Soviet-era debt. But those bonds are
held mainly by Russian investors.
</P>
<P>
   Yet others on the steering committee who are in regular contact
with the Russians say Moscow wants to pay but cannot, which
necessitates patience. ``Russia has been paying its debts incurred
since 1992, but only by borrowing from the Central Bank,'' one
London Club banker said. Russia's hard currency reserves are about
$11 billion now. ``It shows you that they have no further funds to
pay old debts,'' the banker said.
</P>
<P>
   The London Club is forming a subcommittee to do the preliminary
economic research to begin talks with Russia on restructuring,
tentatively scheduled for late June. Russian officials have said
repeatedly that they would like 75 percent of their debt forgiven,
which is unlikely. In fact, some observers think the London Club
should stay in its holding pattern, without restructuring or
calling a default, until the Russian presidential elections in
mid-2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the right time to get into serious negotiations,
because there won't be a stable government until there's a new
president,'' Blitzer said. ``The London Club is best advised to
agree to nothing and wait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
