<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS NEED A BREAK JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The Los Angeles Dodgers have won four of six games
and can finish the road trip in fine shape if they close out
Pittsburgh with two wins. But you get the idea that just as the
Dodgers reach the doorstep of putting together a momentum-building
streak, something, or some things, happen to push them back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make your own breaks,'' manager Davey Johnson said after the
Dodgers lost 5-4 Monday to Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   It's simple, a cliche, and perfectly suitable as the reason the
Dodgers failed in their attempt to win three straight games for the
first time in a month. They had two guys thrown out when relay
throws were cut off and thrown to other bases. They produced one
run in five at-bats with runners in scoring position and played
conservatively on two balls hit to the outfield in an eighth inning
in which the Pirates scored the tying and eventual winning runs.
</P>
<P>
   It looks familiar to Pirates second baseman Warren Morris.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dodgers have failed to put together a head-twitching
winning streak in a month, the Pirates won four straight and seven
of nine, and entered the Dodgers series having swept the Houston
Astros in three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to believe whenever you get on a roll things are
going to go your way and good things are going to start happening
for you,'' said Morris, whose bloop single in the eighth inning
scored the Pirates' fifth run. ``The positive energy carries over,
a lot like Kevin (Young) today, taking advantage on the hustle play
and scoring from first (on a ball hit in front of left fielder Gary
Sheffield).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about momentum. If you can keep the negative things
to a minimum, you can carry it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Using (some of) the 'pen: Dodgers lefty Pedro Borbon is
coming off elbow surgery and hadn't pitched in the big leagues for
two full seasons, Alan Mills is the only right-handed set-up man
the Dodgers have and closer Jeff Shaw has appeared in 10 nonsave
situations. They've combined for 68 appearances while the other 11
pitches the Dodgers have used in relief have combined for 62
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson is taking it slow in developing
rookies Onan Masaoka and Jamie Arnold, and the results of that is
shown in the use of Borbon, Mills and Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Borbon) is not a long reliever, but I also have to bring
Masaoka along,'' Johnson said. When we're more ahead, I can use
Masaoka. I've given more work to Borbon. He's handled it. As
Masaoka comes along and Arnold gets better, they'll get (more
innings). If it were late in the year, after I'd have used Borbon
for an inning, I'd use Masaoka for a few innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Borbon, Mills and Shaw have a 2.33 ERA in 692/3
innings. The other 11 Dodgers used in relief _ including one
appearance each from Carlos Perez and Darren Dreifort _ have a 6.81
ERA in 762/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   With Mills and Borbon both used regularly in the first six games
of the road trip, Johnson went to Masaoka, Doug Bochtler and Jamie
Arnold against the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   __ A draining inning: One reason Dodgers starter Chan Ho Park
didn't pitch into the seventh was a long fourth inning in which he
faced five batters but had a lengthy duel with first baseman Kevin
Young. The at-bat lasted 12 pitches and finished with Young drawing
a walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That situation I had to concentrate and focus on a strike and
not corner, corner,'' Park said. ``Every time I throw too many
pitches in one inning, it's not good for the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   __ This and that: Dodger catcher Todd Hundley's two-run homer in
the fourth inning was his first hit in 18 at-bats during the road
trip. . . . Five of the past seven games have been decided by one
run. The Dodgers are 3-2 in that stretch. . . . Raul Mondesi
extended his hitting streak to seven games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
