<SLUG> BC-NY-SOLOMON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER CONGRESS, STILL TRYING TO BRING GENERAL ELECTRIC GOOD
THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For 20 years, Gerald Solomon represented the 22nd
Congressional District in upstate New York with such pro-business
gusto that environmentalists dubbed him ``the congressman from
General Electric.'' It was not meant as a compliment, but Solomon,
a former Marine, proudly wore the sobriquet like a medal.
</P>
<P>
   Today, six months after Solomon, a Republican, retired from
Congress, the nickname fits better than ever: He is now a lobbyist
for General Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   GE is not the only familiar name in Solomon's new stable of
clients. A staunch supporter of both the timber and dairy
industries in Congress, Solomon now represents both as a lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been tremendously successful, in my eyes,'' Solomon, 68,
said in a recent interview. But Solomon's successes are not welcome
in all eyes. Groups that monitor congressional ethics say it is
just the latest case of a longstanding but growing trend: members
of Congress who step out of office and into lobbying jobs for
industries whose positions they had been advocating just months,
even weeks, before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the classic revolving-door problem,'' said Don Simon,
acting president of Common Cause, a government watchdog group.
``The fact that they were colleagues and often remain friends of
those in Congress certainly can give them not just entree, but also
enhanced influence with very important people.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 128 former members of Congress and scores of former
top congressional aides are now working as lobbyists in Washington,
pulling down six-figure salaries that are often quadruple or more
what they earned in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon's own small company, the Solomon Group, is affiliated
with a lobbying firm headed by former Sen. Paul Laxalt, R-Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon is not alone among recent retirees from the New York
delegation to join the lobbying ranks. Former congressman Bill
Paxon, a five-term Republican of western New York who retired last
year, has joined the law and lobbying firm founded by Robert
Strauss, the former Democratic National Party chairman. And former
Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, a three-term Republican who was defeated last
year, has gone into consulting work for companies like MBNA America
Bank, whose fights he carried in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   By law, former members of Congress cannot directly lobby
Congress for one year after retiring. Paxon and D'Amato have not
yet registered as lobbyists, describing their work as strategic
consulting. And Solomon, though he has registered, says he is only
lobbying Clinton administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon offers no apologies, saying that he considers the ethics
rules barring him from lobbying Congress for one year
unconstitutional. ``You can't deprive a person of their income,''
he said. ``I'm going to work until I'm 85.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that the relationships he developed in Congress,
where he was chairman of the powerful House Rules Committee, will
help his clients. But he asserted that access did not guarantee
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said he quit Congress largely to make enough money to
leave a substantial estate for his five children and six
grandchildren. Having sold off his shares of insurance, stock and
real estate businesses when he entered Congress, and then having
put five children through college, he said he has almost no savings
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``My former partners made fortunes,'' he said. ``And I left the
Congress after 20 years worth less than when I came.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to reveal his income this year, saying only that he
had turned down offers to join big firms as a ``show horse'' who
could have made $600,000 annually. Asked if that meant he would
earn less than that this year, Solomon laughed and said, ``The
year's not over.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress earn $136,700 a year.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, Solomon often defended General Electric in its
long-running battle to avoid dredging toxic polychlorinated
biphenyls, or PCBs, that the company has acknowledged dumping into
the upper Hudson River two decades ago. Dredging could cost
hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, who now splits his weeks between Washington and his
Lake George, N.Y., home, said he is not lobbying on the dredging
issue, but might in the future. His lobbying disclosure form also
listed work on the reauthorization of the Superfund program.
General Electric is pushing to change a Superfund provision that
can require companies to pay for damage caused by their pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said he endorsed the company's positions in Congress,
and still does, because they were supported by most farmers and
officials in his district. ``I am very proud that they were
positions I never veered from,'' he said. ``That's one of the
things I was known for. I never changed from being a hawk to a
dove.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
