<HEADLINE>
CHIEF TECHNOLOGY OFFICER AT MICROSOFT TAKES A LEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nathan Myhrvold, Microsoft's chief technology
officer, will take a yearlong sabbatical to pursue his own
scientific research and travel, the company announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft made the announcement after several news
organizations, including Time magazine, reported that Myhrvold was
leaving after a falling out with Microsoft's president, Steven
Ballmer. Microsoft executives, however, said the reports were
inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Myhrvold, who was the founder of Microsoft's research division,
joined the company in 1986 as director of special projects. He
became a Microsoft executive after the software company acquired
Dynamical Systems Research, a software company he had founded with
his brother, Cameron Myhrvold, who also became a Microsoft
executive.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Myhrvold founded Microsoft Research, and expanded the
effort with laboratories in England and China. Before becoming
chief technology officer in 1996, he was group vice president in
the company's applications and content group and was a key
contributor to Microsoft's early online and consumer efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Microsoft's efforts in the so-called content business
have been disappointing, and when the company announced a
broad-ranging reorganization earlier this year, Myhrvold was not a
member of an executive management group that reported directly to
Gates.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Monday, Myhrvold said that his
successes at Microsoft had outweighed any failures and that he was
leaving on his own decision, not because of corporate political
infighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking about doing this for two or three years,''
he said. ``I was looking for the right time for the company, but
both Bill and I realized that there would never be a perfect
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7839 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-     05-31 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TRIAL FOR CAMPAIGN REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 1:
</P>
<P>
   It was hard enough to keep a straight face when House Speaker
Dennis Hastert declared that there was no time for campaign finance
reform, especially since he said it while the House was preparing
for its vacation. Even funnier was the sanctimonious lecture last
week by Tom DeLay to the half-dozen Republicans who defied Hastert
and signed a petition to force the Shays-Meehan reform bill to the
floor of the House. DeLay seemed to suggest that by standing up for
principle, these reformers were committing lese-majeste against
their speaker. But the issue here is not Hastert's dignity. It is
whether his party has a soul.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Shays is the Connecticut Republican whose bill
passed the House last year after surviving delaying tactics similar
to those now being used by Hastert and DeLay, the party whip. As
Shays obliquely observed, it is not Hastert who runs the show but
DeLay, a partisan infighter from Texas who is the GOP's biggest
fund-raiser and most important liaison with the special interests
that benefit so handsomely from the porous system of campaign
financing that Shays is trying to change.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay is also disingenuous. Even as he lectures Shays about
loyalty, he undercuts the speaker on Kosovo. When right-wing
Republicans block spending bills pushed by Hastert, they get no
lectures from DeLay. Instead, the House adjourns and goes home.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of campaign financing, however, DeLay is
consistently shameless. As if the loopholes in the current
fund-raising laws were not big enough, he and his allies are now
scheming to set up a new committee to raise $25 million without
disclosing any information on the donors or how the money is spent.
The current law, parts of which have been in effect since 1907,
bars donations from corporations and labor unions to individual
political candidates and places strict ceilings on funds from
individual donors. The Shays-Meehan bill would ban unregulated
donations to parties and bar donations to independent groups to pay
for television ads. DeLay's plan for another ``independent'' group
is nothing less than a proposal to create a clandestine and corrupt
slush fund.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of DeLay's scheme is that it comes at a time when
Republicans are attacking the 1996 Clinton re-election campaign for
accepting money that was traced to China. But if the plan succeeds,
foreign money will inevitably find its way into the system, and no
one will know because it will not be disclosed. The Democrats are
seeking a Justice Department ruling to stop DeLay's efforts.
Congress can close the loophole outright by passing the
Shays-Meehan bill.
</P>
<P>
   Five Republicans joined with Shays to sign the petition to force
the bill to the floor: Michael Forbes of New York, Mike Castle of
Delaware, Greg Ganske of Iowa, Constance Morella of Maryland and
Nancy Johnson of Connecticut. Democrats have signed up 196 members,
so that 16 more signatures are needed. Marge Roukema of New Jersey
and Zach Wamp of Tennessee say they want fast action. Why have they
not signed?
</P>
<P>
   The same could be asked of Bob Franks, Frank LoBiondo, Rodney
Frelinghuysen and Jim Saxton of New Jersey and Sue Kelly, James
Walsh, Sherwood Boehlert, Amo Houghton and Benjamin Gilman of New
York. To paraphrase an old 1960s slogan, if you're not part of the
effort to get this bill to the floor, you're part of the problem. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
