<HEADLINE>
`SATURDAY NIGHT': EARLY, UNDISCOVERED SONDHEIM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.Y.)  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ For Sondheim groupies, the in place to be these days
is a utilitarian theater on the campus of a little-known college in
a nondescript Chicago neighborhood. That is where ``Saturday
Night,'' a 45-year-old musical with a book by an author of
``Casablanca'' and a thoroughly enchanting score by a young man who
was yet to make his mark on the musical theater, is having an
understated _ and long overdue _ American debut.
</P>
<P>
   If for no other reason than that it represented 25-year-old
Stephen Sondheim's first stab at a full-blown commercial musical,
``Saturday Night'' would be worth the trip to Truman College and to
this production by the Pegasus Players, the tiny Chicago troupe to
which Sondheim entrusted the material and for which he has written
two new songs. Blessedly, though, the show is no mere peek at
messy, fraying pages from Sondheim's discard pile. ``Saturday
Night'' is a musical comedy of beguiling innocence that hints at a
composer's promise in every downy-smooth and stylish number.
</P>
<P>
   The musical, based on the play ``Front Porch in Flatbush,'' by
Julius and Phillip Epstein, was to open on Broadway in 1955, but
the death of its young producer, Lemuel Ayers, that summer sealed
the fate of a venture that had already been greeted only tepidly in
backers' auditions. In the intervening years, several songs from
the show, including ``Isn't It?'' ``What More Do I Need?'' and the
title number's wry salute to restless bachelorhood, have made it
into cabaret acts and Sondheim anthology evenings. But it was not
until 1997 that Sondheim would authorize a full production, by the
Bridewell, a fledgling London company that had demonstrated an
affinity for the composer's work. (A version on compact disk has
been released by First Night Records and BMG Classics.)
</P>
<P>
   Now Sondheim has pried open the door for Pegasus, a troupe that
has staged several of his musicals. He spent a day with the company
during rehearsals, enlisted his longtime collaborator Jonathan
Tunick to create new orchestrations, added two ensemble numbers
(``Delighted I'm Sure'' and ``Montana Chem'') and even served as
editor, slashing Julius Epstein's book back to a manageable two and
a quarter hours.
</P>
<P>
   Has it been worth the new attention? Yes, absolutely. Though the
book remains a bit static and the direction by Gary Griffin is
stodgy, ``Saturday Night'' is a cold engine that turns over
miraculously whenever the band begins to play. With its treatment
of the amorous mishaps of a group of average Joes and Janes, and
the clean, character-defining songs that playfully introduce us to
a landscape more familiar to devotees of kitchen-sink drama than
musical comedy, ``Saturday Night'' has the unmistakable stamp of
shrewd imagination and originality. And for fans of Sondheim, it
packs something extra: the heart-stopping sensation of a curtain
going up on genius.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1950s musical universe of Siamese kings and Polynesian
temptresses, ``Saturday Night'' must have seemed weirdly unexotic,
a ``Marty'' among musicals. Set in 1929 on the eve of the stock
market crash, it tells the story of Gene Gorman, a Wall Street
clerk from Brooklyn, who is so intent on accumulating wealth that
he pretends to have some, dressing in tuxedos and crashing affairs
at the Plaza. At the hotel doors, Gene, played with an adolescent
charm by Ian Brennan, meets Helen Fogel (Elizabeth Sayre Yeats), a
woman who, though unknown to Gene, is from his neighborhood and
puts on the airs of a Southern belle. Helen's wavering willingness
to put up with Gene's scheming is the thin crux of the tale.
</P>
<P>
   It is Brooklyn, not the Plaza, that this musical seeks to
infiltrate, and it accomplishes that splendidly right off the bat
with the title number, sung by Gene's cronies, bemoaning their
chronic lack of romantic entanglement. ``Alive and alone on a
Saturday night is dead,'' they sing in the sweet outer-borough
bluntness that is one of the show's refreshing hallmarks. These are
the primordial models for the comradely men evoked again and again
in Sondheim's lyrics and musicals, from the Jets in ``West Side
Story'' to the songwriting team in ``Merrily We Roll Along'' to the
Baker in ``Into the Woods.''
</P>
<P>
   The astonishing gift for interior and unusual rhyming _
``peignoirs'' and ``Renoirs''; ``supine'' and ``new pine'' _ is
readily apparent, as are some of what would become the composer's
signature song styles: skillful mimicking of other genres,
demonstrated here in ``A Moment With You,'' a parody in the style
of Rudy Vallee; the exquisitely detailed list song (``Exhibit A,''
a template for ``Now'' in ``A Little Night Music''); the sobering
ballad (``So Many People'').
</P>
<P>
   If that were not sufficient, there is ``That Kind of a
Neighborhood,'' with its superb anthem to a much-maligned borough:
``Brooklyn, the pride of/The thorn in the side of/New York,'' and
``What More Do I Need?,'' one of the best songs ever written about
the utter madness of opting for city living.
</P>
<P>
   Given the limitations of Epstein's book _ the plot, at once
prosaic and convoluted, ends unconvincingly in a police station _ a
director needs to take this material strongly in hand. Griffin, a
Chicago director whose production of ``Beautiful Thing'' is to
close soon at the Cherry Lane Theater in Greenwich Village, is far
too timid; there is a generic feel to the effort to conjure a
specific time and place. Moreover, his young actors seem a bit
intimidated, as if they were abundantly aware of the importance of
the occasion. (The Chicago audience by contrast seems hardly aware
of it; the O'Rourke Center at Truman College was only about half
full for Friday night's performance.)
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, a Loyola University undergraduate, has the hungry,
open-faced appeal, if not the magnetism, necessary for the
opportunistic Gene; Ms. Yeats sings prettily, even if her put-on
Southern accent for the amusing ``Isn't It?'' isn't put-on enough.
Among their colleagues, Charles Karvelas is ideally cast as Gene's
cheapskate buddy Ray; Philip Dawkins brings polish and an
old-fashioned show-biz spirit to his solo number ``Exhibit A,'' and
best of all is Samantha Fitschen's Celeste, half of the show's
secondary romantic couple. Her no-frills rendition of ``I Remember
That,'' a song eerily close to ``I Remember It Well'' from
``Gigi,'' is effortlessly funny, a bright window on how the warming
effect of the whole show might be accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   An evening with Sondheim's Brooklynites in Chicago leaves one
issue unresolved: why ``Saturday Night'' is not yet being produced
in the city that inspired it.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `SATURDAY NIGHT'
</P>
<P>
   Book by Julius Epstein; music and lyrics by Stephen Sondheim;
with orchestration by Jonathan Tunick; directed by Gary Griffin;
musical director, Thomas Murray; choreography by Marc Robin; sets
by Jeff Bauer; lighting by Shannon McKinney, USA; costumes by
Shifra Werch; sound by Steve Mezger; production stage manager,
Katie Klemme. Presented by Pegasus Players, Arlene Crewdson,
executive director; John Economos, managing director. At the
O'Rourke Center for the Performing Arts, Truman College, 1145 W.
Wilson Ave., Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Ian Brennan (Gene Gorman), Elizabeth Sayre Yeats (Helen
Fogel), Nico Tricoci (Dino), Christopher LoDuca (Artie), Charles
Karvelas (Ray), Patrick Sarb (Ted), Philip Dawkins (Bobby, Major
Domo and elevator boy), Elic Ryan Bramlett (Hank and male
vocalist), Samantha Fitschen (Celeste), Harriet Nzinga Plumpp
(Mildred), Bill Tisdale (Eugene Gorman), Susan Kokot (Florence and
Dakota Doran), Derek Hasentrab (Attendant, Clune and headwaiter)
and Paul Hofmann (Fletcher and Fisher).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 2348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990531.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-OBSERVER-NY     05-31 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHY SHOULD DAY TRADERS HAVE ALL THE FUN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The race is on to be the first to offer late-night stock
trading. The New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq and a number of small
electronic competitors have the same brilliant idea _ let people
trade stocks until 10 p.m. If television networks think nighttime
is prime time, why should Wall Street be any different?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, few people on Wall Street much like the idea, for
reasons good and bad. But given the competitive pressures, and the
unwillingness of the Securities and Exchange Commission to block
it, nighttime trading is likely to be here by Labor Day, and will
probably expand after that. Why not midnight madness?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that such trading makes no sense for real
investors, who are looking for the best price on a stock they plan
to own for some time. But those investors are a declining part of
the market. In-and-out trades, with the hope of snaring quick
profits, are all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   Companies fear their employees are sitting in front of their
computers all day trading Internet stocks, rather than doing
whatever it was they were hired to do. Why not let these traders do
their thing on their own time? In addition, those poor souls who
actually have to work during the day could share in the fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The online firms think their customers want to trade when they
get home from work,'' says one person involved in the planning.
``They want to have the fun of hitting the button and getting an
execution.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason most investors would be better off sticking to normal
trading hours is that they benefit from having other investors
there to provide liquidity and make markets more competitive. When
people interested in buying and selling something are concentrated
together, both buyers and sellers are likely to get better prices
than if they have to rely on middlemen who shave off profits from
both sides. That is why medieval towns had market days.
</P>
<P>
   It is also why 24-hour trading has never caught on for
professional money managers, even though it is available because
major stocks trade in markets around the world. The pros know that
they will get the best price if they trade when and where a lot of
others are also trading.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals who trade at night are likely to find that with
fewer people active in the market, the spreads will be wider
between the prices buyers pay and those sellers get. Their loss
will be a gain for brokerage firms that serve as middlemen, but
some of those firms fear they will not make enough from the extra
volume to offset the costs of hiring a night staff.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that only the more active larger companies will be
traded at the start. But you can bet that such barriers will soon
fall. The night traders will crave the excitement of Internet
stocks, and ways will be found to give it to them.
</P>
<P>
   Since the SEC has decided not to try to stop nighttime trading,
the least it can do is try to make sure the gamblers (sorry;
investors) know the risks. Traders should be advised, on the screen
where they trade, that markets may be more liquid the next morning,
and be told that the order will be held for the next regular
session unless they specifically direct it to be executed at night.
</P>
<P>
   While the idea of stock trading as a leisure-time activity may
seem strange to many, it is not a new one. In the 1920s, as now, an
exciting new technology made it far easier to trade stocks while
also providing exciting speculative stocks that led a great bull
market. That technology was radio.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1929, trading on board ocean liners was all the
rage. On the liner Berengaria, which was at sea when the 1929 crash
started, one woman was said to have lost $160,000 on Oct. 24, but
made back most of that through active trading the following day,
when prices briefly rallied. Passengers filled the ship's brokerage
office, where prices were put on a blackboard, and a large crowd
gathered outside. It was a ``death watch,'' one passenger said.
</P>
<P>
   After the crash, the number of people trading stocks on ocean
liners fell sharply. Bear markets just aren't as much fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-31-99 2359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
